export const chapterTranslations3to60: Record<number, string[]> = {
  3: [
    "Wei Pincai returned to find that dinner had already been served in the study; he was still at a loss, thinking he might go to a restaurant outside for a snack. As he reached the door of the accounts room, he suddenly caught sight of a page boy carrying a large square tray — a hot pot and two dishes of food, steaming hot — being brought inside. Then he saw the head steward Xu Shun follow behind. Xu Shun, seeing Pincai, asked: \"Has the young master eaten yet?\" Pincai replied: \"I have only just returned from delivering a message outside.\" Xu Shun said: \"Since you have not eaten, why not join us here in the accounts room?\" This Xu Shun and his wife had come as part of Lady Yan's dowry household, and handled all financial accounts. Pincai entered the accounts room; Xu Shun urged him to eat first, but Pincai refused and drew him to sit together.",
    "When the meal was over, Xu Shun brewed a bowl of strong tea and passed it to Pincai, and they chatted idly for a while.",
    "Glancing at the clock on the wall — already past the first quarter of the wei hour — he noticed a few worn books on a purple-bamboo bookshelf and idly took two down: they turned out to be handwritten opera librettos, nothing more than a few arias from The Peony Pavilion and The Palace of Eternal Life. He took down another slender volume of twenty or thirty pages, a woodblock edition titled A Selection of Flowers from the Song Stage. Flipping through it, it appeared to be a ranking of young dan performers. He took a few more — an incomplete copy of Strung White Furs. Pincai said: \"Are these your own books? You must be quite knowledgeable about musical theory.\" Xu Shun said: \"What would I know about musical theory — I have no idea which gentleman left them here.\" Pincai asked to borrow them; Xu Shun said: \"Take them, by all means.\" Pincai tucked them under his arm, went to his own room, lay down on the kang, and read the Flower Selection for a while, memorizing the names of eight performers. He thought to himself: \"So the capital really does have such excellent young dan roles — no wonder people from other provinces say, 'If you want to see opera, go to the capital.' These performers are not only fine-looking; each has his own exceptional skill and is well versed in literature. The reputation is thoroughly deserved.\"",
    "\"By this reckoning, though Qinguan is as beautiful as an immortal, he may not surpass this troupe after all.\" Then second thoughts came: \"Perhaps what this book says is somewhat exaggerated.\"",
    "\"As for looks, I doubt anyone in the world can rival Qinguan.\" He went through the eight performers again one by one, vividly imagining each, and fixed them firmly in his memory. Just then Si'er came running in: \"A Master Ye who traveled with you by boat is looking for the young master — he is in the accounts room now.\" Pincai said: \"How strange — why would he come here?\" He tucked the Flower Register under his dressing box, latched his door, and went out.",
    "When he reached the accounts room, he found Ye Maolin sitting with a chubby, pale-faced stranger. Both men rose as Pincai entered and came forward with greetings. Pincai said: \"Master Ye, to what do I owe this honor?\" Maolin answered with a broad smile: \"Learning that Your Excellency was here, I came especially to pay my respects.\" Pincai knew this was mere politeness and said: \"I had not yet come to call on you, and here you have honored me with a visit first.\" Then he asked: \"And your companion's honorable surname?\" Ye Maolin said: \"This is Master Jin the Second, head manager of our troupe — he has come to engage Academician Mei to contract a performance.\" Pincai was about to inquire further when Xu Shun came down from upstairs: \"The master's instructions: since the first through fifth of the first month are already booked, the sixth or seventh will do — only no splitting of contracts.\" Jin the Second said: \"No splitting — that I dare not promise. During the first month, never mind our Lianjin troupe, even comparable companies split contracts several times every day. Master Xu, I trouble you to go up and inquire once more.\" Xu Shun said: \"I have already reported. This is the order as it came down; going up again would only meet with another refusal. Otherwise, go and consult His Excellency Wang.\" Jin the Second said: \"And the date?\" Xu Shun said: \"Best consult His Excellency Wang about everything at once — no matter whether the sixth or seventh, settle on one day and that is that.\" Ye Maolin said: \"On the way back from His Excellency Wang's you will pass through here anyway. Why not wait here while you and Master Xu go settle things, then we can all walk back together?\" Jin the Second agreed and went off with Xu Shun. Ye Maolin asked Pincai at once: \"Have you seen any opera in the capital yet?\" Pincai said he had not. Maolin then spoke at length about how splendid the costumes were, how complete the cast, how beautifully the young dan roles were dressed, how lively the theaters, how grand the private banquet performances — until Pincai was most eager. He asked after the others who had traveled on the same boat, and learned that Qinguan was staying at Cao Changqing's and had been ill for a few days but was gradually recovering.",
    "Qiguan was scheduled to make his stage debut on the tenth day of the twelfth month; the others each went with their own masters, some staying with the Lianjin troupe, others going to different companies. Pincai asked for Ye's address and learned he stayed at the Lianjin troupe's main residence in Yangliu Lane. Pincai said: \"I will come to pay my respects another day.\" Maolin said: \"I could not presume to such an honor — just come by whenever you happen to pass.\" At this point Xu Shun came back with Jin the Second: they had settled matters. The performance would be on the sixth day of the first month at the Suzhou Guild Hall; regardless of splitting or no splitting, so long as whoever was named was available in full cast, that was all that mattered. Xu Shun went up to report and received approval; the deposit was paid and they all dispersed. That evening it was Ziyu's lesson day, so he had no leisure to chat with Pincai.",
    "The next day, Pincai, remembering what Ye Maolin had said, finished his morning meal and set his mind on going to the opera. He had Si'er carry some money and changed his clothes. Since Yuanmao was in the study at his books, it was awkward to invite him, so Pincai went out on foot alone. The theater district was not far. The street had five theaters along it; the way was packed with carriages and horses, very difficult to pass. He searched all the Lianjin troupe's posted bills — none today, they were on a command performance. Pincai was displeased and had no choice but to look for another company. He heard gongs and drums nearby; walking past several storefronts, he came to a theater called the Sanyue Garden, home to the Lianzhu troupe. Going in, he saw the upper and lower galleries on both sides and the pit in the middle all packed; the performance was about to begin. A seat-tender came forward and led Pincai to a table against the wall near the stage entrance. Pincai had not brought a cushion; the seat-tender fetched one, set up the teapot and incense burner. Before long the opera began. The opening acts were nothing to speak of.",
    "Looking across at the far gallery, there was a group of men with the look of capital officials, numerous attendants standing behind them. He also saw, at the curtained doorway of the dressing room, several young dan roles with half their snow-white faces showing, smiling over at that party; before long they were clustering in groups of three and five to go offer their greetings. Watching those young dan performers from a distance — some poised and refined, some lively and quick, some mischievous — their costumes were extremely fine: sea-dragon fur, fox-leg trim, otter, tinted sable. Every face was carved like jade and powdered like snow, their manner full of floral grace and willowy charm. Now leaning against someone's side, now sitting beside someone, now resting a hand on someone's shoulder — the company laughed and chatted as though quite overwhelmed with visitors. Pincai was already completely entranced.",
    "He also noticed a man arrive at one of the vacant private boxes. This man was powerfully built, with a dark, near-black complexion, wearing a silver-needle sea-dragon fur cloak, his bearing lofty and imposing — no more than thirty years of age. Three or four household attendants followed him, all presentably dressed. He had brought his own large pewter teapot, covered teacup, water-pipe, and the like, arranged on a table before he sat down. At once a flock of young dan performers came swarming in, filling the great official's box to capacity. The man's manner was supremely arrogant — glancing about with haughty self-satisfaction, ordering his servants to buy this and that, piling up quantities of refreshments, tossing the inferior items to the floor, and cursing his servants roundly. Pincai heard his strange intonation and could not tell which region he was from.",
    "Just as he was watching them, he became aware that two more men had arrived beside him. He turned to look.",
    "One was stout; the other was dark-complexioned and lean, with a sparse beard — both richly dressed, both around thirty, with two young dan performers tagging along chatting idly. A page-boy spread out their seat cushions and they all squeezed in and sat down. Pincai listened to their conversation, then looked more carefully at the two performers with them: rather ordinary, nothing exceptional. Suddenly a young dan from the boisterous official's box glanced over in this direction; in a moment he came across, greeted the stout man and the other with a bow, and wanted to sit down. With Pincai already at the table it made five, and the stout man's girth took up a great deal of room, so there was nowhere left when this performer arrived. Since Pincai was at the same table, the performer assumed he was of the same party and gave him a small bow. Pincai, ever perceptive, quickly shifted to make room. The young dan sat down and immediately asked Pincai's surname; Pincai hastened to reply and was about to ask the performer's name in return when the stout man suddenly reached over and seized the young dan by the arm.",
    "The young dan said: \"What are you gripping so hard for?\" and turned to sit facing the stout man, resting one hand on his shoulder. The two performers who had been sitting there before rose abruptly, shook their sleeves, and walked off. Then the stout man was heard saying: \"Rongguan, why haven't I seen hide nor hair of you for two or three months? You never come into the city to see me either, you sought-after young thing. I waited for you half a day at Sixiang Hall the other day and you never came — what was the reason?\" Rongguan's face flushed; he immediately took the stout man's hand and said: \"Third Master is cross today. You sent for me at Sixiang Hall the other day — I had every intention of coming, but I truly could not find the time. And by then it had grown late; once you enter the city you cannot leave again. Staying in your study is actually very pleasant — the Third Mistress is very fond of me — it is just that I cannot bear to hear Concubine Qing scolding the boys, beating the maidservants, smashing this and throwing that, and then fighting with Concubine Bai, leaving you to mediate on two fronts at once. Then in the morning I find myself stranded in the study while you hide away and will not come out.\"",
    "Before Rongguan had finished speaking, the stout man was laughing so hard his eyes were squeezed entirely shut; he pinched Rongguan's lips and scolded affectionately: \"You little chatterbox. That only happened the once — it is not as if we are always fighting.\" Pincai, listening, found this sharp and delightful. He looked more closely at Rongguan's appearance: thoroughly charming, no more than fifteen or sixteen years of age, a melon-seed-shaped face, beautifully arched brows dark as ink, beautiful eyes with a flowing gaze, dimples on both cheeks, a small gold ring in one ear, his dress magnificent, his fragrance enveloping. Rongguan gave the stout man a knowing look and said: \"Third Master, you must feel wronged — I hear you have been going to the Quanfu troupe regularly and spent three thousand cash buying out Xiaofu's indenture. Just look at Xiaofu there in the opposite gallery — and he is not even coming over.\" The stout man said: \"What nonsense — I have barely set eyes on Xiaofu once or twice; who says I bought out his indenture? You are always making things up.\" Rongguan said: \"It is not I who made it up — others say so.\" Rongguan then turned to the other man: \"This great lord does not care for Kunqu opera, does he? He prefers high-pitched variety acts.\" The man said: \"It is not that I do not like it — I simply do not understand it, cannot make out what they are singing. High-pitched opera has more flavor to it; or else the clapper-opera style — that at least you can follow clearly enough.\" Pincai listened to this while also watching the stage.",
    "The third piece was Nanpu — a very familiar text. He tapped the beat twice on the bench with his foot, then poured a cup of tea and held it in one hand, sipping slowly. Just at that moment the stout man wanted to get up and move about; he put a hand on Rongguan's shoulder to steady himself, Rongguan swayed, collided with Pincai's arm, the teacup tilted, and Pincai's robe was soaked with a large wet patch. The stout man and Rongguan were both mortified and apologized; Pincai, rather embarrassed himself, smiled and said: \"It does not matter at all — it will dry in a moment.\" So saying, he wiped it with his handkerchief.",
    "He watched the opera a while longer. Then he saw a hunched old man with a large tumor on his neck shaped like a gray sack, making his way through the crowd carrying a small yellow-lacquered wooden tray piled with jade objects and various colorful items, murmuring softly: \"Buy some jade pieces — have a look at the jade pieces.\" He worked his way close to Pincai and held out a yellow snuff bottle: \"Buy a snuff bottle, sir.\" Pincai, seeing the bottle's color was rather fine, took it and looked it over, then asked the price. The jade seller said: \"This amber bottle is an antique, sir — if you want it, just take it. For others it is twelve taels of silver, not a cash less. For you, ten taels will do.\" Pincai had assumed the bottle was worth a few hundred cash at most; upon hearing this price he quickly returned it. The jade seller would not take it back: \"Since Your Excellency asked the price, you must make a counter-offer. Look — this bottle is old, with a wide chamber, warm in the hand yet not heavy; it suits you very well. You really must make an offer.\" Pincai, with no choice, said casually: \"Two taels of silver.\" The jade seller took the bottle back, said it was far too little — one could not even buy a fake one for that. After a pause he said: \"Very well. Today is the first sale of the day — if Your Excellency is genuinely interested, call it six taels.\" Pincai shook his head: \"No, thank you.\" The jade seller sighed: \"Business is hard these days; the southern gentlemen are all shrewd. Six taels for this amber bottle — very well, take it. I will rely on Your Excellency's future patronage.\" So saying, he pushed the bottle back toward Pincai again. Pincai had brought no silver with him; having been asked ten taels and offered two, he had assumed the man certainly would not sell — but now that his counter-offer was accepted, he could not very well back out, and was left staring blankly at the stage, ignoring the man, his face now red.",
    "The jade seller was, of course, an old hand at trickery; recognizing at once that this was a newcomer from the south fresh to the capital, he made bold to press harder: \"I have been selling jade for more than forty years and been to dozens of theaters, and I have never once seen anyone make a counter-offer and then say they did not want it after all. Your Excellency need not scrimp on two taels — do not be like this.\" He pressed close to Pincai and gripped the bottle firmly. Pincai had no choice but to say directly: \"Today I truly have no silver on me. Come tomorrow with the bottle and I will pay you.\" The jade seller naturally refused to believe this: \"No silver, Your Excellency? Then use a cash voucher.\" Pincai said: \"I have no vouchers either.\" The jade seller said: \"Then I will follow Your Excellency home to collect.\" Pincai said: \"I live far away.\" The jade seller acted as though he had not heard a word, still gripping the bottle and pressing close to Pincai. Just then on stage a new piece began; a young dan performer had barely made his entrance when someone in the audience shouted \"Bravo!\" — and at once dozens of voices joined in simultaneously from every level of the gallery, like a fire alarm. Pincai started in fright; his body lurched, knocking the jade seller's hand, and with a crash the pine-resin snuff bottle smashed into several pieces. Pincai was startled and stood bewildered. The jade seller, unhurried and composed, slowly collected the shards and placed them before Pincai: \"This gentleman insists on losing his temper — does not want it whole, wants it broken. Well then, let us be friendly about it: the whole one was six taels; the broken one comes to six large cash — twelve jing-cash.\" Pincai grew angry: \"You are most unreasonable. You said two taels just now — why do you want six taels now? Are you not trying to extort me?\" The spectators nearby all took Pincai's side.",
    "Pincai was about to lose his temper when the stout man reached across and grabbed the jade seller by the arm, pointing at him: \"Old Wang, none of that.\" Pincai quickly acknowledged him; the stout man, genuinely angry, added: \"Old Wang, do not try to muddle your way through this. A pine-resin bottle is not worth a hundred cash — and you tried to get two taels for it. Now it is broken and you want six taels? You see a southerner who does not understand your bamboozling tricks and you go right ahead and bamboozle him. Not while I, surnamed Fu, am sitting here, you will not.\" At the sight of him the jade seller dared not be insolent: \"Third Master, however you say it, so be it.\" The stout man ordered his attendant to give the man four hundred cash. The jade seller still tried to argue; the other man said: \"Third Master Fu always takes care of you — if it comes to such a trifle as this, what do you mean by carrying on like this? And it is on behalf of a friend — next time when you have good jade pieces to offer, they will give you more business; that is enough, is it not?\" Rongguan chimed in: \"This old fellow is such a nuisance — bent over, carrying that wretched tray, squeezing through the crowd day after day, without a single decent item. If anyone wants to buy, is the Degu Zhai shop not right there?\" The jade seller had no choice but to swallow his resentment; he took the broken snuff bottle and shuffled off, grumbling under his breath: \"Making a fuss, playing the friend — 'I will take care of you' indeed. Got money, can only spend it on young performers.\" He squeezed away to other parts. Pincai was inwardly most grateful; he immediately took Fu the Third's hand: \"I was clumsy — and have put Third Master to the trouble of losing his temper.\" He also clasped the other man's hand; then had Si'er take out two hundred large cash and offer it with both hands. Fu the Third laughed: \"What is this?\" He took it and passed it to Pincai's Si'er: \"Consider it received — you take it.\" Si'er dared not accept; Pincai smiled: \"I absolutely could not ask Third Master to spend his money — please do keep it.\" He passed the money to Fu the Third's attendant; Fu the Third took it and tossed it on the table: \"You are too prim! What does a little money matter — going back and forth and you still cannot settle it.\" Pincai had Si'er take it and told him to thank Fu the Third with a bow. Pincai had already heard people address him as Fu the Third; naturally his surname was Fu. He then asked the other man's name — surnamed Gui, given name Fen, currently a seventh-rank minor official in one of the Boards. This Third Master Fu's full name was Fu Lun — a degree-holder by hereditary privilege of the second rank, currently serving as a secretary in the Board of Revenue. He introduced himself to each in turn.",
    "Fu and Gui in turn asked Pincai's surname, and where he was from, and what post he was currently serving. Pincai said: \"I am from Jiangning Prefecture, have only just arrived in the capital, and have not yet sought any post. At present I am a guest at the residence of my patron Academician Mei in Mingke Lane.\" Fu the Third said: \"Jiangning is a fine place. When I was little I followed my late father to Jiangning — at that time my father was serving as Provincial Treasurer of Jiangning, and I was only twelve. He was later promoted to Governor-General of Guangdong. That Academician Mei you mention in Mingke Lane — he also served as Education Commissioner in Guangdong and was on very good terms with my father. Afterward everyone returned to the capital; my father became a Vice-President of a Board and within less than a year was gone.\"",
    "\"I never studied properly — I am not fit to consort with these venerable scholars — so for several years now I have not kept in touch. I have heard that the Mei family's young master Yuge is very clever, and fine-looking too, sixteen or seventeen years of age now — has he married?\" Pincai answered each question in turn and exchanged pleasantries with Master Gui. He had already formed the impression that Fu the Third was a warm-hearted man, full of feeling and generosity; Master Gui, on the other hand, was cautious and circumspect, proper and law-abiding in his ways. The three chatted at their ease for quite a while. Rongguan had gone back over to the opposite gallery to talk with the dark-faced man.",
    "He also saw the jade seller squeeze his way up to the gallery, clutching some small jade pieces, working his way among the young performers and loitering about — clearly determined to sell at least one item before leaving. The great dark man was quite fed up with him and barked a dismissal. Still the jade seller would not go, apparently having something further to say. The dark man flew into a great rage and ordered his servants to expel him. The servants, at one word, shoved and drove him out bodily. Seeing that the situation was bad, the old fellow dared not make a scene; hunched back and bent spine, he shuffled out step by step. Still having to mind the things on his tray, with a clatter and a clang he smashed several glass bottles and nozzles; he bent to pick up one thing and two more fell from the tray. Steeling himself to try one last swindle — he looked at the official's face and was frightened even before saying anything; this man was nothing like Fu the Third — and had no choice but to descend the stairs in tears, one step at a time. Down from the gallery, he went cursing his way out of the theater, while the young performers all burst out laughing, leaning out to watch until he was out of the gate before they stopped. On this side Fu the Third also applauded with satisfaction; Pincai was even more thoroughly delighted. But he still did not know who this powerful person was, and thought he would ask Rongguan when he returned. He then saw the dark man rise and, with four young performers in his train, stride out with magnificent disdain. The performers who were not taken along each went separately to find their own parties.",
    "Before long Rongguan came back and sat down. Fu the Third laughed: \"You courted him for nothing — he did not even take you along. You worked on him half a day and could not even wring a meal out of him.\" Rongguan nodded: \"Quite right, I was working on him — but when he called me, I would not go. That lord is not easy to get on with.\"",
    "Fu the Third said: \"Where is this man from? What is his surname?\" Rongguan said: \"He is from Guangdong; all I ever hear is people calling him the Great Gentleman Xi — I too have only just met him. And he has not been in the capital long himself. He treats Chunlan very well. The black fox-leg garment Chunlan has on today was taken from the Great Gentleman Xi's own back and just altered by a furrier to fit him.\" Then he leaned close to Fu the Third's ear and whispered a question. Fu the Third said: \"Why do you happen to have time today?\" Rongguan smiled broadly and, with both hands on Fu the Third's shoulders, gave him a gentle squeeze.",
    "Fu the Third, seeing that Pincai was lively and agreeable, and moreover a family friend of the Meis, said: \"Elder Brother Wei, today's opera is not worth listening to — shall we find a place for a drink?\" Pincai, perceiving that Fu the Third was a generous and open-natured man, was eager to cultivate his friendship and said: \"What a fortunate meeting today — but I must first insist on having the honor of treating.\" Fu the Third laughed: \"Agreed.\" He then reached into his boot-shaft, drew out a boot-paper case, took out a cash voucher, and handed it to his own attendant for the seat-tender — covering this gentleman's theater ticket as well. Pincai thanked him again and again. So they all came out, bringing Rongguan with them.",
    "The others had come by carriage; Pincai rode in Rongguan's carriage, while Si'er mounted the running-board and crouched at the back of the vehicle.",
    "In the carriage Pincai chatted and joked freely, charming Rongguan enormously, and praised his looks as being without equal in all the capital.",
    "Talking and laughing, they arrived at a restaurant; they went in together and chose a private booth. The waiter came to take their order; Rongguan poured the wine. From the next booth they could hear voices like orioles and swallows — quite lively. Rongguan peeked through a crack in the partition wall: it was indeed that Great Gentleman Xi, with Chunlan and three other young performers. Pincai asked Fu the Third: \"What was the late master's honored name?\"",
    "Fu the Third did not grasp the question; it was Master Gui who understood and told Fu the Third: \"He is asking the official name of your honored father.\" Fu the Third said: \"Are you asking my father's name? My father was called Fu Anshi.\" Pincai immediately stood up: \"Now it is clear — Third Master is the descendant of a great benefactor. Your honored father has already become a god in our Nanjing. Three years ago the local people jointly donated several thousand taels of silver and erected a shrine to distinguished officials, placing your honored father's memorial tablet there. This elder was beloved of the people during his lifetime; and after ascending to heaven, they say he still felt attached to the people of Nanjing. When plague, locusts, flood, or drought struck, he manifested himself regularly — every prayer was answered, the efficacy utterly remarkable; the Governor-General will likely memorialize the throne to grant him a posthumous honor. The people are grateful beyond measure and pray that the great elder's descendants shall rise to the highest offices, sealed marquises and ennobled ministers — and this too is only what is fitting. Seeing now Third Master's quality of heart and your fine manner and bearing, your future will certainly reach the first rank.\" These few words left Fu the Third so flattered he could not find words to reply.",
    "Master Gui said: \"This is quite credible. Your father served in Jiangnan for many years — rising from prefect to provincial treasurer over more than a decade — naturally he would feel attached to that region.\" Fu the Third said: \"My father was in Jiangning sixteen years, from prefect to treasurer, never leaving the province — truly he had a special bond with the people of Nanjing. I was born in the Jiangning Prefectural yamen, which is why I can say a few words in the Nanjing dialect.\" Pincai then flattered Master Gui at some length. Master Gui said: \"My career prospects are clear to see — to be promoted is hard enough, relying on selection; it will be either a subprefect or a second-class subprefect, with no other avenue.\" Pincai said: \"Surely in the future you will not stop at those ranks.\" Rongguan laughed: \"And what do you think my future holds?\" Pincai laughed: \"Your future — you will go to the Moon Palace and become an immortal.\" Fu the Third and Master Gui both laughed; Rongguan fined Pincai a cup of wine: \"How glib you are now — why could you not find your tongue when the jade seller was at you?\" Pincai laughed: \"Today I had the good fortune to meet Third Master and Master Gui; otherwise I truly would not have been able to disentangle myself from him.\" Fu the Third said: \"That sort of person respects strength and bullies weakness — the more pleasantly you speak to him, the less he will give in. Did you not see the man upstairs drive him out — smashing so many of his things — and he never dared say a word? But we do not want to play the tyrant and let a poor man suffer. In truth, four hundred cash was more than enough. That glass bottle of his was certainly not worth a hundred cash.\" Pincai praised his generosity and said that such benevolence was sure to bring rich blessings.",
    "Rongguan said: \"That Gentleman Xi's people were really rough — shoving and jostling Old Wang like that. I was afraid he would fall and smash everything in that wretched tray of his — might have been the death of him. Fortunately not too much was broken — only two glass nozzles and one glass bottle. One of the attendants was even nastier: he jabbed Old Wang in the neck right on that great gray sack of his, and Old Wang choked with a gasp, his white eyes rolling back — terrifying to see. That Gentleman Xi's temper is far too violent; if he had jabbed him to death, he would have had to answer for it.\" At this point there was suddenly a commotion from the adjacent booth; someone was heard cursing: \"Putting on airs again!\" Rongguan said quietly: \"Something is wrong — that Great Gentleman Xi has flared up again — I wonder who he is berating?\" He went to peer through a crack in the partition. On this side Pincai, Fu the Third, and Master Gui all fell quiet and listened. They heard a young performer say: \"You open your mouth and right away you are cursing someone.\" Then the man cursed again: \"I most detest people who put on airs — a different face every single day.\" They heard the performer say: \"Even granting that I put on airs, you cannot beat me to death over it.\" The man: \"I will not beat you to death — I will squeeze the life out of you.\" Then came a clang — a wine cup smashed. The man said: \"That sound is too small — let us smash something bigger.\" The performer said: \"If you like loud sounds—\" and then another crash, a large bowl broken. The man said: \"You know how to smash — cannot I smash too?\" and smashed another. The performer said: \"If you like smashing, who is stopping you?\" and proceeded one after another, ding ding dang dang, breaking several more. The man in a fury cried: \"You can smash very well, can you!\" and simply heaved the whole table over — with a crash far more impressive than all the rest. Of the three performers, one had already fled in fright; the other two were frantically mediating, calling without pause: Great Lord, Godfather, Dear Father, begging him not to be angry. The smashing performer also fled to the courtyard and burst into sobbing. The proprietor and the waiters all rushed in to pacify the situation, none daring to say a word, all wearing smiles: Great Lord this, Great Lord that.",
    "The proprietor then went to comfort the performer, laughing pleasantly: \"Why must Chunlan quarrel with the Great Lord like this? Look at this fine new black fox-leg coat — it has been splashed with grease; quickly bring some spirits to rub it clean.\" Some shop assistants brought spirits, and the proprietor carefully wiped it clean. Then he ushered Gentleman Xi into another room, brought the performer forward, and urged him to apologize. The performer kept weeping and refused to bow in apology; but seeing the proprietor bustling about so attentively, Gentleman Xi felt somewhat embarrassed and said: \"It has quite disturbed your establishment. This child grows more impossible every day.\" The proprietor, playing the peacemaker on the performer's behalf with bows and clasped hands, managed to placate Xi's anger; the performer too stopped weeping.",
    "The proprietor then gathered all three performers back inside and instructed the assistants to prepare the dishes as before, bringing the finest bowls and plates, to compose the Great Lord's anger and make peace. The proprietor also took the senior waiter to task: \"Old Three, you do not know how to serve. The sound of smashing bowls is the finest sound there is. You should have brought out only the finest porcelain — then the smashing would have been clear and crisp and would have pleased the Great Lord. This half-fine half-coarse ware makes a rather dull clunk when smashed. See how the Great Lord was going to give you fifty strings of cash — in the end he only gives you forty.\" This set all the shop assistants roaring with laughter as they swept the floor and wiped the tables. The food scattered all over the floor had already been largely consumed by four large dogs who had gotten in.",
    "The four dogs had all scrambled for food together and were now fighting each other inside the room. The shop assistants rushed in from every side with sticks and brooms to chase the dogs out, and then cleared up.",
    "And why, you may ask, did the proprietor fawn so on this man surnamed Xi? He knew that this surnamed Xi was a great Cantonese plutocrat — a young man of immense wealth who had come to the capital with over a hundred thousand taels of silver, intending to purchase a high official post. He had been in the capital for over a month.",
    "He came to this restaurant almost every day, and they had already made a full thousand strings of cash from him. A bill for this table, counting the broken bowls, would be inflated five or six times the true amount — what should be fifty strings would be billed at roughly three hundred.",
    "That surnamed Xi was most fond of drinking this cup of pleasure; even if you billed yet more, he would pay without question, never willing to come up short. He was a great southern profligate come to the capital to make himself a name and play the lavish spendthrift. At this point all anyone knew was that he was the eleventh in his family, and so they called him Xi the Eleventh. The bowl-smashing performer was none other than Chunlan, the one Rongguan had mentioned.",
    "Fu the Third, Pincai, and Master Gui had all watched from the doorway for a while before coming back in. Rongguan stuck out his tongue: \"Quite terrifying! Now that is what I call a proper spectacle.\" Fu the Third laughed: \"Such a spectacle is without interest — but what exactly started the quarrel, I wonder?\" Rongguan said: \"Gentleman Xi's vulgar temper is beyond description.\" Then Fu the Third, Pincai, and Master Gui played a round or two of finger-guessing. Evening was drawing in; the others needed to get back to the city. Master Gui tried to settle the bill first; Pincai insisted on treating; Fu the Third said: \"Neither of you need compete — let old Fu the Third take this small bill. Tomorrow you treat me; the day after, he treats. Nobody need argue.\" Everyone deferred to Fu the Third to pay. Fu and Gui then took their leave. Pincai offered his compliments, feeling genuinely pleased. Pincai also asked their addresses and said he would come to pay his respects the next day. Fu the Third said: \"I live in the East City, west side of Jinpai Tower Lane, across from the tea shop.\" He pointed at Master Gui: \"He is right next door to the tea shop, both doors sealed with the Board of Revenue's official seals. If you come tomorrow, we will be at home waiting.\"",
    "Pincai said: \"I will certainly come — and from today let us count ourselves friends. Only I am a man without rank — I can hardly aspire to your level.\" Fu the Third and Master Gui said together: \"You must be fined a drink! What do our titles matter among brothers — so long as you do not find us too rough, that is all.\" Fu the Third gave Rongguan eight strings of cash and the page-attendant two strings. Rongguan thanked him for the gift, said his farewells to Master Gui and Pincai, and left first.",
    "By now the sun had sunk low in the west; Fu and Gui were in a hurry to get back to the city. Pincai saw them into their carriage, then walked slowly home with Si'er. When they arrived home the lamps were already lit; Ziyu and Yuanmao were both in the study at their evening lessons. Pincai changed his clothes, stepped into his slippers, drank several cups of tea, and sat a while.",
    "After a short while Ziyu and Yuanmao came out and went together to Pincai's room.",
    "Pincai had taken off the wallet from his waist and tucked one hand inside his lapel, leaving the other sleeve to swing freely, and was pacing back and forth in circles around the room. When he saw Ziyu and Yuanmao come in, he broke into a grin. Yuanmao said: \"What has kept you until this hour?\" He peered at Pincai and added: \"Reeking of wine — surely Ye Maolin invited you? Did you see any of those young people?\" Pincai said: \"I did not go to find Ye Maolin — instead I watched the Lianzhu troupe's opera. That company has some fifty or sixty young performers, all very fine-looking. I ran into an acquaintance — the son of the former Jiangning Provincial Treasurer, also connected to us by family friendship. He invited me to dinner and called a young performer — one of the finer sort.\" Ziyu said: \"Elder Brother, the other day you said that Qinguan had a difficult temperament and was given to weeping — what sort of temperament is that?\" Pincai said: \"Qinguan's temperament is something rare. When he was born into this world, I expect the King of Hell put a piece of crystal in his heart — hard and cold, not a shred of mercy or tenderness in it. As for speaking to him of feeling — there is no point. I fell in love with his looks and pursued him like a slave, fawning on him endlessly — not only could I not coax a single smile from him, but on several occasions I made him cry; what manner of temperament can one say this is? To sum it up: in his eyes there is simply no one who is worthy.\" Ziyu thought to himself: \"If his temperament is truly like this, then he must be a figure of the very highest order — perfect in every way.\" He fell into a reverie. Then second thoughts came: \"In this sea of ordinary people, with their common ears and vulgar eyes, all flattering and ingratiating — this pure and self-respecting beautiful person must encounter cold contempt at every turn. Unless a few upright gentlemen join forces to support and nurture him, not letting scheming and base types lay hands on him, there would be no way to see this one — whose voice rings clear as metal, as unblemished and self-contained as ice — truly come into his own. If such a rare figure could emerge from that world — it would be something ancient and modern alike have rarely seen.\" As Ziyu's thoughts reached this point, his heart seemed like a willow catkin falling, carried off by the wind, drifting and swaying toward Qinguan. Suddenly Li Yuanmao threw open the vestibule door and declared:",
    "\"Something terrible has happened!\" As to what happened next, listen to the following chapter for the explanation."
  ],
  4: [
    "To return to our story: Ziyu was brooding over the state of Qinguan's heart when he heard Yuanmao open the vestibule door and cry: \"Something terrible has happened!\" This gave Ziyu and the others quite a start. \"Why are you making such a fuss?\" Yuanmao said: \"Look at the ground — already covered a layer deep, and with flakes as large as cotton bolls coming down, a night of this and we'll have more than a foot.\" Ziyu and Pincai went to the door to look; sure enough, snowflakes were drifting and swirling down. Ziyu said: \"This winter solstice snow is the finest kind. All winter long the wind has been dry; now that it snows at last, it is thanks to our speaking of Qinguan — we have moved Heaven to harmony, and auspicious signs appear on every side.\" Pincai said: \"If it snows all night, tomorrow we may go out to admire it.\" Yun'er had already brought out cloaks and wind-hoods; he helped Ziyu put them on and led him inside.",
    "That night a full five inches of snow fell, and by daybreak sharp gusts of the north wind came in waves — cold beyond measure.",
    "The snow had just stopped. It was truly a world of jade and glass, the heavens and earth carved in white — a scene of surpassing beauty. Master Li Xingquan had risen early, braved the cold, developed a dizzy head and cough, and gone back to bed, feeling unsettled; he told Ziyu and the others not to study. Being himself well versed in pharmacology, he had his page-boy fetch several doses of dispersing medicine, took them, covered his head, and slept. Ziyu instructed the two page-boys to attend carefully outside the study, then went himself to a small three-room studio named the Twenty-Four-Qin Study — its plaque bearing the hand of his grandfather, the late Duke Wenmu. With nothing to do, Ziyu took out Xie Huilian's Ode on Snow and began to read.",
    "When he reached the lines \"The white crane loses its freshness, the silver pheasant its pallor\" — he paused to admire the ancients' skill at rendering scenes in words. Just then the sky darkened again; snow began to drift down once more, and the snow on the rooftops and branches was blown by the wind like pear blossoms scattering in confusion. He at once told Yun'er to instruct the kitchen to prepare extra dishes, and invited the young gentlemen Wei and Li to come admire the snow. Before long a table of fine food was brought over; Pincai and Yuanmao came to enjoy the scene together.",
    "Ziyu could not drink wine, but made a show of accompanying the others. He again turned to Pincai to ask after Qinguan; seeing how deeply Ziyu's mind was engaged, Pincai shifted his approach and spoke of Qinguan's bearing and temperament entirely in terms of praise, leaving Ziyu all the more ardently admiring. He thought to himself: on such a snowy day, to behold one who stands like a jade branch amid ice blossoms — how different from gazing at flowers on a fairy isle! Truly one could laugh at the brocade-tented banquets of the warlord's house, where fine wine and roast lamb never quite shake off the martial swagger. When the meal was done, they boiled snow to brew tea, chatted for a while, and Pincai and Yuanmao each returned to their own rooms.",
    "Suddenly Juner arrived carrying a letter, the envelope inscribed \"For the hand of Master Mei,\" with a line of smaller writing beside it. Inside were one sheet of note-paper and four sheets of verse-paper. Recognizing Zhongqing's hand, he asked Juner who had brought it. Juner said: \"It was sent by Young Master Yan's personal attendant.\" Ziyu said: \"Ask him to wait a moment.\" He opened it and read: the note paper read: \"Yesterday Yong'an and I sat together in the empty room. Only when jade cups grew heavy with cold did we know the six-pointed flowers had begun to fly; only when the silver candle-light guttered did we see the snow's full radiance. Ice mountains piling upon ice mountains, ranged like mica folding screens; pagoda upon pagoda lit from within, gleaming like glass lanterns. Beauties arranging themselves for play, toying with jade cats; arhats piled and assembled, tossing balls at lions. At dusk we chose rhymes, fighting in white verse and setting topics; ashamed at the poverty of our jewelled lines, we offer these bricks to invite jade in return. Respectfully presented for your keen judgment; we await your pearled reply. To my worthy younger brother Yuxiang. Yong'an sends his regards as well. Written in haste by Jiantan.\"",
    "Ziyu read it and said: \"What a beautifully wrought letter!\" He then turned to the verse sheets, which bore the title Eight Verses on the Snow Window.",
    "Snow Mountain: / This peak has truly come flying here — / a lotus of white jade blooms wide open. / Wearing clogs, how pleasant to chant amid the courtyard catkins; / riding a donkey, how hard to find the plum atop the ridge. / Many times I have looked: it is not green though it drips, / though it stays long, how could it be the ash of apocalypse? / In the deep night of cloud and rain, the cold has frozen solid — / how could the Goddess of Gaotang descend from her terrace? // Snow Pagoda: / The flower-scattering figure enters the hall of Brahma King; / all the solemn adornments are the work of the great craftsman. / At its four corners it sometimes blocks the sun; / at its seven levels there is nowhere wind does not startle. / In the moon the relic jewel — how brilliant its light! / On the water the floating image — how empty its color! / Borne on inspiration, if one were allowed to climb the topmost peak, / one would wish to inscribe one's name and question the blue vault above. // Snow Screen: / Last night Liang Garden announced the return of spring; / jade tables and pearl curtains compete in freshness and novelty. / Mica would do well to screen a flowery censor-official; / crystal ought to be bestowed on the tiger-guarding lady. / Without moving the silver candles the light grows cold; / paint the golden geese and still the dream is not real. / Strange — the entertainers are all garbed in white mourning; / if the minister steps near, he ought to take offense. // Snow Lantern: / How many times have I chanted 'wick and flame' in verse; / tonight the lamp burns like the nine-flower pagoda of Jiuhua. / When silk glows bright, why turn toward the wall? / Who is the family that reads with no lamp? / In the clear cold, three candles have already burned out; / sleeping in their light one still sees the six-petalled flowers. / Remember that the Lantern Festival approaches; / fluttering moths and bare willows — do not vie in their boasting. — First draft by Yong'an Wang Xun. // Ziyu read it and said: \"Splendid poems. Of these four, Snow Pagoda must rank first, Snow Screen second, Snow Mountain next, and Snow Lantern last. Now to see Jiantan's poems:\"",
    "Snow Lion: / Uncannily taking shape as a long-haired creature — / the Bai Ze called by name, claiming lordship by chance. / Riding the air, can it truly leap beyond the seas? / Driven by the wind, it can only roar along the eastern river. / A golden throne high-set is not hard to make brilliant; / clad in red trees and new finery — I fear the workmanship falls short. / If the Recluse of Longqiu were to see it, / he would surely cast aside his staff and speak of emptiness again. // Ziyu thought: The topic of Snow Lion was not easy to handle; yet look how he uses his allusions with effortless ease, finely suited to the subject — only a master's hand could manage this. He read on:",
    "Snow Cat: / We play go at random, pillowed on two dressing-cases; / the jade-like creature crouches by the carved eaves. / Coaxed away — how could fish threaded on willow bring it back? / Led off — it is best lured by rice wrapped in salt. / Resembling a tiger's head — there truly was an original; / but those mouse-like things only bask in others' warmth. / Today the red of peony has all flown away — / cold-eyed, no need to add a single thread. // Ziyu said: \"This one is even better; the third couplet is delightfully pointed.\" He read further — the next topics were Snow Arhat and Snow Beauty. Ziyu reflected that these two topics were even more barren and still than the preceding six, and difficult to get one's brush around. He found:",
    "Snow Arhat: / Who at dawn opened the gate of Chan? / Gautama faces the wall, his staff-ring returned. / Deliverance — the mind is like still water; / wandering freely — the intention settles on Cold Mountain. / Turning sutras: in the misty dimness, palm-leaf texts; / forming a society: lotus flowers arise in an instant. / This very body is the same as a phantom image — / do not sigh and shake your head at the stubbornness of stone. // Snow Beauty: / Jade bones, fine and flawless, without a single flaw — / is it she, in the end? Or is it not she? / A spring heart already like floss clinging to mud; / my face should be like flowers blooming in the rain. / In the deep of night, pondering — it has become flowing water; / in a former life, its flavor I recall as brewed tea. / Where now is the pearl-selling maidservant who attended her? / Leaning against the bamboo without a word, the sun slopes once more. — Jiantan Zhongqing, final draft. // Ziyu read through to the end, softly intoning the verses several times. He felt that of Zhongqing's four poems, Snow Lion was gilded and richly patterned; Snow Cat was jade-carved and finely chiselled; Snow Arhat exhaled a clean fragrance, like a courtyard full of lotus; Snow Beauty was deft in both strokes at once, graceful and free as jade camellias — surpassing Wang Xun's. He thought he would compose eight matching poems in the same rhymes, but feared they could not equal the seamless completeness of the originals. Better to choose four new topics and avoid the same grooves. Those eight topics of theirs all conceived from the end backward, turning vacancy into substance, defining the host through the guests. He would instead conceive from a moment before the snow had fallen — and simply use four empty words joined to the character for snow as his topics. He thought: before the snow falls, when heavy clouds mass and a misty indistinctness prevails, the feeling of impending snow is already there. He would make Snow Feeling his first topic. When snowflakes begin to drift, indistinct and shadowy, Snow Shadow emerges — that would be his second. When the snow first begins to fall, the granules pattering and rustling, it has a sound — Snow Sound would be his third. Once snow has fully fallen, all is a brilliant expanse of white — that must be Snow Color, his fourth topic. Novel and original — and with that he set to composing. He had just completed two when Yuanmao and Pincai came in and saw him; Ziyu therefore invited them to compose a few verses as well. Yuanmao said:",
    "\"With a single empty character appended to the word 'snow' as my topic, I simply cannot manage it. All I can do is write a plain snow poem.\" Pincai said: \"Even a plain snow poem — making it rhyme properly is hard work. I can only manage a quatrain.\" Yuanmao said: \"Seven-character lines are too unwieldy; all I know is how to write a five-character regulated poem.\" Ziyu said: \"Either will do perfectly well.\" They each went off to rack their brains.",
    "Before long, Ziyu had completed all four of his poems and written them out on a sheet of cold-gold notepaper. He wrote a reply letter as well, and was just about to seal it when Pincai came over smiling, carrying a sheet of verse:",
    "\"It has not come out well — please help me correct it.\" Ziyu took it and looked: the topic was On Snow, and the poem read:",
    "\"Swirling toward the plum tips, petal by petal, slanting; / moths and powdered butterflies fill all the heavens and earth. / Clearly these are immortal products from the Jade Terrace above — / commanding alone the foremost flower of the human world.\" // Ziyu said in surprise: \"I had no idea you had such skill. You must have put in a great deal of work on poetry.\" Pincai said: \"Where would I find the time for that? I just remembered a few arias and patched them together.\" Ziyu said: \"What arias?\" Pincai said: \"The lines about swirling toward the plum tips, and moths and powdered butterflies, are from the Treading the Snow sequence in River-Sky Snow. \" Ziyu said: \"And the last two lines?\" Pincai said: \"The third line is padded out, and the final line borrows from the Occupying Alone aria in the drama The Flower Queen — I just commandeered it and used it as though it were a classical song.\" Ziyu said: \"You have managed to patch it together without any visible seam, which is no mean feat.\" By this time Yuanmao had also finished; he came with it written out neatly and properly. Ziyu looked it over — it was rather difficult to follow — but could only say in praise: \"Very polished and well-balanced. Why not write both of them out and send them over so the others can have a look?\" Yuanmao, hearing Ziyu's praise, was sure it must be very good indeed, and said: \"Yes, let us invite their instruction.\" It was Pincai alone who knew his own worth, and quickly said: \"Mine had better not go — it would only make a spectacle of itself.\" Ziyu said: \"What does it matter? I will write them out for you.\" He copied them onto a separate sheet of paper, and added two more lines at the end of his reply letter. He sealed the whole thing, and sent Yun'er to go with the attendant.",
    "On the other side, Zhongqing received the reply note and read it together with Wang Xun. It read: \"Your letter arrived like a drift of cloud; the words fell like fragrant snow. The lotus-lantern gutters in the Buddha-pagoda's delicate glow; the kingfisher screen is cold, as one traces the fairy mountain's dim silhouette. White ground, and the golden body of an arhat manifests; a form robed in white comes — jade bones of a beauty, a cat dozing by the chess game beside her. New dew to wash the hands, ancient snow to cleanse the heart; the bright moon comes of itself; the melodies of the bright spring find few to echo them. My seven-character verses, ashamed before the jade and pearls that preceded them; these four vulgar stanzas, abashed that they cannot repay the琼瑶 they have received. I write this in haste to acknowledge; regard it with a smile.\"",
    "To Jiantan and Yong'an, both brothers, for their joint perusal. Ziyu, with clasped hands. Attached are four rough compositions of mine, and one seven-character quatrain and one five-character regulated poem; please kindly correct them.",
    "Zhongqing and the others then looked at Ziyu's poem titles: Snow Feeling, Snow Shadow, Snow Sound, Snow Color. Zhongqing said to Wang Xun: \"These four topics are entirely abstract — even harder to get a brush around than ours. Yuxiang is sure to have produced something fine.\" With that they looked at the poems; they read:",
    "Snow Feeling: / Three thousand worlds gaze, brimming and full — / one knows there are jade flowers a-brewing, a-gathering. / Before becoming flower it first cuts water into shapes; / already, cloud-like, it is about to take wing and fly. // Zhongqing said: \"The opening couplet builds fine momentum before the topic; the second couplet carves out the character for 'feeling' — truly a stroke of divine transformation.\" He read on:",
    "People on earth await the planting of a flawless jade wall; / beyond the heavens a sleepless city is about to open wide. / Where is it now — the jade tower frozen solid? / The assembled immortals, imagining — rank on rank at Penglai. // Snow Shadow: Six-petalled, dimly drifting, the craft of embellishment complete; / beyond the jade balustrade, a delicate tracery is written. / Dim and low it mirrors the water, rippling with empty whiteness; / vaguely perched in the dust, it sways with soft redness. / Flying into plum blossoms — its trace grows faint; / dancing back among willow catkins — its color is all void. / In the clear cold it matches a dream of the Jade Pool — / the jade-tree branches glowing plainly in the moon. // Wang Xun applauded after every line. Zhongqing said: \"This one has summoned the very soul of the topic.\" He read on:",
    "Snow Sound: / In the cold void, jade and jasper scatter; / entering the night, one burns incense to console the loneliness. / On the path the pellets gather, rustling first, collecting sleet; / at the window they are blown in a whisper, riding the gusting wind. / Threading through pine trees — in the stillness I sense pearls ricocheting apart; / sifting through bamboo — lightly, aptly, fine flakes drift. / Waiting until at dawn the clearing scene opens wide — / the dripping of the cold water-clock has nearly worn away its mark. // Snow Color: / Who has been dazzled by that silver sea of jade radiance? / Alone at the summit of the Mountain of Assembled Jade he gazes outward. / The plantain leaf, without intent, somehow touched by green; / the pear-blossom cloud, lost in a dream, ends up piled in yellow. / Richly the pearly dew floats — three parts brilliant; / faintly it borrows from ice-plum — one thread of fragrance. / Dazzling the eyes, this pellucid emptiness is hard to examine closely — / white sands and pale moon — both fade into endless haze. // When they had finished reading, Zhongqing struck the table in admiration, and he and Wang Xun chanted the poems aloud several times. Zhongqing said:",
    "\"These poems surpass all of ours.\" They then looked at Pincai's quatrain. Wang Xun said: \"This one is also quite good — but what made Yuxiang compose this extra one on his own?\" Zhongqing said: \"This one is passable, but it is certainly not Yuxiang's work.\" They then looked at Yuanmao's five-character regulated poem; the opening couplet read: \"In the sky, vermillion clouds spread; / my thoughts come — rain and snow fill to overflowing.\" Wang Xun said: \"What do those two words 'my thoughts come' mean?\" Zhongqing suddenly burst into laughter: \"Read on.\" Wang Xun looked at the second couplet: \"White people, both eyes draw near; / long horses, four hooves grow light.\" He pondered: \"'Horse hooves grow light' — I suppose this uses the image of light horse-hooves when snow has thawed.",
    "But why add the character for 'long'? And the first line is so profoundly obscure I simply cannot decipher it.\"",
    "He looked at the third couplet: \"Burrowing mayflies resemble — / digging out hollow lions, made complete.\" Wang Xun said: \"These two lines are very strange indeed — how do they come into play? The first line probably uses the Book of Songs — since there is the character for snow in 'linen garments white as snow,' the 'burrowing mayfly' passage gets dragged in. And this 'digging out hollow lions' — what allusion is buried there?\" Zhongqing said: \"It is simply saying that the snow-sculpted lion has been hollowed out, that is all.\" They read the closing couplet: \"Going out, one presents world-treasures; / six auspicious signs — the great steps are made smooth.\" Wang Xun said: \"Is such flattery really called for? This poem must be that old Wei's work. Seeing those slick and pat turns of phrase, naturally this sort of joke would come out.\" Zhongqing said: \"Not so. I look at old Wei and, though he is no conventional scholar, he seems a clever man — he would not be this inept. I suspect the seven-character quatrain is his, and this one must be the fine composition of that Young Brother Li — a poem very like the man.\" Wang Xun said: \"Young Brother Li should not have produced this; looking at him, so proper and literary, he still seems to have some scholarly spirit about him.\" Zhongqing said: \"Precisely because he has scholarly spirit, he lacks poetic spirit.\" Wang Xun said: \"Yuxiang asks us to comment on them — shall we or not?\" Zhongqing said: \"You might as well give them a comment.\" Wang Xun said: \"Why should I make enemies?\" Zhongqing said: \"Let me begin by marking Pincai's quatrain with a full circle.\" He wrote a critical note: Captures the spirit of Heaven's sport with jade.",
    "For the first two couplets of Yuanmao's poem he drew single circles; for the last four lines he drew full circles. His critical note read: Couplets are polished and well-matched; classical allusions are dissolved into the new composition; fully worthy of carrying on the tradition of Yuan and Wei. Wang Xun used a needle to pin Ziyu's poems inside a translucent gauze cabinet, then read Zhongqing's comments and laughed: \"The comments are well done — only slightly too barbed.\" Zhongqing said: \"What a pity the day is not long; and this snow will not hold — otherwise we could go and chat with Yuxiang. \" Wang Xun said: \"Let us go tomorrow! If we went now there would be no time to talk properly.\" That day it snowed on for another full day and night, accumulating to about a foot's depth. The next morning it cleared; one blast of the north wind and the whole world was frozen solid as a jade box, dazzling and bright. After breakfast Zhongqing and Wang Xun rode together in one carriage, their two attendants on horseback, and came to call on Ziyu. Halfway there they met another carriage coming toward them; both parties' attendants dismounted.",
    "Wang Xun looked and saw it was Sun Sizhui. The two carriages drew up face to face; Wang Xun asked: \"Where are you headed?\" Sizhui said: \"Owing to the fact that my father and his wife have been at cross purposes — consuming and obliterating, with blood nearly flowing in rivers — a physician surnamed Wang has been treating man with man's own means to eradicate the old taint; looking askance at the situation, he says there is no injury. Now that the illness is somewhat better, one cannot but soothe and bring them around.\" Wang Xun smiled and said: \"I will come by when I return.\" Sizhui agreed and hurried away. Zhongqing said: \"This gentleman deploys his literary style in every conceivable context — truly absurd and laughable. This 'worm-eaten Thousand Character Classic' style is fit to be his name in life and his posthumous title in death; I doubt there is a second person in the world who resembles him in this.\" Wang Xun laughed: \"As I see it, I fear that when it comes time for him to perform his conjugal duties he will still have to compose a couplet or two for the occasion.\"",
    "One does feel sorry for that sister-in-law of ours — though not especially beautiful, she is dignified and chaste, silent and unsmiling. Having married this sort of man — truly she will harbor regret for the rest of her life.\" Zhongqing laughed: \"Perhaps he has one virtue that makes up for it — one never knows.\" Talking and laughing all the way, they arrived at the Mei residence.",
    "The gatekeeper announced them; Ziyu came out to welcome them inside, and said: \"The two brothers have written excellent poems — my admiration is boundless. My own rough scribbles are inevitably a case of a minor shaman meeting a greater one.\" Zhongqing said: \"What my brother and the others have done — how can it compare with your fine compositions, which repay repeated murmured recitation? Refined and fitting in every respect.\" Wang Xun said: \"What I love most are these two poems — Snow Feeling and Snow Color — fresh and vigorous, combining the virtues of Geng Jing and Bao Zhao at once.\" Ziyu said: \"Jiantan's four poems breathe ice and snow throughout, with pearls and jade in hand. The opening lines of Snow Mountain and Snow Pagoda arrive with the force of open sky — especially transcendent. As for Jiantan's finest individual couplets — 'but those mouse-like things only bask in others' warmth,' and 'in the deep of night, pondering — it has become flowing water' — the depth of feeling, the care of expression, a single-minded ardor going forward: as Dongpo put it, one who does not eat the food of this human world — surely work destined to endure.\" Zhongqing said: \"One borrows from the scene to give expression to feeling on a whim — how lightly you say the word 'endure.'\" Wang Xun said: \"That seven-character quatrain and that five-character regulated poem — whose hand are they?\" Ziyu smiled: \"Have you not tried to guess?\" Wang Xun then reported what had been said the day before; Ziyu said: \"Jiantan's eye is as sharp as ever. Have you added your comments?\" Wang Xun took the poems from his sleeve; Ziyu read the comment on the five-character regulated poem but could not make out what the allusion meant — who were Yuan and Wei?",
    "Wang Xun then also told him about the Sun brothers; Ziyu laughed, and had someone summon Pincai and Yuanmao to come out. Everyone met. Ziyu returned each person's poems and said: \"These assessments were made by Elder Brother Yan — he was most complimentary.\" Pincai read the comment and thought to himself: \"This Yan Zhongqing is truly versed in everything ancient and modern — even the opera tunes I borrowed were spotted by him.\" He then went and thanked Zhongqing. Zhongqing said: \"Brother Wei's poetic style is quite fine — both sound and rhythm are excellent; you must compose frequently, as though you have an aria perpetually on your lips.\" Pincai said: \"I have no foundation to speak of, and have neglected it for these several years — what can I call a poem at this point? So long as the tonal pattern is not violated, that is all.\" Ziyu said to Zhongqing: \"Brother Pincai's poem is not too far off the mark.\" Zhongqing nodded. Yuanmao, meanwhile, pressed the circled couplets and the critical note up close to his face, reading them over and over again for quite some time; then he put the verse sheet on the tea table, folded it twice with both hands, undid the buttons of his fur coat, and tucked it inside his lapel. Wang Xun said: \"Elder Brother Li, you are carrying a great deal more, aren't you.\" Li Yuanmao, thinking he was remarking on the moth-holes in his fur coat, answered without thinking: \"The moth-holes are still manageable. Coming by the water route, it was shut away in the hold of the boat and absorbed the moisture — got a bit moth-eaten as a result. I have been wearing it through this one winter; next year I will have to have it seen to.\" Everyone heard this and had no idea what he was talking about. Pincai, realizing he had misheard, said: \"Elder Brother Wang is saying you have written a great many poems — not referring to your fur coat.\" Everyone then understood; seeing Yuanmao's face flush deep red, unable to say a word, they all had to suppress their laughter. Zhongqing asked: \"In your composition, 'long horses' and 'white people' — I imagine these use Mencius; but the three characters 'both eyes draw near' — is there a source for this?\" Yuanmao gave Zhongqing two long looks and said: \"I never rely on sources.",
    "I have seen in the poems of the ancients that they sometimes write themselves into the poem — it was that intention.\" Wang Xun suddenly understood. After more idle conversation, Zhongqing and Wang Xun said their farewells; Ziyu and the others escorted them to the door. Zhongqing said: \"Why not come out with us to see the snow scenery?\" Yuanmao, hearing this, was quite willing to go. Ziyu said: \"The teacher has not fully recovered today — we must stay home to attend to him. We will accompany you another time.\" Yuanmao stuck out his lip but said nothing. Zhongqing and the others bid farewell and departed; Ziyu saw them out the front gate, came back inside, and chatted with Pincai and Yuanmao for a while about the poems, then suddenly again brought up Qinguan. Seeing that Pincai had developed a certain intent, he quietly threw out a hint: \"Another day, why not steal a moment to come with me and make Qinguan's acquaintance?\" Yuanmao said: \"Let us go tomorrow — I shall just say I am going to see friends who came down the same route.\" He pointed at Ziyu: \"And you say you are going to the Wang family to return a call. Once we are out of these two confining doors, what is there to fear?\" Ziyu laughed: \"In a few days' time.\" But let us leave this side of the story for now.",
    "To return to Zhongqing and Wang Xun: they walked out of South Small Street to the Low Hollow to take in the view. All was a vast expanse of white; fields and paths were indistinguishable. Far off they could see Xu Ziyun's Garden of Ease, with its jadeite trees rising in uneven lines, mists and mountain vapors swirling and gathering, layer upon layer of gleaming multi-storied buildings, and the faint outline of high pavilions touching the clouds. They gazed for a while, then saw a carriage coming toward them from ahead. The person perched on the running-board spotted them first and immediately jumped down; then a young performer stepped down from the carriage as well. Zhongqing and the others quickly urged him not to bother; the young performer then leaned out of the carriage and settled himself — carved and powdered like jade, gilded and ornamented — it was none other than Lin Chunxi, the youngest of the performers listed in the Flower Selection. Wang Xun asked: \"Where are you coming from?\" Chunxi said: \"I am coming back from the Garden of Ease. Are you going there too?\" Zhongqing said: \"We are just looking at the snow scenery, and will be turning back soon.\" Wang Xun said: \"Why do we not stop at that restaurant on Small Street and sit a while? One can also take in the distant scenery from there.\" Chunxi said: \"If you are in the mood, I will be happy to accompany you.\" Zhongqing said: \"Excellent.\" They turned their carriages about; arriving at Small Street, they found a restaurant with two facing balconies, east and west. Zhongqing and the others went up to the east balcony; though the day was cold, there was no wind up there.",
    "Zhongqing had the windows thrown open; the view extended a great distance. They ordered food and chatted idly for a while. Chunxi said: \"This month the eight of us have been holding gatherings at the Garden of Ease every three days — a Winter Solstice club. Today is the fifth meeting. At each meeting there must be one entertainment — sometimes a drinking game, sometimes a parlor game. Today Duxiang wanted us to write poems; he set the topic Ice Bed, with each person writing one seven-character regulated poem, and Su Meixiang was judged first.\" Zhongqing said: \"Do you remember his poem?\" Chunxi said: \"I only remember the middle four lines.\" He then recited:",
    "\"Oars and punts have quite become a bed most stable; / storms and waves are no different from a level road. / Who says the Blue Sea is hard to fill to fullness? / I refuse to believe that Penglai's path cannot be passed.\" // \"Everyone said his use of figures was wonderfully inspired, without a single flat line — which is why he surpassed the others.\" Wang Xun said: \"And yours?\" Chunxi said: \"Mine was not good — I cannot remember it.\" Zhongqing said: \"I imagine you came eighth.\" Chunxi laughed sheepishly: \"You guessed it on the first try.\" Wang Xun said: \"No wonder — he is only fourteen years old; if he were to study for two years, do you think he could not catch up with them?\" Chunxi said: \"I was not going to compose at all, but they absolutely insisted I do. Today none of the poems were anything remarkable; it was only that Ruixiang and I got the tonal pattern wrong — as a result Ruixiang was placed seventh and I was placed eighth. Never again shall I write such incompetent poetry. Let me study for a year and then come back and compete with them.\" Then he added: \"Two new performers have come to our company — one is called Qinguan, one is called Qiguan. Have you met them?\" Zhongqing said: \"The other day Ruixiang mentioned the two of them — but just as he was starting to say something, someone interrupted and he never finished.\" Wang Xun asked: \"What are these two like?\" Chunxi said: \"Excellent. That Qinguan is on a par with Yaoqing. That Qiguan — it is hard to say who ranks higher, him or Ruixiang. Neither has appeared on stage yet, but every day there are already three to five requests for them. The other day Duxiang saw them and praised them tremendously, immediately giving them fine gifts and having several complete new sets of costumes made for them.",
    "These two are going to make a great name for themselves. Only Qinguan's temperament is a bit cool — he is not very easy to talk to.\" Just as they were deep in conversation here, suddenly the window on the opposite west balcony opened with a sound. Zhongqing and the others looked up to see a beautiful young man, splendidly dressed — wearing a white heron-frost fur cloak, a violet sable cap on his head, a face like polished jade, lips red as if painted, his gaze bright with something of a cloud-piercing spirit, his bearing most refined, his manner extraordinary. To judge by his age, he appeared to be a little over twenty; he had four young performers in his company, and was leaning against the balcony window gazing out. Zhongqing and Wang Xun were privately astonished: looking at his appearance and bearing, he was fully a match for Yuxiang — truly a phoenix among men. From his accent, he seemed to be from Jiangning, yet there was also something of a Yangzhou intonation mixed in. Looking at the four young performers, they were none of them celebrated names or proven talent — no more than common blossoms of the flower world. Wang Xun recognized one as Rongguan; the other three he did not know, and so asked Chunxi. Chunxi said: \"The one in tinted sable is Yu Mei; the one in Japanese-sword-patterned fur is Si Xi; the one in otter is Quanfu. All three are from the Jianchun company.\" Just then the young man glanced over at this balcony once, and turned his back and sat down again. They could hear the young performers on that side chattering like orioles and swallows, with cups and counters flying about — quite lively. By comparison, the three on this side felt rather like the cold and lean poets of the Jiao and Jia school. They heard the beautiful young man say: \"I hear people say that of the theater companies, Lianjin and Lianzhu are the finest. But listening to those two companies, all the performers are old; not a single fine-looking young dan in the Kunqu roles. What circulates through the gardens is nothing but defeated soldiers and broken remnants — I truly cannot understand why people say they are good.\"",
    "Rongguan said: \"Our two Lian companies mostly do private banquet performances; the few good performers who sing Kunqu are always at banquets and rarely come to the public gardens. A refined person such as yourself — how is it that you do not appreciate Kunqu and instead prefer the clapper operas?\" The young man laughed: \"I pay attention to people, not to opera; I would rather have a vulgar opera with refined people than a refined opera with vulgar people.\" They also heard Yu Mei say: \"It is all opera-singing — why distinguish between Kunqu and clapper style? Even granting that Kunqu has finer verse, it was still composed by the ancients and not by yourselves. The clapper style is merely rougher; in terms of conveying feeling and spirit it is fundamentally the same. What is most laughable is those people who talk only of Kunqu and do not like erhuang. In your two Lian companies, once those few people leave the company and stop performing, there will be no one left who can hold things together — and audiences will likely dwindle. The company might even disband.\" Si Xi said: \"As I see it, it is all the same — erhuang is opera, Kunqu is opera; learn whichever you learn and sing whichever you sing.\" Rongguan laughed: \"Enough — let us not talk about opera; let us drink.\" They could then be heard playing finger-guessing games and singing drinking songs for a while. Then the young man spoke again: \"When I listen to opera I do not listen to the words; I listen entirely to the tonal melody. It is not that I am unaware of Kunqu's moral dignity and musical elegance — but listening to it is like reading Song dynasty poetry: the rhythms are gentle and peaceful, yet the feeling lacks excitement and urgency. When I listen to the sounds of the zheng zither, pipa lute, and string instruments — with their dense and rapid notes and rhythms — there is a fullness and richness of feeling left over, capable of stirring a man to ardor and exaltation, to a vigor of all four limbs and an outpouring of all seven emotions. Even the clapper style, though it is certainly not orthodox music, has something of a quality of rises and falls, pauses and turns — something that moves one to contemplation, to dwell on the present and recall the past, like Ma Zhou passing through Xinfeng or Wei Su crossing the river south, with a chest full of sorrow and lament, feeling tangled and lingering — able to stir the deepest emotions of the lone traveler and the wandering scholar. People say that the sound of the huqin fiddle is the most licentious. But when I hear it I am overcome by sorrow, and it often moves me to tears — just as Dongpo in his Ode on the Cave Flute said: 'like weeping, like complaining, like sobbing, like beseeching' — like the grief of a banished official ten thousand li from home, like the weeping of a widow in a lone boat on the river, each note entering the very depths of the heart. I cannot understand why people call it a licentious sound. Or is it that my ears differ from other ears, that my feeling is out of accord with ordinary feeling? As for the sounds of plucked strings and drums — I hear them and my heart and breath grow calm; there is nothing that moves me. That is how it is when I listen — I wonder whether others find it the same?\" The four young performers could none of them answer.",
    "Zhongqing said quietly to Wang Xun: \"This man's views are partial, yet he has his own private understanding — his unwillingness to follow the common herd is already evident. Moreover his chest must hold much accumulated resentment, which is why he dislikes the peaceful and prefers the stirring. String music is inherently sorrowful; his saying that the huqin is not licentious — now that is indeed a view that breaks from convention, one that no one has ever perceived before. I look at this man and he seems precisely our sort — certainly not a mediocre person. Someday I would like to seek him out.\" Wang Xun said: \"From what he has said and his manner and bearing, one can already form a general impression.\" Just then the young man asked one of the restaurant's people for brush and inkstone, and on the plastered wall he wrote a few lines; then, with his four young performers, he descended the stairs and left. Zhongqing and the others also stopped drinking, told the attendants to settle the bill, took Chunxi with them, and came over to the west balcony. There, in flowing strokes of dense ink, in a fine bold cursive hand, he had written a ci poem to the tune Langtuasha: // The red sun has already sloped to the west — / I smile, watching cloud and rosy haze. / The jade dragon's scales have scattered and spread across all the sky. / I yearn for the spring wind to come ten thousand li / and blow away every jade flower. // Do not boast of worldly things — / no thought of them is without error. / The immortal of Penglai reaches down for the cloud carriage. / Drunk, I ask the guest dwelling in the Great Luo Heaven above — / the colored phoenix — whose home does it grace? // Zhongqing and Wang Xun read it and both nodded in admiration. Chunxi said: \"This ci poem seems written by an immortal — there is a transcendent, unearthly quality to it.\" Zhongqing said: \"This man is one of pure and unconstrained spirit, free and unrestrained — yet the ones he appreciates are that company of young performers. Truly baffling.\" They then looked at the signature: \"Xiangfan — written drunk.\" They could not tell his family name or given name; so they called the restaurant keeper and asked whether he recognized the man. The keeper answered: \"This lord came here for the first time today; when they settled the bill, his second attendant paid in cash, and we never asked his name or address.\" Zhongqing said: \"This ci poem is very fine — the brush of a man of exceptional talent. It illuminates your humble establishment; by all means preserve it and do not scrub it off.\" The keeper agreed and went off. Chunxi said: \"As for this man's background, Rongguan ought to know — when I see him I will ask, and then we will know what manner of person this is.\" The three then talked a while more, descended the stairs, and each went their separate ways. As to what happened next, listen to the following chapter for the explanation."
  ],
  5: [
    "The previous chapter told of Lin Chunxi and Zhongqing discussing the poetry-gathering at the Yiyuan garden. Now let us set the stage for that garden: there was a prince among young noblemen, a leader of literary men, by the name of Xu Ziyun, courtesy name Duxiang, a native of Shanyin County in Zhejiang. Speaking of his family lineage, it was truly among the foremost of the age — seven generations of official distinction, grandfathers and grandsons serving as prime ministers, fathers and sons as Ministers of State (shangshu), brothers as governors-general. Of Xu Ziyun's own line: his father, named Zhen, rose through the Hanlin Academy and now served as Grand Secretary and Governor-General of Guangdong; his elder brother, Zirong, also a Hanlin graduate, had served as a censor and been appointed Inspector of the Huai-Yang Circuit.",
    "His mother had gone to Guangdong to accompany his father's posting; only Ziyun himself remained in the capital. This Ziyun was cultivated and elegant in appearance, distinguished and peerless in character, magnanimous beyond measure, and deeply versed in the classics and histories. He was twenty-five years of age, holding a sinecure post as a departmental secretary through hereditary privilege, and at twenty-two had also passed the provincial examinations as a juren. His wife, née Yuan, was twenty-three years old — daughter of Yuan Hao, the current Governor of Yunnan. She was surpassingly beautiful, supremely virtuous, and possessed literary gifts of the orchid and cassia. She and Ziyun were perfectly matched — a talented man and a beauty — loving and mutually respectful, as lute paired with jade se. They already had one son and one daughter.",
    "Though Ziyun lived amid luxury and splendor, he had no trace of dissolution or extravagance. He disliked the constraints of official dress and decorum, preferring the pleasures of hills and valleys as his enjoyment. Though still in his twenties, he already possessed the refined taste for music of Xie An of Dongshan, and the pleasures of lute and wine-cups of Kong Rong of Beihai. In front of his residence lay a large open plot of land — five or six li in circumference — with naturally rolling hills, natural hollows, ancient trees, and gnarled pines. It had originally been a ruined garden belonging to some former family.",
    "Ziyun purchased this plot and expanded it, buying up the nearby residences at generous prices.",
    "He had a close friend from Xiangtan County in southern Hunan — Xiao Cixian, courtesy name Jingyi, thirty-two years of age, a renowned man of letters who had come to the capital to sit for examinations as a distinguished tribute student. But he had no desire for trifling titles and no ambition to advance. In astronomy and geography, in the writings of all the philosophers and the hundred schools — there was nothing he had not mastered. He and Ziyun had sworn brotherhood, and over the course of three or four years spent enormous effort supervising the construction of the Yiyuan garden. The result was a place of driving clouds and shifting mountains — soaring towers and layered pavilions, secluded recesses and winding depths — all in one sweep of scenic beauty. In the magnificence of its flowers, plants, and scenic walks it surpassed all others in the capital, comprising twenty-four scenic areas with over four hundred rooms. Great hills linked together; streams wound in curving courses — its wonders were beyond description. Ziyun's reputation and connections were vast, and scholars from all directions gathered like stars and massing clouds.",
    "But in character, Ziyun was noble and sincere, responsive to every request and sparing no effort. He was especially fond of selecting friends — not by power or status, but by virtue and principle. Though every day his seats were full of guests and wine cups never empty, only a few true kindred spirits were his daily companions; the rest were merely received with proper courtesy, their wishes accommodated as best as possible. The eight famous dan performers from Shi Nanxiang's Flower Register came and went daily, and Ziyun treasured them all, but singled out Yuan Baozhu for particular affection. His feeling of love and appreciation for beautiful performers was quite different from others': he regarded these fine young opera players as he would rare treasures, fine birds, and celebrated flowers — with only a caring and admiring heart, with no thought of vulgar intimacy. And so these famous performers all forgot the distances of social rank with him, treating him as a kind father or caring mother — able to speak openly of anything, free to follow their hearts. Xiao Cixian was even more pure and detached, taking no pleasure in worldly amusements.",
    "Thus these two men not only sharpened each other in virtue and letters, but in temperament and spirit had no barriers between them whatsoever.",
    "One day, at a theatrical gathering, Ziyun encountered two newly arrived performers, Qin Guan and Qi Guan, and was greatly impressed — marveling that such talent was unprecedented, and seeing that they were perfectly suited to stand alongside the eight famous dan performers. This kindled his desire to cultivate their acquaintance. He asked Yuan Baozhu to bring them to the garden another day. Seeing that their clothing was not yet fine enough, he immediately had several new outfits made overnight and presented them as gifts. The two performers were naturally grateful. But this Qin Guan was different from ordinary people. Let us first briefly describe his background.",
    "Qin Guan's surname was Du. His father was known as Du Qinshi — Master Du the Qin-player — who made his living by crafting and performing on the qin zither. The sons of gentry throughout Jiangsu vied to invite him to give lessons, and so everyone called him Du Qinshi. When this son was born, he was named after the qin, and called Qin Guan.",
    "Qin Guan bore auspicious markings on his palm and was clever from earliest childhood; his parents loved him as their most precious treasure. When he reached ten years of age, Du Qinshi was suddenly humiliated and beaten by a powerful lord, smashed his qin in rage and grief, and died. His mother, a year later, also fell ill with sorrow and died. Left without support, the orphaned Qin Guan was taken in by a clan uncle. When he was thirteen, this uncle too died. His widowed aunt could not maintain her chastity and remarried, so she sold Qin Guan into a theater troupe. Just then Ye Maolin happened to see him and bought him out of the troupe, taking him along to the capital. Qin Guan had begun to learn characters at six, was exceptionally gifted, and could memorize anything upon a single reading. By thirteen he had read many books — poetry collections, ci-lyrics, miscellaneous essays, tales and popular fiction — and understood them all clearly. His heart aspired to lofty things and his nature was one of great purity; he had the ambition of a mountain pheasant dancing before a mirror, a vermilion phoenix perching on its proper plane-tree. When he was forced into the theater troupe, he had tried several times to hang himself, but failed each time to die, and so he used the troupe's disdain for him as a means to preserve his integrity. When Ye Maolin brought him to the capital and treated him with fresh care and regard as a rare treasure, who would not have found peace? Yet he had another worry: having climbed out of the bottom of a well, he feared he had only fallen into the bottom of the sea. He worried that the coral net would be hard to find, that bright pearls might be wasted in darkness, that his jade — like the gem of Bian He — might go forever unrecognized, that drawing his sword might only bring suspicion. So he was always melancholy. The night before entering the capital, he had a dream: he dreamed of a place where ten thousand plum trees bloomed, their fragrant snow filling the air like a sea. He was strolling in delight when suddenly his body sank into a pit.",
    "Just as the earth was about to reach the top of his head — in desperate peril — suddenly a beautiful youth appeared, his face as luminous as jade and divine. With one hand he lifted Qin Guan out. Qin Guan was overwhelmed with gratitude and was about to bow in thanks, when the young man turned gracefully and walked into the plum grove, vanishing. Qin Guan went in to search and found a large plum fruit growing on a plum tree; looking closely, he saw it was made of jade. Then he awoke. The next day upon entering the city, jostled in a traffic jam on the road, he saw Ziyu — who was the very person who had saved him in the dream. He was greatly astonished and could only stare at him dazedly for a while. But they were strangers on the road; he did not know the young man's name or address, and had no way to make inquiries. Whenever he attended theatrical gatherings or visited the theaters, he looked everywhere, but did not see him again. When he later met Xu Ziyun, who greatly appreciated him and gave him many clothes and objects, he became uncertain and wary. Knowing Ziyun was a nobleman of great wealth and rank, he feared such a man must carry the haughty airs of the powerful, and was very reluctant to approach him. But unable to escape his master's command, he had no choice but to go and pay his respects.",
    "That day, Qi Guan had caught a cold and could not get up, so Yuan Baozhu came first to Qin Guan's lodgings. Baozhu's appearance had already been described in the Flower Register — his nature gentle and yielding, his looks like a maiden's. He too was attracted to Qin Guan, whose appearance resembled his own; though they had just met, it was as if they were long-standing friends. After several heart-to-heart conversations, Qin Guan had also come to value Baozhu's character, seeing him as someone who kept his own purity and self-respect. Baozhu then described Ziyun's fine qualities in detail, and Qin Guan felt somewhat reassured. The two of them rode in a carriage together — Qin Guan in front, Baozhu behind. By happy coincidence, as they reached the South Small Street intersection, they met Ziyu returning from Shi Nanxiang's, in a carriage with two horses, coming directly toward them. Ziyu had not drawn his curtain; Qin Guan had drawn his, but through the glass window had already seen clearly.",
    "Unable to help himself, he raised the curtain, revealing a face of unparalleled beauty. Ziyu caught a glimpse and recognized the very Qin Guan he had encountered before — the one Pincai had told him about, the one he had been thinking of day and night. Joy spread across his face and he smiled. He glimpsed Qin Guan's clear bright eyes and slightly parted crimson lips; then the curtain fell, and in an instant both carriages had sped away from each other like wind and lightning. Ziyu saw that the carriage today was finer and more beautiful than before, and thought admiringly to himself: \"Truly, a night-luminous gem cannot be concealed — a bright moon shines of its own accord. Naturally he has met a true connoisseur. But I wonder what sort of person that connoisseur is.\" He also thought: \"Pincai said his temper is peculiar and he is extremely proud — he must be one who chooses whom to follow, and would certainly never drift with the current to seek a momentary meeting.\" On Qin Guan's side, he was thinking: \"This young nobleman — his elegance is in his bones, his beauty in his spirit; his warmth and gentleness overflow naturally. He must be a righteous man of genuine feeling, with not a trace of selfish or improper intent. In my dream he lifted me from the mud — surely in the future he is the one meant to raise me up. Otherwise, why would I meet him so soon after dreaming of him? But in the dream, I saw him walk beneath the plum trees and disappear, and then I saw a jade plum — what does that signify?\" He kept turning this over in his mind, lost in reverie.",
    "Not long after, they entered the Yiyuan garden. Baozhu inquired and learned that Ziyun was that day at the Begonia Spring Court. This Begonia Spring Court had open terraces and winding covered galleries, intimate chambers and secluded rooms, all connecting in a continuous chain of over twenty bays. Baozhu led them inside to a suite of three rooms, where Ziyun and Cixian were sitting around a charcoal brazier drinking together. Seeing the two arrivals, both welcomed them with warm, smiling faces.",
    "Qin Guan timidly went forward, made two bows of greeting, expressed his thanks, and stood with bowed head. Ziyun and Cixian saw that today, in fine and colorful dress, his appearance was even more beautiful than before. But they saw his tentative, bashful, nervous bearing — feelings of tender regard arose in them unbidden — and they invited him to sit. Qin Guan sat close beside Baozhu. Ziyun smiled warmly and said: \"When we first met the other day, we could not speak at length. Please tell me in detail about your background, your family, and how you came to enter the theater troupe.\" When asked about his background, Qin Guan's accumulated sorrow was stirred; without realizing it, his face flushed rose-red and his eyes brimmed with pearly tears. He steadied himself, but could not refuse to answer, so adopting the Mandarin pronunciation and setting aside his Suzhou accent, he recounted his family history. When he came to his parents' deaths, his uncle's care, his uncle's death, and his aunt's remarriage and abandonment of him — his voice became like a gentle breeze playing a flute, softly lamenting. Ziyun and Cixian were quite moved and earnestly consoled him.",
    "They then asked what operas he had studied, which pieces he knew, and Qin Guan answered them. Cixian said:",
    "\"In what way does he resemble a performer at all? What a pity that such spiritual luminosity as heaven and earth has produced, instead of being bestowed upon a fragrant boudoir, is given to the singing stage — wearing a cap instead of hairpins, shoes instead of skirts. It is truly a lamentable matter.\" Ziyun said: \"He and Yaoqing truly could be called a matched pair soaring under auspicious clouds, racing a thousand li abreast. If their hats and shoes were exchanged for hairpins and skirts, I fear even the Two Beauties east of the River could scarcely be compared with them. It must be that the Creator intends to allow a few such extraordinary figures to emerge from this world, washing away all the commonplace and vulgar habits of former times — who can say for certain?\" He then said to Qin Guan: \"Here is different from other places — you need not feel like a stranger. Follow Yaoqing in everything; whatever he does, you do likewise. If you wish to know what we are like, simply ask him in detail.",
    "\"Here Yaoqing is not treated as an ordinary performer. All forms of address are different from the outside world — everyone addresses each other by courtesy names, and formal salutations are not required. If you are inclined, please come here often in your free time — there is no need to stand on ceremony, for ceremony creates distance.\" Qin Guan could only agree. He looked at the two men again — both of extraordinary bearing, serene and approachable — and he knew they were not ordinary men. Cixian said to Ziyun: \"What you have said is exactly right. At this moment he still does not know what our temperament is like; he may suppose that wealth and rank must bring with them proud and extravagant airs — not knowing that we most dislike such things. As for your natural gifts, nothing need be said. But a person's elegant demeanor and refined bearing all come from books; without having read and understood the principles of learning, one's speech and bearing will inevitably fall short of true refinement. Have you studied any books?\" Before Qin Guan could answer, Baozhu laughed and said:",
    "\"His mind is far stronger than ours! If we were tested right now, I'm afraid even Meixiang could not surpass him.\" Ziyun was even more pleased and asked Qin Guan: \"Tell me honestly — have you studied books?\" Qin Guan replied: \"I have studied for five or six years.\" Cixian asked: \"What have you read?\" Qin Guan replied: \"Besides the Four Books, I read through the Shi Lei Fu — A Rhapsody on Classes of Things — and two volumes of Tang poetry.\" Ziyun said: \"That is quite enough. Can you compose poetry?\" Qin Guan said: \"I cannot.\" Baozhu said: \"That is only because he has never been taught — once he begins studying he will certainly be able to do it at once. The other day he told me about the operas — which pieces are fine, which are not — and he explained every point without error. With such innate gifts, how could he fail to learn?\" Qin Guan lowered his head and said nothing. Ziyun said:",
    "\"His name is not suitable. Jingyi, please give him a new character — let us change this word 'guan.' And give him a courtesy name as well.\" Cixian thought for a moment and said: \"What about changing it to Qin Yan — Lute-Words — with the courtesy name Yunong — Jade Youth — would that do?\" Ziyun said: \"Very good. The two characters 'Qin Yan' are both fresh and elegant; and 'Yunong' as a courtesy name suits the person perfectly.\" Baozhu told Qin Guan to express his thanks; Qin Guan rose and made two bows. Cixian said: \"We have already said all this — why are you bowing again?\" Ziyun said: \"Let us establish a rule: on festival days and occasions for congratulations you may bow; in all other ordinary meetings it is entirely dispensed with. The word 'Master' is forever forbidden from your lips. Address me simply as Duxiang, and him as Jingyi.\" Qin Yan stood and said: \"How could I dare?\" Ziyun said: \"If you insist on refusing, it is as if we were the same as common men — that would not be honoring us but distancing yourself from us. Besides, what weight does 'Master' carry? Everyone outside, without exception, is called 'Master.' When you address others, naturally you must do the same; but here, such forms are unnecessary.\" Qin Guan still dared not agree, and Baozhu laughed: \"Since Duxiang has already given his word, just call him Duxiang.\" Qin Yan saw that Baozhu called him by his courtesy name directly, but since this was still really their first meeting, he himself felt somewhat awkward, and so he gave a small smile. Ziyun, seeing this smile — lips like cherries, teeth like strung pearls, beauty blooming on fragrant cheeks, brightness rippling in clear eyes — felt dazzled and stirred to the depths of his heart, and knew a great blossoming of joy. He ordered a servant to set out wine, and the four of them sat together at the table. During the meal, Baozhu guided and instructed Qin Yan in all manner of things. Seeing that neither Xiao nor Xu showed any teasing or flirtatious words or intentions, that their speech was refined and their bearing proper — truly men one could approach and trust — Qin Yan gradually relaxed, his spirit settling and his breath becoming easy. Baozhu also went through several drinking games with him and told him about many famous scholars and men of letters of the day, and how he should conduct himself when he met them. Qin Yan listened to everything attentively. In his heart, he also thought again of the young nobleman he had glimpsed in the carriage — wondering whether Baozhu knew him, whether Duxiang was acquainted with him; he still did not know the man's name, and had no way to inquire. That day they lingered in the Yiyuan for half a day; after the wine was done, Ziyun and Cixian led him through a tour of the garden. The rooms and furnishings, antiques and curios were all things he had never seen in his life, and he took pleasure in looking at each one carefully. Ziyun gave him many more gifts and told him to come and ask for anything he desired. Qin Yan expressed his thanks and took his leave. From this point on, he came often to the Yiyuan together with Baozhu and the other famous performers; after a few visits he felt quite at home there. But let us set this aside for now.",
    "Now let us return to Ziyu, who had again encountered Qin Guan that day and was in excellent spirits. Returning home, he immediately sought out Pincai to tell him what had happened. Pincai was somewhat pleased as well, and proceeded to describe to Ziyu the scene on the road. It turned out that when Pincai and Ye Maolin had been traveling together and reached Jining Prefecture, all the performers had gone ashore, but he found Qin Guan alone in the boat, in tears. He asked about his troubles, but Qin Guan would answer nothing. When Pincai suggested he might not want to go onstage for fear of disgracing his parents' memory, Qin Guan gave him a single glance. Pincai then tried to press further — not pausing to consider whether he was overstepping — and took out a handkerchief to wipe Qin Guan's tears. Just as he was about to do so, Qin Guan snatched it away with one hand and threw it into the river, then covered his face and wept. Pincai had resented him for this ever since. Now seeing Ziyu's delight, he carelessly let this episode slip out. Ziyu felt only deeper admiration and respect — admiring the chastity and reserve, the inviolable dignity. From respect grew love, from love grew longing; these two feelings turned like a waterwheel in his heart.",
    "And so it is that among all the treasures in the world, true beauty is the foremost — if it is genuine beauty, there is no one in the world who does not love it. Ziyu's experience at the theater the other day had been such that Baozhu seemed to have made some impression on him; his heart ought to have been forever unmoved. Yet who would have known that after only two encounters with Qin Guan, it was like a flash of lightning or a spark of flint — passing in an instant without a trace — and yet his heart was now constantly thinking of him? How much more so for others, whose self-restraint was not as great as Ziyu's, and who could be with beautiful people day and night — naturally their love and longing would be even more intense, transforming tempered steel into pliant gold thread. Pincai knew that he and Qin Guan had no karmic affinity and could get nowhere; though he admired Qin Guan's looks, he genuinely resented his temperament. Now seeing Ziyu's infatuation, viewing the inside situation as an outsider, he merely offered encouraging words and a flattering manner; but he himself was not particularly invested. Shortly after, Ziyu went out, and Pincai set the whole matter aside.",
    "One day the weather turned clear and mild, the snow had melted, and Pincai thought of Fu Sanziye and wished to go into the city to visit him. He had his boy Sier hire a carriage and set off toward the Eastern City. Coming from the opposite direction was a crowd of horses and carriages rushing forward like the wind: first a mounted outrider, then a pair of lead horses, then a carriage with its side-curtain hanging open. Pincai leaned out to look and caught — quick as a lightning flash — a glimpse of a beautiful young man with fine brows and bright eyes, his bearing magnificent as a divinity: like the morning sun glorious among clouds and mist, like a crane in flight over the Isle of Penglai — clearly about twenty years of age.",
    "He wore an embroidered python-robe with sable cloak, a magnificent official hat, and court shoes. Behind him came twenty or thirty mounted attendants, all in freshly made uniforms of matching color. Then followed over ten cloth-curtained heated carriages, inside which sat some powder-and-jade-carved children, also resembling small dan performers. Behind these came four or five large carts laden with trunks, clothing bundles, tea stoves, wine boxes, portable kitchens, and other such articles. The drivers were all dressed in short silk jackets, brocade trousers, damask stockings, and satin shoes — striding along in magnificent, vigorous fashion. The procession passed for quite some time. Pincai thought: \"What sort of person is this, with such a grand retinue?\" Just then he heard his driver say: \"Sir, do you know who this person is?\" Pincai replied: \"I have no idea — what person is this, so wealthy?\" The driver said: \"This is the magnificent young nobleman of Jinchun Garden. There is a saying in the capital that everyone repeats: 'In the city, one star; beyond the walls, one cloud. Two great young noblemen, more grand than all the world.' As for this young nobleman's family background, I don't know the full story — I only know his father is a duke and currently serves as Commander-General of the Western Frontier.",
    "\"His residence takes up three or four li in circumference. They have a Master of Stables called Master Lu, and I once heard him say they have a hundred-odd horses and seventy or eighty large mules — would you say that's wealthy?\" Pincai asked: \"What is his surname?\" The driver replied: \"His surname is Hua — people all call him Young Master Hua.\" Pincai asked: \"The men on horseback must be his household servants; but those children in the carriages, who look like opera performers — what are they?\" The driver said:",
    "\"They are xiangong — opera boys.\"",
    "\"His household has its own theatrical troupe. Whenever someone outside hosts him for wine and theater, he always brings his own troupe along to sing a couple of pieces. As for outside performers — if he likes one, he simply has him bought out for a high price and brought home. I hear his current personal attendant is also a xiangong, bought last year for eight thousand taels of silver. Can you imagine such a style — who could match him?\" Pincai said: \"Truly wealthy. But do his parents not manage him at all, letting him carry on this way?\" The driver said: \"His parents are ten thousand li away! And besides, his household has silver without end — spending a little more makes no difference. Today he must be going to a banquet, which is why he has brought his troupe.\" As they talked, they had already entered the Eastern City. At Jinpai Lou they found the address — across from a tea shop — and Pincai had the carriage stop at the large gate. He had Sier deliver his calling card and waited inside the carriage. He saw two official plaques posted on the wall: one for a former Vice-Minister of War, one for the South Jiangsu Division of the Board of Revenue. A man in the gatehouse took the card inside; after a short while, he returned and said: \"Please come in.\" Pincai descended from the carriage and followed the gatekeeper inside. Through the inner gate was a courtyard, and beyond it a passageway.",
    "Through the passageway was the main hall, with six side rooms on either side. Fu San was already standing at the eave of the main room to welcome him. Pincai hurried forward and clasped his hand. Fu San led him past the main hall to two small study rooms where they sat, exchanging polite pleasantries. Pincai said: \"The snowfall delayed me these days — otherwise I would have come to pay my respects the other day. Staying at home has been so dull; I have thought of Third Master every moment.\" Fu San said: \"Likewise, likewise.\" This study was near the inner quarters, separated by only one courtyard. Pincai glanced at the room's furnishings: the center was divided by a floor-to-ceiling carved wood screen of ice-crystal pattern. On one side was a raised kang-bed with four small landscape screens and an alarm clock on the kang table. On the other side stood a square table and several chairs, a large copper coal stove in the center; on the wall above hung a pair of calligraphy couplets on silk, and beside them a delicate Western-style painting. The kang was covered in royal blue satin cushions. Just then a personal attendant came in, wearing a plain silk padded jacket and a fur hat pulled low over his eyebrows — the back of his hair-knot visible beneath — carrying a tea tray. He first served tea to Pincai. Pincai said: \"Please give my respects to the Mistress.\" Before the attendant could reply, Fu San said: \"Today your sister-in-law is not at home — she has gone to her parents'. You must stay for dinner today and we can have a real conversation.\" Pincai readily agreed and asked: \"Is Gui Daye coming today?\" Fu San said: \"That's uncertain. Yesterday he mentioned he had business to attend to — he needed to go to Jinchun Garden to ask Young Master Hua to put in a word for him — I expect he has already gone.\" Hearing the name of Young Master Hua of Jinchun Garden, Pincai asked about him at once, recounting the scene on the road and what the cart driver had said. Fu San replied: \"What does a cart driver know! This Young Master Hua — his given name is Guangsu, courtesy name Xingbei. His father is a hereditary first-class duke, currently serving as Commander-General of the Western Frontier. Because of the great merits of his ancestors, when he was eighteen and entered official service, he was immediately awarded the rank of a second-class idle grand minister. This year he is twenty-one, accomplished in horsemanship and archery, and quite capable in literary affairs as well — his intelligence goes without saying, even those young performers could not match it. The only fault is that he spends too lavishly; but in truth he is not arrogant or haughty at all. People who see his imposing retinue do not dare approach him. His family wealth is beyond reckoning. A few years back he married the daughter of Marquis Jingbian and Vice-Minister Su, whose dowry alone came to a million taels. His wife is truly beautiful as a heavenly immortal — her looks may be the finest in all the realm — and she is supremely virtuous too, accomplished in calligraphy, painting, chess, and music. She also has ten maidservants called the Ten Pearl Maids, all bearing names with the character 'pearl,' all as beautiful as flowers and jade, literate, and able to sing and play instruments. In his residence, Young Master Hua truly passes every day in delight. He is the foremost noble young man in the city, the supreme wealthy patron. I am distantly connected to him — his wife's maternal great-uncle is a relation of my own sister-in-law.",
    "\"This year I hosted him for one meal and spent over a thousand strings of cash. He does not go to restaurants or theaters; when he comes to someone's home, this crowd of twenty or thirty horses and twenty or thirty people — if the house is small there is simply no room to accommodate them all. Besides, his tastes are demanding: he wants both quality and abundance. His own appetite may be limited, but when hosting him you must devise special preparations — you need thirty or forty excellent dishes, twenty or thirty varieties of fruit, and more than ten kinds of fine wine. When his spirits rise, one day is not sufficient — he stays until midnight. Naturally there must be a theatrical troupe — and he brings his own as well.",
    "\"Getting performers to serve as wine companions is also difficult — one moment he thinks of this one, the next moment that one, and you must have all the famous ones present in attendance. Even having performers is not enough: there must also be ensemble troupes, eight-beat drum performers, acrobats, and all manner of miscellaneous entertainments — all must be arranged beforehand to cater to his fancy. When pleased, his tips are several gold ingots. But if anything goes wrong, or someone's face displeases him, he rewards them all the same — and then has them flogged thirty or forty lashes and driven out. Can you imagine such standards? He does not care whether people find it tolerable or not — he simply follows his own whims. That day I was somewhat careless: I love the shibo xian variety performance, and there is a young performer named Xiaoshun'er who is the absolute master of that genre. I thought surely he would like him too. When Xiaoshun'er came out in full costume and walked on, Young Master Hua's face instantly turned furious; he let out a cold laugh, and his attendants at once drove Xiaoshun'er off — leaving me extremely mortified. After that he said not a word, gave not a smile; barely ten dishes had been served when he grew eager to leave, and no amount of urging could detain him. I had to let him go. It was generous of him to save my face and not have the whip used on anyone. For that brief visit, counting the main courses, the middle courses, and the late courses, plus all the various tips and incidental costs — it came to over a thousand strings. Not only did I fail to please him — he went away declaring me vulgar and intolerable. Since then I have never dared invite him again. He has a personal attendant named Lin Shanji who genuinely cost eight thousand taels of silver.\" Pincai nodded with a slight smile and said: \"Befriending this wealthy nobleman would indeed be no easy matter.\" Fu San said: \"Difficult indeed — unless one possesses true abilities that earn his admiration. Otherwise, however assiduously one flatters and courts him, this is precisely the sort of person who most enjoys being flattered.\" Just as they were saying this, the meal arrived — a flask of wine, four side dishes, and a hot pot. Fu San said: \"Today is quite simple — nothing worth eating.\" The two drank and chatted at ease. Then Pincai heard some women's voices from within, quite animated. After a moment it seemed as if two women had gotten into an argument, growing noisy and confused, mixed with the voices of maids and older maidservants trying to mediate, and scattered laughter.",
    "Fu San tried to ignore it, but with Pincai present he felt embarrassed, and went inside.",
    "Pincai listened quietly and could make out Fu San's voice saying \"There's a guest, there's a guest\" once or twice. The women's voices dropped slightly, trailing off in sporadic murmuring. Fu San came back out and drank a cup of wine with Pincai; then the noise inside started up again.",
    "Fu San could not sit still and ran back inside; this time the commotion was very loud, and even with Fu San there trying to suppress it, it only grew worse. They could also hear Fu San shouting: \"Have some consideration for me — this is simply not done!\" Then a woman's voice was heard, half-crying and half-shouting, her words too hurried and rapid to make out clearly from outside.",
    "Pincai had no heart for drinking, and it would have been awkward to ask questions, so he simply asked for the meal to be served. Fu San came out again; Pincai could see that his composure was quite unsettled. He took his leave and expressed thanks for the meal. Fu San saw that Pincai had already eaten and the commotion inside was still so bad; he could hardly urge him to stay, and could only say: \"Today things have been rather informal — please do not laugh at us. The moment my wife steps out of the house, the others lose all restraint and start quarreling.\" Pincai could say nothing in response, and went straight out. Fu San accompanied him to the main gate, watched until he had got into the carriage, then turned back inside.",
    "Pincai then called on Gui Daye's house; he was not at home, so Pincai left his card and departed. Riding in the carriage, Pincai reflected:",
    "\"The other day at the theater, Rong Guan mentioned that the Green Concubine and the White Concubine had come to blows — throwing this, smashing that. I took it for a joke. Today it turns out to be quite true.\" The hour was still early to return home; he left the city, dismissed the carriage, strolled past the theater gates and various other places, then made his way home.",
    "Time passed quickly; after a few days, it was already the end of the year, and the Mei household was full of festive bustle.",
    "Master Li the tutor had finished teaching for the season and went out often, gathering with fellow provincials and examination classmates for conversation and amusement. On New Year's Eve, Pincai and Yuanmao sat idly in the study, feeling very much the melancholy of guests far from home. Presently Ziyu came out and said to both of them: \"Yesterday I heard that Uncle Wang, on the day of the group-visit ceremony, will especially prepare two tables of wine to host us, and also the Sun brothers.\" Yuanmao said: \"I will not go — I am not even from the same province.\" Ziyu said: \"That does not matter. First, Uncle Wang has invited us specifically, and we will not be seated with the others; second, it is also Yong'an's wish — if you do not go, it will be awkward for everyone.\" Pincai smiled and said: \"If that is the case, that day we should be able to watch Qin Guan perform in the opera!\" Ziyu smiled and said: \"There is still something else I must attend to.\" And he went back inside. That evening, when Li Xingquan returned home, entering the gate he already saw the whole hall illuminated with lanterns in brilliant splendor. Looking toward the main hall, he saw Scholar Mei with his wife and Ziyu, surrounded by a group of servants and their wives, offering sacrificial foods before the deity images.",
    "He hurried to the study and found two pairs of red candles and four plain glass lanterns burning within. Yuanmao went forward to bow in greeting. Pincai also came to offer the New Year's salutation. Xingquan hastily returned the courtesies, then led them to pay their New Year's respects to their Teacher and Teacher's Wife. Scholar Mei stopped them from the full formality of bowing. Lady Yan immediately instructed Ziyu to go out and offer New Year's greetings to the Teacher. Scholar Mei then personally escorted Ziyu to the study; they exchanged congratulations, and wine and food were set out.",
    "Scholar Mei with great reverence filled a cup of wine for Xingquan; Xingquan kept demurring that he could not accept such an honor. Mei then made to fill cups for Pincai and Yuanmao as well; Pincai quickly took the wine cup himself, set it in place, and they all took their seats in proper order.",
    "Scholar Mei was a man of strict speech and upright conduct, and now paired with Li Xingquan, the conversation at the table was nothing but discourse on self-cultivation and moral rectitude — all words of exhortation to Ziyu. Li Yuanmao sat stiff and constrained, hardly daring to eat, in considerable discomfort. Only Pincai managed to pretend at being earnest, affecting pedantic speech to converse with them. After not too long, the banquet dissolved. Scholar Mei sat outside a while longer, speaking at length on various matters, then went inside together with Ziyu. Xingquan, Yuanmao, and the rest also retired for the night. But for what follows, please await the next chapter."
  ],
  6: [
    "As one year gives way to another, New Year's Eve passes and the next day is the first of the new year, bringing its inevitable celebrations. After two busy days, on the third day an invitation notice and three sets of visiting cards arrived from Wang Wenhui's household. The notice listed the following guests: Vice-Minister of Revenue Liu; Grand Academician Wu of the Imperial Cabinet; Hanlin Reader-in-Waiting Mei (Scholar Mei); Director of the Eastern Palace Zhuang; Left Senior Secretary Zheng; Tongzheng Commissioner Wang; Deputy Director of the Court of Imperial Entertainments Zhou; Imperial College Director Zhang; Censor Shi; Supervising Censor of the Shanxi Circuit Lu; Departmental Secretary of the Board of War Yang; Assistant Department Director of the Board of Works Sun — twelve men in all. Scholar Mei, seeing even fewer than the previous year, told a page to take two sets of cards to the study for the two young gentlemen Wei and Li.",
    "On the fifth day, Lady Yan also wished to receive guests. She invited Wang Wenhui's wife, Madam Lu, along with the young mistress of the Sun family, and two young cousins; and also invited Sun Lianggong's wife, Madam Lu, along with his eldest daughter and two young mistresses — though the eldest Sun daughter sent her excuses and did not come.",
    "The Madam Lu of the Wang household and the Madam Lu of the Sun household were first cousins. The Wang family's Madam Lu was the paternal cousin of Censor Lu Zongyuan; her own elder brother, named Lu Zongyuan, was currently serving as Judicial Commissioner of Sichuan.",
    "The Sun family's Madam Lu was the full sister of Lu Zongyuan. The Wang Madam Lu was forty-one; the Sun Madam Lu was thirty-nine. Both were second wives. Though in middle age, they were still quite youthful-looking — appearing no more than thirty — and both loved fine ornament and dress, attiring themselves like young women. Wang Wenhui's wife was graceful and slender, direct and lively in temperament, and lived in perfect accord with Wenhui. The Sun Madam Lu resembled her elder sister in appearance, but was fierce and jealous by nature. She had always somewhat looked down on Lianggong, and furthermore he had three peerless, exquisite children from his first wife, who were a constant vexation to her eyes and heart. When she had nothing better to do, she sought out Lianggong for amusement. Lianggong's first wife had been extremely plain, yet had borne him one daughter and two sons in succession. Now that he had married this beautiful woman, he treated her like a bodhisattva to be reverently attended. This Madam Lu had been coddled and pampered since childhood. Now, more than twenty years later, approaching forty, her temper had mellowed somewhat, and she treated Lianggong considerably better than before. Yet Lianggong had long since submitted to her completely in his heart; though she now showed him greater favor, he was still thoroughly deferential in return.",
    "Madam Lu had one child of her own — the young mistress who had married into the Wang family (Wang Xun's wife), named Peiqiu, who united virtue and beauty, loved like the apple of her eye. She was married off to the Wang household at eighteen. There was also the eldest daughter, whose hair had turned white — she could not be married, and this New Year she was twenty-nine. Sihui was twenty-six and Siyuan twenty-four — these two \"useless objects\" had both taken wives already. Sihui had married Miss Shen, named Yun'er, the daughter of Imperial College Director Shen Gong. She was neat, clever, and charming; upon arriving at her new home and seeing her husband, she immediately thought of ending her own life. Only the urgent persuasion of her maidservant restrained her, and she could but blame her fate. She afterward returned to her parents' home and refused to come back.",
    "The Imperial College Director was a rigidly orthodox Confucian man. He scolded his daughter at length and sent her back. Miss Shen was truly at her wit's end, for in addition to everything else, Sihui's lust was without limit — that red nose was constantly rubbing against her face, filling her with revulsion beyond endurance. In the end she had no choice but to give Sihui her personal maidservant from her dowry retinue. This maidservant was called Songer; she had feet a full eight inches long — like barn-door panels — but was an extremely flirtatious creature. Sihui had already secretly enjoyed her a few times, tried her with his instrument, found her quite a capable vessel, and came to love her as a treasure, bestowing on her virtually exclusive favor. How could Miss Shen still feel jealous? She wished they were like a pair of geckos, permanently joined together — it would at least relieve her of that burden. In her outward service to her in-laws she was quite obedient, but in private she often shed tears in secret.",
    "Siyuan had married a woman of the Ba clan, named Laifeng. Her father, Ba Tianchong, was a native of Fengyang in upper Jiangsu, of respectable and clean origin. From boyhood a soldier, handsome in bearing, skilled in archery and horsemanship, and having won military merit, by his early forties he had risen to the rank of Commander-in-Chief, and was currently stationed as coastal defender at Tianjin.",
    "This Ba girl was extremely beautiful — rosy cheeks and apricot-bright face, slender waist and tall figure, willow-leaf brows shadowed with charm, phoenix eyes at once commanding and tender. Her temperament was fiery and fierce, and she had been indulged and pampered from childhood. Alas, she was married off at only seventeen. She had imagined the son of a civil official would be a man of romantic refinement and literary grace — but upon seeing Siyuan's monkey-jawed, dog-faced countenance, paired with his stutter and halting tongue, she wept inside the bridal chamber for half a day. When evening came and Siyuan climbed into bed and attempted to undress her, she slapped him across the face. Half of Siyuan's face swelled red as a sun-ripened peach; he let out a wail like a yelping dog, raised his fists, and made to strike the Ba girl back. The Ba girl, when she saw him coming close, stood up and planted a solid punch squarely in his chest, sending Siyuan tumbling head over heels. He scrambled up and bolted for the door, where the attending matrons, servants, and maidservants all rushed to seize him and urge reconciliation from both sides at great length. The Ba girl herself had also only been acting on a moment's fury; thinking it over, she regretted having been too rash — making a scene was unseemly, and besides, her family was far away and could offer no help. She had no choice but to hold her tongue and endure. Siyuan babbled away, but the attending matron covered his mouth; they helped both of them undress, painstakingly mediated peace, waited until both had lain down, then quietly withdrew. After receiving those two blows, Siyuan was already sorry and dared not approach her again, keeping to the foot of the bed and sleeping through the night. After a few days, the Ba girl's wet nurse reasoned earnestly with her on the principles of propriety: how could a daughter of an official family strike her own husband? Even if the husband was not well-favored, it was a fate predestined for each person. The Ba girl was intelligent; she knew that what was done was done and nothing could change it, and could only weep in private. After a few more days, Siyuan saw she had calmed somewhat and thought to perform the rites of the Duke of Zhou — that is, consummate the marriage. Waiting until she was asleep, he undid her clothing. The Ba girl was inclined to refuse, but then thought a commotion would be most unbecoming, so she would simply see what this blockhead could manage. But who would have thought that this Sun Siyuan, though he disdained his elder brother in every other way, was not as accomplished as his elder brother in this one thing: at first unable to find the way in, and when he finally found it, he was already in tears, soft as wound gold thread. Sun Siyuan was both anxious and ashamed; the Ba girl was both resentful and furious. From then on, unless she was in a willing mood, she rarely permitted Siyuan to approach. So the Ba girl had been a daughter-in-law for five or six years and had still not truly experienced the joys of conjugal life. But we need not dwell on this.",
    "That day, Wenhui's wife, accompanied by two daughters and one young daughter-in-law, arrived at the Mei residence in their fragrant carriages and embroidered sedan-chairs.",
    "Lady Yan, leading a group of female servants and maidservants, came out to welcome them and ushered them into the inner hall. Though Lady Yan was past forty, she still had the bearing of an immortal, and her features resembled Ziyu's. Lady Yan found that Miss Qionghua had grown even more beautiful — as pure as freshly washed snow, as delicate as one who dines on rosy dawn-clouds, seemingly not sustained by ordinary human food. Miss Ronghua was bright and luminous, fair on the outside and graceful within. The young mistress Peiqiu of the Sun household was charming, graceful, and gentle as spring. After the two great ladies had exchanged their formal greetings, the young mistresses and the young lady bowed together in greeting to Lady Yan, and polite conversation was exchanged. Madam Lu asked after Ziyu; Lady Yan said he had gone out with his father, and Miss Qionghua felt her heart settle. Suddenly a servant announced: \"The Madam and young mistresses of the Sun family have arrived.\" Lady Yan went to welcome them. Madam Lu was a familiar acquaintance; the two young mistresses she had seen a couple of times before, but today, dressed for the occasion, they seemed even more beautiful. Lady Yan knew full well that neither had married well, and felt deep compassion in her heart. When all the greetings were done and casual conversation had begun, Wang Wenhui's wife praised Ziyu repeatedly with evident admiration. Lianggong's wife laughed and said: \"Sister, your nephew is fine indeed — but my niece is not bad either. Since you love him so dearly, why not match my niece with your nephew, just as I matched my nephew with your niece? You would be adding kinship upon kinship — and let me share in the four-way family connection, wouldn't that be agreeable?\" Lady Yan initially could not work out what she meant, but after a moment's thought she smiled and said: \"Sister, your tongue is so clever — the way you wound it about had me quite lost! We have long had this in our hearts, but feared our own child might not be worthy enough, and dared not broach the subject lest we meet a refusal. I feared my sister-in-law might not be willing to consent.\"",
    "Wang Wenhui's wife said: \"Aunt, what sort of talk is that? We are close family — there is no need for such formality. Truly, it is my children who might not be good enough for your nephew — that is the truth. Aunt must be leaving the decision to her lord husband — and how does he feel about it?\" Lady Yan said: \"My husband has long had this in his heart, and often mentions it at home. Last year when cousin came to ask us to serve as matchmaker, I was just about to speak of it, when something happened to interrupt me, and it was never said — I have kept it in mind ever since.\" Lianggong's wife, bold and blunt, said: \"Then let's settle it right here and now! In children's affairs, a mother can make the decision — must it always wait for the father?\" Lady Yan said: \"If it were some other family, I would not dare decide alone and would need to wait for his father's agreement. But as for this niece, my husband and I have discussed it many times and are of one mind. It only depends on whether my sister-in-law will honor us.\" Wang Wenhui's wife said: \"We feel exactly the same.\" Lianggong's wife said: \"Then you two in-laws exchange a bow — one word and it is settled.\" Lady Yan bowed to Wang Wenhui's wife; Wang Wenhui's wife returned the bow. Lianggong's wife was wonderfully decisive: she examined Lady Yan's hair carefully, pulled out a jade swallow hairpin, walked over to Qionghua, and pinned it in her hair. Qionghua's cheeks flushed crimson; she raised her hand in a gentle attempt to stop it. Lianggong's wife laughed: \"This is a matter of your whole life — don't be shy.\" Qionghua was so mortified she knew not where to put herself; she could not speak, could not withdraw, could not remove the hairpin. She hung her head, her bright eyes brimming with tears, on the verge of weeping from shame. Her mother and Lady Yan both smiled gently; the young mistresses all smiled too. Ronghua, seeing her younger sister in such distress, took her hand and led her outside the balustrade railing to look at the flowers, then on to browse in other rooms. All the young mistresses followed. Lianggong's wife said: \"Did I play the matchmaker well? Both of you in-laws should be grateful to me — truly a talented young man and a beautiful girl, a perfect match in every way. Nothing like those three useless ones of mine: two useless sons have already ruined two young ladies, and there's still a useless daughter at home — can she also ruin someone? Well, that need not concern us.\" Wang Wenhui's wife said: \"Are your two young mistresses getting along well?\" Lianggong's wife gave a cold laugh: \"How could they get along? Human hearts are all the same — can I take my sons' side against my daughters-in-law? I myself feel bad when I look at the situation.",
    "\"As for the first — outwardly she can still endure it. The resentment is locked away inside, and when she has nothing to do, she finds some small amusement at his expense.",
    "\"The second one's temper is even fierier than mine. Our second son is even worse than the first — mumbling and stuttering all the time, clumsy and restless, never still. I hear he often gets beaten by his wife — beaten so that the whole house rings with it and he runs from room to room; I can only pretend not to hear. She's as beautiful as a flower — how could I say she's wrong? To keep company day and night with a monkey — naturally she suffers both anger and grief. I am the most clear-sighted of women, and not the sort who shields her children's faults and thinks only her own sons are good. Only your brother-in-law could produce children as fine as these.\" This made both ladies laugh. Now let us speak of the young mistresses and Miss Qionghua, who had wandered into a quiet area with three small rooms in a suite, quite elegant and refined.",
    "Famous calligraphy and ancient paintings covered the walls; Zhou-dynasty bronze cauldrons and Shang-dynasty sacrificial vessels were displayed throughout. Inside, two small maidservants brought tea. The young mistress née Shen asked: \"Whose room is this?\" A maidservant replied: \"It is the Young Master's room.\" Shen asked: \"Is the Young Master not in?\" The maidservant replied: \"He is not here.\" The young mistresses relaxed and began to look about freely. Going into the inner room, they saw a small nanmu-wood bed with brocade curtains hung on silver hooks — quite resplendent — and a fragrance drifting over them like orchid and musk.",
    "All the young mistresses found the room refined and elegant and sat down. The young mistress née Ba had never seen Ziyu; she noticed a beautiful young man depicted in the mirror screen — a face of powder-white skin and crimson lips, his elegance and beauty dazzling to the eyes — the likes of which she had never seen in all her life. She pulled the young mistress née Sun over to look, saying: \"Sister-in-law, look at this painting — isn't it well done?\" The young mistress née Sun smiled and said: \"That is our future second brother-in-law — truly a good likeness.\" Ronghua and the young mistress née Shen both came to look at Ziyu's small portrait; only Qionghua would not approach, and went alone to the writing table. Idly opening a book, she found a leaf of flower-patterned stationery on which several seven-character quatrains had been written, entitled \"The Person in the Carriage\" — evidently verses written in longing for a beauty one had glimpsed. Looking at the closing line of the third poem, she saw it rhymed on the character qiong (琼), drawing on the name of the immortal maiden Xu Feiqi; the closing line of the fourth poem rhymed on the character hua (华), drawing on the name of the immortal maiden Ruan Linghua.",
    "Qionghua's heart gave a start. She thought: \"So this cousin of mine is so frivolous — he has taken my very name apart and embedded the characters in his rhyming lines. What if someone were to see this?\" Taking advantage of the others being occupied with looking at the portrait, she used her fingernail to scrape away those two characters, her face flushed red, and quietly withdrew.",
    "On the other side, the young mistresses also came out. The young mistress née Ba could not stop gazing at Ziyu's small portrait; as she came out she turned to look back twice more, and involuntarily exclaimed: \"Now that is truly a fine young nobleman!\"",
    "The beauties smiled. Lady Yan sent a maidservant to invite everyone to the banquet, and the beauties came out. The tables were arranged in two groups: the three great ladies at one table, the five young women at another. At table, the two Madam Lus were most entertaining in their conversation, and the young mistresses on the other side also sparkled in high spirits. Only Miss Qionghua was uneasy at heart all day, sitting at table without a word to say. In her heart she resented her aunt for having pinned Lady Yan's hairpin in her hair — she felt as though her very head now weighed a thousand catties and could not be raised.",
    "The young mistresses knew what was troubling her; though they tried various pleasantries to relieve her, she kept her head bowed and said nothing, regretting that she had come at all. The two great ladies and all the young women spent the whole day in good company, not dispersing until after the evening meal, when the first night-watch drum had already been sounded.",
    "The next day we turn to the fellowship-visit gathering at the Suzhou Guild Hall. Scholar Mei set out early in the morning. Pincai had borrowed a set of clothes from Ziyu the night before — a perfect fit in length and size. Only Yuanmao found his own clothing unsatisfactory and was in a gloomy mood; seeing Ziyu emerge in his fine official hat and beautiful garments, he felt unfavorably compared and stubbornly pulled off his outfit, put his ordinary clothes back on, and said: \"I am not going.\" Ziyu immediately sent Yun'er inside to report to the Mistress and bring out a set of his own clothing for Young Master Li. Yun'er promptly brought out a bundle. But though Ziyu and Yuanmao were about the same height, their figures differed greatly: Yuanmao had a thick neck and broad waist. Never mind anything else — the collar alone would not fasten; and when the waist was tied, the garment was three inches too short. Ziyu said: \"No good — my clothes don't fit you. Better wear our Master's.\" He sent Yun'er back inside to exchange them for Scholar Mei's clothing. Scholar Mei was very tall, and both garments were heavy fur pieces — long and wide. When Yuanmao put them on, the hems swept the floor. Pincai lifted them two or three inches, tied the waist tightly, smoothed the front and back — and produced something resembling a pigeon-breasted hunchback.",
    "Then he put on the outer lynx-fur coat, and Ziyu set a large sable fur hat on his head — a great fluffy ball that barely fit in the carriage. Ziyu and Pincai both broke into laughter. Four book-boys accompanied them; outside, two carriages were already harnessed with four horses. Ziyu took one carriage alone; Pincai and Yuanmao shared the other. They set off directly for the Suzhou Guild Hall, where carriages were already crowded everywhere.",
    "The three entered. The Mei household's servants, seeing them, came forward and said: \"Young Master Wang and Young Master Yan have been here quite some time; all the gentlemen have long since arrived.\" They were led directly to the main seats, where the opera had already begun. Among the distinguished elders in the audience, there were several Ziyu did not yet recognize; Scholar Mei pointed them out and Ziyu paid his respects to each in turn — every elder lavished him with praise. Then Pincai and Yuanmao came forward to greet Wang Wenhui. Pincai, being reasonably nimble, managed well enough; but Yuanmao was nearsighted and hampered by that awkward outfit, moving with difficulty. When he had completed his bow and rose, he inadvertently bumped Wenhui's hat and knocked it askew. Wenhui quickly straightened it; Yuanmao flushed red and tried to back away.",
    "Just then, Imperial College Director Shen — old but fondly talkative — seized Ziyu's arm. Seeing his extraordinary spiritual beauty, like a being from among the immortals, and thinking of his own daughter-in-law, he felt acutely that in the world of human affairs there were two extremes — the transformation of celestial beings into mortals and the appearance of demons and monsters. He asked what books Ziyu was currently reading and what compositions he was practicing; Ziyu answered each question in turn. As he was still young, to be praised on all sides by these venerable elders one after another made him quite embarrassed. Director Shen finally released him; Ziyu and the others took their leave and went up to the eastern upper floor, where Wang Xun and Yan Zhongqing came forward to greet them, bowing and saying: \"We have been waiting so long — how is it you've only just arrived?\" Ziyu said: \"I got up a little late today. Have Elder Brother Sun and Second Brother Sun not come yet?\" Wang Xun said: \"They should arrive any moment.\" Wang and Yan warmly received Pincai and Yuanmao. Just then, on the opposite upper floor, a group appeared: their host was Liu Wenze, son of the Right Vice-Minister. He had invited: Shi Nanxiang, son of Censor Shi; Zhang Zhongyu, nephew of Grand Academician Wu; the celebrated Suzhou scholar Gao Pin; Shen Bocai, son of Imperial College Director Shen; and Ba Lin, son of Commander-in-Chief Ba, coastal defender of Tianjin — these last two being the brothers-in-law of the Sun brothers. There was also a man native to the capital, son of the former Jiangsu county magistrate, Feng Zipei, who had not yet arrived. Of this group, Ziyu knew no one besides Nanxiang and Wenze. Liu Wenze, courtesy name Qianzhou, came from a distinguished family in Zhongzhou and had already received a second-rank hereditary position. He was the most amiable of men — generous in spirit and approachable in manner, and particularly fond of making friends; he and Xu Ziyun and Hua Xingbei were all on the closest terms of sworn friendship. Zhang Zhongyu was a Yangzhou man, handsome and quick-witted, come to the capital to pursue an alternative path to official honors, lodging at his uncle Grand Academician Wu's home. Accomplished in chess, qin, flute, and every manner of entertainment, he had purchased himself a ninth-rank position and was an entertaining figure of the social world. Gao Pin, styled Zhuoran, was a Suzhou man and a supplementary tribute student. Extraordinarily intelligent, widely read, and gifted in witty banter — every remark he made generally sent the entire company into uproar. He was connected to Director Shen by family ties, and through this knew the Sun brothers, whom he delighted in teasing and baiting. Shen Bocai was a provincial graduate already past thirty, recently selected as a county magistrate and about to depart for his post — a shrewd and capable man. As for Ba Lin, he had come from his father's station to visit his elder sister. His appearance was as handsome as his sister's; he was only twenty, accomplished in both civil and military arts. Because he and the Sun brothers did not get along, he preferred to lodge at an inn, and was on excellent terms with Liu Wenze.",
    "Wang Xun and Zhongqing now led Ziyu over and made introductions all around. As everyone was connected by examination-year fellowship or family ties, they exchanged warm expressions of mutual admiration. Liu Wenze said: \"Yong'an, when you were arranging this banquet, how could you not have informed me? Even these two guest-friends of yours — sitting together with us would have been perfectly fine. Why must you be seated separately over there?\" Wang Xun smiled: \"It was not that I specifically wanted to separate us. Yuxiang goes without saying — but these two Elder Brothers Li and Wei are also the most delightful people.",
    "\"Today I have also invited the Sun brothers — and those two are quite a different matter. Elder Brother Shen, though not intimate with them, can at least endure their presence — that's tolerable. But I genuinely feared that the moment Old Third Ba laid eyes on them, a rumpus would start.\" Everyone laughed.",
    "Ba Lin said: \"Elder Brother Wang, this is where you went wrong. Since you have three honored guests, you ought not to have invited those two disagreeable ones — it's enough to make a man unable to eat. It's only out of consideration for the skirt-hem connection, that's all.\" Everyone burst out laughing. Gao Pin said: \"Excellent! Excellent! Let us all sit together today — why should anyone be unable to eat? With the 'worm-eaten Thousand Character Classic' and the 'rhyme-and-alliteration compendium,' it is more diverting than drinking wine to the accompaniment of the Hanshu!\" Shi Nanxiang said: \"What is there to fear? Move them over! Move them over! There are many venerable elders at the main tables — Old Third Ba surely won't start anything in front of them.\" Wang Xun had no choice but to have the two tables from the other side moved over; everyone sat together. Nanxiang said to Ziyu: \"Today you will see fine opera and fine performers — then you will believe that I was not exaggerating.\" Ziyu smiled: \"You named your foremost one; I have already had the pleasure.\" Nanxiang said: \"Well? Does your appreciation hold up?\" Ziyu smiled and said nothing. Wang Xun said: \"When did you see her?\" Ziyu said: \"Don't you remember? That day when you asked me to give you something to eat and I held you up — have you really forgotten?\" Nanxiang leaned in to listen, puzzled by this remark, and was about to ask for an explanation. Wang Xun laughed: \"What an injustice! That was not Yuan Baozhu at all — that was the darkest of the dark-class performers, whose name happened also to be Bao Zhu. Yuxiang heard the name and immediately took him to be your number one. I was about to explain but got caught up in the commotion and never had the chance.\" Nanxiang laughed heartily; and Ziyu now understood it had been a different 'Baozhu,' not the Baozhu in the Flower Register.",
    "Just then the Wang household's servant announced: \"The young Sun masters have arrived.\" Sihui and his brother first paid their respects at the main tables, then came upstairs; everyone welcomed them with smiling faces. Sihui's eyes swept the room, saw the crowd, and offered a general bow to the company. When he saw Gao Pin and Shen Bocai, alarm stirred in his heart and he thought to himself: \"What bad luck today — running into these two arch-enemies.\" Siyuan, on seeing Ba Lin, also felt his heart lurch; he paid his respects to everyone, and Ba Lin made a grudging half-bow. The upper floor was arranged with four tables. Liu Wenze said: \"We're all friends here — no need to stand on ceremony; just sit wherever you like.\" Everyone, eager to be as far from the Sun brothers as possible, scrambled for their seats. Liu Wenze, Shen Bocai, Ba Lin, and Zhang Zhongyu took one table; Shi Nanxiang, Yan Zhongqing, and Gao Pin pulled Ziyu over to another; Pincai and Yuanmao took a third; and Sihui and Siyuan were left at the fourth, with Wang Xun moving between two tables to play host. Sun Sihui launched into his pedantic \"the Master says\" manner and proceeded to ask the two gentlemen Wei and Li for their names and native places. Dishes were served and wine poured. Gao Pin noticed that the pimples on Sihui's face had multiplied considerably; after a few cups, that red nose glowed like a frost-bitten chili pepper — thoroughly red and shiny.",
    "Gao Pin said to Shen Bocai with a grin: \"In all the world, what thing is both red and shiny? You may not give an elegant answer — only the most vulgar thing you can think of.\" Bocai understood immediately that he was alluding to Sihui's nose, and smiled: \"Give me an example first.\" Gao Pin said: \"I'll say: Red and shiny — the year ends, spring returns, and a dog gets aroused.\" Everyone could not suppress a laugh. Sihui understood, glared at Gao Pin, and said: \"Why should one employ such a reproachable approach? Even the crowing of cocks and the barking of dogs can be heard throughout all four quarters.\" Everyone laughed again. Shen Bocai smiled: \"I have one: Red and shiny — in urgent need, an anal hemorrhoid prolapses.\" Everyone, fearing the sound would carry to the main tables below, dared not laugh aloud, but could no longer suppress the sniggers spreading through the company. Ba Lin said: \"I also have one — somewhat more respectable than yours.\" He then said: \"Red and shiny — a wine-blossomed nose hanging in the center of the face.\" Gao Pin laughed: \"No good — you've exposed the whole subject directly. Now there's nothing left to write.\" Sihui said: \"Absurd! What kind of things are red? What kind of things are shiny?\" And then said: \"Red and shiny...\" — then stopped, unable to continue.",
    "Everyone looked at his expression and laughed all the harder. Siyuan broke into guffaws, his drooping eye streaming tears, and said: \"I-I-I have one: Red-red-red and sh-sh-sh-shiny — a-a-a-a fireball f-f-f-flies up onto the b-b-bed.\" Everyone laughed uncontrollably, on the verge of crying out. Yan Zhongqing said: \"With that burning, it truly becomes all red and shiny.\" Gao Pin said: \"That burning has produced Old Second Sun's Three-Character Classic.\" Everyone was puzzled; Gao Pin explained: \"When there's a fire alarm, naturally people cry: 'Come, come, come! Quick, quick, quick! Save it, save it, save it! Grab the valuables — grab, grab, grab! Run for your lives — run, run, run! The wind blows — whoosh, whoosh, whoosh! The fire roars — boom, boom, boom! Things catch fire and burst — crack, crack, crack! Pop, pop, pop! People cry out in confusion — heehee, heehee, heehee! Out, out, out!' Is it not an entire Three-Character Classic?\" Ba Lin said: \"Old Second Sun has two more specialized Classics — do you know what they are?\" Gao Pin laughed: \"I had no idea he had specialized Classics.\" Ba Lin said: \"Firing a hand-gun, and emptying a chamber-pot — these are his two specialized Classics.\" Everyone, hearing the jibes grow rather savage, was uncertain of the meaning, and pressed for an explanation. Ba Lin said: \"Also in three-character format: Firing the hand-gun is: pull-pull-pull. Emptying the chamber-pot is: lean-lean-lean.\" Everyone burst out laughing. Ziyu praised: \"These two Classics are especially fine — truly most naturally expressed.\" From that time, Siyuan acquired the additional nickname of \"the Unapproved Three-Character Classic.\" Siyuan was about to flare up, but because his father was present downstairs, and because Ba Lin had beaten him savagely several times before, he dared not retaliate. He could only swallow his anger and keep his mouth shut, opening that drooping eye wide and staring tearfully in silent resentment.",
    "After a while, Pincai's attendant came to his side and said: \"Master Ye has sent the opera program.\" Ziyu came over and looked through it with Pincai. The first several pieces — \"Sweeping Flowers,\" \"Three Intoxications,\" \"Debating the Sword,\" \"Visiting the Master,\" \"Admiring the Lotus\" — had already been performed. The remaining program was: \"The Banquet of Achievement,\" \"Jasper Terrace,\" \"Dancing with a Tray,\" \"Stealing the Poem,\" \"Inscribing the Tune,\" \"The Mountain Gate,\" \"Riding Out to Hunt,\" \"Returning from the Hunt,\" \"The Peony Pavilion — Awakening in the Garden,\" and finally \"The Hero in Concealment\" from The Bright Pearl Record. Ziyu said quietly to Pincai: \"The program is fine, but I don't know whether Qin Guan is in any of it.\" Before the words were done, they heard a voice below cry out: \"Without Yuan Baozhu's performance, I absolutely refuse!\"",
    "Ziyu and the others looked down: it was Wang Wenhui in a temper. They saw a man continuing to smile and placate him, bowing repeatedly. Then they heard Wenhui say: \"Even at Master Xu's house, what harm is there in singing one piece before leaving? Besides, when this opera was arranged, what were you told?\" The man said: \"In this 'Awakening in the Garden' there is a newly arrived performer, Qin Guan, who is even better than Baozhu. If Your Lordship doesn't believe it, let him sing one piece first — if it is not to Your Lordship's satisfaction, I'll rush off immediately to fetch Baozhu and guarantee there will be no delay.\" Vice-Minister Liu said: \"Very well then — after 'Jasper Terrace' is done, having 'Awakening in the Garden' will do perfectly fine.\" The man acknowledged this with several \"Yes, yes, sirs!\" and, seeing that Wenhui said no more, went into the theater room. Pincai said to Ziyu: \"Did you hear?\" Ziyu nodded, and in his heart felt deep gratitude toward Wenhui.",
    "\"The Banquet of Achievement\" concluded; \"Jasper Terrace\" came on. Ziyu caught his first glimpse and gave a start — in a momentary daze he first took the performer to be Qin Guan, then saw it was not quite so; this one was slightly older than Qin Guan.",
    "What he saw was someone like an auspicious moon amid blessed clouds, morning rose-mist and celestial dew — fragrant and warm, suffused with spring — a flower opened to eight-tenths of its full bloom, its color at its most absolute brilliance. Already he was transfixed, and asked Nanxiang: \"Who is this? Such elegant bones.\" Nanxiang said: \"Do you consider this good? I'm afraid it would be difficult even to include in a ranking.\" Ziyu knew Nanxiang was deliberately taunting him, and so asked Zhongqing. Zhongqing said: \"This is the Flower Register's number two — Su Huifang, the Jade Moon of the Jasper Terrace.\" Ziyu exclaimed: \"All the spiritual essence of heaven and earth is concentrated here — I was truly a summer insect that cannot conceive of ice. No wonder Zhujun reproached me.\" Nanxiang laughed heartily: \"I don't reproach you either — fortunately you bring the charges against yourself!\" Wenze said: \"What? Yuxiang doesn't even recognize Su Meixiang?\" Nanxiang said: \"He is a scholar who never steps outside — how should he know the affairs of the world?\" After a short while, \"Jasper Terrace\" concluded, and \"Awakening in the Garden\" began.",
    "Ziyu was a little apprehensive — he feared Qin Guan might not quite hold his own against this Su Huifang — and concentrated all his attention in anticipation. At the entrance curtain, it was drawn aside, and there was Qin Guan, whom he had glimpsed twice before; those features were graven in his memory with perfect clarity. At the sound of the hand-gong, lotus steps moved, and a fragrant wind arrived. It was exactly like the full-moon night of the Mid-Autumn Festival — the Dragon Palace laying out its treasures, jeweled radiance rising up to meet the descending moonlight — like cloud yet not cloud, condensed into a five-colored celestial canopy of glorious brilliance, its splendor and beauty beyond anything of this world to compare with. This dazzling light shot forth and scattered Ziyu's gaze into fragments, swirling around every inch of Qin Guan, impossible to gather back together. The more he looked, the less distinct everything became. Fortunately, he heard the singing begin — starting from the line \"Returning from a dream, the orioles warble\" — and he listened character by character. Reaching \"All my life I have loved what is natural,\" and \"What avail this fair season and lovely scene\" — he felt a thread of subtle fragrance floating and swaying from Qin Guan's lips, the sorrow and yearning perfectly distinct, the innermost feelings fully laid bare. Truly it was the wonder of a celestial being taking human form. Listening further, to \"In one and the same heavenly bond, what blessed fate — that has cast this green spring so far away\" — every word struck to Ziyu's very heart, and he nearly let his tears fall, barely holding them back. Then watching Liu Mengmei take the stage and sing \"Endure for now and rest tenderly a while\" — Pincai asked: \"Well, what do you think?\" Ziyu had not even heard; his very soul seemed to have attached itself to the young leading man, entering with Qin Guan behind the stage. Just then, Li Yuanmao came blundering over and clapped Ziyu on the shoulder: \"This is Qin Guan — would you say he's good?\" — giving Ziyu quite a start. Everyone else had also been watching in rapt attention.",
    "It turned out that the moment Qin Guan came on stage he had already spotted Ziyu. He had seen him once more in his dream — today made the fourth time in all — and felt secret joy in his heart: \"What a fortunate coincidence — this gentleman is here today.\" At his second entrance, singing the aria \"Fragrance of Rain and Drifting Clouds,\" even as he sang, his eyes kept sliding over to rest on Ziyu; and Ziyu's heart was filled with quiet warmth. Wenze said softly to Nanxiang: \"This newly arrived young performer seems very intimate with Yuxiang — look at his whole expression, all attention directed at him.\" Nanxiang said to Ziyu: \"What is this performer's name?\" Ziyu said: \"He is called Qin Guan.\" Nanxiang said: \"How many times have you two been in each other's company?\" Ziyu replied: \"I don't actually know him.\" Wenze laughed: \"Yuxiang, when speaking of a performer one wishes to keep it from others — but with this kind of four-eyes-meeting, two-hearts-illuminating display, to say you don't know him — what would it actually take to count as knowing?\" Everyone smiled and looked at Ziyu; Ziyu had no words of defense and could feel his face going red. After this piece, they also watched Lu Sulan in \"Dancing with a Tray,\" Jin Shufang in \"Inscribing the Tune,\" and Li Yulin in \"Stealing the Poem\" — all superlative performers of matchless fragrant brilliance. Ziyu could only bow his head to Nanxiang in acknowledgment of his earlier error.",
    "At table, Zhang Zhongyu and Pincai discovered they were connected by marriage ties and got along famously. Pincai also spent time paying compliments to and cultivating goodwill with everyone at the table. Ziyu watched as the opera performers circulated among the main tables — some urging wine, some engaging in conversation — and found it rather charming. He also observed his uncle Wang Wenhui, who was more exuberantly animated than anyone else. Another piece was watched. At the main tables, Vice-Minister Liu, Scholar Mei, Grand Academician Wu, and Director Shen were among the first to take their leave. Seeing his father had gone and the hour growing late, Ziyu also wished to depart. Just as he was rising, a beautiful young man came suddenly up the stairs. Wenze's servant announced: \"Young Master Feng has arrived!\" Feng Zipei came forward and paid his respects to everyone. Ziyu saw he was no more than eighteen or nineteen, his looks lovely as a beautiful young woman, thoroughly captivating. Liu Wenze said: \"Everyone is about to disperse — how is it you've only just arrived?\" Feng Zipei said: \"This morning I went into the city to call on the Hua household at Jinchun Garden to pay New Year's respects, intending not to linger. But Hua Xingbei absolutely insisted I stay for dinner and then listened to a few more pieces of opera before he would let me leave; I rushed here as quickly as I could.\" Ziyu, together with Yuanmao and Pincai, bid farewell; everyone accompanied them to the staircase landing. Wenze, Wang Xun, and Zhongqing escorted them downstairs.",
    "Wenze said to Ziyu: \"On the ninth, I am preparing a small gathering and hope Elder Brother will come for a visit — a refined discourse and elegant assembly. Not many people — just Zhujun, Jiantan, Yong'an, Zhuoran, and a few others. Elder Brother must absolutely not decline.\" Ziyu agreed and expressed his thanks. Wang Xun, Pincai, and Yuanmao also offered their thanks in turn, and they departed first. The remaining guests chatted a while longer, then all took their leave. As for what came next, please await the following chapter."
  ],
  7: [
    "After returning from the guild hall, Ziyu spent two full days thinking about Qin Guan's performance, convinced it was the most beautiful thing in the world. He also assessed Su Huifang, Lu Sulan, Jin Shufang, and Li Yulin as all utterly superlative. On careful reflection, Huifang's spirit and bearing surpassed all the rest; next, Sulan could hold her own against Huifang. But compared to Qin Guan, even by the finest margin, they all fell slightly short. He also thought:",
    "\"If Qin Guan's beauty were not placed on stage, no one in the world could ever admire and praise him, and he would be buried in obscurity. So perhaps the Creator, in its playful bestowing of spiritual essence, arranged for him to fall into the theater world — to display the wondrous workings of fate. Hence it produced this king of flowers, and then so many flower-companions surrounding him, like the hundred flowers that attend the peony.\"",
    "\"But a fine flower offers only one season of enjoyment, while a person's beauty may endure for ten years. In this way a person surpasses a flower, and so naturally the love one bears for a person ought to surpass love for a flower all the more. Who would have thought the eyes of the world are all alike? I had supposed that Shi Zhujun and Wang Yong'an and the rest must have been exaggerating; but now I see they actually fell short in their descriptions. Those claims about his ability to compose poetry and paint must also certainly be true.\" He then thought: \"Although today I saw Qin Guan perform, I still have no way to make any acquaintance with him. When will we meet again? But seeing his eyes glance my way repeatedly, it seems he may have some tender feeling toward me. Before this, in the carriage he raised the curtain to gaze — as if not treating our roadside encounter as mere coincidence. What can that mean?\"",
    "He kept thinking about it without arriving at any clarity. Wanting to look again at the 'Person in the Carriage' verses he had composed earlier — and perhaps add two more — he took them out. He suddenly noticed that two characters had been scraped away from the third and fourth poems, and was greatly puzzled. He asked a small maidservant: \"Who came to look at my books these past two days?\" The maidservant said: \"The day before yesterday the Mistress received guests — a group of young mistresses and Wang Family's Second Miss, who all came to look around. The young mistresses spent a long time looking at Young Master's leisure portrait; the Second Miss looked at Young Master's books; no one else came in. I saw that when the Second Miss was reading, she turned over a piece of paper, looked at it, scraped at one spot with her fingernail, and put it back in the book.\" She then laughed and said: \"The day before, I heard Second Miss's maid Xue'er say that the Sun family Madam had acted as matchmaker, and that Second Miss has been matched with Young Master — and Second Miss even took away one of the Mistress's hairpins.\" Ziyu, half-believing and half-doubting, asked: \"I don't believe it — you must be making it up.\" The maidservant said: \"Would I dare make things up? I was watching the room that day and didn't dare leave — this is what Xue'er told me. I expect the whole household already knows.\" Ziyu felt great joy in his heart. Then he thought suddenly of his second female cousin's appearance — which also bore some resemblance to Qin Guan — and began comparing the two in his mind, uncertain which was the finer. Then, thinking over the scraped-away characters, he understood in a flash: \"Who would have thought I stumbled onto her very name by chance — an unintentional natural coincidence, how extraordinary! She must think I was deliberately thinking of her and writing about her. Her heart must surely reproach me — what is to be done? I have no way to explain myself; this is a truly unjust grievance.\" Then he thought again: \"Since the betrothal has been settled, even if she reproaches me, it doesn't matter.\" Ziyu was then led by the two characters of 'Qionghua' to think again of Qin Yan, and became increasingly absorbed in tender thoughts; the heart of cherishing beauty and longing for it arose from this moment.",
    "On the ninth day, Liu Wenze again sent someone to extend an invitation. Ziyu reported to his mother, changed his clothes, and departed in his carriage.",
    "Now at Wenze's residence, the invited guests Yan Zhongqing, Wang Xun, and Shi Nanxiang had already arrived; then Mei Ziyu and Gao Pin arrived at the gate together. A servant led them past the great hall, through the flowered gate at the side of the reception hall, and onto a path paved with pebblestones, flanked on both sides by Lake Tai rocks piled into irregular artificial hillocks, with sparse, graceful winter trees scattered among them. In the distance one could make out terraces and pavilions — the whole arrangement quite secluded and refined. After two or three turns, they crossed a stone bridge; on either side of the path were all green bamboos, surrounding a stretch of red balustrade railing, and straight ahead were five bays of a rolled-eave hall. Yan Zhongqing and the others were all waiting on the covered walk; Liu Wenze had already come down to welcome them. Gao Pin and Ziyu went forward first to greet the host, and then everyone exchanged introductions in order of age. Shi Nanxiang and Gao Pin were both twenty-five — Gao Pin's birthday fell in the second month, making him the older by birth month. Yan Zhongqing was twenty-four, Wang Xun twenty-three, Ziyu eighteen. Though Wenze was twenty-four, he was the host. Everyone took their seats in proper order and exchanged a few pleasantries. Among them, only Ziyu was here for the first time; looking about attentively, he saw in the center a nanmu-wood plaque with blue characters: 'Chamber of the Leaning Sword and Sleeping Lute.' The flanking pillar-couplets were on areca-palm wood, reading: 'Tea-smoke just rising, the crane's dream not yet awakened — here one finds a few fine moments of peace; / The pine wind slowly coming, the mountain spring heard in clarity — where else could one shed even a speck of dust?'",
    "The inscription read 'Composed by Daosheng, written by Qu Benli' — the calligraphy of archaic and exceptional character. Below stood a large display table covered with many books. To one side were twelve pots of forced winter flowers (tanghua), their fragrance wafting over, intoxicating to the spirit. Looking at all this, Ziyu thought again of Qin Yan's performance that day — truly a jeweled light dazzling the eyes, a fragrance penetrating to the bone — and felt somewhat dazed. Suddenly he heard Wenze say: \"This room is too open. Let us sit inside.\" They followed through to the east side, where a book-boy raised a curtain: inside were three study rooms, with a glass partition dividing the central area into two layers. Going around to one side, past the glass partition, were two more connecting rooms. Through the south-facing window one could see outside. Hung above was Dong Qichang's calligraphy of the two characters 'Xu Bai' (Emptied White); a landscape of dry wood, bamboo, and rocks by Ni Yunlin; and flanking couplets reading: 'Within the realm of moral principle there is a territory of joy; / Beyond wind and moonlight there is little else worth discussing.' In the center of the room stood a long rectangular trough of Han white marble, its sides carved with many poems, filled entirely with narcissus — the flowers half-opened at this time. Beside it, in another pot, stood a large stalk of green-calyx white plum, more than five feet tall — a gnarled old trunk laden with buds, nearly all still closed; only toward the window side had one or two branches opened.",
    "Wenze had the room warmed by a floor-heating kang, and the banquet was laid out within. The host poured the first toasting cup, and everyone sat down.",
    "Nanxiang said: \"What a pity we didn't invite a few performers today.\" Wenze said: \"I had thought of doing so, but on inquiry I found they are all at the Yiyuan today for the ninth-day Winter Gathering — not one was going to any theatrical events — so I decided not to send for them, not wishing to inconvenience them.\" Nanxiang said:",
    "\"Today we constitute, within the crimson dust of the world, a rare moment of refined assembly.\" Zhongqing was sitting just below Gao Pin; Gao Pin leaned over and whispered something in Zhongqing's ear. Zhongqing gave a sudden silent laugh. Everyone asked Zhongqing: \"What did he say?\" Zhongqing said to Gao Pin: \"Shall I say it?\" Gao Pin shook his head. Zhongqing said: \"The seventh character is particularly well-matched.\" As he said this the two of them looked at each other and laughed. Nanxiang, always impatient, said: \"If you two tell us, I'm willing to drink a cup.\" Gao Pin said: \"Drink ten cups first, then I'll tell.\" Wenze, knowing Nanxiang's wine tolerance was ordinary, said: \"Let me mediate — three cups.\" Gao Pin smiled: \"Zhujun drinks three cups; each of the others drinks one cup in appreciation of the remark.\" Zhongqing said: \"I've already received enlightenment privately — I'm exempt.\" Gao Pin said: \"When did that happen?\" Zhongqing said: \"Truly, that mouth of yours — a dog's mouth cannot produce elephant's ivory.\" Nanxiang said: \"Quickly pour the wine and drink — then he can tell us.\" He duly drank three cups; the others all drank one each. Gao Pin smiled at Zhongqing: \"You already received enlightenment — you explain it.\" Zhongqing, still laughing, fined Gao Pin a cup and announced: \"He said: 'In the Xu Bai Study, three matched pairs' — referring to the three pairs of couplets in this room, which he read as matching three pairs of a certain vulgar anatomical term.\" No one understood at first.",
    "Wenze said: \"What is there to laugh about in that?\" Nanxiang suddenly understood, slapped his hands and laughed uproariously: \"That mischievous devil — truly outrageous. But one must admit it was a remarkably quick-witted match!\" The others caught on and also laughed, saying: \"He took the refined characters completely at face value — truly a cleverly struck match.\" Wenze said: \"Brother Zhuo, I'll give you a couplet to match — you may not pause to think. If you match it well, I drink three cups; if you can't match it, you drink ten; if it's poor, you drink five.\" Gao Pin said: \"As the saying goes, it's easy to give the opening line and hard to match it. Three cups if I can't match it, one cup if it's poor — how about that?\" Nanxiang said: \"It depends on how hard the opening line is. Say it first.\" Wenze said to Ziyu: \"May I borrow your honored name? The opening is: 'Zi Yu — a person like jade.'\" Zhongqing said: \"That's not easy to match.\" Before the words were out, Gao Pin said: \"I've already matched it — drink three cups.\" Wenze said: \"Say it.\" Nanxiang said: \"If the match is good, we should each drink a cup of congratulation too.\" Gao Pin smiled: \"'Mao Jin — a face like gold.' How is that?\" Wang Xun said: \"'Mao Jin' as a counterpart to 'Zi Yu' is a perfect opposite.\" Nanxiang said: \"Only the phrase 'a face like gold' lacks a classical reference.\" Gao Pin said: \"It may lack classical pedigree, but it's certainly apt. Haven't you seen the rabbit figurines on stalls at the Mid-Autumn Festival — they all have faces painted gold?\" Everyone burst out laughing. Wenze said: \"You heartless fellow — now you're even insulting your own sworn-brother.\" Gao Pin said: \"Arrow on the bowstring — I had no choice but to shoot.\" The host duly drank the three cups, and everyone else each drank a cup. Nanxiang said: \"Drinking like this — forfeit after forfeit — is rather tedious. The other day we played the poetry-card game all day, which was enormously entertaining. Yaoqing assembled two splendid couplets — what a pity they're all at Yiyuan today. Why don't we devise some fresh new drinking game?\" Liu Wenze said: \"Today let's play the poem-matching game.\" Ziyu asked: \"How does poem-matching work?\" Zhongqing said: \"It's very simple: the person setting the game takes a line of poetry, breaks it into individual characters, and says them one by one for others to match; these are then combined to form a coherent verse of one's own. If the meaning connects, no drinking; if not a single character connects, you drink a cup. It often produces absurd results — quite the most entertaining thing.\" Gao Pin said: \"Poem-matching it is. The host drinks the forfeit cup first.\" Wenze drank, had a nanmu board brought out, wrote the participants' surnames down the side as the game proceeded, and said: \"I'll give the first character.\" He wrote the character 'zhong' (middle). Everyone thought a moment: Yan matched 'wai' (outside), Gao matched 'hou' (after), Mei matched 'shang' (above), Shi also matched 'shang,' Wang matched 'li' (inside). Wenze then put out the character 'feng' (phoenix): Yan matched 'hong' (wild swan), Gao matched 'ji' (rooster), Mei matched 'luan' (mythical phoenix-bird), Shi matched 'ya' (crow), Wang matched 'wu' (raven). Wenze put out 'xia' (descend): Nanxiang said: \"First to submit — I match 'gui' (return).\" Gao Pin next matched 'qian' (before/front); Zhongqing and Ziyu simultaneously matched 'lai' (come); Wang Xun matched 'hui' (go back); Wenze recorded all the results. Then 'fu' (support): Gao grabbed 'kao' (lean against), Shi matched 'song' (escort), Yan matched 'ji' (send/entrust), Wang matched 'yu' (drive/control), Mei matched 'ting' (listen).",
    "Wenze put out 'shuang' (double/pair): Zhongqing matched 'gu' (solitary), Gao Pin matched 'ba' (eight), Ziyu matched 'jiu' (nine), Wang Xun said: \"Oh no — following the counting sequence it would be ten.\" Nanxiang said: \"Quite so — my character is rather tricky to place, but let's say 'san' (three).\" Wenze put out 'nian' (imperial carriage). Nanxiang said: \"I already know which poetic line this is building toward.\" Ziyu quickly matched 'qin' (lute); Wang Xun matched 'che' (carriage); Nanxiang matched 'chuan' (boat); only Gao Pin had not yet responded. Wenze urged: \"Any later and it's a forfeit.\" Gao Pin gave a slight smile and matched 'zhou' (vessel/boat). The judge then assembled the full couplet line, which read: 'A pair of phoenixes in the clouds, supporting the imperial carriage as it descends.' Zhongqing's match read: 'A solitary wild swan sends a letter from beyond the sky.' Everyone praised this as excellent. Gao Pin's match read: 'Eight roosters after the dew, leaning against the boat's prow.' Everyone looked at it and could not suppress their laughter. Wenze said: \"This is truly incoherent to an extraordinary degree — not a single character connects properly. Even he can be stumped! By general vote, how many cups should he drink?\" Nanxiang said: \"Only the final two characters 'boat's prow' connect at all; nothing else flows through — five cups is the absolute minimum.\" Gao Pin just kept laughing, neither arguing nor drinking. The host said: \"What will you do?\" Gao Pin leaned close to Zhongqing's ear and whispered something. Zhongqing laughed so hard he left his seat, went into the outer room, and burst out laughing aloud. Nanxiang, puzzled, hurried out to ask Zhongqing; Zhongqing told him, and then Shi Nanxiang began slapping the table in wild laughter. When the others asked Gao Pin what he had said, Gao Pin just laughed and said: \"Wait until you've seen everyone's results, and then it won't be too late.\" Wenze said: \"The forfeit wine must still be drunk.\" Gao Pin said: \"Of course.\" Zhongqing pulled Nanxiang back inside. Wenze said: \"I wonder what mischief he's been up to.\" When Nanxiang and Zhongqing heard this, they broke out laughing again, tears streaming down their faces. Only after a servant wrung out a towel for them to wipe their faces did the laughter begin to subside.",
    "Then they looked at Ziyu's match, which read: 'A nine-horse imperial carriage from the heavens arrives to hear the lute.' Everyone praised it: \"This line matches every character perfectly and surpasses even Jiantan's.\" They each drank a cup of congratulation. Nanxiang's match read: 'Three ravens on the water escort the boat as it returns home.' Wenze said: \"Zhujun, this match is a bit careless.\" Nanxiang said: \"You are a judge who has seen little and marvels at too much — beware of losing your eyes. This is precisely what I call a well-crafted match.\" Ziyu said: \"It truly is fine.\" Wenze said: \"You'll need to explain it to me.\" Ziyu said: \"'A lone traveler among three ravens on the water, coming home' — this is a line from Han Wo's poem.\" Wenze suddenly understood: \"Is it from 'Seeing Off Lord Xiangyuan Returning to His Country Estate'? My memory is truly terrible — I deserve a beating!\" Nanxiang said: \"Fortunately you still recall the source — otherwise you'd certainly be fined ten cups.\" Then they looked at Wang Xun's match: 'Ten ravens driving a chariot back in the noonday sun.' Wang Xun said: \"My match is poor.\" Wenze said: \"It's just that 'ten ravens' doesn't quite cohere.\" Gao Pin said: \"Wrong again — there is a raven within the sun in mythology; when in Emperor Yao's time ten suns appeared at once, were those not 'ten ravens'?\" Wenze said: \"That's twisting logic — still too much of a stretch.\" By general vote, the ranking was established: Ziyu first, Nanxiang second, Zhongqing third, Wang Xun fourth, Gao Pin last — and in that order they took turns as game-master.",
    "Wenze said: \"Zhuoran's forfeit cup is still undrunk — and what exactly did he whisper just now that produced such laughter? If it was genuinely clever, exempting the fine wouldn't be unreasonable.\" Nanxiang said: \"If he says it aloud, not only can the fine not be exempted — it should be doubled.\" Wenze said: \"Can it be that he's making fun of me again?\" Zhongqing said: \"Indeed.\" Wenze said: \"As long as the mockery is justified, the fine can be somewhat reduced.\" Gao Pin said: \"It seems five cups cannot be avoided. But any more, I absolutely cannot accept — so perhaps I'd better not say it.\" Wenze said: \"No additional cups then.\" Gao Pin said: \"Read my matching line backwards — then tell me if it's good.\" Ziyu, Wang Xun, and Wenze quietly recited it to themselves and all broke into clapping laughter. Ziyu laughed until he was bent over the table; Wang Xun laughed so hard he leaned against Nanxiang, setting Nanxiang and Zhongqing off in another peal of laughter.",
    "Wenze said: \"Zhuoran, when you die, you are certainly destined for the Hell of Pulled-Out Tongues.\" A servant poured the wine. Gao Pin said: \"Five cups drunk in one breath will certainly leave me drunk. Perhaps if I play finger-guessing games with everyone, there's some hope of reducing them.\" He proceeded to play thumb-guessing with each person in turn; some rounds he won, some he lost. When all the rounds were settled and everyone had drunk their due, Ziyu served as game-master, giving out four characters for all to match: 'fei ying shou chang' (expend, shadow, withdraw, sorrow). Nanxiang matched 'jing sheng fang dan' (startle, sound, release, courage); Wang Xun matched 'rong xiang huan ru' (melt, fragrance, wash, milk); Wenze matched 'fan me xiao she' (flip, tiny-note, small, tongue); Zhongqing matched 'duo xian san fa' (many, immortals, loosened, hair); while Gao Pin's, as distinctive as ever, was 'chu yi fang fen' (remove, Yi, release, excrement) — everyone was already smiling. Ziyu then put out the character 'tai' (stage/terrace): Nanxiang said: \"This line has a fine beginning.\" After pondering a moment, he matched 'guan' (hall/lodge); Wang Xun matched 'wu' (room/house); Wenze matched 'xie' (waterside pavilion); Zhongqing matched 'dao' (island); Gao Pin said: \"I live in Hongji Monastery — so I match 'si' (temple).\" Ziyu then put out 'luan' (mythical phoenix-bird): Nanxiang said: \"This character is even more unusual.\" Wang Xun quickly grabbed 'yan' (swallow); Zhongqing matched 'he' (crane); Nanxiang said: \"Not good — beaten to it. I won't use the category of flying birds at all — I'll match 'shu' (rat/mouse).\" Wenze said: \"Can it be 'shadow of a luan-bird'? Under my 'me' (tiny/diminutive) character, what could follow... well, 'me' and 'niao' (bird) do connect.\" Gao Pin said: \"You're matching 'niao,' so I'll also match 'niao.'\" Ziyu said: \"'Wu' (dance).\" Nanxiang said: \"It must be 'dancing luan-bird' — I can only match 'she' (archery/shoot).\" Wenze grabbed 'ge' (song); Wang Xun matched 'hua' (glorious/splendid); Zhongqing matched 'yao' (jasper). Gao Pin said: \"'Ba' (surname Ba) — is that matchable?\" Everyone laughed together: \"As long as you're willing to drink the forfeits, what is there you can't match?\" Ziyu wrote out all the results; the opening line was: 'The dance-stage withdrawing shadows — the luan-bird's sorrow expended.' Nanxiang said: \"Ah — these are such obvious famous poetic images, and I still couldn't think of them.\" Zhongqing said: \"Is the game-master still deep in thought?\" Ziyu was in the midst of writing out Nanxiang's match, gave a smile, and said nothing. Everyone looked at Nanxiang's: 'The archery-hall releasing its sound — the rat's gallbladder is startled.' Everyone said: \"A very good match.\" Gao Pin said: \"He was dreaming of swan meat and didn't want to be frightened off.\" Nanxiang said: \"Keep your glib mouth shut — I'll settle with you later.\" Then they looked at Wang Xun's: 'The splendid house washing its fragrance — the swallow's milk blends and melts.' Ziyu had already written double-circle marks. Everyone said: \"This line is beautifully harmonious.\" They all drank a congratulatory cup. Wenze said: \"I've clearly failed the examination.\" Everyone looked at his: 'The singing-hall's tiny note contains a bird-tongue.' Nanxiang said: \"It does parse.\" Gao Pin said: \"Having a tiny note in the singing-hall is perfectly coherent — it's just that the little note suffers rather harshly.\" Nanxiang asked: \"Why?\" Gao Pin said: \"With both a bird and a tongue, the two cannot be distinguished; no wonder it cannot contain all of this. The person who matched this line must be well practiced at such containment.\" Wenze said: \"Nonsense and rubbish — your 'excrement' match is probably no masterwork either.\" Zhongqing's match was: 'Jasper island scattering immortals — many crane-feathered heads.' Ziyu had already given it partial marks. Everyone praised it in unison. Nanxiang said to Wang Xun: \"I'm afraid he may have stolen first place from us.\" Ziyu said: \"The writing reflects the man — these two matching lines suit their authors exactly.\" Gao Pin said: \"Mine should simply be crossed out — no need to expose my failings.\" Nanxiang said: \"I remember his was 'Ba si fang yi chu niao fen' — damnable, damnable. Who knows what nonsense he was releasing.\" Wenze said: \"Amitabha — you who excel at mocking others, see how you fare today! Tell us — is there a single connected character?\" Ziyu looked at it fresh and said: \"Brothers, don't be too quick to dismiss it — Zhuoran's match also has its reasoning.\" Nanxiang looked it over, nodded, and said: \"Not bad — this person is truly incorrigible.\" Wenze said: \"Can there really be some coherence in it?\" Nanxiang said: \"What is outrageous is that it is not entirely incoherent.\" Gao Pin just kept laughing without a word. Wang Xun went over to Zhongqing's side and asked: \"Where does 'Ba si' (Ba Monastery) come from?\" Zhongqing said: \"I recall that the poet Dai Shulun has the line 'gazing at the monastery, passing through Ba Temple.'\" Wang Xun said: \"As long as there's a source, it will do.\" Wenze asked: \"And the last five characters?\" Zhongqing asked: \"Do you have the Record of the Transmission of the Lamp here?\" Wenze had a literate book-boy fetch the text from the outer bookshelf. Zhongqing found the passage: \"Grand Secretary Cui entered a temple and saw a bird defecating on the head of the Buddha image, so he asked the monk: 'Do birds and sparrows have the Buddha-nature?' The monk said: 'They do.' Cui said: 'Then why do they defecate on the Buddha's head?' The monk said: 'That is precisely why they do not defecate on the sparrowhawk's head.'\" Zhongqing said: \"Judged by this, the line holds.\" Wenze said: \"It's just that 'fang yi' (releasing it) is hard to parse — if the 'niao' (bird) character were changed to 'que' (sparrow), it would work perfectly.\"",
    "Gao Pin said: \"My 'niao' (bird) and your 'que' (sparrow) are essentially the same — if your 'niao' were changed to 'que,' wouldn't that also be an improvement?\" Wenze thought it over and saw there was a point to this as well. In the end, Ziyu accepted only Zhongqing's and Wang Xun's matching lines as passing; the others, Wenze and Gao Pin, were fined their wine.",
    "Next it was Nanxiang's turn to set the game. He put out the character 'chun' (spring): Wenze matched 'xia' (summer); Gao Pin matched 'zheng' (upright/primary). Wang Xun said: \"Can a level-tone character be matched against another level-tone?\" Everyone said: \"Certainly — it has already been done.\" Wang Xun matched 'chen' (morning/dawn); Zhongqing matched 'qiu' (autumn); Ziyu matched 'dong' (winter). Nanxiang then put out 'yue' (moon). Gao Pin said: \"Zhujun's ideas are always different from everyone else's — these two characters surely won't connect logically; I'll match 'yang' (sunshine/sun).\" Wang Xun matched 'shuang' (frost); Ziyu matched 'xue' (snow); Zhongqing matched 'kong' (empty sky). Wenze said: \"Never mind whether they connect or not — let's just match our own.\" And matched 'yun' (cloud). Nanxiang put out 'san' (three): Gao Pin said: \"You see — it's not 'third month' but 'three springs.' If we all match 'yi' (one), they'll all connect.\" Everyone agreed; only Wenze said: \"I'll be different — I match 'ban' (half).\" Nanxiang then put out 'gai' (change/revise): Ziyu said: \"This character is quite unusual — I match 'qiao' (knock).\" Wenze said: \"I match 'dui' (heap/pile).\" Wang Xun matched 'feng' (lush/abundant); Zhongqing matched 'pan' (a turn/dish); Gao Pin casually matched 'fu' (prostrate/conceal). Then Nanxiang said:",
    "\"'Tu' (rabbit). You all match.\" Wang Xun said: \"'He' (badger/raccoon dog).\" Zhongqing said: \"The eagle masters the rabbit — I match 'ying' (eagle).\" Ziyu said: \"A donkey-rider flying a hawk is probably unheard of, but I'll borrow it for the match — 'lü' (donkey).\" Wenze said:",
    "\"'Wu' (raven).\" Gao Pin said: \"I match 'gui' (tortoise).\" Wenze said:",
    "\"Well, well — I had not known. I beg your distinguished pardon.\" Everyone erupted in laughter. Nanxiang said: \"This is your own self-incriminating testimony — from now on, would it not suit you to change your honorable name to Gao Gui (High Tortoise)?\" Gao Pin, realizing his slip and unable to take it back, said: \"These two characters are something of a novelty — better to bestow them on Elder Brother instead. The two characters 'Shi Gui' are in fact an ancient personal name — most refined and classical.\" Wenze said: \"You hear Zhuoran's tongue — having let himself be caught, he immediately transfers the blame to someone else.\" Everyone laughed for a while; then they listened quietly for Nanxiang to present the assembled couplet.",
    "Nanxiang just kept eating from his dish without saying a word. Wenze said: \"Why haven't you announced the couplet?\" Nanxiang laughed: \"The examination papers have all been submitted — do we still need more questions? I put out all five characters in sequence: 'Spring moon three change rabbit.' Among the submissions, the entry just before — 'Summer cloud half-stacked raven' — the 'raven' character is also well-matched by analogy. But judging purely by the composition, it cannot compare with Jiantan's 'Autumn sky one-wheel eagle' — pure and unrestrained; that should rank first. Yuxiang's 'Winter snow one-knock donkey,' Yong'an's 'Morning frost one-lush sable' — are both very skillfully matched. The worst is Zhuoran's 'Upright-sun one-prostrate tortoise.' How can 'upright sun' (zheng yang) apply to a tortoise?\" Gao Pin laughed and asked Wenze: \"Your honored place of origin — where is it, exactly?\"",
    "Wenze said: \"You dog's head! You truly make a man want to die of frustration — are you trying to overturn your confession?\" When everyone thought through what Gao Pin meant, they laughed so hard they could barely contain themselves. It turned out that Wenze was indeed a native of Zhengyang County in Henan — which matched perfectly with Gao Pin's line. Was that not an extraordinary coincidence? Wenze poured him one more large cup of wine before venting his indignation.",
    "Next Zhongqing served as game-master. Everyone was given six characters to match: 'si fa bai ri ru xin' (silk, hair, white, day, as, new). Gao Pin assembled: 'qian mao zhu tian ru chang' (signature/lead, feather, vermilion, sky, enter, long). Ziyu matched: 'jing yan hua nian dui hao' (mirror, complexion, glorious, year, face, good). Nanxiang matched: 'zhu chun zhu sheng chui man' (bamboo, lip, crimson, sound, blow, slow). Wang Xun matched: 'jian yi wu shi shi fu' (scissors, garment, raven, time, try, brush). Wenze matched: 'cao ma huang chao qi shi' (grass, hemp, yellow, morning, rise, gaze). Zhongqing wrote out the opening line: 'White hair like silk threads — renewing day by day.'",
    "He ranked Wenze's match — 'Yellow hemp-cap rises — the morning court gazes day by day' — as first; Ziyu's match — 'Glorious face against the mirror — year after year beautiful' — as second; and Nanxiang's match — 'Crimson lips blow bamboo — note after note (Sheng Sheng Man)' — received circled marks and was placed third. Everyone said: \"Both these matching lines are fine — it seems Zhujun's is actually the better of the two. The judge's ranking doesn't seem entirely fair.\" Zhongqing said: \"That these two submissions are both excellent — that goes without saying.",
    "\"On the surface, Zhujun's 'bamboo' matching 'silk,' and 'crimson lips' matching 'white hair,' is exquisitely crafted; 'Sheng Sheng Man' further conceals the name of a ci tune, which would seem to place him above Yuxiang — that is why I gave him circled marks.",
    "\"But since the opening line is split character by character, each individual character must match exactly. Yuxiang's use of 'year' to match 'day' is most fitting; Zhujun's use of 'sound' to match 'day' — well, if 'day' is not used in reduplication, or if it simply means 'broad daylight,' then 'crimson sound' becomes impossible to parse. In the end it is not as flawlessly balanced as Yuxiang's, and moreover his phrasing is broadly elegant without falling into excessive cleverness. Do you gentlemen agree?\" These few sentences convinced everyone. Nanxiang, who never readily conceded to others, this time also nodded in agreement. Gao Pin said: \"But then my use of 'sky' to match 'day' is even better than Yuxiang's — why was my submission not selected?\" Zhongqing said: \"Write it out and explain it.\" First he wrote out Wang Xun's: 'Raven-dark garment scissors — the raven-colored robe is tried and brushed each time.' Everyone said: \"This line also comes quite naturally.\" Zhongqing said: \"In this round of examination, setting aside Zhuoran, all the rest are awarded passing degrees.\" Gao Pin laughed: \"Watch those eyes carefully — my submission cannot be crossed out.\" Zhongqing wrote it out: 'Vermilion feathers entering the sedge-hat — growing taller day by day.' Zhongqing crossed it out with several strokes; everyone who saw it laughed uproariously. Nanxiang, suppressing his laughter, said: \"I understand the classical allusion he's using. In ancient times, the Red Feather Nation's king conquered the Giant People's Nation and seized their lands.",
    "\"In the Giant People's Nation there was a city called Sedge Hat City, the capital where their king had established his seat. After the Red Feather king entered this city and lived there two days, he began to feel swollen all over, growing larger by the day.\" Nanxiang said this was apparently the allusion being employed, and as he said it burst out laughing. Wang Xun, half-believing, asked: \"What happened next?\"",
    "Nanxiang said: \"This allusion is rather long — enough has been said to serve the matching line.\" Wenze asked: \"In what book is this found?\" Zhongqing said: \"The Unofficial Annals of the Shi Clan.\" Wang Xun and Wenze finally understood, and broke into peals of laughter again. Gao Pin said: \"You are all talking nonsense — haven't you memorized the Four Books? This comes directly from what Mencius described about Yangzhu — 'who would not pull out a single hair' — chasing a young pig into a sedge-hat. Hence 'vermilion feathers entering the sedge-hat.' Now that is what I call true classical transformation!\" Zhongqing said: \"How do you explain the three characters 'growing taller day by day'?\" Gao Pin said: \"Your honor as game-master is being truly obtuse. Since he refuses to pull out a single feather, naturally it keeps growing longer by the day.\" The laughter that everyone produced at this remark was of such volume that, had the rooms not been deep and secluded, passersby on the street outside would surely have heard. The host fined Gao Pin three cups of wine.",
    "Then Wang Xun served as game-master, putting out the opening line: 'Fragrance exhausted, Southern person fades — the beautiful country.' Wenze matched: 'Many tunes, Eastern entertainers compose mountain-names.' Zhongqing matched: 'Rhapsody difficulty, Eastern scholars, refined, capital learning.' Gao Pin matched: 'Combat long, Western sages, conveyed, region, equal-level.'",
    "Everyone paid close attention to Gao Pin's matching line, and each character was level, regular, and coherent. Wenze said:",
    "\"This time Zhuoran is probably taking first place — every character matches very stably.\" Ziyu matched: 'Deep feeling, Western dan-performer, moves Kunlun-mountain fame.' Nanxiang matched: 'Many paintings, Western scholars, paint famous gardens.' They finished matching one by one. Wang Xun wrote out the opening line: 'Fragrance fades in the Southern kingdom — the beauties are all gone.' Wenze's assembled match: 'Tunes composed of Eastern Mountain — many famous courtesans.' Zhongqing's: 'Rhapsodies forged in the Eastern Capital — difficult for scholars.' Gao Pin's: 'Contest-drive the Western region — the sages in long seniority.' Ziyu's: 'Deep feeling moves the Western Kun — famous dan-performer of profound sentiment.' Nanxiang's: 'Paintings of the Western Garden — many renowned scholars.' Wang Xun said: \"First place without question goes to Zhujun. As for Yuxiang, 'famous dan-performer' lacks classical density and is less seamless than Jiantan's — so second probably goes to him, and Qianzhou next. As for Zhuoran's line, I genuinely don't understand it — if there is a classical allusion within it, please explain, so that you don't suffer an unjust mark.\"",
    "Gao Pin said: \"I've never seen a chief examiner ask candidates to explain their allusions. There is indeed an allusion — but if I tell you, you'll say I was manipulating the examination.\" Zhongqing said: \"His allusion originates from the Eastern Land of the Great Tang.\" Gao Pin said: \"Jiantan is a close kinsman of the chief examiner — he should recuse himself and not speak out of turn.\" (It turned out that Wang Xun had never read the Journey to the West, and could only stare blankly at the white board.) Nanxiang was in the midst of drinking when he suddenly saw Gao Pin shade his eyes with his hand like a sun-visor,",
    "glance over at Wang Xun, and could not suppress a burst of laughter — the wine went down the wrong way and he choked and coughed for some time, setting the whole table off. Nanxiang said to Wang Xun: \"Let me finish laughing first, and then I'll read you the Journey to the West.\" Wenze stepped in to explain: \"It's the allusion of the Great Sage Equal to Heaven escorting the Tang Monk to the Western Heaven to fetch the scriptures.\" Wang Xun suddenly understood: \"How can that be? Even so, 'contest-drive' and 'long/seniority' still don't quite connect.\" Nanxiang smiled: \"You don't know — when Sun Xingzhe soars on his somersault-cloud, one flip covers a hundred and eight thousand li. Isn't that a long journey?\"",
    "The host moved to fine Gao Pin more wine; Gao Pin beseeched him earnestly and in the end drank only one cup.",
    "Finally it was Gao Pin's turn to set the game. He rattled off six characters in one breath: 'qian li yan zhao he kou' (thousand, li, speech, summon, grain, mouth). Zhongqing thought: 'That's only seven characters total, and he says six at once — surely he doesn't think no one will see through it. He must be using the character-decomposition method to confuse us.' He said: \"Your six characters — could they be the three characters 'chong zhao he' (Repeat-Decree-Harmony)? If you don't clarify, we'll all refuse to sit for the examination.\" Gao Pin, found out, had no choice but to smile and nod. Ziyu matched with three characters: 'Zhuo yan guan' (Zhuo-speech-penetrating); Nanxiang matched: 'Pin yang chang' (Pin-sun-long); Wang Xun matched: 'Yi ling qing' (One-year-celebrate); Wenze matched: 'Pin jian dong' (Pin-wicked-move); Zhongqing matched: 'Guan hao ding' (Tube-fine hair-determined). Gao Pin then rattled off four more characters in succession: 'jiu xi qi feng' (nine, joy, spirit, phoenix).",
    "Zhongqing said: \"This one is clearly not using character-decomposition — I'll match 'yi gao biao tu' (one-high-mark-rabbit).\" Wenze said: \"I'll match 'yi huan xin ji' (one-joy-heart-rooster).\" Wang Xun said: \"I'll match 'di chang nian gui' (rank-long-year-tortoise).\" Ziyu matched: 'chao yuan jing ren' (surpassing-primal-refined-person). Nanxiang matched: 'yi jing shen long' (one-spirit-dragon). Gao Pin turned his back on the group and wrote out his opening line, set down his brush, looked over everyone's submissions one by one, gave a quiet snort of amusement, then used a wine-dampened paper to wipe all the characters off the white board. Everyone was surprised and said:",
    "\"How extraordinary — can it be that not a single submission was acceptable?\" Nanxiang said: \"No, no — if they weren't acceptable he'd have written them out to hold everyone up to ridicule. Let me think through the characters he gave out — assembled, what line do they form?\" Zhongqing said: \"When he was writing I caught a glimpse of 'feng zhao' (phoenix-decree) at the start.\" Ziyu thought a moment and said: \"Could it be 'The phoenix-decree from the nine heavens brings harmonious joyful air'?\" Nanxiang said: \"Exactly right.\" Gao Pin said: \"No, no.\" Zhongqing said: \"Let us each just recall our own matching line — then it will become clear.\" Ziyu said: \"My line — 'A person of speech who surpasses Zhuo and penetrates to the primal essence' — is not particularly impressive, but there's nothing incoherent about it.\" Nanxiang said: \"He rejected it because of his own courtesy name Zhuoran — 'Zhuo, primal essence' being intolerable to him.\" Zhongqing said: \"Mine was 'A single rabbit-hair brush sets the highest standard (gao biao)' — surely rejected because 'tu gao' (rabbit-high) sounds like his name.\" Wang Xun said: \"I remember mine was 'Tortoise longevity, foremost of all, celebrating the long years.'\" Nanxiang said: \"Excellent match, clearly first — but why was it rejected?\" Wenze said: \"Don't you see him sitting up there in lofty first position?\" Nanxiang nodded and said: \"My match points even more directly at him.\" Everyone asked why. Nanxiang said: \"'The Longyang passion, first quality, ever vigorous in spirit.'\" Wenze said: \"Mine says it even more plainly: 'Male debauchery, first quality, stirring joyful hearts.' How extraordinary — why do all of them manage to mock him by name?\" Nanxiang said: \"This is the clear workings of Heaven's justice — retribution for a glib and mocking tongue.\" Gao Pin said: \"You are all guessing wildly — my opening line was not at all what you think. Since all your submissions were incoherent, I chose not to display your embarrassment — surely I'm not obliged to force you to be embarrassed?\" Everyone said: \"Those of us who sit the examination are not afraid of embarrassment — speak up.\" Gao Pin pointed at the clock and said: \"Look what time it is — haven't we had dinner yet?\" Everyone looked: it was already past the second quarter of the last night-watch. Wenze said: \"Is it or isn't it? Tell us, and then we'll eat.\" Gao Pin said: \"Suppose it is — can I not keep a slight advantage for myself?\" So they all sat down to dinner. When the meal was done and they had washed, seeing that the night had grown quite deep, they bid farewell and departed.",
    "As Ziyu was walking out, he said to the host: \"This garden is tastefully arranged — quite secluded and refined.\" Wenze said: \"This hardly qualifies as a garden — not even a tenth of Xu Duxiang's Yiyuan. Someday I'll go together with you for a stroll.\" While the host and guest were conversing, Gao Pin said to Zhongqing: \"Do you know there's been another exceptional person who has newly arrived in the capital?\" Zhongqing smiled: \"I suppose it must be one of Gao Pin's brothers.\" Gao Pin said: \"This person could indeed be my brother — I hear he is also from Nanjing, and is currently lodging in Hongji Monastery; but I've had no dealings with him. From what I've observed, he seems quite refined and elegant, and his circumstances appear quite affluent. Do you know who he might be?\" Zhongqing said: \"How strange — you live in the same monastery and don't recognize each other, yet you come asking me.\" As they were speaking, they had reached the gate; everyone got into their carriages and went their separate ways. This gathering of celebrated gentlemen had involved two rather vulgar outsiders seeking amusement where none was to be had for them — they had tried to make merry and found themselves without any.",
    "But please await the following chapter."
  ],
  8: [
    "Ziyu returned from drinking at Liu Wenze's home past the second night-watch. He first paid his respects to his parents, changed his clothes, and went to find Pincai and Yuanmao for a chat — but found everything quiet with the door closed. The serving boy Tiger'er came and said: \"After Young Master went out, the private secretary was invited away and won't return tonight. Masters Li and Wei went out after breakfast.\" Ziyu said:",
    "\"Where did they go? Still not back at this hour?\" And with that he went inside. Now, after Ziyu went out, Pincai and Yuanmao both felt bored. Since the sixth day, Yuanmao had seen some beautiful performers and longed to enjoy himself; on one hand, his father kept a tight rein on him; on the other, he had no money and could not do as he pleased. He said to Pincai: \"Today you really ought to treat me to a show.\" Pincai said: \"If I had money, wouldn't I take you without your even needing to ask?\" Yuanmao frowned and paced back and forth with his arms folded, then said: \"Just the two of us listening to the opera wouldn't cost more than three hundred big coins.\" Pincai said: \"If it were only three hundred coins, I could still manage — but just sitting there coldly watching a few pieces of opera isn't much fun. Haven't you seen how others bring cushions for the best seats, surrounded by a circle of performers, all laughter and chatter, so lively? After listening to a few pieces, they take the performers to a restaurant for wine. You haven't seen what it's like with performers attending the table — the scent of cosmetics and face powder, the mingling aromas of wine and flowers, swallows chattering and orioles singing, feigned anger and artificial smiles — all these charms never fail to bewitch and enrapture one. In truth the expense is limited — only seven or eight strings of copper cash — which in silver is only three or four qian. Back home down south, that wouldn't even cover one table of flower-wine entertainments. I just don't have those few strings, so I can't foot such a bill.\" Yuanmao listened and his heart burned with impatience, and he said: \"I have nothing left to pawn, but you still have a few pieces — why not pawn your things to treat me?\" Pincai said:",
    "\"If I pawn them, I'll have nothing to wear.\" Yuanmao said: \"Go borrow from the accounts room — you're quite friendly with the bookkeeper.\" Pincai said: \"How could I face that? We've only been here a few days. Borrowing money to go watch opera would make us look ridiculous.\" Yuanmao said: \"Then there's nothing to be done — can't pawn, can't borrow. Just forget it; I can't think of any solution.\" Pincai said: \"You have a solution — you have silver and won't use it.\" Yuanmao said: \"I have silver? I ran short on the road and no one has given me any since arriving in Beijing — where would I get silver?\" Pincai said: \"Your honorable father's trunk must surely have silver in it. Why not borrow a few taels temporarily, use them, and repay when I figure something out? You needn't tell him.\" Yuanmao said: \"That might not do — what if he finds out?\" Pincai said: \"If he doesn't find out, so much the better. If he does inquire, just say we borrowed travel expenses from Ye Maolin on the road, and he came today to collect, and it was too embarrassing not to repay him at once.\" Yuanmao said: \"That does sound plausible, but since it was never mentioned before, he might not believe it.\" Pincai said: \"Why wouldn't he believe it? Just say you always thought I had already repaid it, which is why it was never brought up.\" Yuanmao thought it over, went straight to his father's room, opened the trunk, reached inside, and found a large bundle — several tens of taels in all. Opening it, he saw many small pieces, so he selected five or six. He stopped there and was about to rewrap it. Pincai said: \"For opera and wine combined, it will run to about twenty strings of cash — you'd better pick out a couple more.\" Yuanmao picked out two more — totaling about eight or nine taels — put everything in a waist-purse and tucked it into his belt, rewrapped the remaining silver, replaced it, and locked the trunk. After eating, with his boy Sier carrying a horse-blanket, they hired a carriage and hastened to the opera theater.",
    "As they approached, Yuanmao asked: \"Which troupe shall we see?\" Pincai said: \"The Lianjin troupe, of course.\" They checked the billboard: the Lianjin troupe was performing at the Taihe Garden. Pincai was familiar with the area from the previous year's wanderings and led Yuanmao straight in. Pincai walked quickly ahead; Yuanmao, dazzled by the colorful decorations at the theater entrance — painted clouds, tigers, and flower displays, all in vivid color — kept looking about and walking forward without watching his feet. He didn't notice a low bench lying across the path just inside the threshold, tripped over it, and fell forward like an upended plant. Sier was just coming to help him up when a man stepped over, lifted Yuanmao to his feet with both hands, brushed the dust from his clothes, and said with a grin: \"Watch where you're going! That was quite a fall — lucky I pulled you up fast. If you'd hurt your shoulder or knocked your head, what then? You came for pleasure and would have found nothing but trouble.\"",
    "Yuanmao, embarrassed, mumbled a word of thanks and went in to find Pincai. They sat at a small table upstairs. The performance had already begun; two pieces had been done, and at this moment they were performing 'Picking Up the Gold.' Yuanmao, seeing no young female-role piece, wasn't interested and looked around in all directions — not only Qin Guan and the others were nowhere to be seen; even Ye Maolin was not on stage.",
    "He was sitting there without enthusiasm when suddenly a man walked over and nodded at him; Yuanmao felt the face was familiar but couldn't place it. The man went around behind Pincai and gave him a pat on the shoulder, saying: \"Having a fine time!\" Pincai turned and saw it was Zhang Zhongyu; his face lit up at once and he hurried to offer him a seat. He asked: \"Elder Brother, did you come alone, or with others?\" Zhongyu said: \"When would I find time to come watch opera? This morning I paid a call at the Hua residence at Jinchun Garden, then went to Master Xu's place at Yiyuan to discuss something, and then had lunch at Tianxiang Lou with Old Third Pan from the Qisheng Bank. Yesterday the Tang Monk from Hongji Monastery asked to meet me here about some business.\" As he spoke, he produced a jade snuff bottle and handed it to Pincai, who accepted it. Yuanmao now remembered seeing Zhongyu on the sixth day and they exchanged a few pleasantries. Zhongyu then passed the snuff bottle to Yuanmao; Yuanmao, not knowing what it was, treated it as medicine to be inhaled against heatstroke and immediately sneezed seven or eight times in succession, with eyes streaming and nose running, making Zhongyu and Pincai both laugh. Zhongyu asked Pincai about life at the Mei household; Pincai answered casually. Zhongyu said: \"Brother, if you are ever in need, come and talk to me.\" Pincai thanked him. Zhongyu didn't watch the opera but just chatted with Pincai. Pincai brought up Qin Guan; Zhongyu said: \"I've seen this person — the looks are fine, but he's rather cool in manner. Now he's at Xu Duxiang's Yiyuan every day. There's also Qi Guan, who is somewhat friendlier.\" Pincai said: \"This Qin Guan is the one our Mei Yuxiang values most.\" Zhongyu said: \"He likes Qin Guan too? I don't often see him out and about.\" Yuanmao had been listening in a daze; just then he saw a performer walk over, bow to Zhang Zhongyu, acknowledge Pincai, and also bend at the waist toward Yuanmao. Yuanmao rubbed his eyes, focused his gaze, and took a look — it was a performer he had seen at the guild hall the other day, whom Sun Sihui had praised extravagantly. The performer sat down beside Zhang Zhongyu, who remained rather cool. Pincai asked Zhongyu:",
    "\"What is his name?\" Before Zhongyu could answer, the performer eagerly replied: \"My name is Erxi — Second Joy.\" He then asked: \"What is your honorable surname?\" Pincai told him. He also asked Yuanmao: \"The other day at the Suzhou Guild Hall when you were watching the opera, you were talking with Elder Sun Master — do you know each other well?\"",
    "Yuanmao thought to himself: \"This performer is very attentive — he met me once and kept me in mind. How rare.\" And so he sat gazing at the man with both his amber eyes, studying him carefully. Erxi simply came over and sat on the same bench as Yuanmao, asking: \"Do you come to the opera often? Which troupe do you prefer?\" Yuanmao mumbled some vague reply. Erxi filled Yuanmao's short pipe, lit it, and passed it over; Yuanmao was greatly pleased — his two eyes grew even more watery and dewy, his heart pounded with joy, his throat itched with words he couldn't quite bring out. The performer stayed seated and didn't move. The next piece was \"Visiting a Brothel,\" and another performer came to sit beside Zhang Zhongyu and also didn't leave. Pincai asked his name: it was Baozhu. On stage the next piece changed to \"Woman Ballad-Singer.\" The moment the performer came on, Pincai recognized it was Qi Guan — beautifully dressed and fragrant, with the charm of a flower holding morning dew, the moon reflected in a quiet stream. Applause from both galleries was unending. Zhongyu said: \"That is Qi Guan.\" Pincai nodded with a smile: \"Qi Guan has become even better than last year.\" Yuanmao couldn't get a clear look, being busy talking with Erxi and glancing at Baozhu, with no attention left for the stage. Baozhu, seeing that Yuanmao was pleased with him, edged closer; Erxi blocked him and wouldn't let him approach. Baozhu went around and sat on the other side.",
    "Two dark-complexioned performers flanked one timid country patron, and had Li Yuanmao looking left and right, unable to attend to both. Baozhu and Erxi competed to stuff his pipe, competed to pour his tea — one pressing close to his shoulder, the other squeezing against his leg. Li Yuanmao was in seventh heaven, his heart blossoming with delight.",
    "When Qi Guan's piece was finished, he came off stage, removed his makeup, stood for a moment at the edge of the curtain, spotted Pincai, and gave him a slight smile. Pincai nodded back. He also noticed that Qi Guan was now dressed in fine furs with fashionable boots and hat — a completely different appearance from before — and thought he would surely come over to say hello. Indeed Qi Guan went into the dressing room; then after a wait, Pincai suddenly looked up and saw him already seated across the way in the gallery, together with the performer who had played 'Inscribing the Tune' the other day, in attendance on two magnificently dressed men. After a short while, those two men took them and left. Pincai was not a little deflated. Just then he heard Erxi ask Yuanmao:",
    "\"Where are we going today?\" Yuanmao, not understanding, simply nodded his head. Then he heard Baozhu ask: \"Which restaurant shall we go to today? I'll be in attendance on you.\" Yuanmao mumbled vaguely without answering. Erxi said: \"Today there are only two or three places open; if we go too late there may be no seats.\" Yuanmao thought to himself: \"These two are both very agreeable — and it looks as if both want to come. But I'm afraid the silver I brought may not be enough.\" He thought further: \"Giving the two of them twelve strings — and spending five or six strings on food and wine — should be sufficient.\" He said to Pincai: \"Shall we go?\" Baozhu took hold of Yuanmao's hand: \"Which restaurant?\" Pincai looked at the two performers and wasn't particularly pleased with either of them; but since Yuanmao was paying and it was nothing to do with him, he was happy enough for some lively company. He said to Zhongyu: \"Elder Brother, please come along — let's have a cup together.\" Zhongyu said: \"You go ahead; I still need to wait a while.\" Pincai said: \"Come with us — at this hour whoever he's waiting for probably isn't coming.\" He pulled Zhongyu along and they all came downstairs — only to realize he had forgotten to pay the theater fee. An attendant ran up and grabbed Sier: \"Not so fast — you haven't paid for your seats.\" Pincai stopped, asked Yuanmao about it. Zhongyu said: \"That's mine — just settle it with the manager.\" The attendant agreed.",
    "They had just left the theater when the two attendant-boys came trailing behind. Pincai asked Zhongyu: \"Which restaurant is good?\" Zhongyu said: \"The Chunyang Restaurant just ahead is quite fine.\" In a few steps they entered; the manager and staff all stood up calling out: \"Master Zhang, Happy New Year! May you gain promotion and fortune!\" and bowed; Zhongyu exchanged a few pleasantries. They chose a quiet corner table; Zhongyu sat first, Yuanmao second, Pincai third; Erxi and Baozhu shared a bench. A waiter brought tea and invited them to order. Zhongyu deferred to Yuanmao and Pincai; both in turn deferred to Zhongyu, who ordered braised tile-cut fish and stewed duck kidneys; Pincai ordered fried gizzards and ham; Baozhu ordered clam tofu and stir-fried shrimp; Erxi ordered stir-fried fish slices, soy-braised meats, and red-braised pork. Yuanmao said: \"I like chicken — I'll just have chicken.\" The waiter and Erxi both laughed. Two pots of wine were brought, along with several plates of fresh fruit and small side dishes; everyone drank a few cups. First to arrive were the fried gizzards, duck kidneys, ham, and fish slices. Pincai suggested playing finger-guessing games. Zhongyu said to Erxi: \"You set the game.\" Erxi said: \"Joy-in-joy, sorrow-in-sorrow. First cup lost — you must sing a little song; second cup lost — you must tell a joke; third cup lost — receive the skin-cup, a drink passed mouth-to-mouth.\" Yuanmao said: \"None of those three I can do.\" Pincai said: \"That won't do. Since that's so, you go first.\" Erxi filled three cups to the brim, set them out, and said: \"Master Li, your turn!\" Yuanmao squinted his eyes and said: \"Keep a close watch for me — my eyesight is poor and I'm afraid I'll make mistakes.\" He extended his hand, played one round against Erxi — and lost. Zhongyu said with a laugh: \"Please sing.\" Yuanmao said: \"Singing is completely beyond me — I'd rather drink an extra cup.\" Baozhu said: \"If you agreed to sing, you must sing.\" Yuanmao drank a cup and begged Baozhu to sing on his behalf. Erxi said: \"Singing by proxy earns a fine of ten cups.\" Baozhu didn't dare act as proxy. Yuanmao bowed to him and said: \"Good fellow, please sing for me — I don't know a single line of anything.\" Everyone saw he truly could not sing, and so Baozhu sang a 'Silver Button Silk' on his behalf.",
    "They played for the second cup — Erxi lost. Erxi said: \"There was once a host who invited guests but had no money to buy wine, so he placed an empty cup before each guest. The host said: 'Please drink.' The guests didn't move.",
    "He said 'Please drink' again. A guest said: 'The wine hasn't come yet — please drink what?' The host walked over, picked up the cup and peered into it, and said: 'Ah, I see — this cup of wine is bone-dry. Just drink it as it is.'\" Erxi then took the cup and brought it to Yuanmao's lips; Yuanmao was greatly amused and drained it in one go. Zhongyu and Pincai both called out: \"Bravo!\" Baozhu said: \"That joke is truly entertaining!\" and immediately filled a cup, brought it to Pincai's lips, and called out: \"Dear papa, drink this cup!\" Pincai was pleased and drained it.",
    "Baozhu filled another cup, brought it before Zhongyu, addressed him as \"Dear papa\" as well, and Zhongyu also drained it.",
    "They played for the third cup — Yuanmao won again. Erxi held a mouthful of wine, cupped Yuanmao's face in both hands, and poured it mouth-to-mouth into him. Yuanmao was happy but embarrassed; he had swallowed half of it when he suddenly lowered his head with a laugh — and that mouthful of wine shot back out through both nostrils, spraying like two streams, drenching the whole table. Li Yuanmao's forehead was both tickling and burning; he buried his face on Erxi's shoulder and couldn't raise his head. Baozhu laughed so hard he couldn't hold his seat and slid off the bench onto the floor. Zhongyu laughed so hard he spilled wine all over himself. Pincai laughed until his stomach ached and had to hold his belly with both hands.",
    "Erxi, still laughing, patted Yuanmao on the chest. Yuanmao finally raised his head, closed his eyes, opened his mouth — his nostrils still itching — and let out several more sneezes. After quite some time, he finally said: \"What's so funny?\" Seeing his expression, everyone laughed again for a while, then returned to eating.",
    "Erxi filled a cup and played finger-guessing against Zhang Zhongyu. Zhongyu lost; Yuanmao urged him to sing. Zhongyu said: \"That's not difficult.\" He drank a cup and sang a 'Ma Tou Diao' tune — everyone applauded: \"Excellent!\" The second cup — Zhongyu lost again and had to tell a joke. Raising his eyes, he noticed a small spirit shrine nailed to the wall, bearing a picture of the Wealth God Zhao Xuantan riding a black tiger. He said to Erxi: \"When you see a wealthy patron, you rejoice and say: 'The God of Wealth has arrived — he likes to spend money!' And when a poor patron sees a dark-complexioned performer, he goes pale and says: 'A tiger is here — he'll eat anyone he meets!' Now look up there — is it the God of Wealth riding the black tiger, or a poor patron straddled on a dark performer?\" Pincai slapped the table in delight; Yuanmao covered his nose trying not to laugh; Baozhu looked up at the shrine. Erxi filled a cup, brought it before Zhongyu, and said: \"You deserve a fine — that remark cut quite deep.\" Zhongyu took it and drank, saying: \"There are no poor patrons afraid of performers here.\" They played for the third cup — Erxi lost again and had to offer the skin-cup to Zhongyu. Zhongyu said: \"We don't need to do it that way — a moment ago Master Li didn't get to enjoy his cup properly; please offer this one to him instead.\" Erxi held the cup, took a small sip, then brought it to Yuanmao's lips. Yuanmao shook his head and clamped his mouth firmly shut. Erxi then straddled Yuanmao's lap, sat upright, cupped Yuanmao's head firmly, and tilted it upward; Yuanmao's face turned up accordingly. Erxi then pressed those pearl-like lips to that wide mouth and slowly let the wine trickle through — three slow mouthfuls in succession.",
    "Yuanmao was like one receiving the nectar of the gods poured over his crown — indescribably blissful. Everyone could hear his throat: gurgle, gurgle, gurgle — three swallows in succession.",
    "Erxi filled wine again; now it was Pincai's turn. First round — Erxi lost and sang a 'Nine Interlocking Rings.'",
    "Second round — Pincai lost. Pincai gave a small laugh first and said: \"A husband was away from home, so his young sister asked to sleep in the same bed as his wife. The wife, thinking of her husband, couldn't sleep, and asked the young girl to imitate her brother and press against her for a while. The wife was wonderfully pleased and said: 'Good as it is, you're not yet skilled — and it's all wet.' The young girl said: 'This is the first time — the second time I'll be more practiced. We should give it a name.' The wife said: 'It already has one — it's called polishing mirrors.' The young girl said: 'That doesn't fit — a mirror is round. Better call it offering the skin-cup.'\" This brought a wave of laughter quite delightful to hear; Yuanmao laughed until tears ran down his face and called out: \"You terrible person — you'll turn into a mute tomorrow!\" Baozhu laughed so hard he tumbled into Pincai's lap; Erxi came over and gave Pincai a tap, saying: \"Where does such a wicked person come from — the mockery cuts to the bone!\" Third round — it was Erxi who lost again. Erxi held the cup and said: \"How shall I sing? Give your instructions.\" Pincai immediately put on a stern face and said: \"You listened to Master Zhang's words but not mine — you look down on me. I won't let you off today.\" Erxi was startled: \"I haven't offended you.\" Pincai said: \"Even though you haven't offended me, you must still follow my word.\" Erxi said: \"Then tell me what you want.\" Pincai said: \"I want this skin-cup offered to Master Li again.\" Erxi brought the cup to Yuanmao; Yuanmao shook his head: \"Oh no — you've all been using me for your entertainment all day. This time I'm not falling for it again.\" Zhongyu said: \"Master Li, if you don't take this cup, I'll make up another joke about you.\" Pincai said: \"Pah! So it's just silver foil over a wax spearhead after all — utterly useless! The moment someone says something, you back down.\" Yuanmao thought: \"I can't outargue them. Never mind — nothing in the world is too hard if you're thick-skinned enough. What brings an advantage is always the better choice.\" He said: \"I'm nothing like you people, scared of shame. Come, come, come! Watch me drink!\" He turned the tables, cupped Erxi's face in his own hands, and drank the cup himself — and nobody could reasonably laugh at him for it. Erxi's game was done; Baozhu played the same game with Yuanmao, and Baozhu sang a 'Full River Red.'",
    "Pincai suddenly saw a monk walk in, saying: \"My dear Second Master! So you're here — I've searched seven or eight theaters without finding you anywhere!\" Erxi and Baozhu saw the monk and bowed in greeting; Pincai and Yuanmao also rose to welcome him. The monk bowed all around and sat down beside Zhongyu. Pincai observed the monk's appearance: a square face of dark purplish complexion, a thick two-strand mustache, about forty years of age; he wore a velvet monk's cap and a sapphire-blue silk fox-fur monk's robe, a yellow silk cord tied at his waist, cloud-cutout green satin soft boots on his feet — nothing of the look of a man who had renounced the world. He was clearly a meat-and-wine monk.",
    "And yet his manner was pleasant and genial, most skilled at being sociable. He immediately asked Pincai and Yuanmao their names and where they were lodging, then said to Zhongyu: \"Second Master, when tomorrow's business is settled — whether at the Suzhou Guild Hall or Tianqing Tang — let's invite your two companions and these two young performers, and have a thoroughly merry day together. Today I truly cannot linger — everyone on the other side has gathered and is waiting for you to come settle things.\" Zhongyu said: \"No need to rush — have a cup yourself and then we'll go.\" The monk smoothed his mustache, grinned broadly, drank a cup of wine, and ate a slice of ham.",
    "Baozhu said with a smile: \"Master Tang, you haven't brought your 'young master' along today?\" The Tang Monk laughed: \"Outrageous! A monk has no wife — where would a 'young master' come from?\" Erxi said: \"Your 'young master' looks just the same as a wife.\" The Tang Monk immediately reached a hand toward Erxi's face. Erxi laughed: \"I only said he looks like a wife — there's nothing wrong in that.\" The Tang Monk, seeing Pincai and Yuanmao present, pretended to be decorous, withdrew his hand, and said: \"Mocking a disciple of the Buddha incurs great sin.\" Zhongyu and Pincai burst out laughing. The Tang Monk urged Zhongyu again to get up and leave. Zhongyu said: \"A moment or two more won't matter.\" Erxi, seeing a gourd hanging on the wall, pointed at it and asked the Tang Monk: \"What does this look like?\" The Tang Monk laughed: \"It looks like your mouth.\" Erxi said: \"Wrong, wrong! How can it look like my mouth? It clearly looks like your head — smooth and bald, not a single hair.\" The monk said: \"Indeed it's bald. Haven't you heard it said that in heaven there are 'three luminosities,' while in the human world there are 'four luminosities'? These are: the monk's head — shaved smooth; the married woman's leg — polished smooth; the wealthy patron's money-purse — spent smooth; and the performer's mouth — eaten smooth.\" He burst out laughing, pulled Zhongyu to his feet and made to leave, then bowed to Pincai with a grin: \"I have been talking nonsense — please do not laugh at me, sirs.\" Zhongyu said: \"Let me settle the account first.\" Pincai said: \"Elder Brother, since you have business, please go — the bill is this younger brother's.\" Zhongyu said: \"Please have a few more cups, gentlemen; I'll be back shortly.\" With that he bid farewell and went out with the monk.",
    "Pincai and Yuanmao played another round of finger-guessing with Baozhu; Baozhu also offered the skin-cup twice. Erxi had more dishes brought; they made merry for quite a while longer. Half a candle had already burned down — it was past the first night-watch. The two performers were growing tired; the two attendant-boys stood by the outer door. Li Yuanmao, having entirely lost track of himself, had been gulping soup and wine; he had taken off his hat and his head was steaming like a rice-steamer. Pincai said: \"We should be wrapping up.\" He leaned close to Yuanmao's ear and said quietly: \"Take out that thing and go settle the bill at the counter.\" Yuanmao felt about his waist with both hands, then with a flustered expression said: \"How strange!\" He stood up, lifted the back hem of his gown, and said to Pincai: \"Look — is it there?\" Pincai said: \"Is what there?\" Yuanmao said: \"The waist-purse.\" Pincai said: \"No.\" Yuanmao's face went blank at once: \"How extraordinary — where did it go?\" Baozhu said: \"Lost something?\" Yuanmao didn't answer and rummaged through his breast again — nothing. His face went pale in waves. He undid his belt and shook it — nothing there either. Pincai grew anxious: \"Think carefully.\" Yuanmao said: \"What do you mean? You saw me with it.\" He lifted his robe again and felt all around his trouser waistband — nothing. Pincai pulled Yuanmao aside to the window; the two attendant-boys were also standing there, so they went out to the courtyard and said quietly: \"This is dreadful! Think — where did you lose it?\" This prompted Yuanmao: \"Oh! I know now. When I was going into the theater, I fell — and someone came and pulled me up and brushed off my clothes. That person must have taken it.\" Pincai said: \"I didn't see you fall — when was this?\" Yuanmao said: \"There was a low bench lying across the path at the entrance; I wasn't watching where I was going and went down just inside the door.\" Quick-witted as Pincai was, he could think of nothing to be done.",
    "Erxi came out and said: \"What are you two discussing in the courtyard?\" The two came back inside and sat down. Erxi said: \"It's getting late.\" He leaned close to Yuanmao's ear and said: \"Come back to my place — I'll take care of you.\" Yuanmao heard this and felt simultaneously happy and flustered, his face burning; he just stared blankly at Pincai. Baozhu and Erxi couldn't make out what was the matter. Pincai had no choice but to say to Yuanmao: \"Now that this purse of silver is lost, what are we to do?\" Yuanmao said: \"There was also something else inside — it was all taken together.\" Baozhu said: \"What happened?\" Yuanmao said: \"The silver — at the theater entrance, a pickpocket cut it away.\" Erxi said: \"I came out with you and didn't see any pickpocket.\" Yuanmao said: \"It happened going in.\" Erxi said: \"It happened going in, yet you watched the opera for so long and drank for so long without noticing? Only now, about to leave, you bring it up? Isn't it more like you forgot to bring it and it's still at home?\" Yuanmao grew agitated: \"That's outrageous — do you think I'm making excuses?\" Erxi gave a cold laugh. Pincai said: \"That's not what we mean — it's not as if we came here without money planning to cheat you. Master Li was careless and lost it; naturally we couldn't say so at the time. Trust us — tomorrow when we come to watch the opera, we'll bring everything we owe, Baozhu's share included.\" He asked Baozhu at once: \"Do you believe us?\"",
    "Baozhu said: \"I have no particular reason not to believe you. Besides, this is our first acquaintance — you would certainly not deliberately cheat us. But when we go back we must give an account to our master. And especially at New Year's, it's even harder to go back empty-handed — not only would it be difficult to face master, it would be unfair to the boys who attended us as well.",
    "\"We only ask that you can somehow manage something to spare us this difficulty.\" He then said to Erxi: \"Brother Xi, isn't that right?\" Yuanmao said: \"I'm telling you the truth, but you won't believe me. Today I had eight pieces of silver — well over ten taels in total — loose in a waist-purse, which was taken, purse and all. To ask us to go borrow from somewhere at this hour — where would we go? This is a truly unfair position to put us in.\" Erxi sniffed and said: \"It's not all that late yet. Why don't you send your boy back to fetch more? We can wait here a bit.\" And he pressed Yuanmao back into his seat. Yuanmao shook his head: \"That's absolutely impossible.\" Erxi said: \"If it's impossible, then you planned this from the start. We spent the whole day in your company as complete strangers, serving wine, offering the skin-cup — Master Li, if you can think of that as sufficient friendship, well and good. But we too are driven by necessity — wanting to please our patrons, earn a few strings of cash, make a showing for our master. If things always go this way, we won't be able to make our living. Master Li, since you refuse to send someone home, here is what I ask — please be kind enough to come back with me and say a word to my master yourself. As for whether you give anything — that doesn't matter at all.\" Baozhu said: \"What he says is perfectly right — as long as our master knows what happened, that's all we ask; we don't need any money.\" Li Yuanmao was reduced to utter helplessness — face flushed deep red, not a word he could say. Pincai had no choice but to say: \"We've now made each other's acquaintance — is this to be the only time, with no future dealings? You want him to go back with you and explain to your master in person — your master would certainly not refuse, but I have never before seen the case of a performer calling out his own master to settle the account.\" Baozhu said: \"This is only because we don't know each other yet. Once you've been a patron for three or four years and we're well acquainted, it would never come to this.\" The two of them were at an impasse. Then Sier came in and said: \"Elder Sun Master is here too — he just stepped out.\" Pincai saw an opening: knowing Sihui was acquainted with these performers, he said: \"Go and ask Elder Sun Master to come in.\" Sier hurried out; Sihui was still at the counter in conversation, accompanied by a performer who had already gotten into a carriage and gone. Sihui couldn't quite recognize Sier, but hearing someone asking for him, he came back in, and now recognized Yuanmao and Pincai. Seeing Erxi and Baozhu, he laughed: \"Today you two gentlemen — what merriment this is!\" Yuanmao and Pincai bowed; Erxi and Baozhu made their salutations; everyone sat back down. Pincai explained the whole situation: how Yuanmao had lost his silver today, had nothing to pay with now, had promised to bring it tomorrow, and the performers were refusing to accept this. Sihui pushed up his hat, rubbed his red nose, pointed at Li Yuanmao, and delivered a long improvisation stringing together phrases from the Thousand Character Classic — his packet of 'gold born of beautiful waters' had become 'fallen leaves adrift in the wind'; instead of going to 'execute the thieves and robbers' he sat here 'dispersing his cares in ease'; he must think Sihui an 'old acquaintance' and so sent for him urgently 'to requite gladness and joy'; seeing the two performers in their 'vigorous and resplendent' condition, something had suddenly been 'pushing forth new shoots' inside Sihui as well; and so on through a parade of absurd classical phrases culminating in suggestions of what Yuanmao might do with the performers to ensure everyone's joyful satisfaction. Wei Pincai and Li Yuanmao were already convulsed with laughter; the two performers could not fully follow — it sounded like reciting opera lines — and they too laughed uncontrollably. Yuanmao spluttered incoherently; Pincai had no choice but to say he himself would take on the obligation and settle with them tomorrow.",
    "Sihui heard this and was startled: \"One whose strength cannot lift a hundred jun cannot bear such a heavy burden on a long road — I fear I am unable.\" Pincai could only entreat him again at length; Sihui reluctantly agreed, saying: \"What can be given tomorrow shall be given — a man without integrity, who knows what becomes of him?\" He then addressed Erxi and Baozhu: \"Come, let me speak with you — why not take your leave now? Tomorrow I shall personally deliver to your door — do not press people too hard.\" The two performers could not follow all of this; Sihui had to repeat it in plain speech. Baozhu and Erxi, seeing Sihui had taken on the matter, were left with no recourse and made a reluctant show of gratitude and took their leave. Sun Sihui, afraid they might also try to make him pay the restaurant bill, hurried away immediately.",
    "The waiter came in and read through the account item by item; everything together came to fifty-six strings seven hundred and eighty copper cash. Yuanmao, hearing this, stuck out his tongue and said: \"What discount can you offer?\" The waiter said: \"Full price — no discount.\" Li Yuanmao counted on his fingers and said: \"At ten-tenths that's five thousand six hundred seventy-eight coins — two thousand eight hundred thirty-nine hard-cash coins — very fair indeed. I shall certainly come here often to patronize your establishment.\" The waiter laughed: \"We don't offer discounts — it's fifty-six strings seven hundred and eighty copper cash.\" Yuanmao said: \"How can there be so much?\" The waiter said: \"We dare not overcharge.\" Pincai said to Yuanmao: \"You're drunk — don't talk so much. Let's go settle at the counter.\" They went to the counter; the waiter recited the total again; the manager worked his abacus and looked at Pincai and Yuanmao: \"You two came with Master Zhang, and Master Zhang left already — are you his fellow-provincials or what?\" Pincai said: \"We are relatives; he had business and left first.\" The manager asked: \"May I ask your honorable names? Where are you lodging? What brings you to the capital?\" Pincai answered briefly, then asked for a credit slip. The manager hesitated and said: \"At New Year's money is tight — today being the very first day of business — and by long custom one always hopes for a few cash payments in the first month. And besides, today is the first time we have had the pleasure of your company.",
    "\"Master Wei is a relative of Master Zhang, and it would be awkward for me to refuse you a credit account. But please remember — don't let it drag on too long.\" He handed a slip to Pincai; Pincai felt deeply indignant inside but wrote out the full amount, added two strings for the wine-service, and noted down: 'Mingke Alley, Mei Residence, Wei surname.'",
    "The manager glanced at it and filed it away. A waiter brought out a lantern; Sier took it, and they left the restaurant. The two walked home step by step, heads bowed in silence. It could truly be said: they had come in high spirits and departed in deflation. But as for what happened next, please await the following chapter."
  ],
  9: [
    "When Wei Pincai and Li Yuanmao arrived home it was past the third night-watch. The Mei household had already barred and bolted its gates; Fourth Boy knocked for a long while before anyone came to open them. The two entered their rooms, and Pincai could not help voicing a few reproaches at Yuanmao for carelessly losing the silver. Yuanmao had no answer. They each slept. The next day, they had no choice but to prevail upon Xu Shun to borrow a ten-string promissory note, which they divided into two drafts, wrapped with a letter, and had Fourth Boy deliver to Ye Maolin to distribute between Erxi and Baozhu. Later, when Ziyu inquired, Pincai and Yuanmao simply claimed that Zhang Zhongyu had treated them to opera and a restaurant, and concealed the truth.",
    "Two days later came the Lantern Festival. Li Xingquan took Yuanmao to the year-end banquet at the guild hall, while Pincai had gone out to view the lanterns and had not yet returned. Ziyu sat alone with nothing to do when, just then, Mei Jinjin came in and announced: \"Young Master Liu, Young Master Yan, and Young Master Wang invite the young master to go out and view the lanterns — they are all waiting at the gate.\" Ziyu reported to his parents, Mei Jinjin had the carriage harnessed, and Yun'er followed along. Zhongqing and the others were waiting in the carriage; seeing Ziyu come out, they stepped down. Liu Wenze said: \"On such a fine night, worth a thousand gold pieces, let us take advantage of the lantern-lit moon and walk — it would be better. Have the carriage follow behind; we can ride back.\" Ziyu agreed. The four strolled slowly, chatting casually along the way, and in no time arrived at the lantern market.",
    "The moment they entered the lantern arbors they were engulfed in a sea of people, with carriages and horses jostling among the crowds. Ziyu and the others strolled slowly along the shop verandahs. Every shop was hung with festive lanterns and colored streamers — glass lanterns, painted gauze lanterns, lantern screens displayed inside, lantern towers built outside the doors — and the lantern vendors set out their wares in dense, layered rows. Fortunately the streets were broad, otherwise one could not have moved a step. There were also people at the doorways setting off firecrackers and rockets: shooting stars chasing the moon, nine dragons playing with a pearl, fire trees and silver flowers, gongs, drums, silk strings and wind instruments — a scene of perfect peace and abundance. Everyone was in high spirits, celebrating the Lantern Festival. There also passed a procession of fine carriages and ornate sedans, all with curtains open, maids and servants sitting on the carriage edges burning superior incense. The ladies inside gazed left and right through large glass windows. Wenze, Wang Xun and the others each looked attentively; some were beautiful, some not, but in festive dress and jewels under the lamplight, all added a few degrees of color. As the four walked they could not stay abreast, some falling ahead, some behind; after perhaps seven or eight carriages had passed, a few more pulled up to join the front of the procession, jamming it so it could not move.",
    "At that moment Ziyu was in the lead and had just been blocked by a carriage axle, unable to pass. Wenze noticed a young woman inside the carriage, quite handsome and exquisitely dressed. Ziyu happened to be squeezed against the front of the carriage; Wenze saw the young woman's eyes fixed unblinkingly on Ziyu, while Ziyu had lowered his head and had nowhere to go. He saw the young woman put one hand on the carriage door and leaning forward, extended one foot — a three-inch lotus hook, slender and fitting no palm. He saw her first arrange the opposite leg, then draw the lotus foot back in and sit properly, the slender hand also lowering. He saw her turn toward Ziyu and give a sweet, gentle smile.",
    "Wenze tugged at Wang Xun's sleeve and murmured softly: \"Look — it seems she is taken with Yuanxiang and wishes to show off her lotus feet.\" Wang Xun nodded. Zhongqing, standing behind Wenze, added: \"How do you know it is not you she fancies?\" Wenze laughed: \"I don't think so.\" Then he called quietly: \"Yuanxiang, what is there to look at in 'The Shi Justice Cases'? — you keep staring at those pairs of lanterns.\" Ziyu turned his face around, only to meet the young woman's gaze directly; seeing she was still watching him from inside the glass window, he felt quite awkward.",
    "After a moment the carriage moved on. Wenze noticed that hanging from the carriage side-panel was a small foreign-style lantern painted with two ruyi scepters, with four small characters on its face reading: Qisheng Hao Pan — the Pan family of the Qisheng trading house. Behind it followed another carriage.",
    "In this carriage too was a young woman, yet strikingly ugly — her face a mass of dark, fleshy features, plastered with powder that, even in the night, showed a purplish, greasy sheen. Her dress, however, was of every fashionable variety, and she was making affected gestures inside the carriage, fluttering her silken sleeve-cloth. Wenze noticed that a character on her lantern read \"Hua\" (Flower). The carriage moved and passed on. The four wandered on to a few more spots; the streets began to narrow again. Wenze said to Ziyu: \"Just now that young woman was so attentive in her glancing at you, yet you gave her no response and kept looking at that old gauze lantern — what is the meaning of this? Could a young woman like that not merit even one glance in return?\"",
    "Ziyu laughed: \"I paid no attention to her, nor did she look at me — she was sizing you gentlemen up.\" The four friends bantered and laughed as they moved on to admire a few more lantern displays.",
    "Just then a crowd of women came rushing toward them on foot in a disorderly cluster. The four men counted some ten or more of them — some in silk robes, some in plain cotton — with oiled hair and powdered faces, giggling and chatting, their sleeves fluttering like frantic butterflies threading among blossoms, their figures darting like startled snakes from the grass. They showed no concern for whether others might give way and came barging straight through. One of them, apparently with natural feet, planted a foot squarely on Wang Xun's boot.",
    "Wang Xun's new black boot had its side smudged and his foot was trodden on with considerable force — he reckoned the blow carried at least thirty catties — but he could say nothing; he quickly stepped aside. Then he saw a woman of some thirty years, of considerable height, wearing high-platform shoes and looking up at the lanterns. Her foot caught on a brick, and she lurched to one side, nearly toppling — and just happened to grab onto Ziyu's chest, clutching it tight, to steady herself. Ziyu nearly fell as well, his heart leaping in fright, utterly bewildered as to what was happening. The woman let go and giggled; the whole crowd squeezed past. He heard one of the women say: \"These gentlemen are truly infuriating — eyes wide open staring at people. Can it be there are no women at home, that they block the road on purpose and won't let anyone pass?\" Zhongqing and the others heard this and burst out laughing. Wang Xun said: \"What rotten luck — that woman's foot hurt me badly, and she still says we blocked the road to stare at her.\" Ziyu had just recovered his composure and said: \"Just now when she grabbed me I was genuinely frightened. I thought she'd mistaken me for someone and was about to start a brawl — is that not bad luck? Who would have imagined that among women there could be such uncouth creatures? Comparing them to the lady we saw in the carriage just now — truly there is a difference of heaven and earth.\" Wenze laughed loudly: \"Without climbing a high mountain, you do not see flat ground. So you have been harboring private thoughts all along, silently taking the measure of things. That young woman in the carriage — earning this praise from you is not a bad return for all her attentive glancing.\" Ziyu smiled faintly and said: \"These lanterns have nothing much to see, and the road is hard to walk. Why not take the carriages back?\" Wang Xun replied: \"Too early — going back serves no purpose either.\" Wenze said: \"Let us go to Yiyuan to see the lanterns there — I hear they have fine lantern riddles too; going to guess a few would be amusing.\" Ziyu said: \"I do not know the host; and since it is evening and we are in plain clothes, how can we go?\" Zhongqing said: \"That is no obstacle. Xu Duxiang is one of our sort — he places no importance on formalities or appearances. Moreover, his garden also has Xiao Jingyi, who is even more an upright and free-spirited person. Going for a stroll would be perfectly fine.\" All three wished to go, and Ziyu agreed to join them. So everyone got into their carriages, the pages riding on the carriage footboards, and headed for Yiyuan.",
    "After about two li they passed Nanheng Street and alighted at the gate of Yiyuan garden. A long wall of tiger-stripe stone — rough yellow fragments cemented together — enclosed the estate; the garden gate was framed by a five-colored ceremonial arch built of bolts of silk, with only a square opening of some five feet for the two large characters \"Yiyuan.\" Below hung four consecutive rows of eight five-colored glass lanterns painted with flowers. Through the garden gate was a set of eight oil-green gold-speckled screen doors. Beside the gate stood a table surrounded by six or seven people writing out lantern riddle strips. Beside it was a long bench with sachets, firecrackers, and the four treasures of the study arranged on it, prepared as prizes for correct answers. In the very center of the overhead canopy hung a five-colored brocade pleated cloud-pavilion, from which was suspended a gourd-shaped glass lantern.",
    "Further inside was a square pavilion built against the wall, surrounded by railings on three sides. A flat rectangular glass lantern hung above the pond, covered with strips of paper; below it a cluster of some twenty people had gathered. Climbing the pavilion steps, they found eight lantern riddles written out facing them. Just as Zhongqing was about to read them, a Yiyuan servant came up to greet them and said: \"Why not come inside to look around?\" Wenze asked about the host; the man replied: \"Our master is out at a dinner and has not returned — Master Xiao is at home.\" Wang Xun said: \"Let us guess a few lantern riddles first and then go in — there is no hurry.\" So they all looked at the first riddle: \"Roosting together, stable and undisturbed, recognizing the Lu family's tortoiseshell rafters.\" Below was a notation: a line from the Book of Rites. Ziyu was pondering it when he heard Wang Xun ask Zhongqing: \"Could this be: 'knowing that one can dwell in peace, like the swallow who is settled and orderly'?\" Zhongqing replied: \"I believe so.\" They looked at the second: \"Though ten thousand waters and a thousand mountains separate us, the wild goose's letter and the fish's message always arrive.\" Notation: a line from the Book of Changes. Zhongqing said: \"This must truly be: 'proceeding through danger yet not losing one's integrity.'\" Ziyu said: \"That fourth one — 'fallen blossoms, one person standing alone; fine rain, swallows flying in pairs' — it must be the character for 'liang' (both/together).\" Wenze said: \"This seventh one: 'In the desolate village, rain and dew — sleep comes early; at the roadside inn, wind and frost — rising must be late' — these two lines on an ancient person's name, I imagine must be 'Xi Fugong.'\" Ziyu agreed. Wang Xun said: \"Let us go submit our answers.\" Zhongqing said: \"Let us simply solve all four remaining ones too, then submit — there is no hurry. That second one, 'A crow's back lit by the setting sun' — it is a line from the Book of Rites; it must be: 'the sun is in the Wing constellation.'\" Ziyu said: \"That seven-character regulated verse on eight titles of ancient Music Bureau songs — the first couplet: 'I remember how at your home, morning and evening, the Qinhuai River wound its fragrant banks in several bends' — the answer must be 'Midnight Song' and 'Jinling Ballad.'\" Zhongqing said: \"The lower line of the second couplet, 'the moon's shadow particularly dislikes the dark and dusty world,' is 'Night Yellow'; but what of the upper line, 'Let not the thread of rain urge the flower-petals along'?\"",
    "Wenze said: \"Perhaps it is 'Wash Not the Red' (Xi Hong). The third couplet — 'Through the long night I hear the broken water-clock dripping; in middle age I pour out my heart and yet labor in vain' — must be 'Five-Watch Bell' (Wu Geng Zhong) and 'Mourn Not, Joy' (Mo Chou Le).\" Wang Xun said:",
    "\"The seventh line, 'Thirty-six pairs of crows fly in steady formation,' is unmistakably 'Crow with Eight or Nine Chicks' (Wu Sheng Ba Jiu Zi).\" Zhongqing said: \"The last line, 'She should send the distant traveler on the road to Zhangtai,' must be 'Breaking the Willow' (Zhe Yang Liu). As for the fifth entry — 'Born in the years of chen and si' — on a line from the Classic of Poetry, and the eighth entry — 'Not a word written, yet the style is perfect' — on a Tang poetry line, I cannot solve those.\" Just then someone was heard asking: \"'Born in the years of chen and si' — could that be 'Where there are vipers and serpents'?\" The man at the garden gate replied it was not. Wenze said: \"Do not let others take it from us — let us go submit.\" Everyone descended the pavilion steps. Ziyu said: \"As for that Classic of Poetry one, I have thought of it — it must be 'not belonging to the fur-bearing creatures.'\" Zhongqing said: \"Precisely right. That answer was truly remarkable to have thought of.\"",
    "Wang Xun said: \"The one on the Tang poetry line — could it not be 'Yin Zi writing in the air'?\" Wenze replied: \"Let us go and try submitting it.\" Everyone went to the garden gate and reported their answers one by one; from inside came \"Correct\" for each one, until the very last, which no one had solved. Wang Xun said: \"'Certainly poetry has no rival.'\" From inside came \"Correct\" for that as well. A person came out with a new lantern and swapped it for the one already hanging. From behind the screen door someone came walking out: Ziyu saw a man of about thirty, with clear brows and fine eyes, an air of lofty elegance, dressed in understated, refined clothing, strolling over in leisurely, graceful fashion.",
    "Wenze, Zhongqing, and Wang Xun all stepped forward at once to greet him, addressing him as Master Jingyi. The man exchanged courtesies with the three, then bowed to Ziyu, who hastened to return the salutation.",
    "Wenze thereupon said to Xiao Cixian: \"This gentleman is Mei Yuanxiang, the peerless scholar of this age. Has Master Jingyi not had occasion to meet him?\" Cixian replied: \"Meeting such a distinguished personage today is truly my great good fortune.\" He then invited the four men inside. Ziyu said: \"Being in plain clothes this evening, I fear it is somewhat discourteous — please allow me to pay a proper formal call another day.\" Cixian laughed: \"Master Yuanxiang is the foremost distinguished scholar of the age — such trifles should not matter. Moreover, the host is not at home; we are simply gathering to chat informally. Please do not stand on ceremony.\" Ziyu found it hard to persist in declining, and had no choice but to follow him out of the pavilion. On either side, at ten-pace intervals, stood ground lanterns, illuminating a flat open space; not far ahead rose a sheer cliff face. At the foot of the cliff was a five-bay veranda-room with carved windows and fine lattice-work, beneath whose eaves hung over twenty foreign glass lanterns of uniform style, all of the western fragrant-lotus type. Cixian invited them inside; guest and host took their seats. He was acquainted with Wenze, Wang Xun, and Zhongqing, and had only an exchange of heartfelt admiration to make with Ziyu. Ziyu, seeing his speech proper and his bearing extraordinary, knew this was a man of distinction, and the two found themselves thoroughly congenial. After some conversation and tea, a page-boy came from the inner room and brought out prize gifts, arranged on the table — fine Hu brushes, Hui ink-sticks, Duan inkstones, and elegant fans. Only the prize for Ziyu's solved riddle — \"fallen blossoms, one person standing alone; fine rain, swallows flying in pairs\" — was the heaviest: a jade qin zither in an old brocade case. Ziyu saw the qin and felt a sudden vague sense of memory. Finding the prize too generous, he repeatedly declined with Zhongqing and the others. Cixian asked:",
    "\"Was it you, Master Yuanxiang, who solved the qin riddle?\" Ziyu replied: \"I merely guessed at random; I could not possibly presume to accept such a generous prize.\" Cixian replied: \"This was set by the garden's master for Du Yunong, and carries a particular meaning — pray do not decline. An inscription still needs to be engraved on the qin; I will send it once that is done.\" With this he had a page-boy carry the jade qin back inside; the remaining prizes were given to each guest's attendants. The fact was that because Qin Yan, when Duxiang was composing the riddle, had loved to recite the couplet about \"fallen blossoms,\" Duxiang had asked Cixian to make this a riddle with the qin as the prize — embedding within the playful game the intention of making a match. Not only did Ziyu not know who Du Yunong was; even Zhongqing, Wenze, and the others had not been fully informed. When everyone asked, Cixian did not immediately explain, and replied only that all would be known in due time.",
    "They conversed idly for a time. Zhongqing remarked that it was a pity that the capital, despite being in the very season of lantern-viewing, had no southern-style novelty lanterns — a considerable diminishment of the festival's splendor.",
    "Cixian replied: \"You gentlemen wish to see lanterns? That can easily be arranged. Though these are not from the south, they are by no means unrefined.\" He had a page-boy lead the way; skirting along the sheer cliff face, they walked the length of an arrow-shot, then mounted a succession of stone steps, climbing over thirty tiers, turned a corner of the cliff, and found themselves on a white-stone terrace on the other side.",
    "At the center stood a round pavilion, all of whose windows were inlaid with whole panes of glass — concave on the inside, convex on the outside.",
    "Entering the pavilion, they found the floor laid with a velvet carpet; in the center stood a large round table surrounded by fan-shaped stools, fitted together in a perfect circle, precisely encircling the table. Because the night air was mild, Zhongqing and the others sat on the outer gallery railing. Page-boys brought round tea-tables, one before each guest; tea was served. Looking upward, a hazy moon shed diffuse light while sparse stars lay scattered; looking downward, drifting mist hung light and vast, the void and water both clear and fresh — one felt the spirit broadened and the heart refreshed. Looking far into the distance, one could just make out overlapping peaks and towering pavilions, dimly visible and unclear — not a single lantern light yet to be seen. Suddenly, from the Lake Tai rock cave in front of the pavilion, a pair of bright lanterns lit the way for two jade-like figures. Coming closer, one proved to be Yuan Baozhu, the other Jin Shufang. Zhongqing asked: \"Where have you been hiding?\" Baozhu replied: \"We were playing chess in the little boat room at the front.\" Wenze said: \"Have you performers been keeping your eyes open?\" Baozhu and Shufang both smiled. Of those present, only Ziyu did not know them — though he had seen Shufang's \"Preface to a Song\" that day, that had been in full makeup and costume. Now he saw them in plain dress: their flesh fragrant and smooth, of jade-pure clarity and crystalline freshness; Baozhu standing slender as jade, too delicate to bear the weight of clothing. He thought: \"These two in beauty seem comparable to Qin Yan — but what their characters are like, I do not know.\" Just as he was thinking this, he heard below the terrace a cloud-gong strike once; in the far tree-groves across the way, several shooting-star rockets rose, and immediately a succession of clay-cylinders followed — one after another, near and far, some two hundred in all. Orchid-flower bamboo-arrows shot across the garden, setting the green bamboo groves and winter trees aglow as if painted in firelight. After the clay-cylinders had burned for a while, several large cannon shots were heard; yellow smoke rose from the groves in every direction; then a thousand firecrackers rang out in unison, and countless fireworks lit up all around: on one side, nine-linked lanterns; on another, the Myriad Years of Joy; on one side, cannon battering Xiangyang City; on another, the burning of Red Lotus Temple; on one side, the Great Fire of Efang Palace; on another, the burning of troops at the Red Cliff. In the distance, golden drums beat in a furious gallop, evoking the charge of ten thousand horses; fire-birds and fire-mice flew like a hundred flashes of lightning, darting and weaving through the entire garden — Ziyu and the others gazed in dazzled astonishment.",
    "Wenze thought to himself: \"What a pity there is no wine — we are squandering this magnificent evening of flowers and lanterns.\" Just then he heard Cixian say: \"On such a splendid night, why do you gentlemen not drink a few cups?\" He at once ordered wine to be brought. In a short while the page-boys brought four jars of wine and handed them to Baozhu and Shufang, who went before each guest, removed the teacups, and lifted a layer off the tea-tables — revealing inlaid tiered boxes within, each containing twelve plates of fruits and dishes, with silver cups and ivory chopsticks fitted inside — all of exquisite ingenuity. Baozhu and Shufang poured the wine; Cixian said \"Please!\" and everyone began drinking in slow, relaxed sips. After several rounds, the cloud-gong below the terrace struck once; the fireworks in all directions died away. Then on every treetop, countless colored lanterns trembled into view — birds, flowers — scattered and layered, growing more and more numerous; in a short while the entire surrounding area held some several thousands. When all the lanterns in the trees had been lit, on the ground several hundred cloud lanterns began to dance, their five colors swirling and folding, circling and spiraling. At the sound of the gong, a golden dragon emerged dancing — over ten zhang long, soaring and twisting like a real dragon. Presently, from within the Immortal's Grotto came a green dragon dancing; then another white dragon; from the groves came a black dragon; in the light of the fireworks came a fire dragon — each over ten zhang long. They tumbled together, dozens of gong-beats roaring like crashing waves, their shifting smoke-clouds truly magnificent to see. Then several dozen large and small ball-lanterns rolled out among the cloud-dragons, spinning and turning, drawing the five dragons to spread their claws and toss their horns, twisting and grasping in a frenzy — everyone in the party was completely transfixed.",
    "Suddenly a Yiyuan servant came forward announcing: \"Young Master Shi has arrived!\" Everyone rose to look; they saw two attendants supporting Shi Nanxiang, who came stumbling and staggering, step by halting step, up the stone stairs.",
    "Just as he reached the terrace, he suddenly heaved in a great surge of vomiting.",
    "After retching for a while, he shook his head and stood panting at the edge of the terrace, pointing at the assembled company and saying:",
    "\"You are having such a fine time, such a fine time...\" — and then could say no more. A servant first brought a bowl of warm water for him to rinse his mouth; then he managed: \"What a fine time you are all having!\" Zhongqing said: \"Sit down first; rest and then tell us.\" They helped him up into the pavilion; he sat on the floor. Baozhu and the others went up to greet him; he nodded to them. Wenze asked: \"Where have you been drinking to this state?\" Nanxiang shook his head again. Baozhu whispered a few words to Cixian; Cixian instructed a page-boy to bring a small gold box, from which he took out a pill, placed it in a bowl, dissolved it in boiling water, and gave it to Baozhu, who carried it over to Nanxiang and bent down to offer it to him. Nanxiang shook his head refusing. Baozhu said: \"This is a sobering draught — drink it and you will be well.\" Nanxiang's mind was clear enough; he drank the draught, closed his eyes and said: \"I am drunk and wish to sleep — my friend may go.\" He lay back as if to sleep. Cixian, fearing he might catch cold, had servants carry him to a kang in the small inner room, helped Nanxiang inside, and pulled the door behind him. Ziyu asked Cixian what the pill was. Cixian replied: \"It is something Duxiang himself makes. No matter how dead-drunk one may be, one pill and all the stored wine is consumed, with the vital energy additionally restored — it is called the Immortal Peach Life-Prolonging Pill.\"",
    "Before long, they saw Nanxiang already open the door and walk out, saying: \"Delightful! Delightful! I nearly became Liu Xuanshi who slept a drunken sleep of three years — I was nearly buried alive.\" Zhongqing said: \"Your head has cleared — why are you still talking drunken nonsense?\" Shufang had wrung out a damp cloth; Nanxiang wiped his face and asked: \"Where are we?\" Everyone laughed. Cixian smiled and said: \"Zhujun, this is Yellow Crane Tower — how can you not recognize it?\" Nanxiang looked around and burst into wild laughter, saying: \"So Jingyi is here too — when exactly did all of you arrive?\" Everyone laughed again. Baozhu and Shufang drew him outside the pavilion and showed him around a while; only then did Nanxiang understand they were in Yiyuan, and thinking it through carefully, laughed loudly again. Just as he was about to ask something, the entire garden erupted: golden drums filled the sky, explosions burst in continuous succession, wind-swift fire-fast, sounds and spectacle overwhelming — from all eight directions, a hundred beasts converged, all fashioned from five-colored silk gauze, their fur realistically painted: on one side, a cavalcade of elephant lanterns; on another, a cavalcade of tiger lanterns; on one side, a charge of rhinoceros; on another, a charge of lions; plus black bears, white bulls, spotted leopards, and yellow bears — strange and wondrous, numbering in the hundreds, each with four small wheels beneath, pulled by people at a run, emitting smoke from their nostrils and belching fire from their mouths — as thunderous and electrifying as if the earth had collapsed and the mountains fallen. Ziyu and the others were so astonished their skin rose in gooseflesh. On this side a hundred beasts; on that side five dragons — merging together, black fog rising to the sky, firelight covering the ground — truly evoking the ferocity of the Red Cliff battle. After a long commotion, suddenly a single crack was heard; in mid-air a nine-burst cannon was set off. In an instant the firelight below scattered like shuttles; in a moment the whole garden fell utterly silent, not a single lantern to be seen. The distinguished scholars all cried out in praise together: \"Truly the artistry of heaven and earth — the strategy of Sun and Wu — we have never seen the like!\" Zhongqing said: \"Counting this one display, I calculate there must have been at least a thousand people. Where did the garden find so many people?\" Cixian replied: \"If one uses people for everything, of course there are many. These five dragon lanterns use people throughout. The hundred beasts and cloud lanterns use wheels to move — one person can operate several. The beasts leading beasts require advance and retreat, fast and slow, in coordination — this too requires rehearsal. Today's actual number was probably still fewer than two hundred.\" All the distinguished scholars were full of admiration. Cixian invited his guests down the hill to a spacious place to rest a while; the company was reluctant to disperse so soon and followed him down the hill.",
    "Threading through several grottoes fashioned to resemble immortal caverns, they followed a path lined with tree-screens and bamboo until they reached a pear-blossom garden. Cixian ushered the guests inside. Passing through several more sets of gates, they entered a five-bay Western-style building, three rooms wide and two rooms deep, facing east. The interior was appointed with extraordinary elegance: lacquered beds, painted writing-tables, golden tripods, and bronze vases — all pleasingly beautiful. In the center hung a plaque inscribed with three characters, \"Yichun Pavilion\" (Lodge of Welcoming Spring), in the calligraphy of Qu Benli; on one side hung several panels of small-script calligraphy by Sulan; on the other side, several panels of ink-painted orchids by Yuan Baozhu. In the middle of the floor stood a lamp imitating an ancient chicken-foot design in silver, some four feet tall, holding a nine-petal lotus lamp-basin above, burning nine wicks, filling the whole room with bright light. Everyone sat down. Cixian said: \"Why not drink a few more cups?\" Everyone replied: \"We have already drunk too much in the pavilion — we can do without wine; let us have a quiet, simple gathering.\" Nanxiang said: \"I have no idea how my drunken state cleared — what happened?\" Baozhu replied:",
    "\"We who were sober today watched others in their cups — that also had its charms.\" Nanxiang said: \"Yaoquing, I recall that you poured a great bowl of wine down my throat.\" Everyone laughed and said: \"This fellow is still befuddled from drink — how much did you actually consume in the end?\" Nanxiang said: \"Today I went with Gao Zhuoran and Zhang Zhongyu, bringing Wang Jingfang and Li Peixian, and spent the whole day drinking at the winehouse — I don't know how much it was; they all got drunk and left before me. I saw Jingfang home, then dropped by Yong'an's place on the way; learning he had gone out to see the lanterns, I went too. I don't know what the carriage-driver was thinking — he just pulled me here. The people at the garden gate said you were inside viewing the lanterns, so they helped me in.\" As he spoke, he pulled from his lapel a bundle of lantern-riddle strips; everyone looked: one read \"A spring breeze song for which the embroidered silk wrapping costs a fortune\" and another read \"Little horse, run quickly along\" — both were theater-title riddles, one being \"Enjoying Autumn\" (Shang Qiu) and the other \"Chasing the Carriage\" (Gan Che). Baozhu said to Shufang with a laugh: \"One is yours, one is mine — he solved them both.\" Nanxiang laughed: \"So you two made them!\" He then turned to Ziyu and said: \"Yuanxiang, what do you make of these two? Judging from their looks and talents — am I telling the truth or not? Now look at this —\" he pointed at the calligraphy and paintings on the walls — \"this is painted by Yaoquing, that is written by Xiangwan. Compare the outside crowd of pseudo-scholars — can any of them match these real performers?\"",
    "Ziyu laughed: \"I long ago made my acknowledgment — yet my elder brother still dwells on it at every moment.\" Nanxiang declared: \"Henceforth, among your company, when you meet us you must not bow in salutation — you may only address us by our courtesy names. Violators will be penalized.\" Baozhu said: \"This is exactly the same disposition as Duxiang and Jingyi — so it shall be.\" Wang Xun said: \"Yuanxiang, look at this Yaoquing — how does he compare to what you saw at the theater last year? Could the real and the fake possibly be confused?\" Ziyu laughed: \"Can rubble and stone presume to the name of pearl and jade? That person's name should be changed.\" Baozhu was puzzled and asked Wang Xun; Wang Xun told the story of having seen the fake Baozhu the previous year and of Ziyu's mishearing. Baozhu gave a sweet smile.",
    "Thereupon Shufang drew Wang Xun into a game of chess while Wenze looked on. Ziyu and Baozhu admired the ink-painted orchid, praising it without end. Nanxiang, Zhongqing, and Cixian sat together on the Drunken-Scholar's Couch in easy conversation. Nanxiang said: \"Brother Jingyi, do you still recall those fine lines: 'Only the poet-drunkard is famed among the scholars — drunk and chanting, he may ascend Yueyang Tower'?\"",
    "Cixian replied: \"That cannot compare to the celebrated lines: 'I only grieve that the immortals' elixir is scarce, preventing wine from filling the whole of Dongting Lake.'\" Zhongqing said: \"If wine filled Dongting Lake, I fear Shi Zhujun would long since have drunk himself to death. Master Jingyi, why not paint him a 'Drunken Bamboo' picture tomorrow.\" Cixian nodded and smiled faintly. Taking advantage of the others' conversation, Ziyu quietly asked Baozhu: \"These past two days, have you seen Qin Yan from your troupe?\" Baozhu, hearing this, looked Ziyu over carefully and asked: \"Are you and Qin Yan close friends?\" This question rather caught Ziyu off guard; quite embarrassed, he could only answer: \"We have never met — I merely admire his name.\" Baozhu replied: \"He is no longer called Qin Guan; his name has been changed to Qin Yan. What a pity you were just a step too late today — Duxiang took him to a dinner engagement.\" Ziyu thought to himself: \"It is as if fate is sparing in its dealings with us — I do not even have the fortune of a proper conversation with him.\" As he thought, he stared absently at Baozhu; Baozhu too was staring absently at Ziyu — four eyes met and both fell into a trance. Liu Wenze, turning his head and seeing the scene, gave Ziyu a light tap on the shoulder and said quietly: \"Is Yaoquing fine?\" Ziyu, thinking he was asking about Qin Yan, replied: \"His performance of 'Startled by the Geese' is straight from heaven among immortals.\" Baozhu gave a languid smile. Ziyu came back to himself and realized the question and answer had been mismatched — luckily what he had said was not wrong. He followed Wenze over to Nanxiang's side. Zhongqing asked Cixian whether any fine lantern riddles had been solved by others. Cixian replied: \"Yesterday there were two love-letters that a young man solved; I happened to have a matter to attend to and stepped away, and did not get his name and address.\" Zhongqing asked Cixian for the rough drafts of the two love-letters; everyone read them together. One contained herb names concealed within it, the other flower names. They read:",
    "\"Last autumn, in the eighth month (Xixin — asarum). We gathered in joy at Jin Gate (Suhe — styrax resin). Huang first smiled and beckoned (Qianniu — morning glory). Fragrant as the oil-walled carriage that came to meet me (Cheqian — plantain). Though my talent is but a peck and a bushel (Baihe — lily). I am privileged to follow in your perfumed train (Xiangfu — nutgrass). The road ahead stretches ten thousand li, regretting this search for rank and title (Yuanzhi — polygala, also meaning 'distant ambition'). A thin shadow dwelling alone, still hoping to continue my life (Duhuo — lovage, also meaning 'live alone'). Asking who governs the heart of the grass (Wangsun — bedstraw, also meaning 'prince'). Fearing that the flower-tidings come too often to urge me on (Fangfeng — siler, also meaning 'guard against the wind'). Though powdered like a fair young gentleman, the black silk not yet old (Heshouwu — fleece-flower root). Yet the fragrant attendant's jade bones have already grown cold (Fubi — rubus, also meaning 'rotting servant-girl'). Only by maintaining propriety can one protect oneself (Fangji — stephania). Alone through the remaining years, enduring the winter (Rendon — honeysuckle). Counting on fingers, the gourd-harvest time is nearly upon us (Danggui — angelica, also meaning 'should return'). This heart's bitterness is entirely dissolved (Gansui — euphorbia, also meaning 'sweet follow-through'). This letter arrives before you (Baiji — bletilla orchid, also meaning 'white and immediate'). I hope for a brief reply (Xuanfu — elecampane, also meaning 'return revolving'). The fifteenth of the fifth month (Banxia — pinellia, also meaning 'middle of summer'). Respectfully bowing before your jade presence (Bailian — ampelopsis, also meaning 'white and modest').\"",
    "Ziyu exclaimed: \"What a fine puzzle in the guise of a Lantern Festival riddle!\" Baozhu said: \"I love most the couplet about the 'powder-faced young gentleman.'\" Nanxiang said: \"Among us here, only Yuanxiang qualifies as a powder-faced young gentleman — do you admire him?\" Baozhu gave a little smile; Ziyu's cheeks turned thoroughly red in embarrassment. Then they read the reply letter:",
    "\"A foot away, reluctant to convey its fragrance (Suxin — jasmine, also meaning 'plain heart'). A fragrant letter suffused with crimson (Cihong — barberry, also meaning 'prick the red'). Bowels twisting as if turning back upon themselves (Baijie — hundred-knot vine). The year cycling round, now renewed (Siji — four-seasons flower). Remembering the joyful meeting of that former night (Yehe — night-blooming jasmine). The farewell banquet, the parting flight (Jiangli — Siberian iris, also meaning 'about to leave'). The jade maiden playing pitch-pot, faintly opening fragrant cheeks in a smile (Hehe — lily magnolia, also meaning 'together smiling'). Golden lotus steps on the ground, small steps soft in the dust (Hongjhizhu — azalea). Ever since the distant search for Chang'an, only grieving over shyness and timidity (Minang — opium poppy, also meaning 'rice sack'). Lingering by the Luo River bank, suddenly light meets light (Shuixian — narcissus, also meaning 'water immortal'). For you, with rouge and powder cases, your beautiful form is naturally fine (Fuli — a supporting plant, also meaning 'support beauty'). For me, already with snow-thread and frost-temples, all worldly habits forgotten (Laoshaonian — a plant name, also meaning 'old yet young'). Past ninety days of spring light, a few fallen petals (Baixihong — crape myrtle, also meaning 'hundred-day red'). Praying that through all the great Dharma-realm, lotus-pairs bloom for three lifetimes (Xifanlian — a variety of lotus, also meaning 'western barbarian lotus'). Reckoning the jade ladle at the conjunction of yin and mao (Zhijia — a plant, also meaning 'fingernail'). May the jeweled box divine the starry meeting (Qianniu — morning glory, also meaning 'lead the ox'). Cut into frosty silk (Jianqiuluo — a type of cloth/plant, meaning 'cut autumn gauze'). Wishing to send but repeatedly delayed, hovering back and forth (Paihuai — a plant name, also meaning 'hesitate and linger'). The sixteenth of the second month (Changchun — jasmine, also meaning 'everlasting spring'). At the yin hour, another respectful salutation is enclosed (Huci — a plant, also meaning 'tiger thorn').\"",
    "Zhongqing said: \"These two love-letters, even setting aside the riddle element, are supremely fragrant and beautiful in their own right. Moreover the concealed herb names and flower names fit each context perfectly without the slightest strain. The person clever enough to solve them must truly be a peerless wit — yet what a pity we do not know who it was.\" Wenze said: \"Are both these letters written in Master Jingyi's hand?\" Cixian replied: \"The original letter is in Duxiang's hand.\" As he spoke, Wang Xun had already finished his chess game, having lost three stones to Shufang. Ziyu, the night being already deep, took his leave together with Nanxiang and the others. Ziyu also conveyed that when Duxiang returned to the garden he would first pay his respects, and that he would come again in earnest on another day; Cixian replied affirmatively and saw each guest to their carriage. So they scattered. Hear what follows in the next chapter."
  ],
  10: [
    "After the gathering dispersed, Xu Ziyun made his way back alone, for the night was already deep, past the hour of Hai, and he went straight to his residence.",
    "Ever since his first audience with Ziyun the previous year, Qin Yan had followed the company of celebrated beauties daily to the Yiyuan garden, and Ziyun's fondness for him was no less than that he bore Baozhu. Yet Qin Yan was by nature proud and aloof, cold and reserved, ill-suited to social niceties; no amount of gold could buy so much as a smile from him. Whatever antiques, delicacies, or fine garments he desired, Xu Ziyun provided without stint, and could truly be said to have treated him with the utmost care. Qin Yan was not unaware of this kindness, yet he counted him only half a soulmate. From the very day he entered the capital and caught sight of Ziyu on the road, he had recognized him as the one who had rescued him from the pit in his dream, and had carried him in his heart every moment since. Then on the day of the opera at the Gusu Huiguan, seeing him seated among a company of young gentlemen that included Wei Pincai and Li Yuanmao, and asking after Ye Maolin, he learned for the first time that this young gentleman's surname was Mei — fulfilling the omen of the plum blossom tree. From that moment, a thread of secret longing, like a catkin mired in mud, had become hopelessly entangled about him.",
    "During these evenings he dreamed of Ziyu several times — hazy, indistinct visions in which they were sometimes laughing together, sometimes weeping together.",
    "Or he would dream of setting out on a long journey while Ziyu saw him off, clinging to his sleeve and clasping his hand. Then of returning from that distant journey to find the two of them sitting knee to knee in intimate conversation. It was all murky and unclear, and when he woke he could not recall it with any precision. He knew Ziyu was a scion of a great family, yet he knew nothing of his temperament and predilections, nor how he compared to Duxiang; and he feared he might be one of those young men of wealth who were shallow, heartless, and fickle, or one of those arrogant lords of luxury who expected others to fawn upon them. Yet looking closely at the warmth in his bearing, he seemed a man of genuine goodness, and surely could not be so. Then one day he dreamed that Baozhu had taken on Ziyu's appearance and performed the scene of the \"Spring Dream\" with him, and he could make no sense of this at all. The following day, when Ziyun came to the garden, Cixian spoke at length of the young gentlemen who had come to view the lanterns the previous evening, and praised Ziyu's talent and appearance effusively. Hearing this, Ziyun was inwardly quite pleased and said: \"This Mei Yuxiang — though he does not know me, I happened to see him last year. Our families share old ties: his late paternal grandfather, the Grand Secretary, and my late great-uncle, the Censor-in-Chief, were classmates and the closest of friends. Mei Yuxiang's outward appearance admits of no criticism whatsoever, but I know nothing of his character.\" Cixian replied: \"As steadfast as gold, as smooth and warm as jade, without the slightest air of displaying his talents or asserting himself. Though we were together only a brief time, I have already seen his quality.\" The two talked for a long while, and Ziyun did not go out that day. By the hour of You, Baozhu arrived at the garden with Qin Yan. Seeing them, Ziyun laughed and said: \"Yu Nong, this time things have gone well for you — I have found your match. Do not forget me when the time comes.\" This so startled Qin Yan that he immediately flared up, and unable to hold back the tears that streamed from his eyes, he said: \"Duxiang, you have treated me with such great kindness, never looking upon me as a low creature, and I feel your generous grace deeply. Even if I have failed in some service to you, and you are angry with me, hate me, scold me, or drive me away, I would not dare to resent you. But you need not go so far as to bring someone in to ruin me. May I ask: what is this talk of 'finding a match'? I would like a clear accounting.\" Ziyun, knowing he had spoken rashly, felt embarrassed and had no reply; he had no choice but to ask Baozhu to accompany and comfort Qin Yan with kind words, and then, using the pretext of viewing paintings, he slipped away to Cixian's room.",
    "Here, Yuan Baozhu used his handkerchief to wipe away the tear-stains on Qin Yan's face, then described Shi Nanxiang's drunken antics and his adorned appearance in such amusing detail that Qin Yan cheered up, and they sat together on the daybed. Baozhu said: \"Among those who solved the lantern riddles yesterday, there was one called Mei Yuxiang, no more than seventeen or eighteen years of age, with the finest appearance of them all.\" Qin Yan said: \"His surname is also Mei?\" Baozhu said: \"He asked after you.\" Qin Yan pondered a moment and said: \"This Mei person — did he say he had met me before?\"",
    "Baozhu said: \"That is just what was so strange about it. Because he asked after you alone, I assumed you must have drunk together somewhere at some time. I asked him if he was on intimate terms with you, and he hedged a bit, saying something like 'not previously acquainted, though I have long admired you by reputation,' which did not sound like someone who had met you. He also said he found your performance of the 'Spring Dream' scene very fine.\" Qin Yan thought: \"Might this Mei-surnamed gentleman be the Mei young master who was watching the opera that day?\" He therefore asked Baozhu: \"This Mei young master — was he in the upper eastern gallery of the Gusu Huiguan on the sixth day of the first month?\" Baozhu laughed: \"I wasn't performing that day, so how would I know whether it was him or not?\" Qin Yan sat lost in thought for a long while, then asked Baozhu again: \"Does his appearance resemble, more or less, that of Lu Xiangwan from our troupe? Just that the eyes are somewhat longer and seem to radiate a brilliant light, and the nose is a little straighter and gives the whole face an air of elegance — is that right?\" Baozhu laughed: \"From the way you describe him, you must know him quite well. Why hide it?\" Qin Yan had no answer. Recalling the dream, he said: \"How many years have you been close with this Mei gentleman?\" Baozhu said: \"We only met yesterday.\" Qin Yan said: \"I don't believe it. If you only met yesterday, how could he have taken your form the evening before?\" Having said this, Qin Yan covered his mouth with his sleeve and laughed. Baozhu was thoroughly bewildered: \"Yu Nong, what nonsense are you talking?\" Qin Yan said: \"It's not nonsense — you had taken on his appearance and were even singing the role of Liu Mengmei.\" Baozhu was more baffled than ever: \"Are you still play-acting, or were you dreaming?\" Qin Yan smiled sweetly and then gave a full account of the day the Mei young master watched the opera and of the dream in which Baozhu had transformed into him. Baozhu said: \"This person is indeed good-looking. If you were truly to pair up with him and perform this 'Spring Dream' scene, you would make a fine match. It's just a pity I can't transform.\" Qin Yan fell silent for a long while. \"What a pity I was out yesterday and missed seeing him.\" Baozhu, having gauged that Qin Yan's affections were fixed on Ziyu, then said: \"Do you realize now that you wronged Duxiang today?\" Qin Yan said: \"How so?\" Baozhu said: \"The match he said he had found for you — do you know who it is?\" Qin Yan said softly: \"Could it really be the Mei young master?\" Baozhu said: \"If not him, then who?\" Qin Yan said: \"I thought Duxiang meant to harm me. Little did I know that the one who solved the lantern riddle was the very same person.\" Baozhu said: \"From where I stand, you and this Mei young master have a great deal of predestined affinity. Let me go tell Duxiang to invite him tomorrow so you can meet — what do you say?\" As she spoke, she rose and made to leave; Qin Yan caught hold of her sleeve and said: \"You are being reckless again. For one thing, I have never met the Mei young master, and I don't know for certain whether he is who I think he is — if it turns out he is not, what then? And even if it is him, I have no idea what kind of person he is inside. For another, I just quarreled with Duxiang a moment ago — how could I suddenly turn around?\"",
    "While this lively conversation was going on, Xu Ziyun and Xiao Cixian had long since slipped around into the adjoining side room and overheard every word quite clearly. Now the door was pushed open and Ziyun and Cixian walked in together smiling. The moment Qin Yan saw them he flushed crimson with embarrassment and turned his back to sit facing away. Ziyun said: \"Yu Nong, do you still blame me or not?\" Qin Yan lowered his head and said nothing. Ziyun continued: \"Even granting that I spoke amiss, it was an unthinking remark.",
    "Besides, you are not a girl — what is there to fear in talk of a 'match'? Could I really be marrying you off to Mei Yuxiang?\" This made Cixian and Baozhu both burst out laughing. Baozhu said: \"Say no more — he has already understood. Why don't we simply invite Yuxiang here to meet him?\" Ziyun said: \"I have my own way of determining whether it is he or not.\" Baozhu and Qin Yan dined at the Yiyuan that evening, then sat on until the second night-watch before returning home.",
    "The following day, Ziyun went to call upon Ziyu. They exchanged words of mutual admiration and longing, and agreed to meet for an intimate dinner on the evening of the nineteenth. On his way back, Ziyun stopped at the residences of Wang Xun, Liu Wenze, and Shi Nanxiang to pay visits, but found none of them at home. Returning home, he reflected: \"This Mei Yuxiang is indeed everything his reputation says. Yu Nong is already drawn to him; once they meet, it goes without saying that he will become Yuxiang's man.\" Then he thought further: \"Yu Nong's temperament is something most people can never quite fathom. If a single word goes wrong, a decisive break is possible. Even if Mei Yuxiang is a man of deep feeling, he may not be able to understand and accommodate Yu Nong as I do.",
    "According to what Yaoqing said, Yuxiang knew nothing at all of the name that was changed for Yu Nong — which shows that the two have never been truly intimate.",
    "He has only watched one opera, and I should think his admiration is no more than appreciation of Yu Nong's face and figure. There is no certainty that Qin Yan alone fills his heart. I shall put him to a test.\" He thought further: \"If on the nineteenth I simply have Yu Nong serve wine beside him, this being their first meeting, even if both have feelings for each other it will be impossible to speak plainly, and no one else will be able to discern it. I shall now employ the stratagem of substituting one flower for another: first I will hide Yu Nong, then find someone who resembles him, and use carefully chosen words to probe Yuxiang — watching to see how he responds will reveal everything naturally.\" His mind made up, he disclosed the plan to Cixian and Baozhu.",
    "On the nineteenth, all the arrangements were put in order. At the hour of Shen, Mei Ziyu arrived at the Yiyuan garden. The host went to welcome him and they walked together to the Meiyan. This Meiyan was one of the garden's most celebrated spots, and just then the plum blossoms were in full bloom. At the foot of the great rocky hill, amid a dense grove of trees, stood several dozen chambers arranged in five distinct clusters: buildings surrounded by blossoms, blossoms surrounding buildings, layer upon layer, so that at a distance the trees and structures seemed indistinguishable from one another.",
    "The antiques and furnishings within were too numerous to describe. One simply felt that to be there was to be inside the flowers themselves — no need to invoke the immortal realm of Luofu; this was truly the ocean of fragrant snow that mortals may know.",
    "The central pavilion was the heart of the plum grove, where five chambers had been combined into one long room, which was then subdivided into five distinct spaces. Above hung a plaque bearing the two characters \"Meiyan.\" To either side was a couplet: \"Ten thousand plum trees — the nose attains virtue; / One ancient house on the hill — the heart finds peace.\" In the center hung a portrait of Lin Hejing, the hermit poet who loved plum blossoms. Facing it stood a daybed of zitan rosewood carved with plum-blossom designs, upon which rested a guqin wrapped in antique brocaded silk. Ziyun invited Ziyu to take his seat inside. Ziyu said: \"The other day I had the boldness to come here and try the lantern riddles, already an uninvited guest. Today I am once again graced with a summons and seated in your exquisite studio — your kindness, good host, surpasses what I can properly receive.\" Ziyun said: \"Master Yuxiang — you are as auspicious as a lucky star, as honored as a favored minister. I deeply regret not having received you sooner. That you now condescend to come is a matter of sincere delight to me.\" Ziyu then asked: \"Are there other guests at today's gathering? Why do I not see Master Jingyi?\" Ziyun replied: \"Jingyi has a small matter to attend to and will join us shortly.\" Then, indicating the qin on the daybed, he said: \"Today's banquet has been arranged expressly for the occasion of Yu Nong presenting this qin; it would not be fitting to invite other guests, lest the occasion for intimate conversation be spoiled.\" Ziyu said: \"I was just about to inquire: why, simply for solving a lantern riddle, was such a generous gift made? And who exactly is this Yu Nong, for whom you make so much of the occasion?\" Ziyun then directed his page boy to untie the silk case and, with both hands, to deliver the qin to Ziyu, saying: \"There is an inscription on the back of the qin — please have a look.\" Ziyu received the qin and examined it: jade tuning pegs, pearl fret-markers, plum-blossom grain, serpentine crack patterns — a magnificent ancient qin of scorched paulownia wood. On the back were engraved two lines of Han-dynasty seal script that read:",
    "The qin's heart runs deep, deep; / The qin's virtue is serene, serene. / Its owner is fair as jade; / Together they appreciate the music.",
    "Below the four-line inscription was a further line in cursive running script: \"Xu Ziyun of Shanyin, on behalf of Yu Nong Du Qinyan, presents this as a gift for the refined appreciation of the celebrated scholar Yuxiang.\" Below this were engraved two seals: one in intaglio reading 'Composed by Cixian,' and one in relief reading 'Carved by Jingyi.'",
    "Ziyu, recalling what Baozhu had said about the change of name, now understood that Yu Nong was none other than the qin-player — and was overjoyed beyond all expectation. He made a deep bow of thanks and then directed his page boy to rewrap the qin. Ziyun, to test him, said: \"I have heard that you and Yu Nong are on the most intimate terms — is that true?\" Ziyu replied: \"My family is kept under such strict supervision by my father that ordinarily I am confined to the house. It was only on the sixth day of the first month, when I went to the Gusu Huiguan, that I saw him perform one scene of the 'Spring Dream' — someone there told me his name was Qin Guan, and I found his beauty and artistry both admirable.",
    "Not until the other day, here in your company, did I chance to learn that your honor had changed his name to Qin Yan. I have in fact never met him in person. As for the talk of intimacy — that is surely a misconception. You might ask Qin Yan himself when you see him.\"",
    "Ziyun said: \"You admired him well, but do you know that Qin Yan harbors considerable feeling for you?\"",
    "Ziyu laughed. \"The word 'feeling' is not a light matter. Even in our circle of literary friendships — whether by affinity of spirit, where at first meeting one feels as if reunited with an old friend, or by covenant of principle and morality, where souls commune across a thousand li — there must be mutual affection before one can speak of 'feeling.' There is simply no such thing as bearing feeling toward a stranger. With regard to Qin Yan and myself: we are still strangers to each other. I have already put him out of my heart; how then can he bear feeling toward me?\" Ziyun said: \"In your estimation, how does Qin Yan compare with Baozhu, whom you saw the other day?\" Ziyu, aware that both Qin Yan and Baozhu were Ziyun's favored companions and not wishing to rank them, said: \"When it comes to appraising beauties, one must observe their bearing after they have fully dressed for the stage, and then observe their true appearance after they have removed their makeup. And one must be long acquainted with their interests and conversation before one can know their true nature. I have seen both Baozhu and Qin Yan only once each — one in stage costume, one without makeup — just as one catches a fleeting glimpse of flowers while galloping past; it is impossible to discern any depth.\" Ziyun said: \"Supposing someone were to offer Qin Yan to you, what would you do?\" Ziyu replied: \"To cherish the fragrant and treasure the beautiful is a feeling natural to all men. Even if I have no golden chamber in which to conceal such a treasure, I have you, Master Duxiang, to serve as the presiding host of this romantic world — I need not worry about a celebrated flower falling into neglect.\"",
    "Just as they were speaking, Baozhu arrived, adorned like a flowering branch, accompanied by someone — and when Ziyu looked, it was none other than the very person for whom he had yearned day and night: Qin Yan. His heart gave a secret start of surprise. Then he heard Ziyun say: \"Yu Nong, your heart's beloved is here — come and be introduced.\" Qin Yan smiled sweetly, walked forward, and made a greeting bow; this left Ziyu neither knowing whether to sit or to stand, and he simply stared blankly at Qin Yan. Qin Yan then made a greeting bow to Ziyun as well. Baozhu said: \"Yuxiang, following Zhujun's instructions I shall dispense with ceremony.\" Ziyu said:",
    "\"To be free of such formalities is the finest thing. Why does Yu Nong not do likewise?\" Qin Yan smiled faintly but said nothing. Ziyu looked at Qin Yan, then at Baozhu, and felt that Baozhu was considerably cleaner and more vivid in looks, considerably lighter and more charming in speech, considerably more poised and graceful in manner. Inwardly he thought to himself:",
    "\"So this is all there is to Qin Yan. How is it that those two fleeting glimpses of him from the carriage were so remarkable, and that his stage performance had such richness of spirit and manner? And yet Wei Pincai praised him without end, and Xu Ziyun's affection for him runs so deep — it truly defies understanding.\" As these thoughts passed through his mind, a faint trace of disappointment appeared in his expression. Ziyun had already detected it and was secretly pleased that his stratagem was working so well. Baozhu said: \"You have long yearned for each other, and today is your first meeting — surely you ought to say a few heartfelt words and be affectionate. Why are you both cold as ice and not speaking a word?\" As she spoke, she took Qin Yan's hand and placed it in Ziyu's. Ziyun said: \"Quite right — don't let our presence here inhibit you.\" This only made Ziyu feel all the more awkward — taking the hand seemed wrong, yet refusing to seemed wrong too — so he made a pretense of needing to step outside, and went to look at the plum blossoms through the window for a while. Only after Ziyun had urged him repeatedly did he return inside with slow and hesitant steps. Ziyun said: \"It is too open here. Let us move to the inner room.\" Baozhu walked up to the mirror screen and gave it a press; the screen turned on its axis like a door, and the party walked through, after which the screen closed itself again. Ziyu looked about the inner chamber: its layout was that of five plum-blossom petals, though not overly spacious. While he was carefully examining the room, a page appeared outside the glass window holding a red visiting card and reported: \"Master Jia requests an audience.\" Ziyun said: \"I am entertaining a guest. Tell him to come another time.\" The page replied: \"This master says he has something urgent and has already come inside.\" Baozhu said: \"Is that not Jia Ren, Old Master Jia?\" Ziyun said: \"Who else but him?\" Baozhu said: \"I was just looking for him. Why don't we all go and greet him?\" Ziyun said: \"We have an honored guest here — how can I leave him unattended?\" Ziyu said: \"Since we are on intimate terms, why stand on such ceremony?\" Ziyun begged Ziyu's pardon, Baozhu reminded Qin Yan to keep the guest well company, and together they went out.",
    "The mirror screen was pulled shut again, leaving only Ziyu and Qin Yan in the room. Qin Yan invited Ziyu to take a seat on the daybed, while he himself stood beside him, eyes fixed upon Ziyu without blinking, until Ziyu began to feel abashed and lowered his head.",
    "Qin Yan tilted his body sideways, leaning against the low table beside the daybed, one hand propping up his fragrant cheek, and in a coquettish, honeyed voice said: \"Master Mei, were you not the one watching me perform in the gallery on the sixth day of the first month?\"",
    "Ziyu gave a single nod. \"Do you know of the longing I have felt for you?\" Ziyu shook his head. Qin Yan said: \"The lantern riddle about the jade qin — was it you who solved it?\" Ziyu nodded again. \"What a fine mind. And do you know Duxiang's plan?\" Ziyu shook his head once more. Qin Yan raised Ziyu's chin with one finger and said: \"I heard from Baozhu that behind my back you asked quite a lot about me — I am touched by your feeling. Now we have met today, and there is no third person here. Why be so distant?\" Ziyu, pressed to the point where he had no retreat, forced himself to reply: \"Yu Nong, I have heard your temperament is extremely proud and aloof, and so I respect you for it. How is it that, just a few days after arriving in the capital, you have lost your true nature?\" Qin Yan said:",
    "\"So you are ignoring me because you look down on me — no wonder you are so cold and indifferent. It is only a pity that I wasted my earnest feeling.\" As he spoke, a flush of red spread across his face; the waves of his eyes swept toward Ziyu, and their gazes met exactly. Ziyu lowered his eyes, his own face reddening, feeling deeply ill at ease. Qin Yan let his half-drowsy eyes linger there, and then tilted his fragrant shoulder sideways so that his cheek pressed right against Ziyu's cheek. Ziyu shifted aside, and Qin Yan leaned directly into Ziyu's arms, laughing softly. Ziyu, now genuinely annoyed, pushed him away and stood up, then could only say: \"True friendship, between people, lies in knowing each other's hearts. By behaving this way, you are treating me as if I were someone who frequents the pleasure quarters. Though the company of beauties may serve to lighten the idle hours, it must remain within the bounds of a gentleman's conduct. To stoop to the very lowest, to cease striving for what is noble — even those who merely wish to be respectable in their community would disdain to do so. I have long held this to be contemptible behavior, and take it as a warning to myself. How could I steel myself to act against conscience and transgress all moral bounds? Though your station is that of an actor, you can still make your name through beauty and art. What pleasure can there be in the vile and the dissolute? I truly do not understand what kind of heart would seek it. At first I thought you were a person of elevated feeling and unconventional spirit, difficult to win — and I had aspirations of drawing near you. Now you are like this: not only have you wasted your own feeling, but I too deeply regret having invested mine in error.",
    "As for Wei Pincai's praises — they were certainly not to be trusted. But what a pity that Xu Duxiang, loving widely with feeling spread too thin, takes pleasure in the flattery and servility of others — that is truly the habit of a pampered young lord. In truth, how could it move me?\" So saying, he angrily made to press the mirror screen open and leave. But the screen gave no hint of yielding; push and press it as he might, it simply would not open.",
    "Just as he was at an utter loss and on the verge of despair, a soft sound was heard at the mirror screen, and Ziyun, Cixian, and Baozhu, all smiling, walked in from the other side of the screen. At that instant the figure of Qin Yan vanished without a trace, leaving Ziyu dazed and bewildered. Then he heard Ziyun laughing: \"What an admirable Liu Xiahui who can sit unmoved in the presence of a beauty — I offer you my deepest respects. Though I must say your censure of me, Xu Duxiang, was somewhat too cutting.\" Ziyu turned his head — and realized that the whole party had been in the adjoining suite on the other side of the mirror screen all along. He exchanged greetings with Cixian, then immediately took his leave of Ziyun: \"Today I forgot an important matter before leaving home. I must come again another day to impose upon your hospitality.\" Ziyun laughed: \"Brother Yuxiang, you must be vexed with your younger brother because of what happened just now. The wine table is already laid in the inner room — please have a cup, and allow me to present myself in sackcloth and beg your forgiveness.\"",
    "Cixian said: \"I have only just arrived, and was looking forward to a long and candid conversation — but your honor intends to leave in displeasure. Am I to blame for arriving too late to escort you?\" Baozhu took Ziyu's hand and led him into the inner suite, saying: \"Come and have another look at your heart's beloved — do not let him weep himself sick on your account.\" Ziyu saw a figure sitting with his back turned, weeping. Thinking it was the same Qin Yan as before, he reflected that since Qin Yan knew enough to weep, he was capable of regretting his conduct; and he resolved to use the occasion of the banquet to reform him gradually through gentle words. Imagine his surprise, then, when the figure turned around, wiped the tears away with a handkerchief, and looked at Ziyu: \"Yuxiang, I now know your heart.\" Ziyu heard that the voice was not quite Qin Yan's; he looked more closely and saw — glowing with brilliance, beautiful as a heavenly being — this was truly the very person he had glimpsed from the carriage that day and seen on the stage. At this sight, Ziyu was so startled it was as if he had been caught doing something shameful; his heart hammered in his chest without stopping. He felt as if ten thousand tender emotions and an entire breast full of things to say were all pressing upon him — yet he could not utter a single word. He stood there stupefied for a long moment. Then suddenly he heard someone say: \"The host is over there presenting wine.\" As if waking from a stupor, Ziyu stepped forward to return the courtesy — and forgot to offer a cup in return. Only when Baozhu handed him a cup of wine did he remember, and he sent it to the seat opposite his own. Cixian said: \"You are the guest — how can you present wine on behalf of the host?\" Ziyu then realized he had gone to the wrong seat, and could only make the best of the mistake by sending a cup, composing himself, and then refilling the host's cup. After Ziyun had declined with repeated courtesies, he said: \"I will convey this cup on behalf of Brother Yuxiang to one person.\" And he placed it at the seat beside Ziyu, saying: \"Yu Nong, come and sit here.\" Qin Yan had no choice but to comply. He filled a cup and placed it before Ziyun, then filled one for Baozhu as well, and then took his seat. Evening had fallen and the lamps were lit. Ziyu said: \"What a strange day this has been — was what happened earlier a dream of confusion?\" This set the whole table laughing. Qin Yan, who rarely permitted himself so much as an easy smile, heard these words and could not help letting his teeth gleam in laughter. Those beautiful eyes, sending ripples of light — their effect was enough to rob a man of his very soul. It was not only Ziyu, who had never seen it before; even Ziyun, who had spent nearly a month in Qin Yan's company, was seeing this for the very first time. Knowing that the laughter was on Ziyu's account, he could not help but feel a pang of jealousy. Yet fortunately Baozhu's beauty and manner could hold their own beside Qin Yan's, and moreover seeing Ziyu's refined and gentle elegance as he sat beside Qin Yan — a perfect pair of jade figures — his admiration overcame his jealousy. Meanwhile, Ziyu looked Qin Yan over carefully once more and noticed that the Qin Yan he had seen by day had brows that were shapely but not bewitching, eyes that were beautiful but not captivating, complexion that was fair but not lustrous, a face that bore some resemblance yet in spirit and manner was entirely different.",
    "He could make no sense of whether they were one person or two, and the more he puzzled over it the more it became an insoluble knot — yet he found it impossible to ask.",
    "After several rounds of wine, Cixian said: \"Brother Yuxiang, have you seen the inscription engraved on the jade qin today?\" Ziyu said: \"I nearly forgot to express my thanks. The brushwork is ancient and masterly — truly the work of a skilled hand. But as for the lantern riddle, it was not so very difficult to solve. As for what Duxiang said about it being arranged for Yu Nong — I still do not quite understand why.\"",
    "Ziyun pointed to Qin Yan and said: \"This younger brother of mine set the riddle because he watched me compose it, and Qin Yan loved to recite the two lines about 'fallen flowers' and 'gentle rain.' And because his name contains the character for qin, I used it as the prize — it was meant as an augury of a soulmate for him throughout his life. As it happened, it was you, elder brother, who solved it — which vindicates my small effort at making a match.\" Ziyu said: \"To refuse would be discourteous, to accept leaves me feeling unworthy — I shall treasure it carefully on Yu Nong's behalf.\" A shadow of pleasure crossed Qin Yan's face. Baozhu, seeing this, recited a line of Tang poetry with one character changed: \"The same moonlight as always shines upon the qin; / Only with the plum blossom is it no longer ordinary.\" Ziyun and Cixian together praised: \"The change of 'qin' for the original word is wonderfully apt.\"",
    "Ziyu, noticing a slight flash of annoyance on Qin Yan's face, understood that Baozhu was playing on the character 'qin' in his name, and so said: \"If Yaoqing did not possess brilliance like a pearl within her breast, she could not have made such a quick and exquisite substitution.\" The others took this for ordinary praise, but Qin Yan alone felt deeply moved by Ziyu's care in avenging the slight of that character 'qin.' Cixian said: \"Why has Yu Nong not said a single word all evening?\" Ziyun said: \"He is like the Lady Xi, who refused to speak. In the future, Jingyi, you might write him a couplet with those lines: 'If flowers could speak they would only cause trouble; / The stone that cannot speak is the most admirable.'\" Ziyu kept nodding in agreement. Baozhu said: \"He is only good at dreaming — what does he know of speech?\" Qin Yan shot Baozhu a sidelong glance.",
    "Ziyu thought: \"This is clearly someone entirely different from the one I saw earlier. Can there really be two of them?\"",
    "Ziyun, perceiving that Ziyu and Qin Yan were already mutually drawn to each other, said: \"Did not Brother Yuxiang say he had something to attend to? Why not send someone home with word? We could then drink freely to our hearts' content.\" Ziyu hedged: \"The matter is a small one, and putting it off until tomorrow will cause no harm. You are a generous host — it is a pity the whole company of fine friends who came the other day is not here.\" Ziyun said: \"They are often here, and there will be other occasions for another gathering.\" Ziyu said: \"Apart from them, there is still one of truly outstanding and uncommon character.\" Ziyun said: \"Him I know as well.\" Qin Yan said: \"Now that is a name with a distinctive quality to it.\" Ziyun raised his cup toward Ziyu: \"Rarely does Yu Nong open his golden lips — we ought all to drain a full cup.\" After Ziyu had drained his, he raised one toward Cixian, who also drained his to the dregs.",
    "Baozhu said: \"Why do we not make a forfeit rule for this evening based on Yu Nong's speaking — every time he says a sentence, the whole table drinks a cup?\" Ziyun laughed: \"What a novel rule. Let it be so.\" Ziyu said: \"For every sentence spoken, the whole table must drink a cup — that would mean far too much wine. Would it not be better if each person he speaks to drinks a cup?\" Qin Yan nodded. Baozhu said: \"That might lead to abuses.\" Ziyun said: \"No matter — and if anyone does get drunk, I have my sobering pills.\" Everyone agreed to the arrangement.",
    "Qin Yan asked Ziyun: \"What sobering pills are those? What are they called?\" Ziyun explained each ingredient and preparation — which amounted to two cups for Qin Yan. Qin Yan asked Cixian: \"Why did you return so late today?\" Cixian said: \"I was acting as a matchmaker and came back late.\" One more cup. Qin Yan looked steadily at Ziyu but said nothing; then turned back and asked Ziyun: \"How many plum trees does this garden have in total?\" Baozhu gave a slight cough. Ziyun replied: \"Approximately two thousand trees.\" That was one cup.",
    "Baozhu came over and filled Ziyun's cup, then leaned over and whispered something in his ear. Qin Yan said: \"If you change the rules, the penalty is ten cups.\" Ziyu said: \"No one changed anything.\" Baozhu came over to fill Ziyu's cup. Qin Yan took up Ziyu's cup and said: \"I did not speak to him — why should he get wine?\" Baozhu said: \"Him speaking to you is the same thing.\" Qin Yan said: \"This I do not accept.\" Ziyu, feeling embarrassed, said: \"I simply wanted a drink — let me have one cup.\" Qin Yan said: \"If you want to drink, use his cup.\" Baozhu reached to take the cup from Qin Yan's hands, but Qin Yan had already snatched it away and hidden it. Baozhu had no choice but to pour another cup and bring it to Ziyu. Just as Ziyu was about to reach out for it, Qin Yan covered the cup with his left hand, refusing to let him drink. Everyone gazed at that hand: full and rounded yet suggesting abundance, soft and pliable as if without bone — the very image of a jade bamboo-shoot. Even a heart of iron or stone would have quickened at the sight.",
    "Ziyun, though he had once clasped that hand himself, could now only look on in admiring envy. Ziyu thought of the hand of that daytime Qin Yan — rough and dark — and understood at last that they must be two different people entirely. Baozhu thought of a scheme and said:",
    "\"Why is everyone staring at his slender, delicate hand?\" At this, Qin Yan drew back his hand — and Baozhu immediately seized the cup and placed it in Ziyu's hand. Qin Yan turned to Ziyu: \"You must not drink this cup.\" Ziyu said nothing in reply. Ziyun said: \"Yu Nong, you should represent me as host and offer a cup to our guest.\" Baozhu chimed in: \"Besides, under this rule, that very first sentence was not addressed to Yuxiang either — could it really have been said to someone else?\" Qin Yan considered this for a moment, acknowledged the point, and allowed himself a smile.",
    "When Ziyu had finished drinking, he turned and asked Baozhu: \"Who exactly was that Yu Nong just now?\"",
    "Baozhu laughed: \"That is something to ask your own Yu Nong.\" Ziyun, still laughing, called out: \"Yu Ling! Come and show yourself again for Master Mei.\" From the inner suite there emerged a person — it was the false Qin Yan from before, standing with arms at his sides, composed and upright, attending beside Ziyun. This false Qin Yan was a member of the troupe of Master Hua's household, a boy named Yu Ling, who had originally been a page in Ziyun's household and given to Master Hua. Because his face bore a certain resemblance to the real Qin Yan's, he had been called upon and used for the occasion. This, then, was the stratagem of substituting one flower for another.",
    "At the sight of him, Ziyu felt distinctly awkward, and suddenly everything became clear: the Qin Yan he had first seen was truly the false one. All his doubts dissolved at once. Ziyun said: \"I wanted to test Brother Yuxiang's discernment, and so deliberately presented an inferior likeness to impose upon a true beauty. That you saw through it proves your keen perception.\" He then directed Yu Ling to bring two large jade cups and said: \"Present a cup to Master Mei on my behalf.\" Yu Ling poured and brought the cup to Ziyu. Ziyu received it and said: \"The wine has already been too much, and the evening grows late — let us have our rice.\" Ziyun said: \"If Brother will not drink this cup, then he is truly angry with your younger brother. Yu Ling, drink a cup in my name and make my apologies.\" Yu Ling duly poured that cup as well and took a large sip. Baozhu offered him a few sections of spring orange to go with it, and after two more sips he finished. Ziyu, with no way out, drained the first half of his cup in one breath, ate a little fruit, and then, while Qin Yan squeezed some spring orange juice into what remained, slowly finished the rest.",
    "Today was Ziyu's first meeting with Qin Yan, and the beauty of natural endowment and celestial grace had already intoxicated his heart. Then to drink this large cup on top of all the rest — though joy poured into a joyful breast, the wine had passed its proper measure, and before his eyes the world dissolved into a swirl of colors. He could no longer hold himself steady. Ziyun dared not offer more. They all ate their rice, washed, and then Ziyu prepared to take his leave. It was Qin Yan who, concerned that he might be unwell from the wine, asked Ziyun for a dose of the Immortal Peach Longevity Pills, prepared them properly, blew on them until they were not too hot, and gave them to Ziyu to take. Before long, Ziyu felt his mind and spirits wonderfully clear. He then looked his fill at Qin Yan once more; though neither could speak plainly of what filled his heart in the presence of others, there had already been a silent mutual pledge, an unspoken understanding conveyed through glance and expression. Ziyu directed his page boy Yun Er to take the jade qin, and then said his farewells to Ziyun and Cixian and took his leave. Qin Yan quietly asked when they might meet again; Ziyu felt a great weight of pain in his heart, but forced himself to say: \"As soon as a moment of leisure presents itself, we shall meet again.\" The whole party saw him off to the place where the carriage waited. There was a great air of reluctance to part; they watched his carriage until it passed through the garden gate, and then Baozhu and Qin Yan each mounted their own carriage and departed. What happened next — hear it told in the following chapter."
  ],
  11: [
    "After Xu Ziyun had seen Ziyu out of the garden, he talked a while with Xiao Cixian and then returned home. Ziyun's residence was not far from the garden — directly across the way — the old ancestral mansion of his late great-grandfather, the Grand Chancellor, spacious and grand. His parents, elder brother, and sister-in-law had all left the capital, so the household now consisted only of Ziyun and his wife, with the remaining staff being servants. Ziyun told his wife, Mrs. Yuan, about the affair of Qin Yan and Ziyu, and they both marveled at the delicate tenderness of the attachment. Mrs. Yuan smiled and asked:",
    "\"These young gentleman-actors — what is it about them that you all find so appealing? What is really so wonderful about them?\" Ziyun laughed: \"You have seen them yourself and heard them sing — can you really say they are not fine?\" Mrs. Yuan said: \"When I watch them perform, it seems to me they are only imitating the manners of young ladies. And when they remove their makeup, they are indeed fair and delicate-looking. But to call them priceless treasures beyond compare — that I cannot understand. From my perspective, they seem hardly superior to my own maids.\" Ziyun said: \"From your vantage point, naturally the female of the species seems best. But we cannot bring young women along to banquets and social gatherings — that would injure the refinement of the occasion. The merit of these young actors lies precisely in this: they have a woman's face but not a woman's body. They delight the eye and yet restrain the heart, giving one pleasure without desire. Is that not doubly perfect?\" Mrs. Yuan laughed: \"Nicely put, at any rate.\" Ziyun also laughed: \"I mean every word — in all my life I have never said anything I did not truly mean.\" Mrs. Yuan said: \"Granted you are like that — but are all your friends the same?\" Ziyun said: \"If they were not, they would be as incompatible with me as fire and ice. Just now, did I not tell you how Mei Yuxiang — when that Yu Ling said a few flirtatious words — flew into such a rage that he even came around to scolding me? Is that not worthy of trust? Besides, those boys themselves dislike being teased.\" They chatted a while longer, and then Mrs. Yuan mentioned that the following day was Lady Hua's birthday — her twentieth birthday, a major milestone — and they really ought to pay a visit. Ziyun said: \"We certainly should go. Besides, she came in person for your birthday last year and brought quite a number of gifts; we ought to prepare a few fine things to send in return.\" And so the evening passed without further incident.",
    "Early the next morning, Mrs. Yuan selected ten choice curios — all of considerable value — and drew up a list: a jade interlocking ring of jasper and nephrite; a seven-treasures hairpin; a fan of kingfisher feathers; a coral hair-pin; a filigree gold mountain-censer; a qin of pale jade; a rare piece of aquilaria incense; a zither bridge of precious sinking-wood; a strand of lignum aloes; an agate seal. These were dispatched ahead by servant. Then, from among her twelve red-named maids, she took Hongxue, Hongzhu, Hongxiang, Hongyu, Hongwei, and Hongwen — all six of them fifteen years old in the prime of their bloom, slender and graceful, literate, skilled in calligraphy, accomplished in poetry and embroidery. After attending their mistress through her morning toilet, Hongxue said: \"The weather is cold today, and there seems to be snow in the air; we must bring several extra garments.\" She went to the heavy-lined clothing and selected a sky-blue satin cloak embroidered with golden figures on purple sable fur, a red satin skirt embroidered with golden celestial horses, jade pendants that clinked and chimed, and a strand of pearl tassels. In addition, a large red padded bundle was packed with two or three more garments. All the floral ornaments and precious accessories were placed in a brocaded case. The six reds finished their own preparations, and then all boarded the fragrant carriage; household men mounted horses outside and proceeded toward the Hua mansion.",
    "Now as for the young master Hua: he was twenty-one years old. Though his appearance had briefly entered Wei Pincai's field of vision and his character had been touched upon in Fu San's words, neither account had been thorough. In truth, young Master Hua's bearing was extravagant and imposing, yet his nature was extremely pure and genuine. He indulged himself in the pleasures of daily life — good food, fine lodgings, the enjoyment of wealth and comfort. Pampered and at ease, he was disinclined toward social obligations. He was highly skilled at horsemanship and archery, and even more accomplished in verse and rhapsody; he had read a thousand volumes and could compose seven paces at a time without effort. His wife, Lady Hua, came from the Su family on her mother's side: her father, Su Chentai, was a descendant of meritorious founders, a hereditary marquis, and currently serving as President of the Board of War. He had no sons, only two daughters — the elder named Huanxiang, the younger Huanlan — both of surpassing beauty; when they walked idly beneath the flowers, a hundred butterflies would follow and dance around them. They excelled at poetry, music theory, calligraphy, painting, and the qin and chess, each accomplishment reaching a level of exquisite refinement. Beyond the household walls, a couplet circulated as a byword: \"Better than ten pecks of dragon-palace pearls / Is but one glimpse of the two young ladies of the marquis's gate.\" At the age of eighteen, Huanxiang was wed to Hua Guangsu — truly a match of jade qin and jade zither, harmonious as fish and water. Their domestic life was all moonlit chanting and wind-watching, refined and leisurely beyond description. They also had ten beautiful maidservants, each named with the character for pearl: Baozhu, Mingzhu, Aizhu, Huazhu, Hezhu, Ruizhu, Zhangzhu, Zhenzhu, Huazhu (second), and Zengzhu. All ten were of surpassing beauty, each fifteen or sixteen years old, truly like ten varieties of fresh blossoms or a cluster of powdered butterflies — every one quick of mind and fragrant of speech, with dainty lotus-steps and willow waists, needlework that surpassed the heavenly artisans, and poetic phrases that each reached a level of marvelous refinement. Compared to Zheng Kangcheng's poetry-composing maids, they lacked the pedantic moralist's air; compared to Guo Lingong's household singers, they possessed the distinctive grace of a romantic mistress. Such refined talent and abundant happiness in the young couple was a rarity even by the measure of this world; moreover, their parents at home were still in vigorous old age, commanding prestige over all the surrounding regions, carrying on seven generations of glory, and holding a rank at the very head of the Three Excellencies.",
    "On this day of Lady Hua's birthday, the outside world was entirely unaware. The day before, the young master and his wife had spent a family banquet together, with the Eight-Ages Troupe performing opera throughout the day. The names of all the Eight-Ages boys contained the character for \"age\" (ling) — simply variations of the kind: Golden-Age, Jade-Age, Orchid-Age, Cassia-Age, and so forth. Several had been trained by household tutors, several had been selected from various troupes. Though they could not compare with the celebrated female-role players celebrated in the Flower Selection, they were nevertheless superior to the ordinary run of stage performers; in their leisure hours they were normally assigned to attend in the study.",
    "On this day, Lady Hua knew that her younger sister, Miss Huanlan, would be coming, and then word came that the Xu household had sent ten curios as gifts — confirming that Mrs. Yuan would also come. She and the young master rose early and paid their respects at the ancestral shrine and before the Buddha altar. The young master had intended to host another family banquet for his wife, but since her sister and her sworn-sister were coming, he was obliged to withdraw. Before long, Miss Su had arrived; the fragrant carriage pulled into the entrance corridor, and a soft sedan chair carried her directly into the inner courtyard. Four maids helped the young lady from the chair; Lady Hua came out to welcome her; the sisters exchanged the ritual greetings; and young Master Hua also came in to pay his respects. He inquired after his parents-in-law's health, and was just about to take his seat when a servant announced: \"The mistress of the Xu household has arrived.\" Young Master Hua withdrew; Lady Hua and her sister came out to the main hall to receive the guest. The curtain of the palanquin was lifted, and from within, surrounded by six beautiful maids, a heavenly being emerged. She took small, delicate lotus-steps into the main hall, took Lady Hua's hand, and they exchanged deep bows with smiling warmth. Miss Su also exchanged New Year's greetings with Mrs. Yuan and said: \"I had planned to come to your house tomorrow in any case — my mother and aunts all intend to come as well.\" Mrs. Yuan said: \"I have been meaning these past two days to invite your honored mother and your sisters to come and sit a while — it would be simply delightful if you would deign to call.\" Lady Hua said: \"On the occasion of my humble birthday, you honor me with your gracious attention and shower me with so many precious gifts — how can I but receive them with the deepest gratitude?\" Mrs. Yuan laughed: \"These few trifling things are merely a token of my feeling — they are far too slight to deserve mention. I had meant to come yesterday, but was unexpectedly detained by something that came up.\"",
    "Miss Su said: \"On the eleventh, my mother sent someone to inquire after your health. The messenger came back and reported that your sister had invited a party of ladies to her garden to admire the lanterns. He went on describing those lanterns for the better part of half the day — saying what a spectacle it was to set them up, talking of several thousand people needed, painting the most vivid picture — so that I dreamed of going to your garden to see the lanterns that very night, and then didn't see a single one.\"",
    "She laughed at herself as she said it. Mrs. Yuan also laughed: \"The lanterns you could certainly have seen — several thousand people would never be needed, though two or three hundred there were. We ladies hurried ahead and took a full day on the eleventh to test them out; after that, various gentlemen came one after another and the merriment continued through the eighteenth without a single day's break. And since you all live in the city proper and can only come by day rather than enjoy the lanterns in the evening, we did not send invitations.\" Lady Hua expressed great admiration at this account. Mrs. Yuan then turned to Miss Su: \"We are grateful your honored mother thought of us and was kind enough to send gifts.\" Miss Su said: \"When you left that day, mother said you seemed a little indisposed, and she has been thinking of you ever since.\" Mrs. Yuan again rose and expressed her thanks. The Ten Pearls and Miss Su's maids all came forward and paid their respects to Mrs. Yuan. The Six Reds likewise paid their respects to Lady Hua and Miss Su. After some general conversation and domestic chat, Lady Hua proposed having the opera performed. Mrs. Yuan said: \"We sisters are having such a delightful conversation — there is no need to let the commotion of performers disrupt it.\" They took a brief stroll through several rooms and then withdrew into Lady Hua's private chambers. Lady Hua's bedchamber occupied five large bays: three as a suite of inner rooms, the outer two fitted as a study, shelves filled with books and bronzes arranged about. Mrs. Yuan admired it all briefly, and then the cluster of pearl-named maids came in to report that the banquet was ready to be laid. Lady Hua said: \"Set it right here, then.\" The table was spread; Lady Hua offered the first cup; they settled into their seats. The jade-clear wine flowed freely; the table was laden with mountain delicacies and sea rarities beyond description.",
    "The three ladies talked and laughed and drank for a while, until Mrs. Yuan said: \"I recently came across a wine-game that is quite entertaining. It uses five set phrases linked in sequence, though I find fault with it for lacking rhyme, and the fourth and fifth phrases each add two meaningless filler words, which feels a little unnatural. In that version, the first phrase is drawn from classical prose, the second from Tang poetry, the third from dominoes names, the fourth from aria titles, and the fifth from the Almanac — all chosen at the player's discretion, which makes it too easy. Here is my version instead: with six dice, whatever pattern falls, one starts from that pattern. The first phrase must be a domino name, the second a five-character line of Tang poetry, the third a lyric from the Xixiang, the fourth an aria title, and the fifth a line from the Mao Shi. These five phrases must rhyme, so that when spoken aloud they ring out in a pleasing cadence.\" Miss Su was delighted to hear this, and asked her sister at once to bring the dice so they could try the game. Lady Hua said: \"Clever as it is, it is quite difficult — you must be both natural and in rhyme. Don't you find that demanding?\" She directed a maid to bring the dice tray, set the dice inside, and offered it to Mrs. Yuan, saying:",
    "\"Elder sister, please set us an example first.\" Mrs. Yuan picked up the dice, threw them several times, and produced a pattern: a flock of crows cawing in the wind. She stared at the tray, reflected for a moment, and said: \"I shall venture a try, though it may not be well done — please don't laugh at me.\" Then she recited: \"A flock of crows cawing in the wind — / Clamor of phoenixes descending through the void — / Each gone their own way, the shrike and the swallow, east and west — / At the fifth watch it turns — / I shall share with you a dream's content.\"",
    "Lady Hua and Miss Su praised it lavishly. Lady Hua said: \"The first three phrases are truly excellent, and phrases three through five are even more exquisite. The sentiment is warm and languorous — reading them makes one's heart melt. I doubt I could manage anything like this.\"",
    "Mrs. Yuan laughed: \"You are always so modest in everything. And then when it comes to your turn, you always put in great effort and refuse to let anyone surpass you by a hair.\" Lady Hua also laughed, picked up the dice, threw them several times, and produced a pattern: iron chains mooring a lone boat. She thought for a moment and then recited:",
    "\"Iron chains moor a lone boat — / The broad river rushes swiftly through the night — / He set our reunion for the ninth day of the ninth month. / Night Journey on the Boat — / Adrift, now sinking, now floating.\"",
    "Mrs. Yuan said: \"What did I tell you? I said you would have phrases to astonish the listener — these five read as one, and are far better than mine.",
    "The third phrase from the Sequel to the Western Chamber is used with particular wit. Now I must see what Younger Sister Lan will do — surely even better, and last will surpass first.\" Lady Hua offered a few more modest disclaimers.",
    "Miss Su was impatient and eager to throw; she had no time for modesty, and pulled the dice tray toward her. With a great clattering she threw several times before landing a pattern: a general hangs his seal of command. She was delighted by this. She fixed her autumn eyes in concentration, thought for a moment, assembled five phrases, and recited them with a bright smile:",
    "\"A general hangs his seal — / Three frontier regions lie in quiet solitude — / All because within you there are a million troops. / Song of Victory — / A pillar of the realm, a duke and a marquis.\"",
    "Mrs. Yuan praised: \"I said that last would surpass first, and so it is — Sister Lan's entry truly leaves me in absolute admiration; I can only offer a brimming cup in congratulation.\" Miss Su was rather pleased with herself and smiled while offering a modest disclaimer. Lady Hua also praised: \"Truly fine — though it also helped that the dice fell on such an auspicious pattern and gave you your opening.\" She too offered a cup of congratulation, and directed the attending maids each to drink a cup as well, as a grand reward to the three armies in honor of the general's hanging his seal. The Ten Pearls, the Six Reds, and the rest all drank; Aizhu tugged at Hongxue's sleeve and whispered: \"Your mistress's 'at the fifth watch it turns — I shall share with you a dream's content' is full of feeling; our mistress's 'iron chains moor a lone boat, riding the Night Journey ship' is full of good sense; and the Second Young Lady's entry is full of force and grandeur — each one has its own particular excellence.\" Hongxue nodded: \"You have put it exactly right.\" Mrs. Yuan and the others, overhearing this, could not suppress smiles.",
    "Mrs. Yuan threw again and produced a pattern: fallen red petals blanketing the ground. Determined to excel and not willing to speak hastily, she pondered carefully for a while, composed something she was quite pleased with herself, and recited: \"Fallen red petals blanketing the ground — / She wipes away tears and knits her dark brows — / It is only that since last night this waist has grown more slender still.",
    "Scolding the Jade Lad — / You shall not return until you are drunk.\"",
    "Miss Su praised: \"Elder Sister, this is truly superb — how can you say things so full of delicate, graceful allusion? I could never express things in quite this way; I feel my own efforts are rather blunt and coarse. We ought to congratulate you on this one.\" Each offered a cup of congratulation. Mrs. Yuan laughed: \"You are in the grand style of Li Bai and Du Fu, while I am in the delicate, ornate manner of Wen Tingyun and Li Shangyin — how can I compare?\" Lady Hua laughed: \"This one is absolutely exquisite, and perfectly suited to its theme. I think Elder Sister is scolding her husband for bringing his young actor companions to the garden every day and coming home drunk, so that Elder Sister has grown thin at the waist.\" Mrs. Yuan felt somewhat embarrassed and said: \"Coming here to tease me, are you? Take care — you are watching for color patterns, and there will be a return gesture.\" Lady Hua and Miss Su both laughed; the Ten Pearls, the Six Reds, and the rest, hearing all this, also smiled faintly and found it all very entertaining to listen to their mistresses banter.",
    "Lady Hua picked up the dice and threw a pattern: two gentlemen entering the Peach Blossom Spring. She spent a moment composing her thoughts and found several fine phrases — but having just teased Mrs. Yuan, she now feared retaliation if she spoke them aloud, and felt herself involuntarily hesitating, a blush spreading across her peach-blossom cheeks. To change the phrases seemed a pity, however, and so she had no choice but to recite:",
    "\"Two gentlemen enter the Peach Blossom Spring — / The path to Peach Blossom Spring may still be found — / A heaven-ordained new-wedded pair of swallows. / Beside the dressing mirror — / Walking hand in hand.\"",
    "Miss Su, hearing this, turned to Lady Hua with a knowing smile. Mrs. Yuan laughed: \"What made you suddenly think of the time when you were first married? These phrases are the very height of romantic, entwining sentiment. It is as if one can see a fragrant-hearted figure leaning against the dressing mirror, two people propped side by side, murmuring softly together.",
    "Lips still fragrant with rouge. We are here today as guests — it is somewhat awkward of you to make us feel out of place.\" Lady Hua laughed:",
    "\"I knew you would retaliate — that is why I hesitated and considered changing a phrase or two, but couldn't find anything better. It is my own fault for provoking this from you, Elder Sister.\" At this, everyone burst out laughing together, and all the maids smiled as well; cups of congratulation were offered all around.",
    "It came round to Miss Su again; she threw a pattern: moonrise above the plum branch. She thought for a moment and recited: \"Moonrise above the plum branch — / Fragrant and translucent the flowering tree — / The jade face of the beloved, deep-locked within the embroidered bed-curtains. / Cold Lock on the Casement — / The dew falls thick and heavy.\"",
    "Lady Hua praised it first. Mrs. Yuan said: \"Your entry achieves the ultimate in gentle warmth and fragrant allure, and has exactly the voice of a sheltered young lady of good family. Being a few years older than you, I can no longer achieve such delicate, exquisite rhyme — it truly cannot be forced.\" Miss Su only smiled in return, and another round of congratulatory cups was drunk. On the other side of the curtain, Hongxiang leaned over and said softly to Baozhu: \"Have you noticed? Each person's entry sounds exactly like that person's way of speaking, feeling, and character — even matching their looks. Why should that be? If you were to exchange them among the players, none would suit the one who said it.\" Baozhu and the others smiled faintly. Mrs. Yuan picked up the dice again and threw a pattern: viewing lanterns on the fifteenth night.",
    "Miss Su said: \"This is Elder Sister's home territory — surely you can describe all those hundreds of birds and beasts, divine dragons and mangy elephants, fire-blossomed trees and silver-flowered cascades, and speak them all out together in a grand and festive lantern-festival scene.\" Mrs. Yuan laughed: \"That is what I was thinking too — but I'm not sure I have the power to pull it off.\" She thought for a while and couldn't assemble anything suitable, so she set it aside and tried again, then recited: \"Viewing lanterns on the fifteenth night — / What need of someone to support me when I am not yet drunk — / Voice after voice saying, better to go home. / Step by Step Graceful — / Beware the heavy dew when you walk.\"",
    "Lady Hua and Miss Su lavished praise on this. Lady Hua said: \"Elder Sister is carefree and graceful, and her feeling shows through her words. These phrases are as if one sees Elder Sister leaning on a maid's arm, stepping slowly along — and then again as if one sees Elder Sister viewing the lanterns in her garden. It fills one with admiring envy.\" Each offered a congratulatory cup. At this point Lady Hua called out to Baozhu and the others, directing them to go with the maids of both households to the back room to eat their meal.",
    "The attendants on this side had thus thinned considerably. Mrs. Yuan could hear from the back room the intermittent clatter of dice and scattered sounds of laughter and mutual teasing and commentary. Miss Su said: \"They are in there playing the wine game too — I wonder how their entries are turning out?\" Lady Hua laughed:",
    "\"Even if they manage a phrase or two, there isn't likely to be anything very fine — they'll surely fall short of ours.\" So the dice tray was moved over again; she threw a pattern: peach-pink and willow-green, and after a moment's thought recited: \"Peach-pink and willow-green — / Flowers and heart alike feel renewed — / Beyond the flowers the beloved is far away, yet the horizon feels near. / Drunk Beneath the Flowers — / Playing the zither, blowing the pipes.\"",
    "Mrs. Yuan said: \"This one too captures all your sentiment and grace — it is as if I see you beneath the shade of the flowers, in the midst of red and green abundance, gently dispelling your own longing. Truly a companion fit for an immortal beneath the jade-peach blossoms.\" Lady Hua said: \"I feel my lines always come out somewhat flat — none of the electric wit of Elder Sister's. Today Elder Sister truly ranks first: a seamless richness of fragrant warmth glows through every character. I can only bow in respectful defeat.\" Mrs. Yuan said: \"Not at all! The pure, bright elegance has all been claimed between the two of you sisters.",
    "The scholar Xie Lingyun once said: 'Of all the talent in the world, there is but one measure of ten; Cao Zijian alone claimed eight of it.' I would say today you two together claim six tenths of it; and then there is one other small talent who would snatch away three tenths — leaving only one tenth for all the other educated ladies in the world to divide among themselves, until by the time it reaches me there isn't even a drop left.\" Lady Hua and Miss Su both laughed. Miss Su asked: \"Who is this 'small talent' Sister speaks of?\" Mrs. Yuan said: \"Do you not know her? She is the second daughter of Senior Kinsman Wang Zhifu, named Wang Qionghua — we are all sworn sisters.\" Lady Hua said: \"That would be the Senior Kinsman Wang who serves as Supervisor of the Court of Transmission? We have not had much contact with that household.\" Miss Su said: \"What is this Wang Qionghua like?\" Mrs. Yuan said: \"She is seventeen this year, and her appearance is beyond compare — she and the two of you can truly stand as three equals forming a tripod. A few days ago I invited her and her sisters to come view the lanterns, and right there at the table she composed a 'Lantern-Moon Lyric' — in a matter of moments a sweeping piece of seven or eight hundred characters, brilliant and dazzling, astonishing to ear and eye, as if Li Bai himself had returned. This is something simply impossible for the women's quarters ordinarily to produce.\" Miss Su said:",
    "\"Does Elder Sister happen to remember this poem?\" Mrs. Yuan said: \"I do not recall it, but another day I will copy it out and send it to you.\" Each then drank a cup of wine and ate a few dishes. They could hear from the back room that the maids were having a fine time with their dice — laughter and jokes, penalties and forfeit cups. Miss Su threw a pattern: lattice-work eyes, and said with a laugh: \"This one has no obvious appeal.\" She thought for a while.",
    "Then she recited: \"Lattice-work eyes — / A gentle breeze makes a pleasing sound — / Flutter, flutter, the paper strips are singing. / Hating the long night — / The eastern sky has not yet grown light.\"",
    "Mrs. Yuan said: \"You claimed the 'lattice-work eyes' pattern had no appeal, yet it has yielded you this fine entry — truly natural and unaffected.\" By now each of them had gone through several rounds, and a good long while had passed. Lady Hua said: \"Let us rest and play another round in a moment — let us eat a little, rather than exhausting ourselves for nothing.\" We will set aside the outer room for now and speak of the beautiful maids in the back room, who were playing their own wine game. Some had composed good entries, some had stumbled; and some, unable to manage at all, were looking for others to compose on their behalf. Though they dared not be overly raucous, they were nonetheless leaning in to whisper in each other's ears, shoulders brushing and hair strands touching as they crowded together. The Twelve Reds of the Xu household and the Ten Pearls of the Hua household were well matched in age, appearance, and ability — as they should have been on the best of terms, each respecting and fond of the other.",
    "But this was not the case. All harbored a competitive spirit, each unwilling to yield to the other. So long as they avoided these matters of literary and artistic skill, they got along well enough. The moment poetry, lyrics, or such accomplishments came up, however, it would inevitably become a matter of you belittling me and me belittling you, each trying to gain an edge. It would end in a war of words, faces reddening on both sides. In this round of the wine game, several had already composed poorly and suffered no small amount of cutting remarks. When Hongwei's throw produced a pattern, she was unable to think of anything for a long while, her cheeks flushing crimson with frustration. Aizhu thought of something and said with a laugh: \"I'll compose for you, but you'll have to thank me, the matchmaker.\" Still smiling sweetly, she pointed a finger at Hongwei and recited: \"Intoxicated Xi Shi — / The flush of wine and beauty come on slow — / Last night in the clear moon and gentle breeze, deep in the night. / Good Elder Sister — / The gentleman of quality tempts her with his wooing.\"",
    "Everyone praised it as fine. Hongwei said: \"You truly are a 'good elder sister' — no wonder someone wants to tempt you.\" Aizhu said: \"I was describing you, with your good looks. Don't you think you look just like an intoxicated Xi Shi?\" Everyone laughed again.",
    "Ruizhu threw a pattern called \"a loach slipping into a water-chestnut nest,\" and objected that the name was distasteful and wanted it not to count. Everyone refused to accept this.",
    "Ruizhu had no choice but to think hard, but try as she might she could not string the phrases together in a connected way. Hongxue laughed:",
    "\"I'll compose for you too, but you'll have to thank me, the matchmaker.\" Ruizhu said: \"If it's something decent, then say it. If it's an insult, spare me the favor.\" Hongxue said: \"I won't insult you — you'll actually be grateful to me.\" Everyone said: \"Go on, recite it.\" Hongxue laughed and said: \"A loach slipping into a water-chestnut nest — / A green-feathered bird sporting on the orchid sedge — / A marquis's gate — the old monk is not permitted to knock. / That bald little fellow — / Shall grow old together with you.\"",
    "Ruizhu reached out and pinched Hongxue's mouth shut. Hongxue struggled to pry the fingers free; everyone doubled over with laughter. Mingzhu laughed so hard her sleeve knocked over a wine cup. The ladies outside could hear all of this clearly; Mrs. Yuan laughed: \"They are even more entertaining than we are.\" On this side, Hongyu threw a pattern called \"eight refusals,\" and said: \"This pattern is also difficult — it can't be assembled; let me throw again.\" Baozhu said: \"Of course it can be assembled — I'll assemble it for you, and I guarantee it won't leave you with 'eight refusals.'\" Hongyu said: \"Are you saying this in fun, or are you serious? If you are going to be unkind to me, I'll tear your mouth open.\" Baozhu said: \"I don't like being unkind to people.\" Then she pointed at Hongyu and recited: \"Eight refusals — / Startled from her dreams, the mandarin-ducks rise — / What sustains her through this long, long night? / Taking Off the Cloth Shirt — / The heart's longing, center-deep.\" She added: \"The character for 'longing' here must be read as 'itching.'\" Hongyu cursed: \"There seems to be a certain itch in your mouth too — let me scratch it for you.\" She picked up a piece of sea cucumber with her chopsticks and pushed it toward Baozhu's lips. Baozhu knocked her chopsticks away with one hand; they clattered to the ground under the table, and a white cat dashed out and ate up the sea cucumber. The maids dissolved into helpless laughter once more.",
    "Zhangzhu threw a pattern called \"climbing the ladder to gaze at the moon,\" said something about it that was merely passable and showed no particular brilliance. Hongwen said: \"The name of this pattern is itself so fine — presenting it so poorly is an injustice to the subject. Let me say it for you.\" She then recited: \"Climbing the ladder to gaze at the moon — / Song Yu is in the western neighborhood — / Over the wall they exchanged poems and compositions until the sky grew light. / Stirring of the Flower's Heart — / A young woman is moved by longing.\" Zhangzhu laughed and scolded Hongwen: \"What a way for a girl to behave — climbing a ladder to peep at someone, and then saying your own heart is stirred! Aren't you ashamed?\" Hongwen laughed: \"I am saying it of you — you are suppressing it all inside. Better to say it plainly rather than make yourself sick holding it in.\" Zhangzhu gave Hongwen a shove; Hongwen, caught off guard, stumbled backward and fell against Baozhu, landing on her bound feet. Baozhu frowned, placed one hand on Hongwen's shoulder for balance, and used the other to rub her own shoe-tip; after rubbing it for a moment, she gave Hongwen two light smacks on the back. Everyone laughed again.",
    "Hongxiang threw a pattern called \"a pair of matched butterflies, precisely.\" She too could not assemble anything. She thought of a few phrases, but they wouldn't rhyme together. Hezhu said: \"I'll compose a good one for you — one that'll make sure you never ignore me again.\" Hongxiang, assuming this was a kindly offer, said: \"Good elder sister, please compose it for me then.\" Hezhu laughed: \"Although I am composing it for you, the entry still counts as yours.\" Then she recited: \"A pair of matched butterflies, precisely — / When will the wish be granted — / Every moment endured stretches like a summer's day. / Parallel Lotus Blossoms — / May it be so, morning and night.\" Hongxiang's face went red; she tried to tear Hezhu's mouth open, but the others intervened and held her back. Hezhu threw a pattern called \"a single flower.\" She was just beginning to think of some fine phrases when Hongzhu turned toward her with a bright smile and said: \"Let me compose for you.\" Hezhu, suspecting nothing good would come of it, shook her head: \"No thank you.\" Hongzhu said: \"Even if you don't want it, I'm going to say it anyway.\" Everyone was eager to hear something amusing, so they all pressed for her to speak. Hongzhu recited: \"A single flower — / We still cherish the time of the embrace — / This is what is called 'the talented youth and the beautiful maiden, indeed.' / A Single Point of Red — / Lightly soiling my private heart.\" Everyone burst into irrepressible laughter. Hezhu was furious; she walked over, grabbed Hongzhu around the waist, and with great force pressed her down onto the heated bed-platform, pinning her and saying: \"Now let me ask you in earnest about this 'single point of red.'\" Hongzhu, being weaker, could not turn over; her skirt had already parted to both sides. Everyone saw her two little bound feet flailing and kicking in all directions; everyone's sides shook with laughter until they could barely hold themselves upright.",
    "Hongxue and Hongxiang went over and pulled Hezhu off. Hongzhu found that the flowers in her hair had fallen out and her tresses had been thoroughly disheveled; she smoothed them back with her hand for a while and then scolded Hezhu: \"What rough and reckless play — saying a thing is all very well, but you didn't have to take it so seriously.\" The commotion had now grown to a pitch where Lady Hua and Mrs. Yuan could no longer contain themselves; they sent a married maidservant to go in and inquire and forbid any further play. The cluster of maids immediately fell silent and composed themselves; they hurried through their bowls of rice and came out to resume attendance. The ladies looked at this troupe of unruly maids — some with flowers askew, some with hair disheveled, some with their backs turned, still trying to suppress laughter, and some with brows knit in aggrieved silent reproach — and could not help but find them amusing. They turned to Aizhu and the others and said: \"At your ages, how can you still be this mischievous? Were it not for our guest being present today, I would certainly punish you.\" Mrs. Yuan also spoke a few words of mild censure to the Six Reds. The maids all bowed their heads and stood in attendance with looks of contrition. Miss Su asked: \"What kind of entries were you playing in there? What was so terribly funny?\" At this, several of the maids could not hold back their smiles again, which in turn nearly set both ladies laughing as well.",
    "Lady Hua laughed: \"These foolish girls — they are at once maddening and amusing.\" Miss Su said further: \"If any of your entries were really good, you may as well tell us — we would like to hear and appreciate them. If they are truly fine, I shall even give you a reward. And your mistresses certainly won't scold you for them.\"",
    "Aizhu's expression suggested she was about to speak, but Hongxiang tugged at her sleeve, warning her not to. Aizhu said: \"There were a great many — I can't recall them all clearly.\" Miss Su was eager to hear and so addressed Lady Hua and Mrs. Yuan: \"They are afraid of their mistresses and don't dare speak — if you call on them to say it, they will.\" Lady Hua also knew that the maids had their own sharp little wits and that several of them had produced good entries; she exchanged a smile with Mrs. Yuan. Mrs. Yuan, being by nature lively and unconventional, also wished to display her maids' talent, and so said: \"If what you say is coherent, you may go ahead and say it. If you say something incoherent, each one will kneel and drink a large penalty cup.\" Among them, Hongwei and Mingzhu had the best memories, and moreover none of their own entries were among the questionable ones, so they said: \"They are coherent enough — but I fear that having said them, instead of earning a reward, we will receive a punishment.\" Lady Hua laughed: \"Go on and say them one by one.\" So Mingzhu reported all three of the entries by Aizhu, Baozhu, and Hezhu that had offended the others; and Hongwei also reported all three of the entries by Hongxue, Hongwen, and Hongzhu that had caused trouble — to such effect that both ladies laughed until the pearl ornaments on their hair quivered and swayed. Though they tried to compose their faces into stern expressions to reprimand the girls, they simply could not manage it. Miss Su, though she felt the entries were somewhat too free and familiar, nonetheless admired the sharpness of mind behind them, and refrained from laughing outright, contenting herself with a slight nod of appreciation.",
    "The two ladies laughed for a good while, and then together called forward the six culprits — the three Reds and the three Pearls who had given offense — and, suppressing their laughter, said: \"You are so impertinent — how could you? If word got out, what face would you have to show anyone? Now kneel, all of you!\" The six maids, blushing with shame, had no choice but to kneel before the assembled company. Miss Su interceded on their behalf: \"Two dear sisters, for my sake — forgive them this first offense. Though their words were improper and free, we must give them credit for their quick wits and nimble tongues. Let the merit cancel the fault.\" Mrs. Yuan said: \"Since Second Sister has spoken, I dare not refuse — but we must still admonish them. If we do not, they will get into the habit of it and become completely unbridled.\" She and Lady Hua then judged the six entries: for the most egregious, the penalty was a large cup of wine drunk at a single draft and three slaps of the palm, as a token chastisement; for the lesser offenses, a forfeit cup was sufficient. Thus Hongxue, Hongzhu, Hezhu, and Baozhu received both wine and punishment; Aizhu and Hongwen received the wine-forfeit only. The maids in receiving their punishments felt utterly ashamed, and having drunk those hasty cups of wine found themselves a little unsteady on their feet; they struggled to hold themselves upright, and privately regretted their moment of high spirits.",
    "Mrs. Yuan saw that the day was growing late and that it was time to break up the banquet; she laughed and said to Lady Hua: \"Throw once more and say a few well-turned phrases to close the game — something to cleanse the air after all that.\" She directed that the rice be brought at the same time. Lady Hua, seeing that the hour was indeed right and it would not do to stay too late, ordered the dishes to be served and the rice brought. She picked up the dice, threw, and produced a pattern: golden chrysanthemums facing lotus blossoms. She was privately delighted — such a fine pattern — and after quiet thought composed her entry and recited it: \"Golden chrysanthemums face the lotus blossoms — / Patterned candles curl as the plates gleam red — / And yet you ask me, blue-sleeved, to hold the jade cup with tender care. / Perfectly at Peace and Happy — / May ten thousand blessings converge upon you.\"",
    "Mrs. Yuan and Miss Su praised it without end. Lady Hua urged both of them to drink two more cups each, and then the rice was eaten and the meal concluded. After washing and rinsing, Mrs. Yuan saw the evening sun beginning its descent and knew she must not delay further; she offered her thanks and bid farewell. Lady Hua and Miss Su, attended by the Ten Pearls and the cluster of maids, escorted her to the palanquin. The Six Reds supported the sides of the chair; with small, careful steps they made their way all the way to the outer corridor before mounting the carriage, which then flowed smoothly away.",
    "On the other side, Miss Su did not return home until the second watch of the night. As for what happened next — hear it told in the following chapter."
  ],
  12: [
    "After Mrs. Yuan returned from the Hua household that evening, she arrived home late, changed her clothes and removed her ornaments, and then told Ziyun all about the wine-game they had played, including the maids' entries. Ziyun praised it all enthusiastically.",
    "Later, without telling his wife, he had all sixteen entries engraved and divided into two grades: the ten entries by the ladies and the young miss formed the Upper Game, and the six entries by the maids formed the Lower Game. He composed titles and wrote a good number of poems for them, though without recording any names. Because the first entry had been \"a flock of crows cawing in the wind,\" and the maids' ruckus had followed afterward, he named the whole collection the Flock-of-Crows-Cawing-in-the-Wind Game. When people outside the household saw it, they passed it around as a delightful story.",
    "By the time Mrs. Yuan found out, it had already spread everywhere, and there was nothing to be done about it.",
    "Time passed swiftly, and before one knew it mid-spring had arrived. There is now one particular person's affairs that must be told — a person of great importance in this book. Who is he? In a previous chapter, Xiao Cixian mentioned two lantern riddles in the form of love letters, which had been solved by someone whose name he had unfortunately failed to ask. This person's surname was Tian, his given name Chunhang, his style Xiangfan, and he was twenty-three years old. Also a native of Jinling, he was residing in Yangzhou. He had lost his father while still young. His mother, née Zhang, came from a distinguished family of long standing and was well versed in the classics and histories. She bore Chunhang at the age of twenty-five; when Chunhang was three years old, his father Tian Hao passed the jinshi examination and promptly died in the capital. Lady Tian kept her chaste widowhood and raised her son alone, with the support of her elder brother, Prefect Zhang Tongsun, who helped them from time to time. Chunhang's learning owed much of its foundation to his mother's teaching. As a child he had a reputation for extraordinary gifts; as he grew, people marveled at his exceptional qualities. At thirteen he entered the district school; at eighteen he passed the supplementary examination.",
    "He had a distinguished and imposing appearance — luminous as a jade mountain, clear as autumn water. His disposition was graceful and cultivated; his bearing was outstanding and free.",
    "In the school, people said he stood among the crowd like a crane among chickens. But his luck had not yet come — he failed three times in the provincial examinations.",
    "He had taken a wife from the Yan family — virtuous and comely, daughter of a district school instructor — and they were harmonious together, like qin and zither in tune.",
    "In the first month of the previous year, Lady Tian, seeing that her son was trapped in the countryside with no prospects, concluded this could not be a long-term plan. Moreover, a good number of his father's fellow jinshi from the same examination year had by now risen to prominent positions. So she directed Chunhang to go to the capital to pursue his studies, with the old family servant Tian An accompanying him. Departing from home, he first went to Hangzhou, then to Suzhou, where old friends and current acquaintances, as well as several influential officials, all lent their support. Chunhang lingered in those two places for half a year; his poems and writings were copied and circulated almost everywhere. People of the day said he could rival the Hanlin compiler Hou and the district magistrate Qu in literary fame, and as a result his purse filled up nicely and his luggage box was full of gifts. Needless to say, there was also visiting the pleasure quarters and carousing with wine, calling on singing-girls and sleeping in their fragrant rooms, until he was nearly too happy to think of leaving. When he received his mother's letter urging him to proceed promptly to the capital, Chunhang was obliged to choose a departure date. He first sent a thousand taels home, then engaged two dashing servants, outfitted himself in furs and fine horses, was seen off by singing-girls and escorted by pleasure-seeking friends. The whole journey was wind and flowers, poetry and wine, roaming with eyes and heart wide open — thoroughly enjoyable.",
    "He took a roundabout route, gazed east upon Mount Tai, paid his respects west at Mount Hua, and did not arrive in the capital until the end of the eleventh month. He took lodgings at Hongji Temple in the southern part of the city, living in the courtyard just adjacent to Gao Pin's. All the fellow provincials and old acquaintances he had yet to visit could wait; alone, he spent his days at wine houses and opera theaters, finding pleasure and solace. Fortunately, the singing-girls here were by no means attractive — they wore their trouser legs tied tight, stuffed their hair full of paper flowers, puffed out their chests with bloated, overfed airs, powdered faces and greasy hair; they ate garlic and onions, drank raw spirits, lay on heated beds hot as the Goddess of Wushan's mountain terrace, and practiced their secret arts like exhausted hunters after a day's chase — so that Chunhang's appetite for women was thoroughly extinguished. Seeing the young gentleman-actors, who in their way resembled those of the south, he devoted himself wholeheartedly to watching opera. And he did not care for kunqu, but loved the clapper-style bangzi operas, and so was captivated by several rather undistinguished performers. Chunhang's capacity for feeling was truly like scattered coins all over the ground — utterly without a central thread. Moreover he was soft-hearted and warm-faced: if someone treated him well, he would treasure that person like a priceless jewel and could absolutely not bring himself to part. In the several months since coming to the capital, he had not accomplished a single serious thing — every day he took several performers along, and beyond eating and drinking, he was also buying them clothes, gifts, and contributing to various expenses.",
    "What little money Chunhang had could not possibly withstand such wholesale dissipation; by the time the new year passed, it was entirely spent. Afterward he began to pawn clothes one after another; as the clothes dwindled, some of the performers began to sense his circumstances and gradually grew distant. Chunhang, being a man of broad and easy temperament, was entirely untroubled by this.",
    "Though Tian An repeatedly remonstrated with him, Chunhang paid no attention and continued finding pleasure in hardship just the same. He had a prior philosophical conviction of his own: \"When funds are exhausted, friendships dissolve\" — if he could enjoy himself one more day, he would count that one day gained; only when he had truly reached the end of all resources would he stop. By this point, Gao Pin and Chunhang had already become acquainted.",
    "They gathered together morning and evening and were on the most intimate terms. Gao Pin would often weave words of gentle remonstrance into his banter. Chunhang would mouth his agreement while inwardly dissenting, and would even try to drag Gao Pin out with him; Gao Pin went along a few times. Gao Pin was currently a supplementary seventh-rank minor official at the Board of Punishments; keeping up carriages, fine clothes, and social obligations was already a strain, so he could not manage things the way Chunhang did. Moreover, he was not fond of the performers Chunhang admired, saying that the crowd Chunhang loved were not remarkable, and Chunhang disagreed. But then, when Li Yulin came to visit Gao Pin, and Chunhang saw that particular graceful, tender, elegant beauty — which seemed somewhat finer than Rong Guan and the others — he spent a few days privately revising his own opinion.",
    "One day Gao Pin came over and happened to find Chunhang at his meal — half a dish of plain vegetables and a bowl of white rice.",
    "An old manservant and a young boy stood in attendance on either side. The dashing senior manservant had long since departed. Chunhang talked and laughed easily, entirely at his ease. Gao Pin said: \"You treat yourself so sparingly, yet you treat others with such lavish generosity — I must say you fall far short of the little players in this.\" Chunhang, hearing this suddenly, thought Gao Pin was mocking him; yet knowing that mockery was habitual with him, he let it pass and asked: \"How do you arrive at that conclusion?\" Gao Pin said: \"Look at your current lodgings and meals — in which respect do you match the little players? How is it that you have such warmth for others and yet none for yourself? Besides, I know your circumstances well enough — you are no better off than I, Gao Zhuoran, in this regard. Even granting that generosity is your natural character and lavishing money is your habit, you need not pour good gold into a bottomless cesspit. Let me ask: did you come to the capital to seek a career, or to make merry with young players? Buying flowers and plying wine may be occasional pleasures; but to become as reckless as you, spending yourself to the bone — I fear you may meet a bitter end before you ever drink the pledging-cup in triumph, and suffer a fate you cannot undo while the plum blossoms still bloom. This is what I cannot fathom.\"",
    "Chunhang gave a wordless laugh and said: \"I used to take you for a man of true understanding. Having heard you now, I see you have not yet attained it. You have read twenty years of books and still do not understand even the two characters 'nature' and 'principle' — yet you come to lecture me on right and wrong. Let me explain it for you.\" Gao Pin said: \"Please do enlighten me.\" Chunhang said: \"True and without falsehood — that is sincerity. From sincerity one reaches clarity — that is human nature. If there is one part falseness, one part emptiness, then sincerity is forfeit.\" Gao Pin said: \"Granted. But surely you are not saying that true sincerity means making merry with young players?\"",
    "Chunhang said: \"Ranging across ten thousand li in every direction, up and down five thousand years of history — where is there anything finer than these young players? Anyone who does not love them is not worth counting. If there were one part falseness in one's love for a young player, that person would be false through and through — and if not genuine here, where would one use one's genuine self? If there were one part emptiness in one's love for a young player, that person would be empty through and through — and if not true here, where would one use one's true self? Furthermore: nature is principle, and principle is Heaven. If one cannot be at peace with one's nature, where does one seek principle? Without principle, where does one speak of Heaven? The Creator expended great effort in bringing these young players into being — surely the Creator has been most generous toward them. Since the Creator spares no labor, arranging for each one a face like this, eyes and brows like this, skin and body like this, a coquettish smile and artful pout, delicate and alluring — if the Creator did not intend for people to love them, why not place them in some primordial wilderness, some vast and empty waste, cut off from the world, left for wind and smoke to erode, so that the world would never know that such beauties exist — would that not have saved a great deal of trouble? Since they are not permitted to live out their lives in quiet obscurity, but must instead be gathered in the capital, the center of power and distinction, clearly the Creator's intent is that eminent gentlemen and men of fame throughout the realm should appraise and appreciate them — lest this devoted effort of the Creator's go to waste. Consider seasonal flowers and beautiful women, the bright moon and gossamer clouds, rare books and renowned gardens — all manner of supremely beautiful things, which everyone loves, yet which can seldom be gathered in one place; to obtain even one of them is already a source of deep satisfaction. But a young player is like a seasonal flower, yet not a mere plant; like a fine jade, yet requiring no artifice; like the bright moon and gossamer clouds, yet close enough to hold and enjoy; like a rare book or a famous painting, yet capable of speech and conversation; like the most exquisitely beautiful of all wonderful things, yet with a thousand charms and a hundred graces shifting and varying endlessly. To lose a young player and gain all the beautiful things of past and present would not be worth calling remarkable; to gain a young player and lose all the beautiful things of past and present need cause no regret. Mencius says: 'When young, one pines for father and mother; when one discovers beauty, one pines for lovely maidens; when one holds office, one pines for the ruler.' We of the humble scholar class have no occasion to offer hymns to sage rulers and worthy ministers; and living far from home, the rites of morning and evening attendance on parents are forgone. Of the three pining loves, only the two characters 'lovely maidens' — which the sages decreed thousands of years ago as our object of longing — remain. And surely even the sages must have been there themselves at some point; otherwise, how could they have said it so precisely? What I most fail to understand is why people today consider love for women ordinary and love for men extraordinary — in the end it is just love of beauty, so why draw a distinction between male and female? To love women but not men means ultimately one loves lechery, not beauty. If a man is devoted to lechery, then beauty is not his real concern; whereas if he is truly devoted to beauty, he will not dare indulge in lechery. And what I most fail to understand of all is placing equal weight on wealth and beauty: loving another's beauty while begrudging one's own money — exchanging rotten, stinking dung for a rare and fragrant treasure flower, which is heavier and which lighter? Zhuoran should be able to judge.\"",
    "Gao Pin, having heard this speech, had no ready answer. He then said: \"The deepest feeling belongs to people like us — am I someone who does not understand human sentiment? My reason for advising you is that your bedside gold is entirely gone, and I have no purse I can offer. Even if you could one day be ennobled as a duke of Xingyang, I fear that among this crowd there would be no one willing to play the Guo Guifuren to your salvation. The young man in the dark kerchief may enjoy a fine name in the wine houses for now — but the tattered beggar in rags may suddenly find himself starving in the flower streets. I privately fear you may end up like Zheng Yuanhe, mocked by history.\" Chunhang laughed: \"Would a true man be spoken of in the same breath as a miser who hoards money? What I gained by myself, I lose by myself — what regret is there in that?\" The two were deep in their lively exchange when a servant of Gao Pin's came to say: \"Young Master Yan has come to call on you, sir.\" Gao Pin went out to his own room and found Zhongqing seated there. Asking where he had been for so many days, Zhongqing replied: \"After viewing the lanterns on the festival night, I caught a chill and fell ill for several days — I have not left home for more than half a month and was growing restless indoors.\" He then spoke of Nan Xiang's drunken state on the lantern festival evening. Gao Pin laughed: \"I was there that day too and was quite thoroughly drunk myself. I managed to slip away at an opportune moment — otherwise I too would have been caught in the crossfire. Why on earth would anyone try to pick a quarrel with a man sodden with drink?\" They then fell to talking about the lanterns at the Yiyuan garden and the lantern riddles. Gao Pin said: \"There were two fine riddles — two love letters: one made up of flower names, one of medicinal herb names. Both were solved by someone staying in this same temple — a fellow named Tian Xiangfan. Truly inspired.\" Zhongqing, hearing the name Xiangfan, thought of the young man who had written a lyric in the wine house while snow was falling the previous year — the signature had been Xiangfan — and so he asked Gao Pin:",
    "\"What sort of person is this Xiangfan?\" Gao Pin said: \"Also one of our kind. I mentioned him to you last year — exquisite in every way, a truly refined specimen. Nowadays he is exquisite in a different sense — having polished himself clean of everything.\" Zhongqing smiled and asked: \"How so?\" Gao Pin then recounted his arguments just now and everything Chunhang had done since arriving in the capital, one by one. He added: \"This man is truly a pity — talented and handsome together, broad in temperament and spirit, but loves making merry and has no restraint at all. He is also a native of your Jinling, though now residing in Yangzhou. He says his wife's family is named Yan — perhaps a kinsman of yours? Why not meet him?\"",
    "Zhongqing said: \"A fine idea. Go in and introduce me.\" Gao Pin immediately brought Zhongqing inside. Zhongqing caught sight first of a young man — luminous as jade, radiant as a pearl — was this not the very one he had seen in the wine house the previous year? Gao Pin introduced them. Chunhang, seeing Zhongqing, also felt he looked familiar.",
    "Zhongqing said that ever since seeing the lyric in the wine house last year he had been full of admiration, and truly regretted that they had not met sooner. Chunhang also recalled that encounter, and they exchanged words of mutual esteem. Zhongqing inquired in detail about his family background, and learned that Chunhang's father-in-law was indeed his own relative by a collateral line — Zhongqing had simply been so long in the capital that he had lost track of this branch of the family. The two found their temperaments perfectly matched; being also kinsmen, they were thoroughly congenial, and before long the conversation turned to the most intimate confidences. Zhongqing noticed that Chunhang's dress, which had been so elegantly fine the previous year, was now quite unlike what it had been; recalling Gao Pin's words that he had polished himself clean and had nothing left, he was also curious about the caliber of people he had been so lavish with. He asked: \"I hear you have a considerable fondness for young actors — but which ones have you been admiring? Do they live up to the distinction you bestow?\" Gao Pin cut in: \"His way of admiring is quite unlike other people's — let me tell it for you:\" and then he recited: \"Clack-clack-clatter, the bangzi beat; / Eeee-aaah, the two-string fiddle sings. / Trouser-legs white as autumn cloud, thin; / Climb Shamans' Mount and the farts smell sweet.\"",
    "Zhongqing burst out laughing. Chunhang's face went red and he said: \"Rubbish! Your farts, for their part, have a certain fragrance about them. It's just a pity you've buried Bai Juyi's fine line inside your three stinking verses.\" Zhongqing laughed: \"In all seriousness — who exactly have you been admiring, elder brother?\" Chunhang said: \"I have by no means surveyed all the celebrated beauties in all the troupes — they vary in quality, I imagine. I have simply been going along with whatever presented itself — as they say, unable to escape convention, just making do. Among the main troupes, I would put Dengchun's Yumei and Quanfu's Cuibao at the top; and Lianzhu's Rong Guan is also passable. I suppose these are the ones that meet with general appreciation.\" Zhongqing gave a small smile and said: \"Lord Ye was fond of dragons — yet when a real dragon appeared, he took fright. The man of Zheng dreamed of a deer — yet in the end it was only a dream-deer. Xiangfan has the reputation of being fond of young actors, yet the reality falls short of the reputation. The finest young actors in the world are in the capital, and the finest in the capital are assembled in the Lianjin troupe. Shi Zhujun's Flower Selection from the Qu Stage ranks them most fairly: Yuan Baozhu, Su Huifang, and such as these alone may be called celebrated flowers — and moreover they are accomplished in poetry, lyrics, calligraphy, and painting without exception, truly capable of being our good companions. As for Cuibao, Yumei, and the like, they are nothing more than foxy charmers courting patronage, narrow-eyed creatures given to jealousy, who regard money as their very lives and use clothes to cultivate friendships, welcoming the new today and casting off the old tomorrow. How can Xiangfan be so reckless in his affections?\" Chunhang sat in silence for a long while, head bent in thought. Zhongqing said: \"Are you perhaps regretting that you have admired the wrong ones?\"",
    "Chunhang said: \"What is there to be wrong or right about? It was a passing fancy. Besides, different people have different taste. When it comes to appraising these matters, one must develop one's own discernment and not simply echo others. This crowd need not be expected to affect the manners of the cultivated class — if they try too hard to cultivate refinement, it will seem contrived, and they are better off with the natural ways of young actors, which is where true, unaffected vitality lies. If I were to achieve my ambitions, I would not begrudge ten thousand taels of gold to build a golden chamber of several storeys, with light-robed, long-sleeved attendants in front and powdered and rouged beauties behind, to wait upon me for a few years — and then I would match all these good men and faithful women off in pairs, like jade zithers and jade lutes, fulfilling the grand wish of every heart under heaven, creating a world of joy; and then I, like Maitreya, would smile a smile that never closed — how happy would that be?\" Gao Pin said: \"For your golden chamber, I shall certainly compose you a couplet.\" He then recited: \"In the bright moon of the jade isle, three thousand li wide; / The person stands at the very summit of the Penglai peak.\" Chunhang said: \"That couplet doesn't quite fit the subject.\" Gao Pin said: \"It fits perfectly — the upper line fits your powdered and rouged beauties in the rear; the lower line fits your long-sleeved, light-robed attendants in front.\" Zhongqing and Chunhang both puzzled over this. Gao Pin said: \"With this couplet up on the wall, everyone will know that this golden chamber of yours has a tent erected out front and a kiln opened in the back.\" Zhongqing burst out laughing. Chunhang said: \"Put away that sharp tongue of yours.\" The three talked and laughed for half a day; then Zhongqing returned home and told Wang Xun that Chunhang was a kinsman of his, and also the very young man who had written the lyric in the wine house last year — truly possessed of both talent and looks, but with ambitions too lavish and pleasures that had carried him off. A few days later he went to call on Chunhang again, but made several successive visits without finding him in. Chunhang had by now fallen into complete disarray. Zhongqing, pitying his talent and wishing to help him, heard that he was in a hopeless predicament and scraped together two hundred taels of silver, which he sent with a letter saying he had heard that Chunhang's journey was going poorly and was offering a small contribution toward the cost of his pleasures — it was in truth a test of his character. Chunhang was overjoyed and wrote back to thank him, then proceeded to enjoy himself for another ten or more days, and was once again empty-handed. The things he had recently redeemed from pawn were in pawn again. Zhongqing heard of this and sighed deeply.",
    "One day Chunhang was again at the theater watching the opera — this time the Lianzhu troupe. He sat alone in cold isolation at a spot behind the exit door, in shadow. Watching Rong Guan's performance, he felt his heart stirring with pleasure again. Just as he was absorbed in enjoyment, he noticed a table in front of him where a plump man of about thirty sat down, wearing a fur-lined coat inside out, accompanied by a clever-looking young man of about twenty; behind them stood a manservant. The plump man spoke in pure Beijing speech; the other was from the south. These were in fact Fu San and Wei Pincai. Before long, Rong Guan had removed his stage makeup and was sitting in the gallery upstairs talking with a young man. He came down again and sat for a moment in the lower area, then walked over toward this side, greeting and acknowledging people along the way.",
    "Suddenly catching sight of those two at the table in front, he quickened his steps and greeted them, then sat down in the middle. Chunhang's clothing was by now utterly unlike what it had been — he had only a few everyday old garments left — and moreover he was sitting in the shadow; his appearance was all the dimmer and darker for it, and Rong Guan did not come over to acknowledge him at all. He only heard Rong Guan say: \"Second Master, someone was very grateful for your kindness yesterday.\" The plump man said: \"Who was that?\" Rong Guan said: \"Er Xi of the Lianzhu troupe — he says you are very good to him, gave him quite a number of things, and he stayed at your house for a night. Is that right?\" The plump man said:",
    "\"I don't know him, actually. That day Master Wei brought him into town and they drank a few cups of wine; by evening the city gates were closed, so he stayed overnight. In the morning they visited a temple, and then he said he wanted to buy a few small things and went out. This Er Xi is all right — he knows how to make himself agreeable.\" Rong Guan said: \"Nowadays everyone is about making themselves agreeable. Our master was not good enough — when he was teaching us to perform, he forgot to teach us how to make ourselves agreeable.\"",
    "The young man put his hand on Rong Guan's shoulder and said: \"You too just need to know how to make yourself agreeable — would Master Fu San not like you then?\" Rong Guan said: \"I've said I don't know how. If you would teach me, I would take you as my master. However you teach me, that's how I'll learn from you.\" The young man smiled and gave Rong Guan's cheek a pinch. Rong Guan turned his head and caught sight of Chunhang; he lowered his eyes briefly, then cast them back for a lingering look — then turned away again. After a long moment he turned back again and looked Chunhang up and down, in a manner that seemed to want to acknowledge him but then stopped itself. Chunhang was quite puzzled and thought: \"Can it be that he doesn't see clearly? This is already mid-spring, yet people are still wearing medium-weight furs. Chunhang was already in a full cotton-padded garment.",
    "His boots were also stained with mud — utterly unlike his former appearance. Rong Guan was therefore startled, and inwardly thought: \"It looks plainly like Master Tian — but how has he come down to this? Sitting there all alone in the cold and quiet.\" He was inclined to go over and acknowledge him, but feared it might not be him. After looking more carefully and satisfying himself, he went over, made a greeting bow, sat down, and they talked quite a good while. Fu San paid no attention; but Pincai noticed and tugged at Fu San's sleeve, saying: \"Look there — Rong Guan is actually paying court to that person. What sort of person could that be, to have anything worth paying court to?\" Fu San said: \"Hard to say.\" Rong Guan took his leave of Chunhang and returned to Fu San's side. Pincai said with a smirk to Rong Guan: \"Some grand old patron, eh?\" Rong Guan's face reddened and he said: \"He really was grand, once. He never left debts for others to settle on his behalf.\" After a short while, Fu San and the others took Rong Guan with them and called for another performer, and they all left.",
    "The sky had turned to a fine drizzle. Chunhang had no more heart for watching; he paid what he owed and left. Outside, the ground was already slippery as oil. After a while, the carriage of Cuibao of the Quanfu troupe came straight toward him; Cuibao caught sight of him, turned his head away, and passed right by. Chunhang felt distinctly displeased and could only lower his head and slowly pick his way toward the drier patches of ground.",
    "Who would have expected that the streets here were narrow and crowded with horses and carts — where was there any dry ground to be found? Up ahead a large mule-cart came bearing down at flying speed, its curtain drawn, a person perched on the carriage rail beside the driver. The road was too narrow; the cart was already upon Chunhang. The mule tossed its head and knocked against Chunhang's shoulder; Chunhang swerved, stepped on a slippery patch, lost his footing, and went sprawling. The fall was rather well-timed in one respect — he was splattered head to foot with mud, yet his face was spared. The person inside the carriage was startled and hurried to lift the curtain, leaning out with a voice like a warbler calling: \"Quickly hold the beast still and help that person up!\"",
    "The driver had already leaped down and reined in the mule; the manservant also jumped down to help Chunhang up. Chunhang, burning with shame and rage, was on the verge of scolding the driver, when he saw the one riding in the carriage — smiling profusely and leaning out from inside — saying: \"You must have had a dreadful fright! The driver was careless and failed to look out properly — how dreadful to have soiled your clothes so!\" And she gave the driver a few sharp words of reproof.",
    "Chunhang looked — and it was a young actor of surpassing beauty. A luminous radiance seemed to fly out from the carriage, wrapping itself around his eyes, and all his anger he knew not where it had dissolved to.",
    "This young actor was as if fashioned from ice and snow, carved from jasper — charm within charm, fragrance enfolded in fragrance.",
    "Just like the bright moon and the pear blossom, all in white; entirely suited to an orchid heart and a wisteria soul, the whole person suffused with a pure fragrance. Chunhang stood there stupefied, longing for a house of gilded rooms to place this beauty in, longing for a curtained chamber of patterned silk — and all at once five hundred years of karmic debt and three thousand kalpas of demonic entanglement came tumbling out of him; he even forgot that he himself was lying in the mud. Smiling broadly, he steadied himself against the carriage rail with his two muddy hands and said: \"It is nothing, nothing at all — this was my own carelessness, a momentary misstep. These clothes are old in any case; it is no loss if they are soiled. Please do not be troubled on my account.\" With that he stepped back and bowed repeatedly: \"Please, please be on your way.\" The young actor leaned out once more, with many apologies, and departed. Chunhang stood there watching the carriage until it had gone far away, then turned and walked on. Those who had watched this scene covered their mouths and laughed.",
    "Chunhang, dripping mud and water, made his way step by step back to the temple, regretting all the while that he had not thought to ask which troupe this small-role actor belonged to. Entering the temple gate, he took off his clothes and handed them to Tian An to clean, changed out of his muddy boots, and in only a lined jacket went to sit in Gao Pin's room. Gao Pin, seeing that he wore no outer robe, and that the rain had made the weather cold, asked why he was not wearing more. Chunhang explained that the rain had soaked his clothes and he had had Tian An dry them out. Gao Pin took a robe from his own luggage and gave it to him to wear. Chunhang sat down and said: \"Although I took a spill today and got rather muddy, that particular spill was in fact a most amusing one. Two months of making merry with young players was not as satisfying as this one fall. By some extraordinary dispensation of Heaven I encountered a surpassing beauty — even if I had fallen to my death from the encounter, I would not become a wronged ghost.\" Gao Pin laughed: \"What sort of nonsense are you talking?\" Chunhang then described the young actor he had seen, and Gao Pin said: \"Let me compose a little verse in the style of the Book of Songs and recite it for you.\" He then recited:",
    "\"Rain falls, rain falls, east of the Pear Garden. / There is one beautiful person, whose carriage moves swiftly. / Not the carriage moves swiftly — / Why is he in the midst of the mud?\" It is in the mode of direct presentation. Chunhang laughed and then described the young actor's appearance and clothing, and even the color of the mule-cart's curtain, and asked: \"Do you know which troupe this actor belongs to?\" Gao Pin thought for a moment and said: \"From your description, it must be either Lu Sulan, or Jin Shufang — or else Yuan Baozhu.\" Chunhang said: \"Jin Shufang is in the Lianzhu troupe and I have seen his performance — he is rather thin and spare-looking; not him. As for Lu Sulan and Yuan Baozhu, I do not recognize either — I cannot say who this was.\" Gao Pin said: \"Yuan Baozhu is not much given to wearing pale-colored garments. From your description, it doesn't quite sound like Lu Sulan either. Then it must be Su Huifang — yes, it must be Su Meixiang. A truly ice-clear autumn sky of purity, absolutely spotless and refined. He is neither heavy nor slight in build, with a face like a hen's egg, and habitually wears pale-colored garments. He is in the Lianjin troupe. Shi Zhujun ranked him second.\" Chunhang said: \"Only second — then who is first? Is there really someone finer than him?\" Gao Pin said: \"The first is Yuan Baozhu. In a few days when the spring drains are opened, you will see for yourself.\" Chunhang said: \"Why then?\" Gao Pin said: \"Seeing the second-ranked actor already landed you in the carriage rut — if you were to see the first-ranked, you might well end up in the drainage ditch.\" Chunhang just kept laughing; he continued to trace the young actor's image in his mind, and after a while that face and voice, those graceful spirit and charm, appeared vividly before him — he sat there without speaking, smiling foolishly to himself. He dined that evening at Gao Pin's and they talked on until the third watch, when they each went to bed.",
    "The next day the sky had cleared. Chunhang rose very early, hung out his clothes to air and dry, brushed away the mud, changed into a new pair of boots, and felt the urge to go and hear some opera — but was tormented by the lack of funds, having nothing left to pawn.",
    "He thought of Tian An, who still had a few garments. He went to Tian An's room, but found him absent; unable to wait, he opened Tian An's luggage pack, and there inside, wrapped up, was a lined robe of pongee silk. He took it out, sent the young servant Zhanghe to pawn it — yielding six strings of cash — and was greatly pleased. He skipped eating and went to see the Lianjin troupe five days running before catching a glimpse of that young actor. He watched him perform one scene of a solo opera, then inquired after his name — it was indeed Su Huifang. Huifang happened to pass near Chunhang, recognized him as the one who had tumbled in the mud the other day, and, noticing his clothes still mottled with stains, could not help smiling faintly — but felt too awkward to come over and acknowledge him. Chunhang, seeing Huifang smile at him, felt as if he had encountered a jade maiden tossing rings from Heaven, as if Heaven itself had opened its mouth in welcome — and was so happy he could find no words. He thought and thought, but alas he could not call him over. And looking at the way this one conducted himself, it seemed he would not easily consent to sit beside someone at a banquet — he was clearly not the kind to come flying over at the drop of a note. With no plan in mind, he sighed and groaned by day; his dreams were tossed and turned at night; he was on the verge of coming down with lovesickness. Then Tian An would come in with one fretful complaint after another — saying he had pawned his robe, what did he need to keep it for — and also saying that coal and rice were completely gone, that the shop refused to extend further credit because the previous debt was still unpaid, and that the monks were pressing for the rent, which was due positively the next day.",
    "Chunhang simply let it wash over him; he lay on the heated bed fully clothed, thinking only of Huifang. Tian An went out, muttering and grumbling without pause. Chunhang was also somewhat at a loss.",
    "But in his whole life he had never asked anything of anyone — to whom could he go now to borrow? Moreover, he had been in the capital for two or three months without paying a single social call on any fellow provincial or old acquaintance; how could he now go to ask someone for a loan? Then his thoughts turned to Yan Zhongqing — just one meeting between them the other day, yet he had spontaneously given him two hundred taels of silver, without Chunhang even asking. This person was truly an ancient man in a modern age. It seemed he had not done it out of the slender bond of distant kinship — he must have understood Chunhang's true nature. It seemed there was still room to discuss matters with him.",
    "After spending the night in thought, the next morning he wrote a letter — not stating things plainly, but hinting obliquely in terms that suggested a plea for help — and sent Zhanghe to deliver it. Chunhang waited at home for good news; before long Zhanghe returned empty-handed, without even a reply letter, and said: \"The gatekeepers said Young Master Yan had received the note and would send a reply shortly.\" Chunhang assumed he must be working out the money, ate his meal, and waited a while. Then suddenly someone came from Yan Zhongqing, carrying a rolled painting, and said: \"Our young master sends his respects to your honor. He asks that your honor write an inscription on this painting — I am to wait and take it back.\" Chunhang was mystified, and no reply letter had come; he could only open the painting and look. It was a portrait of Zheng Yuanhe painted by Tang Liuru — Zheng in his tattered rags, begging for food in the wind and snow. Chunhang understood at once that he was being mocked; an involuntary surge of fury reddened his cheeks. Yet he could not very well make a scene in front of the messenger, so he simply said: \"Wait outside for a moment — I shall write something at once.\" The messenger went out. Chunhang, seething with indignation, spread the painting on the table, and saw that two seven-character quatrains had already been inscribed on it, under the signature \"Composed by Jiantan.\" The poems read: \"On the day the prince went begging, starving near the Huai — / On the day the Minister Wu languished in strange poverty — ",
    "These are the trials that try heroes through all ages; / How unlike the dissolute idler, adrift in the pleasure lanes? // Coat patched a hundred times, sheepskin in tatters, / Still singing lotus songs, feeling no shame. / Had the bewitching beauty lacked a woman's fierce integrity, / This life would have ended without ever turning homeward.\" Chunhang thought to himself: \"Though his mockery is cutting, his reasoning is not wrong — how am I to counter it?\" He composed his thoughts briefly, took up his brush, and with a single sweep wrote:",
    "\"To make the moth-brow beauty become a righteous heroine, / One must first allow the fine steed to suffer a time of hardship. / This was Heaven's arrangement from the beginning — / None but those who know what love is can easily understand it. // A talent that surpasses all the ages — truly no vain boast; / In the remains of the tattered coat, the man of feeling can still be seen. / Let not the gilded youths of the Five Tombs hold him in contempt — / Who of them will match his later name and fame?\" He added his signature, affixed his seal, rolled the painting back up, and gave it to the messenger. Feeling stifled and disheartened, Chunhang went out alone.",
    "The messenger returned and presented the painting. Zhongqing and Wang Xun read it together. The two quatrains, though forced in their argument, revealed something of their author's spirit — and they could not help feeling a renewed pity for the man. Zhongqing had originally intended his two poems to reform Chunhang; who would have thought they would only provoke him further? He also heard from the messenger that Chunhang's circumstances were still more wretched than before.",
    "According to his manservant's account, that very day the kitchen fire had gone out, and there was nothing to cook. Zhongqing and Wang Xun both sighed. Zhongqing said: \"From the look of things, this man is truly like the saying: 'My heart is not a stone — it cannot be turned.' What can be done? What can be done?\" Wang Xun said: \"You sent him two hundred taels the other day; in less than half a month it has completely evaporated. Given the way this man behaves, sending him another two hundred taels would be equally useless. Unless you were to divide half of Xu Duxiang's entire fortune and give it to him — then he would have something to squander. But a man who cannot even keep his kitchen fire going is in a sorry state. In my view, we might help him with another hundred taels right now, to be held at Zhuoran's, who can dispense it as circumstances warrant, and gradually enlighten him. Perhaps relying on Zhuoran's way with words, he might yet be brought around — it is not entirely impossible.\" Zhongqing agreed. Wang Xun immediately prepared a hundred taels and handed it to Zhongqing to deliver to Gao Pin's quarters. As for what happened next — hear it told in the following chapter."
  ],
  13: [
    "After Zhongqing had provoked Chunhang into anger, he sent the hundred taels that Wang Xun had prepared to Gao Pin, to cover Chunhang's daily expenses of firewood and food. Chunhang sat brooding for two days; pressed on all sides for rice, coal, and the repayment of debts, with nowhere to turn for a loan, he accepted Gao Pin's kind offer to stay and was thus obliged to take his meals there for the time being.",
    "One day, after eating, Gao Pin went out to pay calls, and Chunhang went to the theater, his heart entirely fixed upon Su Huifang. Having no money to watch the opera, he could only stand at the entrance, waiting to catch a glimpse of Huifang going in or coming out. Just as the performance was about to begin, he did indeed see Huifang arrive in a carriage and step out at the entrance; but just then a crowd of people pressed in to see the opera, and in the jostling Chunhang was shoved to the rear, so that they could not come face to face. Chunhang was deeply vexed; he pushed his way out again, but Huifang had already gone inside. He could only stand there motionless, waiting for him to come out. While waiting he also saw many of the celebrated performers, every one the equal of Huifang.",
    "Chunhang thought: \"Who would have expected the Lianjin troupe to have such fine performers — truly their fame is no exaggeration.\" He waited a full three hours before seeing Huifang emerge with his head lowered, two splendidly dressed beautiful young men ahead of him and two manservants carrying cushions and clothing bundles — and Huifang boarded his carriage and was gone. Chunhang, knowing Huifang had not seen him, returned home in a mood of dejection.",
    "He spent another night there; the following day he went again to stand at the theater entrance the whole day, but did not manage to meet with Huifang. That day was thus wasted, and he sighed his regrets without end. Chunhang had been in this obsession for so long that he could not easily come to his senses; every day he went looking for the Lianjin troupe, waiting for Huifang. For more than ten days running, Huifang had also noticed the person who had previously fallen in the mud — every time he mounted or dismounted his carriage, that same figure stood at the theater entrance, like one drunk or bewitched, eyes fixed without moving. Huifang found this deeply strange. Looking more carefully at the man's appearance, he saw a clarity and refinement of spirit and bone, a poetic elegance that was pleasing to the eye; though his face showed a touch of haggardness, his jade-like frame still glowed with sentiment and grace. Huifang's heart already understood clearly that this person was coming on his account, and he could not but be somewhat moved; he sent rippling glances his way on several occasions. Chunhang was so delighted his eyebrows danced — every day he followed Huifang's carriage all the way to the door of Huifang's lodgings in Jixiang Alley, lingering there for a long while before departing.",
    "Then one day Chunhang's good fortune arrived — it was, as they say, the destined affinity of each: just as he was following Huifang's carriage, Huifang noticed him carefully and felt a stirring of compassion. The moment he went inside, he sent his manservant out to invite Chunhang in. The manservant went out,",
    "gave Chunhang a look, and said: \"Sir, are you looking for our young master? Our young master asks that you come inside for tea.\" Chunhang was overjoyed beyond all expectation — and yet stood rooted to the spot, unable to move forward. The manservant invited him again; Chunhang was still too bashful and self-conscious to move. Then suddenly another person came out from inside and said, would the gentleman who had been following the carriage please come in. Chunhang finally straightened his clothes and followed the manservant through the main gate into a courtyard. On both sides were two layers of delicately constructed bamboo fences. It was now the last ten days of the second month, when all the flowers were in simultaneous bloom — the entire courtyard was a profusion of vivid crimson and brilliant violet, fragrant and resplendent. In the front stood a modest three-bay reception room, fitted out with bronze vessels, a qin, and books — altogether refined and elegant. Before long, Su Huifang came out, dressed in a plain pearl-skin ensemble, and stepped forward to make a greeting bow. Chunhang instantly seized his hand — and felt a soft, delicate grip, like spring bamboo shoots, slender and fine. Standing side by side, the two were nearly the same height. Huifang was already seventeen. Huifang faced Chunhang with a smile: \"We have seen each other every day, yet I have not yet had the honor of knowing your honored home and distinguished name. The other day, when you suffered the indignity of the mud, I was deeply grateful for your gracious forbearance. As for your repeatedly honoring me with such attention — this has been the blessing of three lifetimes.\" Chunhang was thoroughly astonished: \"Such refined and elegant speech, such graceful command of words.\" He said: \"From the moment I first beheld your honorable face, I have been unable to sleep or rest; my humble admiration can only be pledged in my heart. Yet rather than reproach me, you receive me with this invitation — truly a generous and deep-hearted regard, which I, Tian Xiangfan, shall never forget as long as I live.\" He then explained his native place and name, and added a few words of admiring affection. They looked at each other, then at each other again, and for a while stood in wordless silence.",
    "Huifang then invited Chunhang inside. They passed through the reception room, entered through the western bamboo fence, and came to a small courtyard. Five bays of rooms lay in a row: on the east side, one bay separated off as a guest room with a bed for unexpected visitors. The middle two bays were left open as a small study. The western two bays formed a suite of inner rooms — Huifang's sleeping quarters. Chunhang first sat down on the heated bed in the center room, where eight hanging panels of meticulous figure-painting by Qiu Shizhou depicting an Assembly of the Immortals adorned the walls; on both sides the windows were set with nanmu wood frames and glass panes; the floor was covered with a three-blue velvet carpet, spotlessly clean. After sitting a moment, Huifang led him into the western inner suite. A floor-standing partition screen of hongmu rosewood in a plum-blossom pattern divided the space; outside it stood two small bookshelves and a multi-treasure cabinet. Against the wall was a small wooden heated bed with a cream-colored embroidered silk cushion; on the low table beside the bed stood a Fen-ware rectangular porcelain basin in which five or six stems of plain-hearted orchid were blooming. On the facing wall hung six panels of small regular-script calligraphy on gold-flecked paper — one panel per person, each written in balanced, graceful characters. One bore the signature Duxiang Zhuren; one, Jingyi Yishi; one, Zhujun Cike; one, Jiantan Shanren; one, Qianzhou Waishi; one, Yongan Jushi. They appeared to be a set of seven-character regulated verses composed in a matching rhyme scheme. Looking at the heading inscriptions, Chunhang saw they were six chapters of seven-character regulated verse composed in response to Meixiang's original rhyme scheme for the Long River Purification Festival poem. His admiration deepened even further. He thought to himself:",
    "\"So he can compose poetry.\" He asked: \"These are composed in response to your original rhyme — your poetry must be of a most profound and accomplished level.\" Huifang laughed: \"Just hasty scrawlings — I merely cobbled together a few plain sentences. What do I know about composing poetry?\" Chunhang said: \"And your original piece — why has it not been written out?\" Huifang said: \"Yuan Baozhu wrote a copy of it for me last year; someone borrowed it to read and it was lost.\" Chunhang then looked Huifang over once more with careful attention, and said: \"I observe that your bearing is lofty and pure, your speech refined and elegant — you seem entirely unlike anyone from the world of performers. When did you come to the capital to learn the theatrical arts?\" A look of self-conscious shame crossed Huifang's face; he let out a sigh and said: \"If you ask about my origins — I am indeed from a respectable family. My father also served as an official.\" Chunhang rose and said: \"My apologies — I had indeed thought you did not look like someone from a humble background. But then why did you take up this profession?\" Huifang's eyes reddened at the rims and he said:",
    "\"Please sit, and I will tell you properly.\" Chunhang sat down. Huifang said: \"When I was small I followed my father in his official posting in Yunnan. When I was eight years old, my mother died. By the time I was twelve, my father was impeached by his superior and fell gravely ill from the shock; within less than a month he was gone. He had always had nothing but empty sleeves — not a private saving to his name — and whatever small funds there were, various relatives and personal attendants divided up like a melon or bean, leaving me with nothing but one old family servant. We stayed in Yunnan for more than a year. Pitiably, there was not a soul to look to; in that world of snobbery and self-interest, who would spare a thought for us? We survived entirely by relying on the old servant to carry loads and walk from place to place. When it became truly impossible to hold on any longer, I had no choice but to make the journey home with the old servant. Along the road we endured every hardship imaginable; it took a full year and two months before we reached Suzhou. What greeted us there was rank weeds and desolate smoke, mulberry fields turned to sea — cold eyes from relatives and neighbors, arms folded and no one lifting a finger. We could not even obtain so much as the loan of a single room or a single meal. We lodged at a temple for several days. I made inquiries and learned that a distant relative was serving as a private secretary to an official in Zhili; we used every last bit of our strength, caught a grain transport boat heading north, and came up that way. We arrived first at Baoding and went to the address of that relative — but when we inquired, we found he had become embroiled in some affair and had been exiled to the frontier passes. His family had also dispersed, no one knew where. Now you tell me — was our fate low or not?\" Chunhang said: \"When the mountains are exhausted and the rivers run dry and it seems there is no road ahead — what happened then?\" Huifang said: \"What were we to do in Baoding? We thought of coming to the capital to find some means of livelihood, and as it happened, right as we came out of Qianmen gate, we met a good person — a fellow provincial and my early childhood teacher, Mr. Gu. He was a licentiate, and seeing our miserable state, he took us to his lodgings and asked us everything from beginning to end. Now let me ask you to guess — what was this teacher of mine doing in the capital?\"",
    "Chunhang said: \"A private tutor, surely.\" Huifang said: \"He was not a tutor at all — his ways were in some respects rather like yours. He was at that time only twenty-seven years old. He came to the capital and spent all his days watching opera; when all his money was spent on opera, he had mastered opera — and had gotten to know a great many performers. So he became a teacher of theatrical arts. Then one year when he failed the autumn examination, he burned his examination writings, joined the Lianjin troupe, and became a secondary male-role performer.\" Chunhang said: \"That is truly the act of an untrammeled man — without any hesitation or inhibition.\" Huifang said: \"He took us in, and whenever he had free time he would teach me to read and write and look into poetry and lyrics; we lived there quietly and comfortably. But alas, my poor old servant — worn down by the hardships of the road, and burdened with grief and worry — fell ill the moment we arrived in the capital. After two months of illness he died. At that point I felt all the more solitary and alone, with nowhere to advance and no way to retreat, and I could only rely on my teacher for my very survival. Not until the spring before last did my teacher urge me persistently to study the theatrical arts. At first I was unwilling; but then thinking it over — there was no other path open to me — I finally agreed and learned a few pieces. Gradually, day by day accumulating, I became accustomed over time. My teacher was most fond of composing poetry; every poem he composed he would explain to me and teach me to try composing as well. Mine may have been incoherent, but I found myself genuinely enjoying it. But fate was unkind — before I could repay his deep kindness, my teacher contracted a seasonal illness last summer and died, leaving me utterly alone, pitying my own shadow.\" At this point his voice choked.",
    "Chunhang was also genuinely moved by this account and said: \"In five years — the stars shifted, things changed — you tasted so much of the ways of the world.\" He offered a few words of comfort. Then, drinking two cups of tea, Huifang asked Chunhang: \"Since you enjoy the opera so much, have you come to admire any particular performers in the various troupes?\" Chunhang laughed: \"I am one who prizes beauty over artistry; I pay no attention at all to the technical aspects of the opera, and as for ranking the performers — I have no understanding of that either. I simply take those who have fine looks and treasure them as the supreme. At first I was reckless, my eye untrained, and upon meeting any seductive face I would be quite swept away. Having now gazed upon your jade-like countenance, I feel as though the wondrous dwelling Bodhisattva has appeared upon the lotus throne — beyond what a creature of the lower world can hope to approach. What came before was truly like Wang Xizhi studying calligraphy under Lady Wei — a futile expenditure of years. My shame and remorse have no end.\" Huifang, having heard these few words from Chunhang, was already half won over. He gazed at Chunhang for a good while without speaking, then smiled again: \"You say you treasure those with fine looks as supreme — but I would like to know, what specifically is it that you treasure?\" Chunhang stood up, and in high spirits, arms and feet moving expressively, face glowing with animation, he said: \"Meixiang, you are a person of understanding — try to guess!\" Huifang blushed slightly and said: \"I would not know how to guess.\"",
    "Chunhang said: \"It is for no other reason at all.\" Huifang then asked with a serious expression: \"Then for what reason?\" Chunhang said: \"If the looks are fine and the temperament fine, I am willing to die for that person.\" Huifang said: \"Someone else being fine has nothing to do with you — why should you die for them? Come, tell me: what is it that deserves treasuring?\" Chunhang said: \"Listen to me. Those of us who travel thousands of li from home, aside from two or three intimate companions, have four other kinds of fine friends that are most difficult to obtain — and even when obtained they commonly have some unsatisfying imperfection. So while one can call them treasures, one cannot call them the supreme treasure.\" Huifang said: \"How strange! What are these four kinds of fine friends? I must ask to be enlightened.\" Chunhang said: \"The first is fine weather: the evening sun, the bright moon, gentle rain, clear breezes, light mist, crystalline snow — even sitting alone, one's heart and spirit become open and glad. Feeling the beauty of spring and autumn days, lingering over the scenery and surroundings — whether in open countryside or pavilioned courtyard, with elegant bamboo and scattered blossoms, under the shade of parasol trees or willows — leisurely reciting verse and strolling slowly, savoring the fragrant season, one forgets the mundane world.\"",
    "Huifang nodded: \"Quite so — that is indeed fine. The second must be fine scenery.\" Chunhang said: \"Exactly: a hill, a valley, the mountains and waters serene and secluded, with every step revealing a changed view and drawing one deeper in. The third is fine books — those that lack a single dead sentence and a single idle brushstroke, leaving the reader endlessly exploring.\" Huifang also nodded. Chunhang said: \"The fourth is fine poetry arising from the spirit's depths — no need to confine oneself to worshipping Du Fu and venerating Han Yu; if one line or two can express what others cannot express, one may contend with the ancients for supremacy.\"",
    "Huifang said: \"Quite so — you are truly a person of refined and universal understanding.\" Chunhang said: \"These four friends are indeed fine, yet each has its imperfection. Fine weather — how many such days in a month? Often the morning is beautiful and by afternoon it changes, so that even the morning's beauty is retroactively spoiled. When one's mood flags, one begins to dread wind and rain and dares not linger. Fine scenery — how many places of the kind in an entire province? Some can only be reached on foot by treacherous or obscure paths, with sand and rocks and thorns, eight or ten li away, so that one grows exhausted — often knowing its beauty yet unwilling to make the journey. As for books: aside from the few volumes on every household's lips and strings, the ocean of writing is vast, yet most of it consists of texts that waste wood and paper. Even where something new emerges from the old, it reflects individual hands and styles, and cannot fully satisfy every taste. As for poetry — it is small in scope yet difficult to perfect. Sometimes when one first composes a poem it seems like refined gold, yet when one reads it again it is like chewing wax; one regrets having let the brush fall too easily. These four friends are difficult to obtain, and to obtain them and find them perfectly satisfying is even more difficult — so one can call them treasures but cannot call them the supreme treasure. Only those of your distinguished profession form, beyond these four friends, one perfectly beautiful friend of unmatched quality — a treasure friend.\"",
    "Huifang laughed: \"The term 'treasure friend' is quite remarkable — we ourselves have no idea we possess anything worth treasuring.\" Chunhang said: \"Soft as jade, warm as perfume, flowering with richness, gleaming like snow — that is the treasure of beauty. Rounded like Lady Huan, slender like Lady Yan, flesh smooth and bone fragrant — that is the treasure of the body. Bright eyes that glance bewitchingly, a coquettish smile and an artful pout — that is the treasure of the face. A thousand charms gathered to one side, a hundred allurements born across the whole — that is the treasure of manner. Tender crying that sips the dew, lovely speech that chides the flowers — that is the treasure of feeling. Pearl hairpins carved in kingfisher hues, gold hair ornaments with flying rosy clouds — that is the treasure of adornment. Add to all this the pure song and the exquisite dance, the sandalwood clappers and the golden goblets, the trills of the voice-box and the light steps on the verge of falling — and one calls this the treasure of artistry, the treasure of a person.\" Huifang said: \"Your argument here is truly excellent — though in some places it sets the standard too high.\" Even as Huifang said this with his mouth, he was in fact deeply moved and grateful toward Chunhang within his heart; he could not help casting languid sidelong glances and allowing his powdered cheeks to soften with sweet tenderness. He studied Chunhang carefully, and the more he looked the more fine qualities he found; in his eyes, all the wealthy princes and elegant young gentlemen were quite eclipsed.",
    "Chunhang said: \"Tea-smoke and the sound of the qin, wind and rain and the cock's crow at night, thinking of one's old friends with a heart that reaches a thousand li — without a kindred spirit to share morning and evening, where is there joy to be found? And then in the desolate temple, loneliness and sorrow, a fading lamp and solitude — where indeed can one find two or three intimate companions to endure the bleakness together? Only you people of refinement — a word or half a phrase that sinks into the bones of the heart, turning a hundred-tempered blade of steel into soft silk wrapped around the finger. And then a heavenly beauty like you — even if you could only be seen and not approached, I would be like the pilgrim who, upon catching sight of the Bodhisattva, prostrates himself at every step — I would do that willingly. How could I dare to harbor any other hope?\" Huifang, hearing this, could not restrain the tears that flowed down his face; he said: \"Your heart I now understand — say no more. Come, tell me what has been happening with you since you arrived in the capital.\" Chunhang then gave a full account of everything from last winter to the present day. Huifang smiled again and said: \"You are truly a person of utterly devoted feeling and utterly wild fancy — yet I also admire your two legs for running every day, and standing without moving at the theater entrance.\" Chunhang said: \"Were it not for you, I would not come even if invited.\" Huifang smiled, went out, and directed someone to bring in several kinds of fruit, several dishes, and two pots of wine, inviting Chunhang to drink a little.",
    "Chunhang made no show of refusal. The two sat across from each other at the small huali-wood table and drank, each pouring out what was deepest in their hearts. By this time Huifang's own heart was completely drawn in, without a trace of calculating self-interest.",
    "When the meal was finished, they moved to the inner room and sat for a little while; then Huifang told the manservant to hitch up the carriage outside and take Master Tian back to his lodgings. Huifang clasped Chunhang's hand and said: \"We have become friends today — do not betray this friendship for the rest of our lives. If I, Su Huifang, speak a single false word, let the bright sun be my witness. From now on you need not come out to look for me — I will come to see you, early or late, every single day. You must take good care of yourself and make effort toward your prospects. Please do not, for our sake, lose your good name and give others occasion to talk.\" Chunhang, hearing this, was so moved that his admiration turned to reverence, the feeling penetrating to his very marrow; tears were already streaming down his face. The two looked at each other and choked with emotion for a while — only the manservants and other attendants did not understand what this was about and found it quite puzzling. Still talking as they went, they came outside; Huifang saw Chunhang into the carriage and gave him a few more parting words; Chunhang went directly back to his lodgings — there is nothing more to say of that.",
    "Huifang also went to bed that night, but carefully went over everything Chunhang had said, and lay for a long time thinking about his circumstances. When he finally fell asleep, Chunhang appeared before him — transformed into magnificent ceremonial dress, bearing a grave and imposing demeanor that inspired awe; then transformed again into a middle-aged man wearing the robes of the first rank. Through a night of vague and disjointed dreams, he finally woke the next morning late.",
    "It was already breakfast time before he washed his face and ate something light. A manservant came in and announced: \"There are visitors outside.\" Huifang asked: \"Who is it?\" The manservant said: \"It is Master Zhang from Fuhu Bridge, together with Third Master Pan from the Qisheng Silver Exchange.\" Huifang had no choice but to dress and go out to receive them.",
    "Now, this Master Zhang was none other than Zhang Zhongyu. This Master Pan, Pan Qiguan by name, was a wealthy man of the capital with assets of a million taels: he operated three silver exchanges, two pawnshops, and also ran a spice shop; he also held a sixth-rank purchased post. His original home was in Shanxi, and the family had lived in the capital for two generations. As a person, he was miserly and sordid, mean-spirited and obstinate, and moreover a thoroughgoing lecher — pursuing both genders day and night without tiring. He had one saving grace: he was a grand commander utterly afraid of his wife. His current wife — taken as a second marriage — was possessed of perhaps eight or nine parts of good looks, but of a jealously fierce temper beyond ordinary measure. Though Pan despised this third-master Pan, she would not permit him to carouse outside. If Pan Qi stayed out for a single night, she would mount her carriage with her attendants and search every pleasure-house in the area; when she found him, she would make such a scene that everything fell to pieces. Pan had no countermeasure, and lately had conceived the idea of acquiring a boy companion from among the theatrical troupes, and was keeping a watchful eye for the right candidate.",
    "He had settled his eye on Su Huifang. Today he had brought Zhang Zhongyu along, wanting him to act as a go-between. Zhongyu thought to himself: \"Huifang's character and bearing are refined and superior; he will hardly be willing to follow Pan Qiguan.\" And so he hedged and demurred, reluctant to help bring this about. Pan Qiguan pressed him repeatedly, promising generous gifts of gold and silk. Zhongyu had no choice but to come along and make whatever he could of the situation. They arrived at Huifang's home, sat down, and exchanged some idle talk.",
    "Now consider what manner of appearance Pan Qiguan presented:",
    "He was of short and stocky build, with a round face the color of soy sauce and a mouth full of bristly yellow-brown whiskers; he was over forty years old. His belly protruded in the middle and his buttocks were concave — coarse and offensive. He wore a suit of blue silk padded clothing and a velvet-trimmed informal hat, with a small sable tail hanging behind; on his feet he wore blue satin stockings and gray-trim shoes; from his collar hung a short tobacco pipe, with half a green-leather tobacco pouch showing. His pale yellow eyeballs were threaded with red veins; he wore a fawning, squinting smile and assumed an exaggerated manner of humility and warmth. Huifang had no choice but to sit down and keep them company. Zhang Zhongyu glanced at Huifang with an expression of someone about to say something yet not saying it. Huifang lowered his head; after a moment he stood up, went to the window, and looked at the orchids planted in the basin — his thoughts were with Tian Chunhang all the while, and yet he could not tell them to leave; he sat and stood in alternating unease. Pan Qiguan sat without moving and without speaking, his eyes fixed on Huifang. Zhang Zhongyu said: \"We need not bother to find another location — why not lay a spread of wine right here, and have a few informal dishes? Would that not be fine?\" Pan Qiguan said: \"Excellent — and the house is nice and quiet too.\" Huifang said: \"That would be fine, but I cannot keep you company for long today — I must leave shortly. The Gusu Huiguan has a performance, and my part comes in the second act.\" Pan Qiguan said: \"That doesn't matter — it is all right not to go.\" Huifang said: \"But I really cannot not go.\" Pan Qiguan said: \"You have no master anymore — who are you afraid of offending? A person as celebrated as you — who could you possibly displease?\" Huifang said nothing, and could only tell the manservant to quickly prepare wine. Before long the wine and dishes were laid out; Huifang urged them to take their seats; Pan Qiguan pushed Zhongyu to sit at the head. After a few cups had been drunk, Pan Qiguan began talking on and on in a cloying, nauseating stream. Huifang was thoroughly repelled, and a scheme came to mind: making a pretense of being warmly attentive, he stood up, offered several cups of wine, and engaged in a few rounds of finger-guessing games — inwardly hoping to get him drunk so he could make his escape.",
    "But Pan Qiguan turned out to be a veteran at drinking — the more he drank the more sober he remained. As the wine went down, the words that came out of his mouth grew worse; he extended that short, fat, blunt, hard hand of his and grasped Huifang's hand, saying: \"My dear child — why have you never come to see me? I have been longing so for you. Every time I watch your performance, I dream of you that night — the two of us so close and warm, playing together for such a long time; when I wake I feel exhausted. You are truly killing me. And I have no son — what is all this great fortune of mine for? You come and be my adopted son, and the two of us, father and child, can enjoy ourselves every day — is that not fine?\" Huifang, hearing this, nearly burst into angry tears; his eyes reddened. Inwardly he thought: \"This wretch doesn't even consider his own standing — how odious! Let me bait him.\" He suppressed his anger and assumed a smiling expression: \"Third Master talks such nonsense. A foolish child like me — how could I possibly attract attention? I see that you listen to the opera every day, and you have never so much as glanced my way, never called out a word of praise, and today in front of Master Zhang you tell nothing but fibs and try to hoodwink people.\" These few words made Pan Qiguan feel as if there were no bones left in his body.",
    "Zhang Zhongyu was secretly astonished and thought to himself: \"How extraordinary — who would have expected Su Huifang to actually like Pan Qiguan? Does money truly move even the spirits? My financial luck is in — I shall make a handsome profit from this commission.\"",
    "He chimed in at once: \"Third Master Pan talks of you to everyone he meets — praising your looks, praising your temperament and skill, never a day without saying it at least twice. He often says: 'If only you were willing, he would give you a silver exchange.'\" Turning to Pan Qiguan, he said: \"Didn't you say that in so many words?\" Pan Qiguan nodded. Huifang smiled: \"How many silver exchanges do you have? One for each performer — with several hundred performers in the capital, do you have several hundred silver exchanges?\"",
    "Pan Qiguan said: \"Other people cannot squeeze a single cash from me; only for you I would be willing to do anything.\" Huifang's mind was already made up; he fixed Pan Qiguan with a sidelong glance, sweeping away all seven souls and three spirits in the man's body. Zhongyu was also in high spirits, knocking his finger on the table and calling out his approval. Huifang said: \"Third Master Pan, since your heart is set on me, you must drink freely today without holding anything back.\" Pan Qiguan said: \"Bring the large cups!\"",
    "Huifang then went himself to fetch two large cups, filled them to the brim with wine, and offered one to each: then filled two more and said: \"Third Master Pan, I would have drunk a 'twin-cup' with you today, but in truth my capacity is small and I cannot manage it — so you drink this pair.\" Pan Qiguan nodded and bobbed his head as he drank them down. Two more cups were filled; turning to Zhongyu, Huifang said: \"Master Zhang, you also drink a 'twin-cup.'\" Zhongyu laughed: \"Who am I supposed to be twinned with?\" Huifang said: \"Will you be twinned with me? Today I ask you first to be twinned with Third Master Pan.\" Zhongyu flicked a playful finger against Huifang's forehead and said: \"Is someone like me worthy?\" Huifang pressed him to drain it, and he did. By now both Pan and Zhang had reached about seven parts drunk; they ate another couple of dishes. Huifang then went to his room, changed into a fresh outfit, and came back looking all the more neat and radiant. Third Pan started up with his pinching and pawing — flesh-crawling enough to make Huifang frantic — but Huifang could not very well run away, so he had no choice but to play more drinking games with them, and even sang a few little songs. Zhang Zhongyu, noticing a pipa hanging on the wall, took it down and plucked the strings in accompaniment, and they talked on leisurely.",
    "By the time it was nearly the hour of You, Huifang saw that the two were still not soundly drunk, and decided to test Pan's true intention: \"Third Master Pan, there is something I should not by rights say, given that we are not really close acquaintances. But I am in a bind: I owe someone a sum of money, promised for tomorrow. Today I was planning to go out and arrange it, and then you, the god of wealth, arrived — could you possibly lend me a hand?\" Pan Qiguan said: \"How much?\" Huifang said: \"Not much — two hundred taels.\" Third Pan glanced at Zhongyu. Zhongyu said: \"Look here — is Huifang worth only two hundred taels? And you, Old Third Pan, are starting to hedge. Either way it's all the same.\" Pan Qiguan paused for a long moment, then felt in his inner pocket for a leather account folder with a sheaf of money notes, counting out tens of strings of cash at a time until he had assembled two hundred strings of Beijing cash. He handed it to Huifang and said: \"Here are two hundred strings — take them for now.\" Huifang thanked him and tucked the notes into the side of his boot, then said: \"How can I accept such a generous gift?\" Pan Qiguan said: \"Let your conscience be your guide.\" Huifang smiled beguilingly and threw Pan Qiguan a glance that made Third Pan half-delirious with delight, clear saliva streaming from the corners of his mouth. Huifang then filled a large cup of wine, held it in his hand, and said: \"In honor of these two hundred strings of cash, I shall break my rule today and offer Third Master Pan a 'skin cup.'\" Pan Qiguan, hearing this, felt a tingle run through every part of his body, and a heaving began to build in his chest. Huifang took a mouthful of wine, walked to Pan's side, and with a beguiling smile let it flow back out again and gave a little laugh. Third Pan had already opened his mouth and was waiting; Huifang, seeing this, picked up a piece of fish with his chopsticks and put it in Pan's mouth. Third Pan accepted it; Huifang then picked up a piece and ate it himself, and then said: \"Oh my, oh my — this is no good at all!\" Zhongyu said: \"Don't choke on it.\" Huifang said: \"I'm afraid that's exactly it.\" Pan Qiguan said: \"Quickly, bring some rice — swallowing hard will fix a choke.\"",
    "An attendant brought half a bowl of rice; Huifang ate a few mouthfuls and then leaned his head back against the chair-back, saying he was not well, that it hurt terribly. Zhongyu said: \"Eating green plums will clear it.\" Huifang ate several green plums and still said it was no better. Third Pan leaned over and brought his face close to Huifang's face, trying to get a sweet gesture, and said: \"Open your mouth and let me have a look.\" Huifang covered his face with his sleeve and said: \"How can one look when it is covered like this? And all because of that skin cup I offered you — if you just drink a few more cups, the pain will go away.\" Third Pan said: \"Really?\" and drank a large bowl, then asked: \"Is it any better?\" Huifang nodded; Pan Qiguan drank two more cups before stopping. Huifang then complained of pain again; Pan Qiguan urged Zhongyu to also drink a cup; Huifang said it was much better, and then remarked: \"Watching the two of you drinking so freely, I forget the pain.\" Pan Qiguan, now thoroughly besotted with nine-tenths of a drunk, had no idea he was being played, and dragged Zhongyu along — one cup for me, one sip for you — until Zhongyu was drunk too, and in his muddled state could not keep his wits, and drank a prolonged round. When both men had drunk to their absolute limit, a surge came all at once: Pan Qiguan's head spun, he leaned backward, and with feet flying up in the air, went tumbling over backward, crashing to the floor. Zhongyu, seeing Pan Qi had collapsed, rose to his feet with a great laugh — then crouched, and toppled sideways. The two of them lay on the floor like half-dead creatures, neither moving a muscle. By now it was twilight. Huifang called for the table to be cleared, laughed, and said: \"So you wished to eat swan's flesh — well, you brought this upon yourself. Today you have learned at last the formidable nature of Su Meixiang.\" He then told the manservants: \"Help them to sleep on the bed in the reception room, remove their outer garments, lay a large quilt over them, and let the two of them enter the clouds of Shamans' Mountain together.\"",
    "Having made all these arrangements, Huifang at the same time called for the carriage to be hitched, and went to his own room where he opened his chest and selected five sets of clothing in lightly padded cotton and lightweight silk and single-layer gauze; these he packed together with the two-hundred-string cash notes Pan had given him, added a set of bedding, and had the whole of it carried out by the manservant and loaded onto the carriage. Huifang mounted the carriage; the manservant rode on the footboard; and they went together toward Chunhang's lodgings. Just as they reached the entrance of the alley, they saw in the moonlight a figure standing there; the driver looked — and recognized it as Tian Chunhang. He stopped the carriage and called out: \"Old Master, we are on our way to your place!\" Huifang and the manservant, hearing this, both jumped down from the carriage. Huifang seized Chunhang's hand: \"What are you doing here again?\" Chunhang said: \"I waited all day without seeing you come, and I couldn't go on. I had been standing outside your door for a long while, too embarrassed to go in, and so I was standing here.\" Huifang sighed: \"You impossible creature — you truly give me no way to handle you.\" He asked Chunhang to sit inside the carriage, while he himself rode on the footboard. They talked the whole way there and arrived at the temple gate where they dismounted. The manservant took the clothing bundle and shouldered the bedding; they all went inside together and sent the carriage back with instructions to come again the next day.",
    "Gao Pin had already gone to bed; Chunhang did not want to disturb him, and went directly to his own room. Tian An was dozing over the table. Chunhang trimmed the lamp brighter and woke Tian An: \"Go quickly and make tea.\" Tian An rubbed his eyes; seeing a beautiful young person, he took him for a young gentleman and hurried off to make tea. Huifang sat down and, looking at the sparse and meager state of the lodgings, felt a genuine pang in his heart. He then had the manservant bring in the clothing and the cash notes, and said: \"These five sets of clothing are all things I have worn — if you don't mind their being used, please keep them. This money I give you for travel expenses. I had originally thought to invite you to come and stay at my place, but for the sake of appearances that would not be suitable. If you are short of anything, just ask me.\" Chunhang said: \"How could I possibly accept this? I absolutely cannot receive it.\" Huifang said: \"If you refuse to accept, then you are looking down on me. Am I bringing things here to play tricks on you? You must not have that kind of thinking in your heart — once you have it in your heart, even your feeling becomes false. I ask only one thing of you: from now on, you are not allowed to go out to hear the opera.\" Chunhang gave his ready assent again and again. They spoke further of their most intimate thoughts and feelings, each moved by a sense of having found a kindred spirit — until they could not help but be stirred to emotion. Sitting facing each other, the two had formed what was purely a friendship of moral principle, without the slightest improper thought, and they talked until the cock crowed, at which point each lay down, still clothed, and slept.",
    "Now as for Pan and Zhang: they slept through in complete oblivion. At the fourth watch of the night, Pan Qiguan turned over, rolled off the heated bed with a rumble, and sat on the floor, needing to relieve himself. He groped around in all directions for a chamber pot. His hand found one of his own shoes; he pulled down his trousers and urinated into the shoe — mostly into his trouser seat. Fumbling in the dark, groping about the floor, he found the edge of the bed and climbed back up. His mind, while still muddled, turned over the question of where he had been drinking, and somehow, even in his drunken state, his thoughts fixed on Su Huifang. He then groped around on the bed, found Zhang Zhongyu, and took him for Huifang — wrapped his arms around him tightly and cried out \"Dear son, dear treasure\" without stopping, tugging and pulling at him, so that the quilt had long since been knocked to the floor. He then seized Zhongyu's clothing and pulled with full force, tearing one lined jacket; his arms gave out; he pulled at his own trouser cord with great force and broke it — yet rather than pulling his trousers down he kept trying to pull them up; the urine-soaked trousers were already thoroughly wet through, even soaking the mattress — and could not be pulled off, so he simply pressed himself tightly against Zhang Zhongyu's back and writhed. Zhongyu awoke feeling as if someone had grabbed him and was shaking him; the wine in his stomach surged straight up to his throat, and as he turned his head he vomited. Pan Qiguan happened to have his mouth wide open at that moment and received a generous mouth-to-mouth full-face installment, the skin-cup delivered in seven orifices. A thick coating accumulated all over Pan's face; he cried out loudly, shaking his head, splattering everything in all directions. Zhongyu's second round arrived — this was pure wine — and poured down, washing Pan's face clean; but the stench was utterly unbearable. Pan, now frantic, sat up and wiped his face wildly with his sleeve, muttering \"Little creature, little demon.\" Zhongyu, hearing this, said: \"Who are you? Who are you cursing?\" Pan Qiguan cursed: \"You unbearable little rabbit — splattering your own father's face with filth!\" Zhang Zhongyu flew into a rage: \"Who is your father?\" He shoved with both hands; Pan Qiguan rolled off the bed. Zhongyu sat up and cursed: \"Which son of a turtle-egg dares to curse at me in my own bed?\" Pan Qiguan said: \"You accursed little rabbit — how dare you curse at your own father? This is outrageous!\" He scrambled up and back onto the bed to strike — but just then Zhang Zhongyu was climbing down, they collided, and in the confusion Zhongyu landed a slap, and Pan Qiguan went sprawling again. Zhongyu said: \"Who on earth are you?\" Pan Qiguan bellowed at full throat: \"Mutiny! Mutiny! Mutiny! You accursed little rabbit, actually striking your own father! You want to sleep with your father — yet you pretend not to recognize him. Do you think I, Third Master Pan, have come here to assault you by force?\" Zhang Zhongyu thought it over and said: \"What Third Master Pan? Can this really be you, Old Third Pan — when did you get here?\" Pan Qiguan cursed again: \"I didn't say you invited me to stay — now you say I just turned up of my own accord? You truly are a death-defying evil rabbit! And where have you hidden Zhang Zhongyu?\" Zhongyu said: \"Hmph — making such a confused, incomprehensible scene — I am Zhang Zhongyu.\"",
    "Pan Qiguan said: \"What do you mean — you are trying to impersonate Zhang Zhongyu to frighten me?\" The ruckus woke the entire household; the odd-job workers, the gatekeepers, all came in with lamps, overcome by the reek of wine. Holding up the light, they saw: Zhang Zhongyu standing with the quilt underfoot; Pan Qiguan seated on the floor, face mottled with a chaotic splatter of colors, one foot bare, one finger pointing at Zhang Zhongyu. Everyone who saw it could not help bursting into laughter; they helped Pan Qiguan to his feet. Zhang Zhongyu stepped over and got a good look at Pan Qiguan; Pan Qiguan in turn got a good look at Zhang Zhongyu; each turned his back and walked away, which set everyone laughing again. The quilt was picked up — and underneath lay a thoroughly soaked single shoe, reeking of urine. A large dark puddle on the floor, and the quilt itself half-ruined. Looking at the heated bed — it was as devastated as an outhouse. A pity for that set of bedding. Pan Qiguan said: \"Where have my stockings gone?\" A search found, in the middle of the floor, one trouser-leg, one stocking, and the bills from the leather account folder scattered all over. Pan Qiguan paid no attention and let them pick it all up. Two servants brought two large basins of hot water; Pan and Zhang washed their faces clean. By now they had both sobered up. Pan Qiguan, feeling the crotch of his trousers cold and clammy, put a hand to it — thoroughly wet through and through, unwearable; he took them off and borrowed a pair of single-layer trousers and a pair of shoes from a servant and put them on. Zhang Zhongyu looked at Pan Qiguan and said: \"How remarkable!\" Pan Qiguan said: \"Remarkably how!\" The two of them thought back over the whole sequence of events from start to finish, and then clapped their hands and laughed for a good while. By now the sky was fully light and the sun had come out. Pan Qiguan then asked where Huifang was hiding. Huifang had, as it turned out, given all the necessary instructions and then slipped out. The odd-job worker said: \"Last night, after the two masters had fallen asleep, a message came unexpectedly from Young Master Hua, who lives outside the city, summoning Huifang. We servants dared not refuse Young Master Hua; it is feared that today he has been taken into the city and may be staying several days before returning.\"",
    "Zhang Zhongyu said: \"One can hardly blame Huifang for that — Young Master Hua is not to be trifled with.\" Pan Qiguan had no recourse; he could only regret the two hundred strings of cash, which had effectively bought him a face full of vomit from Zhang Zhongyu and a slap in the bargain. He could only bide his time and work things out later, and the two departed together in a state of gloomy frustration.",
    "On the other side, Huifang and Chunhang rose in the morning, washed their faces, and ate their breakfast. Huifang noticed a qin hanging on the wall.",
    "He asked Chunhang: \"Do you know how to play the qin?\" Chunhang said: \"I know a little.\" Huifang said: \"Why not play a piece for me to hear?\" Whether Chunhang played or not — hear it told in the following chapter."
  ],
  14: [
    "Huifang had been asking Chunhang to play the qin, and Chunhang said, \"Just a moment.\" He kept his eyes fixed on Huifang without blinking. Huifang laughed and said, \"Can you really not make me out yet? Why do you keep staring so blankly?\" Chunhang laughed and replied, \"I look at you from every angle and see a hundred different charms — like the glow of flowers in morning dew, or the evening sun greeting the breeze. My eyes cannot hold you fast; the more I look, the less I can fully take you in.\" Huifang clicked his tongue, stood up, and began undoing Chunhang's buttons, helping him out of his robe. Chunhang said, \"Let me do it myself — you're not accustomed to this, there's no need to trouble yourself.\" Huifang opened the clothing bundle and took out a small fur garment, which fit Chunhang perfectly when he put it on. He then had Chunhang change into new boots and a new cap.",
    "Huifang smiled as he took up a mirror and held it beside Chunhang, and it reflected back two figures of jade. Chunhang looked at Huifang's image in the mirror — there he was, like a lotus that could speak, like autumn water without a speck of dust — and gave a slight nod. When he turned his face back, it happened to brush against Huifang's cheek. Huifang tilted his face aside, and half of it flushed crimson.",
    "Chunhang felt his heart stir; he could not resist a wave of strange fragrance that penetrated directly into his nostrils and the innermost chambers of his heart.",
    "His will could no longer hold itself in check, but he urgently pulled his thoughts back: this person is my confidant in times of hardship — how could I allow the slightest impure thought? He steadied his spirit and composed himself. Huifang gave a smile and moved away. Chunhang, now dressed in his new clothes, was once again resplendent in bearing and radiant in spirit, just as he had always been.",
    "Huifang sat down and idly leafed through the books on the writing desk. He came upon a manuscript of poems, written in a hand halfway between regular and running script, running to several dozen pages, with the title \"Drafts from the Yan Capital\" (燕台旅稿) inscribed on the cover. Huifang turned at random to a page and found a heptasyllabic ancient-style poem entitled \"Vexing the Beloved\" (恼公), which he began to read aloud in a low voice:",
    "The curtain hooks click like jade, their sound crystalline; / Cherry blossoms are mirrored in the silver latticed window. / Green cloudy hair tilts to one side, the swallow-tail hairpin falls — / Year after year the brocade characters bloom red on the spring loom. / Huifang said, \"A fine poem! This style derives from the 'Thirty-Six Forms' of Wen Tingyun and Li Shangyin — exquisitely lush and delicate.\" Chunhang replied, \"It was written on a whim; I can only approximate their manner, no more.\" Huifang read on:",
    "Far hills, an inch of blue-green — two eyebrows of kingfisher hue; / Gauze half-dyed with the red of rouge-laden tears. / In the painted beams the swallows fly; / On the mandarin-duck tiles the cat lies asleep. / Huifang said, \"What fine craftsmanship, and the rhyme turns crisply. The line about the cat surpasses the one about the swallows — and placed against the mandarin-duck tiles, it becomes all the more fresh and original.\" He read on:",
    "A waist of drifting smoke, of clasped moonlight, a single foot around — / Star-bright eyes jealous of the spring clouds' proud allure. / Huifang called out \"Wonderful!\" and added: \"'She drew near, and a hundred charms were born; she turned to go, and that autumn glance' — even those lines are not sufficient to convey this poem's subtlety.\" Chunhang said, \"The image seems to be you.\" Huifang said, \"Am I worthy of it?\" He read on:",
    "Jade dragons, slender, coiling in the ring's tracery; / Golden sparrows, paired, flying in the trembling hairpin. / The tender lover, like the paulownia blossom wind, / Draws near her cloudy tresses — yet her body does not stir. / Soft love for fragrant gauze, the mist of fine silk light; / Coy disdain for brocade curtains, the silver hooks too heavy. / Huifang said, \"How richly gorgeous, how even and assured. Even I feel tenderness looking at it — but for whom did you write it? If she 'draws near her cloudy tresses yet her body does not stir,' why must you haunt the theater every day?\" Chunhang walked over and leaned lightly against the back of Huifang's chair. \"Could this person perhaps not be reckoned among the theater folk? Before, I longed to draw near such fragrant grace and could not; now, it seems, my wish is fulfilled.\" Huifang said, \"Who is it? Someone from our troupe?\" Chunhang nodded. Huifang said, \"Let me think — who does it resemble? The upper couplet — 'a waist of embracing moonlight, star-eyes jealous of clouds' — none but Yuan Yaoqing could answer to those two lines. The lower couplet — 'soft love for gauze, coy dislike of heavy curtains' — none but Jin Shouxiang would quite fit. Is it those two?\" Chunhang shook his head. Huifang said, \"Then who is it?\" Chunhang said, \"There is one person who combines the charms of both — and you simply cannot guess him.\" Huifang said, \"I truly cannot guess; tell me plainly.\" Chunhang laughed and said, \"I'll tell you plainly: it is an empty allegory. If there happens to be someone who resembles him, we may as well say it is that person.\" Huifang did not press the matter and read on:",
    "Behind painted railings and pearl curtains a dragonfly hangs; / A single peach tree blossoms, graceful as a lovely girl. / Morning after morning she permits the young man to gaze at her flowers — / Only a single pane of glass stands between them. / Huifang closed the volume and pondered a moment. \"What a beauty — fair as flowers, bright as the moon. What a fine talent — embroidered lips and brocade heart. What does 'a dragonfly hangs' refer to? I suspect there is an allusion.\" Chunhang said, \"Li Yishan's (Li Shangyin's) poem: 'At dawn the curtain's strings break a dragonfly's wing; on the gauze screen there is only an empty blue expanse.'\" Huifang said, \"I have seen that poem — I had momentarily forgotten it. Let me see how you make the transition below.\" He read on:",
    "Young man, the peach blossom's color rivals my face — / Yet the peach blossom is easily seen, while I am hard to meet. / My beauty will always be like the moon at the second day — / But your heart, I pray, will not follow Wen Sanbian's example. / Huifang said, \"It must open this way — only then does what follows have room to breathe. 'Wen Sanbian' — is that to say you have changed your heart?\" Chunhang replied, \"I am drawing on a line from the Preface to the 'Collected Literature' (艺文序): 'Tang literature changed no fewer than three times.'\" Huifang looked at Chunhang and said, \"So by that reckoning, you too cannot be counted a man of good conscience.\" Chunhang said, \"How so?\" Huifang replied, \"Her beauty cannot always remain like 'the moon at the second day,' and so your heart will inevitably arrive at 'Wen Sanbian's three changes.'\" Chunhang laughed and said, \"When reading poetry, one cannot take it so literally — otherwise the poem becomes a dead thing through and through.\" Huifang gave a smile and read on:",
    "The gauze curtains lie desolate in the pearlescent chamber; / Musk and dragon-brain incense linger — how one mourns their fragrance. / Thirty-six brocade carp-scales are too hard to convey; / The jade flute blows broken — cloud and sky stretch without end. / Huifang nodded and sighed: \"In this life, partings and reunions, joy and sorrow — all are fixed and certain.\" He continued reading:",
    "Green embroidered sheng-bag hangs on the eastern wall; / No flowers, no words — spring is desolate and still. / The wronged woman yearns to pluck the Sang-fu zither string; / The palace lady leans in grief upon Yang Fei's flute. / Huifang said, \"What a clever parallel. The pairing of 'Sang-fu's zither' and 'Yang Fei's flute' is truly an ingenious oblique correspondence. The upper line naturally alludes to Luo Fu of the 'Mulberry Path.' But this 'Yang Fei's flute' — I recall Zhang Hu's poem: 'In the small window of the quiet courtyard, unseen by any, / At leisure I take up Prince Ning's jade flute to play.' And I once read the 'Outer Biography of the Precious Consort' (贵妃外传):",
    "\"The Emperor Xuanzong was dwelling with his brothers when the Consort secretly took Prince Ning's jade flute and played it — and for this she incurred the imperial displeasure. Is that the allusion you are using?\" Chunhang said, \"That interpretation can stand, but it does not quite fit the phrase 'the palace lady leans in grief.' My source is a passage in the 'Records of the Unusual' (集异记): when the Emperor fled to Shu, on a moonlit night he ascended a tower, and a former attendant of the Precious Consort, Hong Tao, sang the 'Liangzhou Melody' composed by the Consort, while the Emperor took the Consort's jade flute and played along, and when it was done they looked at each other and covered their faces and wept.\" Huifang nodded, then read on:",
    "The begonia flowers, drunk, fall; butterflies drift away; / Cotton-soft willow catkins, too weak to fly, cling and yearn. / The water at the bottom of the well is like my heart's intent; / The dust on the roadside clings to the garment of my lord. / Huifang felt a pang of sadness, and his expression changed. \"Such depth of emotion, such lingering tenderness — what a devoted soul. This must be the closing passage.\" He read: \"Kingfisher-feather wind-trains drag the phoenix's red tail.\" Huifang said, \"This line arrives from out of nowhere — the brushwork is bold and startling, and then it opens up again. Does a phoenix have a red tail?\" Chunhang said, \"Wen Feixing's (Wen Tingyun's) poem has the line: 'The Qin King's daughter rode upon a red-tailed phoenix.'\" Huifang continued: \"Astride the phoenix, following my lord for thirty thousand li. / One day, this fragrant heart turns over a hundred times; / At leisure it rises again with the smoke from the censer.\" He had just finished reading when Gao Pin walked in. \"What a fine poem! Only such a sweet and winsome voice is fit to recite these fragrant and elegant verses. But there is one line in the poem that, with three words changed, would be even more apt and fitting.\" Huifang stepped forward. When he saw who it was he said: \"Last night I meant to come and pay my respects, but you had already retired.\" Gao Pin laughed: \"By that account, the two of you have already spent a night together.\" Huifang clicked his tongue: \"We talked through the night until just now.\" Gao Pin said, \"Your complexion doesn't look like it.\" Chunhang said, \"Which line of the poem do you think should be changed?\" Gao Pin said, \"The line that corresponds to 'The water at the bottom of the well is like my heart's intent.'\" Huifang looked again at the next line and read: \"'The dust on the roadside clings to the garment of my lord' — what is wrong with that?\" Gao Pin said, \"It is fine, but too vague. Better to change it to 'The mud before the carriage wheels smears the garment of my lord' — that way it is vivid and full of flavor.\" Huifang smiled sweetly. Chunhang said, \"Whenever you open your mouth, there is never a single good word.\" Gao Pin then examined Chunhang from head to toe for a good while and said, \"Yesterday I cast a divination: Heaven-Wind Gou, transforming to Mountain-Wind Gu, with Water-Heaven Xu as mutual hexagram. The line text is rather difficult to interpret.\" He then recited: \"'The field yields one hare; going, one meets rain; tarrying in the mud; meeting the golden man; encountering the master at the temple; there is a torn hemp garment — perseverance brings good fortune.' I cannot quite work out the meaning.\"",
    "Huifang listened intently, as if lost in thought. Chunhang laughed: \"You cast the divination yourself, yet you cannot interpret it.\" Gao Pin laughed too.",
    "Huifang was about to ask Gao Pin's opinion when footsteps were heard outside the window — a shadow passed back and forth. Chunhang asked, \"Who is it?\" A cough sounded, followed by a reply: \"It is I — I have a word to say to Lord Gao.\" Gao Pin recognized the voice at once and said, \"Ah, how delightful!\" He stepped out and looked: sure enough, it was Tang the Monk from the temple. Gao Pin asked, \"What do you have to say?\" Tang the Monk grinned and squeezed himself inside. He greeted Chunhang, then caught sight of Huifang and pressed his palms together: \"Amituofo — so a bodhisattva has descended to our realm! This little monk failed to come out and welcome you — a sin, a sin! No wonder there were auspicious clouds and blessed rain all through last night. And this very morning, beside Guanyin in the main shrine, one of the Dragon Lady's bodhisattva attendant figures had gone missing — and here she is!\" Huifang, who recognized Tang the Monk, covered his mouth and laughed at this. When Chunhang had first arrived in the capital the previous year, he had gone in pursuit of pleasure and fragrant company, and Tang the Monk had served as his go-between on those occasions, which is why the monk had often come to call on them. Later, finding him vulgar and tiresome, Chunhang had largely stopped associating with him. Gao Pin was on terms of regular banter with him, so he snatched the monk's hat off his head, rubbed his tonsured crown, then said to Huifang: \"Meixiang, I'll propose a couplet — you match it.\" He said:",
    "\"Like an awl inside a bag — the tip pierces through and emerges.\" Huifang gave a small smile. Tang the Monk snatched his hat back and put it on, then started, \"Lord Gao, you — you — you —\" and said nothing more, just grinning. Huifang said, \"I have already matched it,\" and recited: \"Like a gourd floating on water — the top is round and bald.\" Chunhang and Gao Pin both laughed and said, \"Wonderfully matched — quick-witted and apt!\" Tang the Monk laughed and said, \"Many thanks, many thanks — this little monk has the great good fortune of being praised by the bodhisattva, and it didn't even come out to mean what I feared it might.\" He then drew Gao Pin aside and they exchanged a few words in the courtyard, after which the monk departed. Gao Pin came back in, and the three of them ate together. Huifang wished to listen to Chunhang play the qin, so he retrieved the instrument, loosened the brocade case, placed it on the table, and said, \"Play on! Shall we burn incense?\" Chunhang replied, \"Burning incense is a rather hackneyed convention.\" Gao Pin said, \"With Meixiang's own fragrance already filling the room so richly, incense is surely unnecessary.\" Huifang pushed Gao Pin aside with a laugh, sat down beside the qin table, and looked on attentively as Chunhang tuned the strings. Gao Pin said, \"I understand none of this — it seems to me no different from a cotton-fluffer fluffing cotton. What is there to enjoy?\" Huifang replied, \"You don't understand; today you are truly a case of playing the qin to an ox.\" As it happened, Gao Pin had been born in the year of the ox, and he laughed and said, \"In that case, please match that line for me.\" Huifang paid no attention and said off the top of his head, \"There is no match.\" Gao Pin said, \"Seeing a hare, one releases the arrow.\" Huifang paused a moment, then said, \"Your Li Yulin is born in the year of the rabbit — he is sixteen this year. Why not go and call that jade rabbit to us?\" Chunhang also wanted Gao Pin to summon Yulin, and Gao Pin was delighted at the idea; he immediately sent someone to fetch Yulin, and also ordered several dishes to be prepared.",
    "Chunhang sat tuning the qin for a while. The first and third strings were a little flat and could not be tightened properly, so he settled on the Man Shang tuning (慢商), slackening both the first and third strings by a peg, then adjusted the second, fourth, fifth, sixth, and seventh strings in the standard five-tone method. He played a few passages from \"Chen Tuan the Immortal Sage\" (陈抟得道仙翁). Then, sounding some harmonics, he launched into the suite \"The Young Gallants' Gathering\" (结客少年场). Starting with harmonics on the fourth string at the ninth position, he plucked the second string and struck the sixth, plucked the fourth and struck the fifth — qiong-qiong, twenty-two notes, and back again to harmonics on the ninth position. The words of the piece ran:",
    "On stony-cornered fields a fine bull grazes; / A biting-hoof horse neighs through the flowers, apart.",
    "After these four lines, he swept the seventh string open, then the sixth, hooked the fourth, struck the sixth, and hooked the second.",
    "From here on came the solid tones. One saw his left hand's thumb on the second string at the ninth position, vibrating the string twice; then he played five notes, executed a pinch-and-lift ornament of three notes, the middle and index fingers plucking the fourth and sixth strings together while the left thumb hovered over the sixth string at the ninth position. He played five more notes, plucked the seventh and fifth strings together; five more, the fifth and third; five more, the seventh and fifth; five more, the fifth and third — in all some thirty-four notes sounded. The words of the section were:",
    "Across the flowers the proud horse knows men well; / The stalwart young man's spirit is true and bold. / Fine-cloud soft shoes of light leather; / A gleaming single-line cap upon his brow. / A lined robe like Su Qin's, a sword at his side; / And wind-and-rain firewood, like Feng Yi.",
    "This was the first section — measured, with deliberate rhythmic rises and falls, its lingering resonance unforced and natural. He then moved into the second section, plucking and thrusting on the seventh string — the opening full of vibrato techniques and ascending glides, with many back-and-forth pulls and slides, the fingering intricate, giving rise to an ardent and impassioned quality. The tenth note brought a double-string pluck, the fifteenth another, and the twenty-third note produced a clear ding-dang — two notes of great beauty, forming a back-lock cadence. It was most lovely to hear. After that came six more notes. The words of this section were: \"Elder Brother holds life lightly — his heroic spirit pierces rainbow and sun. Second Brother holds money lightly — fearing the laughter of misers. Little Brother holds power lightly — before no king or lord does he bend his knee.\"",
    "After a brief pause, he launched into the third section, hooking the first string while the left hand's middle finger slid down from the thirteenth position. From there, he hooked the second, then third, then fourth strings at the thirteenth position — and the sound suddenly opened up, vast and rich, the shang mode shading into gong. After a few more notes, there came three resonant cries on the seventh, sixth, fifth, and third strings, articulating a suoling ornament — the loveliest sound of all. Then, after the thirteenth note, the seventh string rang out langlinging on five or six notes, making a brief suo cadence; the fifth and seventh, then the fourth and sixth strings, were plucked in turn for four notes, and then nine slow notes brought the section to a close. The words were:",
    "Achievements that will ring through a thousand autumns — / The spirit for them lies in youth. / Below the age of twenty, / Stand at the head with Elder Brother. / At twenty-four — three-and-twenty more than one — / Second Brother, I stand shoulder to shoulder with you. / In the white light of day I point to the blue sky above, / Pouring out the wine libation, wordless, in silence. / Chunhang made to rise, but Huifang pressed his hand down: \"This is just the finest part — please play on.\" Chunhang said, \"The piece is finished.\" Huifang said, \"How can it be over so soon?\"",
    "Chunhang said, \"This suite has only three sections.\" Huifang said, \"Too short — play a longer one.\" Gao Pin laughed: \"Xiangfan, Meixiang finds you too fast and too short. You had better go and paste up a placard advertising some thousand-charm, hundred-beauty remedy.\" Chunhang said, \"Nonsense!\" Huifang made to pinch Gao Pin's mouth shut; Gao Pin bowed deeply and said, \"Grant me pardon this once.\" This made Huifang burst out laughing. Huifang asked Chunhang to play \"The Eighteen Stanzas on the Nomad Flute\" (胡笳十八拍) and then \"Spring Dawn in the Grotto Heaven\" (洞天春晓), saying: \"These two suites I have heard Xiao Jingyi play most beautifully; he also has a combined score for qin and xiao flute. He once taught me to play the xiao.\" Chunhang said, \"'Spring Dawn in the Grotto Heaven' is indeed a fine suite, but it is too long. 'The Eighteen Stanzas' does not quite suit my present mood. Better to play 'The Water Immortal's Air' (水仙操).\" After another pause, he retuned the strings and began to play — clear, cool, and spare. This suite has twelve sections, requiring the most refined fingering, with every vibrato, roll, glide, and press precisely placed, not a hair's-breadth of error permissible.",
    "By the fourth and fifth sections, one seemed to see the Spirit of the Xiang River beating her zither, and Feng Yi the River Lord striking his drum. By the sixth and seventh sections, one seemed to see the Xiang Goddess weeping over bamboo, and Lie Zi riding the wind — the music moaning and lamenting, full of grievance and longing, of weeping and sighing. Truly it could split sword-strokes and probe the heavens; a cool wind stirred and rustled in through the cracks of the window. Huifang and Gao Pin both sat upright and composed, listening with breath held and expression gathered. Suddenly the seventh string at the second division of the sixth position went flat, the fifth string at the sixth position went sharp, and the fourth string at the ninth position was off by several fractions. Chunhang said, \"How strange — why have the tones suddenly gone out of order?\" Gao Pin and Huifang could not detect it. Chunhang tried to retune the strings but could not bring them right, and so he stopped and asked Gao Pin: \"Is there anyone in the temple who plays the qin?\" Gao Pin said, \"The monks may play the huqin fiddle, but no one plays the qin.\" Chunhang said, \"There must be someone who knows the qin listening outside — that is why the string pitches have shifted.\" He had barely finished speaking when wild laughter broke out in the courtyard — startling Gao Pin and the others.",
    "Gao Pin hurried out to look, and who should it be but Shi Nanxiang, his left hand clasped around Wang Lanbao's arm and his right hand holding Li Yulin, already a little flushed with wine. Yulin held a sprig of apricot blossom in his hand, and three or four more people followed behind. Gao Pin noticed that his own attendant was in the courtyard, and asked, \"Where have you come from?\" Nanxiang said, \"You asked your young protégé to keep it secret from me, and now you ask me where I've come from? Today I went with Jingfang to Yiyuan; they were all at home and kept me for dinner. Peijian was there too, along with Yaoqing and Shouxiang. After dinner, someone came from Peijian's household to fetch him. Duxiang asked about it and that's how I learned you had summoned them — so I took leave of Duxiang and came along.\" He pointed at the blossom in Yulin's hand and said, \"We were enjoying the apricot blossoms over there today.\" Then he asked Gao Pin: \"Since when do you know how to play the qin? If you want to learn, I'll teach you. That 'Water Immortal's Air' just now was rather well played.\" Gao Pin said, \"When did I ever play? The one playing is Tian Xiangfan.\" Nanxiang had already heard of Tian Xiangfan's talents from Zhongqing, and said, \"Since it is Tian Xiangfan, why does he not come out and meet Shi Zhujun?\" Gao Pin said, \"Allow me to make the introduction.\" At that moment Huifang had already come out to greet him, and promptly drew Nanxiang inside. Nanxiang said, \"Well! You are here too — I had no idea that Gao Zhuoran's monastic chamber would today become Shi Jilun's Jingu Garden!\" Chunhang also came forward to meet him, and the two exchanged the expected words of mutual admiration. Yulin and Lanbao greeted Chunhang as well, then sat down with Huifang. Nanxiang turned to Gao Pin: \"Since Zhuoran has summoned the young gentlemen, there must naturally be wine — don't pretend ignorance, produce it at once.\" Gao Pin said, \"The wine is ready — it is only the Immortal Peach Life-Extending Pill that I lack.\" Nanxiang said, \"Even if I get drunk, I am unlikely to roll off an upper-story balcony.\" Everyone laughed.",
    "Gao Pin's attendant and the cook brought out wine and dishes. They all sat around a round table. Nanxiang and Chunhang talked further about qin scores and literary arts, each finding much to admire in the other. Gao Pin said, \"Today's Shi Zhujun is the Di Renjie of the pear-garden world; Tian Xiangfan is the Li Yaoshi of the theater troupe.\" Nanxiang said, \"You are talking nonsense again.\" Chunhang said, \"How so? I don't quite follow.\" Gao Pin said, \"Zhujun compiled the 'Yantai Flower Register' (燕台花选), and all these young dan actors became the peach-and-plum of his gates — every rabbit-toadstool and horse-puff ball now a useful ingredient in the medicine chest — is that not Di Renjie? As for Xiangfan: he spent everything he had, and then last night a certain 'Red Whisk' came eloping with him in the dead of night — is that not Li Yaoshi?\" Everyone laughed, except Huifang, who reddened and said, \"For falling off that upper balcony the other day — it would have been better if you had turned into a snapping turtle, or at least broken a leg.\" Gao Pin laughed: \"Tumbling off an upper balcony is still fairly ordinary. What is really frightening is tumbling in the gutter by the theater entrance and being trampled to death by a mule.\" When Nanxiang asked for the story, Gao Pin told it from beginning to end, and Chunhang was so ashamed he wished the ground would swallow him.",
    "Nanxiang burst out laughing too: \"Xiangfan is truly a man of rare romantic sentiment! A peerless beauty moved to feeling by a single fall — that is something that has never happened before. Of old we heard that Sun Shou's falling make-up brought Liang Ji down from his horse. Today we see Su Lang performing onstage, and Tian Zi chasing the carriage. A splendid parallel couplet — let me present it to Meixiang.\" Huifang gave Nanxiang a sidelong glance and said, \"Why must you also imitate that sharp-tongued fellow and mock me?\" Gao Pin said, \"These words are spoken as if you have a deep grudge against me — when in truth I bear you no enmity at all. Why so harsh?\" Huifang said, \"Say another word and I'll expose your secrets.\" Gao Pin said, \"Go ahead and expose them — I am not afraid.\" Huifang then recited: \"Presiding over banquets and feasting officials; Honored with the bestowal of sable-tipped plumes; Vice-Director of the Guild Hall; Officer in Attendance at the Theater; Proofreader at the Painting and Calligraphy Market; Concurrent Supervisor of the Southern City Streets Office; of all Pear-Garden Musical Troupes; Inspector-General of Intelligence from Every Quarter; Libationer at each venue attended; Scholar Drenched in Perspiration; Grand Counselor of Foreign Affairs; Minister of the Bureau of Music and Song; Hereditary First-Rank Duke of the State of Shi; add an urgent promotion, and one further step in meritorious service — Gao.\" Everyone burst out laughing.",
    "This string of titles had been composed by Liu Wenze; of those present, only Nanxiang knew their origin, while to Chunhang it was entirely new. Gao Pin said, \"There is one title you have left out.\" Huifang said, \"It seems there was nothing more.\" Gao Pin said, \"You have omitted Superintendent of the Compilation of the Rabbit Garden Catalogue.\" Nanxiang laughed again. Huifang paid no attention to this, and poured several cups of wine for Lanbao, Yulin, and the others at the table. Chunhang had met Yulin once before; now he saw that Yulin's grace and charm, though falling a step short of Huifang's, was far superior to the general run of young protégés he had previously admired. He noticed the peach-blushed cheeks, the powdery smoothness, the lotus-face fragrant with life — an altogether different quality of bearing and elegance. He also observed that Yulin seemed to show Gao Pin especially warm regard, so that one could clearly make out the territories each had staked out.",
    "Then he noticed Wang Lanbao — the one Shi Nanxiang held in highest favor — and Chunhang felt a touch of awe before him. Willow eyebrows pressed close and green, containing both coquetry and vexation. Phoenix eyes cast sidelong glances that seemed to carry both sentiment and suppressed anger. He went his own way entirely, free and unconstrained. He was seventeen years old and a martial dan (wǔ dàn) actor, trained to a fine standard in boxing and acrobatics. Nanxiang was a man who lived entirely beyond social conventions; when he first met Lanbao there had been several major scenes between them, but afterward they had grown intimate again. Lanbao also understood Nanxiang's temperament and disposition well, and they were in fact most congenially suited. Whenever Nanxiang fell into a drunken frenzy, one glimpse of Lanbao standing before him was enough to bring him to his senses.",
    "At the table that day, only Chunhang could not hold his wine well, and Nanxiang would not hear of excuses — they began finger-guessing contests and drinking forfeits, creating lively chaos all around.",
    "Chunhang kept losing, and after a while refused to drink any more. Nanxiang ordered Lanbao to pour a cup and make Chunhang drink it. Lanbao rose and walked over to Chunhang with the wine; but Huifang, knowing that Chunhang could not hold his drink, leaned forward and drank it from Lanbao's hand for him.",
    "Lanbao laughed: \"What does this have to do with you? Must you step in and act in another's place?\" Huifang laughed: \"This is what is called borrowing another's cup of wine to wash away one's own sorrows.\" Lanbao said, \"In that case, please drain a few more cups.\" He poured several full cups and pressed Huifang to drink them. Huifang said, \"I have had enough — I know when to stop.\" Lanbao said, \"That is not for you to decide — have you not heard: 'Between feuding enemies, bare blades cross'?\" Nanxiang and Chunhang watched them, while Gao Pin pulled faces at Wang Lanbao, urging him to impose more forfeit wine on Huifang. Li Yulin reclined on one shoulder, smiling languidly. Lanbao also laughed: \"Are you truly not going to drink?\" Huifang was a little afraid of him, and could only smile along, saying, \"Lan-ge, please let me off.\" Yulin pleaded on Huifang's behalf repeatedly, but Lanbao would not relent, and in the end still imposed one cup on Huifang before the matter was settled. The company drank on for a while longer, when a servant came from Huifang's household to summon him. Huifang went out and asked, \"What is the matter? What became of those two drunkards?\" The servant replied, \"Those two made a scene all night and left early this morning. Just now someone unfamiliar has called — says he is a Cantonese gentleman named Xi, Xi Eleven. He greatly admires your name and is waiting at home.\" Huifang said, \"What sort of man is he? Don't tell me he is another Pan Qiguan type.\" The servant said, \"By appearances he is quite well-off — he has four attendants with him, around thirty years old.\" Huifang said, \"Go back and tell him to leave — say I am not returning today.\" The servant left.",
    "Huifang came back inside, and Chunhang asked what the matter was. Huifang replied, \"Someone at home came looking for me; I sent him away.\" Gao Pin asked, \"Who was it?\" Huifang said, \"I don't know him. The servant said his name was something like Xi Eleven — a Cantonese man.\" Gao Pin said, \"What a cumbersome surname! One stroke sweeping down at the top, three punches gripping at the neck, with tangled silk threads in the middle that will never sort themselves out — and he wants to pass himself off as a great official. Among the nine varieties of Eastern barbarians, I wonder which sort he is.\" Huifang said, \"You would do well to set up a fortune-telling stall at the temple gate.\" Everyone laughed. Gao Pin said, \"Today's drinking is dull without a game — why not use 'Xi Eleven' as the basis for a forfeit round?\" Nanxiang said, \"How can 'Xi Eleven' serve as the basis for a round?\"",
    "Gao Pin said, \"The three of us will find the character 'xi' (奚) in the Four Books — starting from the first occurrence and going to the eleventh. Whoever makes an error drinks a number of cups equal to the number of characters in the passage. Those three will serve as our seconds.\" Chunhang said, \"There may not be that many instances of 'xi' in the Four Books.\" Nanxiang said, \"Even if there are, we couldn't get through them all.\" Gao Pin said, \"We'll simply drink a few cups of forfeit — no harm in trying. I'll go first.\" He said: \"Xi (奚).\" Chunhang said, \"You must identify which passage in the Four Books the character comes from.\" Gao Pin said, \"'What does he draw on from the three families' — the 'xi' from that passage.\" Nanxiang said: \"'Why should the son... why should the woman...'\" Gao Pin said, \"That is two passages — two cups of forfeit.\" Nanxiang said, \"Is it not permitted to cite two?\" Gao Pin said, \"Not permitted.\" Nanxiang drank. Chunhang continued: \"'This thing, for what reason...'\" Gao Pin praised him: \"Well said!\" He then said: \"'Since it is so, for what reason...' and also 'The Son of Heaven is august and dignified — for what reason...'\" Nanxiang said, \"You've penalized others and then fallen into the same trap yourself — who told you to cite two passages? Moreover this 'xi' is the very same first 'xi' you yourself began with — that deserves double the forfeit: ten cups.\" Gao Pin said, \"Mine were one line of four characters and one of five characters — they are not the same, so why should I be penalized?\" Nanxiang said, \"You yourself declared it was not permitted to cite two passages — how can you break your own rule?\" Hemmed in on all sides, Gao Pin had no choice but to drink five cups, slowly.",
    "When it came to Nanxiang's turn, Nanxiang fell silent, unable for the moment to recall anything. Gao Pin said, \"I was penalized five cups — let me say it for you.\" Nanxiang thought a while longer and could not recall a passage, so he drank three cups while Lanbao drank two on his behalf. Gao Pin said: \"'This too is governance — for what reason...'\" Nanxiang said, \"How could I not think of that one!\" Chunhang thought for a while and said: \"'Yu did not employ Baili Xi...'\" Nanxiang slapped the table: \"Unfairly penalized! 'The people of Youbi — for what reason...'\" Chunhang and Gao Pin both applauded this. It was now Gao Pin's turn to cite the seventh instance, but Chunhang jumped in first: \"'To those who serve me — for what reason...'\" Nanxiang then pointed at Gao Pin and said: \"'In that case with the birds and beasts — for what reason...'\"",
    "Everyone burst out laughing. Gao Pin said, \"You have all earned forfeits. The seventh 'xi' was my turn to cite — why did you both rush in?\" Li Yulin duly poured the forfeit cups. Nanxiang and Chunhang had been so eager to recite that they had quite forgotten about the penalties. Nanxiang drank five cups and Lanbao drank two for him. Chunhang drank three cups and Huifang drank four for him.",
    "Gao Pin pressed Nanxiang to cite the eighth 'xi'; Nanxiang said, \"You have not yet given the seventh — you must be penalized.\" He called upon Lanbao to pour wine. Gao Pin said, \"This is outrageous! You both rushed in and said it before me — what am I supposed to say now? And yet you want to penalize me? Where is heaven and conscience?\" Li Yulin also spoke up on Gao Pin's behalf, and Nanxiang finally relented. Nanxiang then said: \"'To exchange millet for it.' Therefore, 'Master Xu, for what reason...'\" Chunhang said, \"The ninth is left to me.\" He thought for a while, then said: \"'Compare it with the lesser ritual — for what reason? Compare it with the greater ritual — for what reason?'\" Huifang stamped his foot: \"Why must you say two lines?\" Gao Pin said, \"Excellent — nine cups of forfeit.\" Huifang said, \"This can't be right.\" Gao Pin would not give way; first he imposed five cups on Huifang, then four more on Chunhang. Nanxiang suddenly thought of two more lines and could not resist blurting them out, heedless of the penalties: \"'South he marches — the Northern Di resent him. He says: for what reason...' and 'Trust in small things to be trustworthy in great ones — for what reason...'\" Lanbao jumped up and said, \"Grandfather, even if you love to drink there's no need to drag everyone else in. It was not your turn to speak — why say two lines?\" Nanxiang felt a bit regretful himself. Gao Pin said, \"There is nothing to discuss — eighteen cups.\" Nanxiang said, \"Eighteen cups is absolutely impossible — I really would need the Immortal Peach Life-Extending Pill for that.\" Chunhang, Huifang, and Yulin all pleaded on Nanxiang's behalf, and the penalty was reduced to nine cups, which Nanxiang defiantly drained himself. Gao Pin said, \"Now for the seventh 'xi' — I have thought of it.\" He said: \"'Therefore in his sincerity and delight in him — for what reason...'\" And immediately continued: \"'Not to supply the four directions with food — the steward said: for what reason...'\" Chunhang counted on his fingers and said, \"Now you have earned your forfeit — you should have given the tenth, but you gave the eleventh.\" Gao Pin said, \"I was mistaken.\" He tried again: \"'Then all they can do is save themselves from dying — for what reason...'\" Nanxiang counted — again only nine. Huifang stood up and insisted on penalizing Gao Pin nineteen cups. Gao Pin refused; Lanbao sided with Huifang and also demanded the full count without reduction. After much pleading by Gao Pin, the penalty was reduced to eleven cups; Yulin drank three on his behalf, and Gao Pin drained eight in a row. Nanxiang thought for a while, traced ten strokes on the table, and said: \"'The brave warrior does not forget that he may lose his head — Confucius, for what reason...'\" It was now Chunhang's turn; he also thought for quite a while, then said: \"'Zilu lodged at the Stone Gate; the gatekeeper said: for what reason...'\" Gao Pin said, \"Retribution comes swiftly — ten cups of forfeit. You were supposed to give the eleventh.\" Chunhang thought, and realized he had indeed made an error. Huifang stepped in: \"You must consider each person's capacity — don't just blindly impose penalties.\" Gao Pin said, \"The drinking-game rule is as strict as military law — it must be applied without partiality.\" Huifang said, \"We'll note it down and drink tomorrow.\" Gao Pin said, \"Your promissory notes may be settled tomorrow — the wine, however, cannot wait until tomorrow.\" Yulin said, \"Let's split it in half — drink five cups.\" Huifang drank three more on Chunhang's behalf, and Chunhang forced down the remaining two. It was now Gao Pin's turn to close out the round; he thought for a moment and said: \"'Of old, Zhao Jianzi sent Wang Liang as driver for his favorite, Bi Xi...'\" — and with that the round was complete. Everyone looked at one another and smiled. By now it was well past the second watch of the night; they ate, and the party prepared to disperse. Huifang's carriage had been waiting a long time; he at once took leave of everyone and headed home first.",
    "Nanxiang first saw Lanbao home, then escorted Li Yulin to his gate.",
    "Yulin invited him to come inside; Nanxiang said, \"It is already late — let us meet again another day.\" He turned and went straight home. Passing by Wang Xun's gate, Nanxiang suddenly felt thirsty, and sent his attendant inside to ask whether young Master Wang had yet retired. The attendant went to the gatekeeper and passed on the message; the gatekeeper looked in on the study and found that Wang Xun and Yan Zhongqing had not yet gone to sleep. The gatekeeper reported back, and Wang Xun told them to invite him in. Shi Nanxiang entered. As for what happened next — let the following chapter tell the tale."
  ],
  15: [
    "When Shi Nanxiang entered and greeted Zhongqing and Wang Xun, they shared a few cups of tea. Wang Xun asked him where he had been, and Nanxiang recounted the day's events one by one, then spoke at some length about Chunhang and Huifang. Wang Xun and Zhongqing could not conceal their admiration. Zhongqing said, \"Who would have thought Su Meixiang capable of this? From now on, Tian Xiangfan may truly be able to turn over a new leaf.\" He then recounted the episode of the painted admonition a few days earlier, and mentioned that Chunhang had still shown some resentment. Nanxiang said, \"Another day I shall mediate between them — what do you say?\" He also asked after Ziyu. Zhongqing said, \"Gengxiang was here during the day. His tutor Master Li was appointed to the post of county magistrate in Anhui at the beginning of the month and is about to set off.\" After a few more words, Nanxiang took his leave and went home.",
    "Now let us speak of Ziyu, who had been at Wang Xun's for a long chat before returning home. Master Li had already packed up his tutoring post and needed to arrange travel funds; Wei Pengcai had found a financial connection for him — asking Zhang Zhongyu to borrow a draft of silver from Xi Rong, which included a measure of empty credit amounting to over two hundred taels. With this, Master Li supplemented his clothing and also hired young protégés for several days. Li Yuanmao wished to register his household registration in the capital; Xinquan had no choice but to let him do as he wished.",
    "That evening, Ziyu and Pengcai were chatting in the study. That day was a memorial anniversary, so Pengcai had gone alone to Cherry Blossom Lane (Yingtao Xiang) during the day and found Ye Maolin. The two talked for a long while, and Pengcai treated him to a meal at the Flat-Dumpling Restaurant; they then went together to call on various young dan actors, visiting several tea parlors in a row. At the last stop they went to Qinyan's place; Qinyan actually came out and exchanged a few words with Pengcai, and asked after Ziyu. Pengcai dressed up Ziyu's feelings for him a little more vividly, and spoke in such a way that Qinyan was genuinely moved. He also arranged with Qinyan to bring Ziyu to meet him the following day. Returning home, he told Ziyu all of this, and Ziyu found himself with yet another thing to weigh on his heart, and lay awake all night. That evening, Shi Ze was on night duty in the Board of Rites and had not come home. The next day, Ziyu was just making plans to go with Pengcai to see Qinyan when suddenly Mei Jin, the gatekeeper, came in with a face full of smiles and announced: \"Congratulations to the young master — the master has been appointed Jiangxi Education Commissioner, and the messenger reporting the good news is at the gate now.\" Ziyu felt pleased at this news; he went with Mei Jin inside to report it to Lady Yan, whose delight goes without saying. Li Xinquan, together with Yuanmao and Pengcai, went upstairs to offer their congratulations. Before long, Shi Ze returned home; colleagues and relatives and friends came calling one after another, and they were kept busy for several days on end. Then came the date of departure for Master Li's new post; Shi Ze also hosted a farewell banquet for the teacher. On the day of departure, Ziyu went with Yuanmao and Pengcai to see Master Li off thirty-five li outside the city to the inn where he would spend the night. Xinquan gave him a thorough send-off, then admonished Yuanmao: \"Although Gengxiang is younger than you in years, his learning far surpasses yours — you must in future ask him with humility.\" Yuanmao assented again and again. Xinquan then said to Pengcai: \"My son originally came out of the capital together with your brother; I see that in future he will accomplish nothing — I rely entirely upon you to look after him.\" Pengcai also agreed repeatedly. Ziyu, by nature devoted and affectionate, lingered reluctantly at parting; he could not bear to say goodbye, but was forced at last to see the teacher off with Yuanmao, shedding tears as he and Pengcai bade farewell.",
    "Shi Ze had also chosen the tenth of the third month for his own departure, and today was already the fifth. Lady Yan said to Shi Ze: \"At the New Year, Madam Sun acted as matchmaker and a verbal agreement was reached with Cousin Wang's wife for the second daughter, with a jade hairpin as a token of betrothal. Now you are going far away again — we must perform some formal ceremony; one cannot simply leave it at that, or people will start to grumble.\" Shi Ze laughed: \"Without you to remind me, I would have entirely forgotten. It is certainly necessary — I'll ask Sun Bojing to act as matchmaker tomorrow.\" While they were still talking, Sun Lianggong came to pay a visit. Shi Ze received him and, after asking about Sun's planned travel date, brought up his wife's thoughts on the matter, saying: \"At New Year we arranged an engagement with the Wang family — that was all conducted by the women among themselves; still, we must perform a proper ceremony to make it a respectable arrangement. Moreover, you will be away for three years before you return, and it is not right to leave things so hurried and casual.\" Shi Ze said, \"We were just discussing this very matter, and had been planning to ask you for your help. Tomorrow I shall first send over a formal letter; the full ceremony can wait until I return.\" Lianggong agreed.",
    "The next day, Lady Yan prepared decorative gift boxes with formal betrothal documents and asked Lianggong to convey them. The return gifts from the Wen Hui household were lavish; Yan Zhongqing helped Lianggong bring them back, and Shi Ze hosted a wine reception. That day no outside guests were invited; only Pengcai and Yuanmao were asked to keep the company. This Li Yuanmao had, at this auspicious moment, achieved a sudden clarity of mind — his speech became quite articulate. When Xinquan left the capital, he had left two hundred taels of silver for Yuanmao; Yuanmao purchased several items of clothing and was now presentable from head to toe. Lianggong's discernment was ordinarily rather limited, but now, seeing Yuanmao's broad face and full features radiating an air of scholarly refinement, he pronounced him a man of promise and was very inclined to consider him further. He inquired about Yuanmao's marriage prospects. Zhongqing had already seen through the situation and praised Yuanmao effusively. Li Yuanmao himself was unaware of what was afoot and was thoroughly gratified, feeling genuinely grateful toward Zhongqing. But let us leave this thread for now.",
    "Now, Ziyu found little enjoyment at home; while the others were drinking, he took Yun'er along and went to find Liu Wenze and Shi Nanxiang.",
    "He went first to Wenze's house, but Wenze was not at home. He went on to find Nanxiang, and just as he arrived Wenze's carriage also pulled up at Nanxiang's gate. Ziyu said, \"I was just looking for you.\" Wenze said, \"I missed calling on you earlier. I went to find Feng Zipei, but he had just gone into the city.\" So saying, they went in together and sat down in Nanxiang's study. Long'er, the attendant who served Nanxiang, brought tea and said, \"Our young master hasn't got up yet!\" He then went back inside; about the time it takes to drink a cup of tea, Nanxiang appeared, bareheaded and barefoot, wrapped in a woman's padded jacket. \"You've come early,\" he said. Ziyu laughed at the sight: \"I've already eaten before coming.\" Wenze said, \"What a fine figure — wearing your wife's clothes out here. Don't tell me your wife hasn't got up either?\" Nanxiang said, \"She's been up for a long while. I had just woken from sleep; hearing that you two had come, I didn't have time to dress properly and just grabbed whatever was at hand.\" Long'er brought in water for washing his face, and Hu'er brought out his clothes, boots, and cap. Nanxiang washed his face and slowly dressed and put on his cap, then with a cheerful smile made a bow to Ziyu and said: \"Congratulations, congratulations! You've been hiding from us such a fine attachment.\" Ziyu assumed he was speaking of his betrothal and became flustered. Wenze said, \"What attachment is this?\" Nanxiang said, \"The other day I was at Duxiang's place; he told me there is a young dan actor called Du Yunong — the finest name actor of all ages past and present — and that Gengxiang has taken exclusive possession of him. They even performed a scene from 'Pledging the Heart' (定情) at Yiyuan together.\" Wenze said, \"Who is this Du Yunong? How is it we've never seen him?\" Nanxiang said, \"Splendid! According to Duxiang and Jingyi's assessment, he surpasses Baozhu — yet I don't know him. Gengxiang, why not take us today to have a look?\" Only now did Ziyu understand that this was not about his betrothal; but still, this was his first foray out of the proverbial thicket, nothing like these worldly habitués of song halls and feast stages, and he was too flustered to reply. After Wenze pressed him repeatedly, he had to answer: \"This Yunong is actually Qinyan — whom you've all seen before.\" Wenze said, \"It's a grave injustice — we not only claim never to have seen him, we've never even heard his name.\" Ziyu said, \"How is it an injustice? Have you forgotten that young dan actor who performed 'The Startled Dream' (惊梦) at the Suzhou Guild Hall on the sixth day of the first month?\" Wenze thought for a moment: \"Yes, yes, that's right! In that case you deserve all the more to be penalized. That day the two of you had eyes only for each other, heart illumining heart — anyone could see it. I asked you then, and you still insisted you had no acquaintance with him whatsoever — how can you deceive people like this! Today there is nothing else for it — you must take us there, and you can hardly say now that you don't know him.\" Nanxiang burst out laughing: \"Acknowledging a young dan actor is not such a great offense against propriety. Gengxiang truly has the manner of a girl in a secluded inner chamber peering around a folding screen. Today we'll see how you manage to wriggle out of this — quickly, let's go! We'll eat there today.\" After being laughed at and teased in this fashion, Ziyu found it impossible to explain himself, and could only blush awkwardly and say: \"Whatever you say — I have nothing of the sort, and besides, I don't know where he lives.\" Nanxiang said, \"You're lying again.\" Wenze said, \"As for that particular person, I have made some inquiries. I only know he is called Qinguan (Qinyan), that he is the newly purchased disciple of Cao Changqing, and that he lives at Qiushui Studio in Cherry Blossom Lane.\" Nanxiang said, \"Let's go!\" He called out to Long'er to have the carriage brought round. Ziyu said, \"I am not going.\" Nanxiang said, \"Very well, very well! Now that you have a beloved, you no longer need your friends — you intend to enjoy yourself all alone.\" He pulled Ziyu into the carriage, and they set off directly for Qinyan's quarters in Cherry Blossom Lane.",
    "Wenze's attendant went inside to inquire; Qinyan was not at home — they heard from within that the Lord Liu had taken him to Chunxi Garden. Wenze was somewhat put out; Ziyu, on the other hand, felt quietly relieved. Nanxiang said, \"Where to now? I haven't eaten yet — isn't that Miaooxiang Hall, where Sulan lives, right across the lane? Let's go and find Xangwan.\" Wenze said, \"I'm not sure he'll be at home either. Send someone to ask.\" As it happened, Sulan was indeed at home; someone came out from inside and invited them in. They sat down in the reception room and were served tea. Wenze asked Ziyu: \"Have you met Xiangwan before?\" Ziyu said, \"No, I haven't.\"",
    "Nanxiang said, \"This gentleman's elegance and charm stands alongside Yuan and Su as one of the three pillars of the pear garden.\" Before long, Sulan came out, greeted Nanxiang and Wenze, and was introduced to Ziyu. Sulan looked Ziyu over carefully and then asked Wenze: \"Is this young gentleman surnamed Mei?\" Wenze said to Ziyu, \"Another lie exposed — you just claimed not to know him, yet he already knows you. How can that be?\" Ziyu was genuinely puzzled and had no idea how to answer; it was Sulan who clarified: \"I don't know him at all — I simply guessed.\" Nanxiang said, \"I don't believe it — how could anyone guess so precisely? If you can guess his name, I'll take you for a divine being.\" Sulan said, \"His name contains the character 'yu' (玉), and his courtesy name is Gengxiang — am I right?\" Nanxiang and Wenze burst out laughing:",
    "\"This proves it — and you still claim not to know him! We thought Gengxiang was a man of perfect sincerity, and now it turns out he is quite accomplished at telling lies.\" With these words Ziyu's cheeks flushed slightly; the injustice of it was such that he had no one to whom he could complain. He looked closely at Sulan's features and noticed a certain resemblance to himself; fearing that Nanxiang and Wenze might notice and make sport of it, he moved away and went to look at the calligraphy and paintings on the nearby wall. Nanxiang said to Wenze:",
    "\"Can you see who Xiangwan resembles?\" Wenze said, \"He resembles Gengxiang. The very first time I saw Gengxiang, I was going to say so, but because he looked so young, I held back.\" Ziyu pretended not to hear and let them talk among themselves. Sulan said, \"Don't make sport of him — how could you compare me to him?\" He laughed and drew Ziyu over to sit beside him. Nanxiang said, \"We haven't eaten yet — please bring food quickly.\" Sulan at once ordered the kitchen to prepare a meal. Though Ziyu had seen Sulan's performance of \"The Spinning Plate Dance\" before, on that occasion he had been entirely preoccupied with Qinyan and had not paid Sulan any attention. Now, seeing Sulan before him — refined as orchid and iris, [radiant] as peach and plum, out of the purest clarity blooming the most vivid brightness — Ziyu was struck with admiration. He was seventeen years of age, wearing a padded jacket of lotus-pink crepe silk; his starlike eyes cast their gaze downward, his fragrant cheeks just barely parted — truly one who could bewitch the soul and stir the spirit. Ziyu secretly praised him greatly: he was in no way inferior to Qinyan or Baozhu. He only wondered what his character and temperament might be. The food and wine were already being brought in from outside; the three sat down without ceremony and helped themselves. Sulan poured wine and said to Ziyu: \"This is your first visit — I must offer the first cup to you.\" Ziyu accepted it.",
    "He then poured cups for Nanxiang and Wenze. Wenze asked: \"Are you not going to the theater today?\" Sulan said, \"There is no role for me today, so I may stay away.\" Seeing Sulan's manner — quiet, serene, and composed — Ziyu felt a deep affinity in his heart. Sulan raised his eyes and, noticing that Ziyu kept stealing glances at him, broke into an involuntary smile, from which wafted a quiet romantic sensibility and languid charm. Ziyu dropped his gaze. Wenze laughed: \"Coming out with Gengxiang, we are at a disadvantage in so many ways.\" Ziyu did not understand. Wenze laughed: \"With you here, it is like the night we went to see the lanterns — the young ladies in their carriages all had eyes only for you, none for the rest of us. Is that not putting us at a disadvantage?\" These words made Ziyu's cheeks flush crimson. He said, \"I'm sure I don't know what there is to admire.\" Sulan turned to Nanxiang and said, \"I am particularly fond of that 'Mulan Hua Man' lyric you wrote to accompany my painted orchid.\" Nanxiang said, \"Your own lyrics have gotten considerably better of late.\" Sulan suddenly fixed his gaze on Ziyu with a faraway expression, as if in thought. Wenze caught this and said to Sulan, \"Are you taken with him?\" Sulan smiled again. Ziyu felt embarrassed and could not sit still or stand easy. Sulan said to Ziyu, \"Have you seen your beloved today?\" Ziyu could not work out who was meant. \"Which one do you mean?\" Sulan said, \"I only know of one for you — I have no idea how many there may be.\" Ziyu was even more puzzled. Nanxiang and Wenze could not guess either, and both asked: \"Who is this beloved of Gengxiang's that you speak of?\" Sulan said, \"His beloved comes to see me every single day; he lives right across the lane. How is it you have not called, passing his door? Go and invite him here.\" Only then did Ziyu understand — it was Qinyan. His heart misgave him: \"How is it they all know about this?\" Wenze said, \"You see — even Gengxiang's beloved is known to him. Clearly you two are on terms of deep friendship.\" Nanxiang said, \"We went first to the other side of the lane — Qinyan was not at home, so we came here.\" Sulan said, \"So it is because he was not home that you came over here.\" Ziyu, hearing this, felt somewhat uncomfortable in his conscience and was just about to say something when Wenze cut in: \"Coming from that direction, we naturally passed his gate first and would inquire there before coming here — it is the logical order, from near to far.\" Sulan said, \"I don't blame any of you, nor need you make smooth excuses. Let me tell you the truth: I have not actually met Gengxiang even once — everything Yunong told me. This Yunong naturally gets along very well with me; from the seventh day of the first month onward, he has come every single day to have long conversations with me, and we have become the closest of friends. Lately he often slips up and calls me by the wrong name — calling me Gengxiang.\" Ziyu, hearing this, already sensed what Qinyan must be feeling; he felt a pang in his heart, and quietly composed himself, waiting for Sulan to continue. Wenze pointed at Ziyu and said, \"He is Gengxiang — why does Qinyan call you Gengxiang?\" Nanxiang said, \"Do you even need to ask? Can't you work out the reason?\" Wenze fell silent and listened as Sulan continued: \"How was I to know that he was called Gengxiang? At first I paid no attention to it; but after he kept calling me by the wrong name, I pressed him, and he refused to say.",
    "\"One day Yaoqing was here, and I brought it up with him; Yaoqing then laid out your situation in full. After that, Yunong himself admitted it: 'I am somewhat like you — to see me is to see you.' So it is for that reason that he comes here so often; it is not that he is genuinely drawn to me as a friend — he is merely using me as a painted portrait, a small likeness. Would you say this is a deep feeling or not? He has put in all this effort for you — how rare. That you should come today is fortunate; I have told you all this clearly on his behalf, so that you may know and his devotion should not be wasted.\" Ziyu, hearing all this, was like a mute who has swallowed bitter herbs — unable to express the bitterness. The moisture in the corners of his eyes he could only force back down into his chest. Wenze and Nanxiang nodded repeatedly: \"This is truly exceptional.\" Wenze added: \"Yunong's feeling for Gengxiang must amount to twenty-four parts deep — I wonder what Gengxiang's feeling for Yunong is? Do you know?\" Sulan said, \"How could I not know? That too was told to me by Yaoqing.\" He then recounted the whole episode of Xu Ziyun testing Ziyu with the false Qinyan, and Nanxiang and Wenze laughed and praised it by turns. Ziyu found this all very difficult to bear, and could only say: \"Such small matters — once they pass through others' mouths, they sprout a hundred embellishments.\" Sulan then sent someone to ask again after Qinyan; he still had not returned. They finished the meal and talked idly for a while. Ziyu asked Sulan for a sample of his calligraphy. Sulan said, \"I have nothing done already.\" He went inside, and after a short while returned with a bamboo-paper folding fan of mottled Xiang-consort bamboo and presented it with both hands: \"This is what I've just written — please accept it as a trifling gift; it is poorly done and not worth viewing.\" Ziyu looked: the brushwork was like iron drawings and silver hooks — round as pearls and smooth as jade, rich with an antiquarian elegance, the seals also classically refined. Ziyu made a deep bow in thanks. They talked and chatted on until it was nearly the end of the申 hour (around 4 p.m.), and Ziyu prepared to leave; Nanxiang and Wenze departed with him. Sulan saw them to the main gate; they each mounted their carriages and left.",
    "Now let us speak of Sun Lianggong, who returned home and discussed with Madam Lu the idea of betrothing his eldest daughter to Yuanmao. Madam Lu laughed coldly several times without saying a word; Lianggong did not dare press her further. Nevertheless, his mind was made up, and the next day he went to ask Wang Wenhui to act as matchmaker. Wenhui hesitated at length, thinking to himself: \"How can this pallid creature be given in marriage?\" But then he thought again: \"That Li Yuanmao is no great match either — a dull-headed fellow if ever there was one; the day he bowed to me, he knocked my hat askew with his head. They'll suit each other perfectly.\" So he agreed. He went specifically to Shi Ze's residence to convey Lianggong's intentions. Shi Ze was greatly pleased; he called Pengcai and Yuanmao out, Pengcai naturally gave his wholehearted approval, and Yuanmao was thoroughly delighted. Shi Ze then wrote on Yuanmao's behalf a letter formally requesting consent, which he handed to Wenhui; on the sixth day the betrothal letter was conveyed. This was indeed a match made across a thousand li, destined a hundred years in advance. Li Yuanmao, that blockhead, could not wait until the very next day to move into the family — only that would relieve the misery of his chronic empty purse.",
    "On the tenth day, Zhongqing and Wang Xun came very early to see Shi Ze off. The Academician Mei's luggage had long been properly packed and put in order; his servants had been dispatched out of the city on the ninth to transport everything. On the day itself, relatives and friends crowded the house. As it was still early, Zhongqing and Wang Xun waited first in the study with Ziyu, Yuanmao, and the others. Zhongqing offered Yuanmao his congratulations, saying: \"Congratulations, congratulations! Today you have truly obtained a 'snow beauty.' Did you not once write a line of poetry — 'The white one's eyes draw near'? Now it has come true as a poetic prophecy.\" Yuanmao did not understand but was rather pleased with himself.",
    "Shortly afterward, Shi Ze finished seeing off other guests and called Ziyu out to deliver a thorough admonition. He then also gave a few words of instruction to Yuanmao and Pengcai. After that he bade farewell to Lady Yan, mounted his carriage, and departed. Yan Zhongqing, Wang Xun, Wei Pengcai, and Li Yuanmao followed close behind. Lady Yan, leading Ziyu and a group of female servants and maids, also accompanied him in carriages out of the city. Outside the city gate, Wang Wenhui, Sun Lianggong, and a dozen or so fellow examination graduates and close friends were all gathered at a roadside inn to host a farewell feast. Shi Ze lingered for a while; Wenhui and the others then reentered the city. As the sky was growing late, Lady Yan could only take the female servants and maids back first, in tears. Ziyu, Zhongqing, Pengcai, Yuanmao, and some servants stayed the night at the inn; they paid their final respects the following morning.",
    "Shi Ze offered a few more words of encouragement to Ziyu; Ziyu had no choice but to return weeping with Zhongqing and the others. But let us leave that aside.",
    "That day Xu Ziyun had also been at the roadside inn for the farewell; rather than returning directly to his residence, he went straight to the garden and on to Cixian's room — where he learned that Cixian was in the Peach Blossom Grove (Taohua Wu) enjoying the peach blossoms, along with Baozhu and Shufang. Ziyun came to the grove at once. Though it was within his own garden, he could not wander through it every day; in just a few days, the peach blossoms had opened in full — blazing like morning radiance, reflected in a clear expanse of water, with the grassy banks embroidered like brocade. It truly felt as though the full splendor of spring had arrived. He entered through the third gate and found, within the winding covered pavilion, Cixian, Baozhu, and Shufang drinking and enjoying the blossoms. Seeing Ziyun come, Baozhu and Shufang rose to welcome him, and Cixian too greeted him with a smiling face.",
    "Ziyun laughed: \"Jingyi, today you've entirely left me out of your pleasures.\" Cixian said, \"Knowing you would return early today, I left a seat waiting for you.\" Shufang said, \"Did you not notice there are four places set?\" Ziyun sat down across from Cixian.",
    "Cixian asked: \"Were there many people at the farewell today?\" Ziyun said, \"Quite a few — Gengxiang and Jiantan went to see him off to the first inn overnight, so they will not be back until tomorrow.\" He then pointed with a smile at Baozhu: \"I dare say none of those in their party were here to see him off; I suspect this elder gentleman has never once invited any of them throughout his life.\" Baozhu laughed: \"This Lord Mei, whenever there was a theater feast, would summon us to attend on a number of occasions. His manner was modest and refined — he simply never once exchanged a single word with us. Little did we expect him to produce such a romantic-hearted son. This Mei Gengxiang was actually at Xiangwan's place for dinner the other day, and then went over to Yunong's place without finding him. According to Xiangwan, the depth of his feeling for Yunong is truly unparalleled.\" Ziyun said, \"How do you know he went to find Yunong? Did he go alone?\" Baozhu said, \"It was Xiangwan who told me. He went with Zhujun and Qianzhou together; Xiangwan also gave him a fan. They were well suited to each other.\" Cixian said, \"I think those two — Gengxiang and Yunong — are truly what one might call 'minds focused and undivided, their spirit crystallized in each other.'",
    "Now that these two have found each other, all manner of trials and sorrows will surely come to them in future — just watch them slowly unfold.\" The four of them drank for a while and enjoyed the blossoms. Cixian said to Baozhu: \"Those sixteen drinking-game lines that Duxiang had engraved — have you seen them?\" Baozhu said, \"Of course we have.\" Ziyun said, \"Why don't you two today compose a few rounds of your own in the same vein? It would give us a chance to see what your minds can produce.\" Before Baozhu could answer, Shufang said: \"I'm afraid we won't be able to manage it — in the first place our wits are not nimble enough, and in the second, we are not very familiar with the Tang poetry or the Book of Songs (Shi Jing), so how could we produce anything as perfectly synchronized as those? Unless we went home and spread out several books and searched out suitable lines one by one — only that way might we piece something together.\" Baozhu said, \"We are truly ashamed of ourselves. Those young ladies are roughly the same age as us — how can their minds be so brilliant and their mouths so fragrant, while we are so dull?\" Ziyun said, \"Try a round today — I guarantee you'll do well.\" He called for a set of dice; a servant fetched a set in a basin and placed it on the table. Ziyun asked Baozhu to throw first; Baozhu still demurred, but after Ziyun and Cixian pressed her, she had no choice but to say: \"Why make us a laughingstock? Not only can I not remember other things clearly, even the tune-pattern names (qu pai ming) are only vaguely in my memory. Perhaps Gengxiang might manage, but I am sure to do it poorly.\" She threw the dice several times until she got a combination whose name was \"The Shadows of Green, the Scarceness of Red\" (绿暗红稀). She sat blankly thinking for a while; unable to come up with anything, she said:",
    "\"This is nothing but inviting vexation!\" Shufang said, \"Let me throw to see what pattern I get before I start thinking.\" He too threw several times before getting \"Su Qin Turns His Back on His Sword\" (苏秦背剑). He said, \"This is even harder.\" Then Baozhu was seen asking Cixian: \"There is a line in the Book of Songs — something about 'sighing without end' — I can't recall it exactly.\" Cixian said, \"'Whenever I have good companions, / all the more do I sigh without end.'\" Baozhu said, \"Good — that's one; only it's not the most apt.\" Ziyun said, \"Go ahead and say it.\" Baozhu recited: \"The shadows of green, the scarceness of red — / Good dreams are rare to find again. / In the twilight upon your powder-tower the apricot blossoms are spent. / Too weary to paint the brows — / All the more do I sigh without end.\"",
    "Cixian and Ziyun both praised her: \"Very well said — and so coherent for the first one! Truly exceptional. The one line from the Book of Songs is slightly less apt, but it still works.\" Baozhu said, \"The Book of Songs is genuinely difficult to fit rhythmically, and with the rhyme scheme adding another constraint, it gets even harder.\" Shufang said, \"What I've thought up is even less polished. Is there not a line in the Book of Songs that goes 'None would look to me'?\" Ziyun said, \"There is — say it quickly.\" Shufang was about to recite, then hesitated, feeling a touch of shyness. Cixian urged again, and at last Shufang recited: \"Su Qin turns his back on his sword — / Do not submit a memorial to the northern palace. / It is you who have misled these Three Academicians of the Hall of Jade and the Terrace of Gold. / It is the wrong path — / None would look to me.\"",
    "Ziyun said, \"This is excellently done — every phrase fits in perfect cadence.\" Cixian said, \"It really is a remarkable achievement.\" Baozhu said, \"His is better than mine — it doesn't leave mine looking mediocre.\" Yet slight color rose in both cheeks, and there was clear chagrin in his expression. Ziyun offered comfort: \"Yours is fine too — only your topic was broader and more general, making it harder to achieve the precision of a tight fit. His topic of 'Su Qin Turns His Back on His Sword' is inherently more favorable, so his piece more easily shows to advantage over yours.\" Somewhat consoled by these words, Baozhu relaxed a little. He then threw again and got \"A Purple Swallow Threads the Curtain\" (紫燕穿帘). He said, \"This is a fine topic.\" He thought carefully for a good while, then asked Ziyun: \"I seem to recall a line — 'by the embroidered window, sad and unable to sleep' — is it a poem or a lyric?\" Ziyun said, \"It is a poem by Han Wo.\" Baozhu said, \"This might work a little better.\" He then recited: \"A purple swallow threads the curtain — / By the embroidered window, sad and unable to sleep. / Lingering slowly, / Until at last standing before the lattice door. / All around is still — / Cherished but unseen.\"",
    "Ziyun and the others praised it greatly. Shufang said, \"Do you know what this 'all around is still — cherished but unseen' of his is really about?\" Cixian smiled: \"There is a deep charm of spring longing and yearning for someone.\" Ziyun also laughed. Shufang laughed: \"That's not it. Yesterday a Qin Jiliao (talking myna bird) flew away from him. Yesterday I went to his place just as he came dashing out of his room in a panic, looking in every direction.",
    "He asked me: 'Have you seen it?' — his manner just now in reciting that passage was exactly like his manner yesterday.\" Baozhu laughed too: \"Today it came back again.\" Shufang threw again and got \"Butterflies Fill the Blossoming Branches\" (花开蝶满枝). Shufang thought for a while, then said: \"Butterflies fill the blossoming branches — / This is the season of my breaking heart. / I am the Five-Pestilence Emissary who scatters lovesickness. / Butterfly Loves Flowers (蝶恋花) — / The spring days pass slowly, slowly.\" Cixian and the others praised it greatly: \"This one is even better.\" Baozhu said, \"His are always better than mine — both of my rounds today were not as good as his.\" He threw again and got \"Smashing the Brocade Screen\" (打破锦屏风). He said, \"This is a fine topic — and yet extremely difficult. One must center the thinking on the phrase 'smashing through'; if one can make it cohere, it will be a fine piece indeed.\" Shufang said, \"This is the hard one — I could never piece it together, and I fear the line from the Book of Songs alone would be no easy matter.\" Baozhu sat in rapt thought: he thought of a Tang poem line but could not attach it to the Romance of the Western Chamber (Xi Xiang Ji); he thought of a line from the Western Chamber but could not attach it to the Book of Songs. The anxiety was considerable. After a long while, he asked: \"Is there not a line in the Book of Songs that goes 'whereby to pierce through my wall'?\" Cixian said, \"Perfect — that line is already secured; the trick now is to make the middle part connect smoothly.\" A pleased expression came over Baozhu's face, and he recited with relish:",
    "\"Smashing the brocade screen — / The twilight shadows fill the latticed chamber. / Jing-dong-dang — the curtain rings clatter. / The moon is high — / Whereby to pierce through my wall.\" / Ziyun and the others praised it highly. Ziyun said, \"This is truly excellent — even among those sixteen forfeits, it would rank in the top tier. Let us drink three cups in congratulation.\" Only then did Baozhu truly smile with satisfaction. Shufang began to feel anxious again, fearing that another round would leave him unable to match this, and said: \"Let's leave it here — it's really quite taxing on the mind. I won't throw anymore.\" Ziyun said, \"This game is indeed taxing, but he has completed three rounds and you only two — throw one more.\" Shufang said:",
    "\"What if the dice pattern comes up again as a repeat?\" Cixian said, \"A repeat doesn't count — it must be a new one to have any interest.\" Shufang had no choice and threw several repeated patterns before finally getting \"Chu and Han Contend for Supremacy\" (楚汉争锋). He said, \"Now that I've thrown this, I'll call it the last one.\" Ziyun agreed. Shufang composed himself in thought and walked off alone among the peach blossom thicket. Ziyun and the others also strolled through the flowers. After a while Shufang said: \"I have thought of something — only this line from the Tang poetry still feels a little forced. But if I drop that line, I can't find another, so I'll have to make do.\" He recited: \"Chu and Han contend for supremacy — / The Hegemon King is divinely martial. / You who lend your divine might, beat the drums three times. / Urgently three strikes — / A hundred men's match.\" / Everyone praised it.",
    "Ziyun said, \"Today we have produced six more — now we have twenty-two altogether. It would be wonderful if we could eventually collect a full hundred.\" Cixian said, \"A hundred is not attainable — and besides, there are not that many bone-tile names (gǔ pái míng). Tune-pattern names (qǔ pái míng) are more than sufficient; better to drop the bone-tile names and replace them with something else — that way a hundred might be achievable. If we keep the bone-tile names, the useful ones amount to only fifty or sixty. Among them there are a few with delightful names that one never manages to throw — such as 'Grandfather Leading Grandchildren' (公领孙), 'Zhong Kui Binds His Forehead' (锺馗抹额), 'Greedy Flower — Not Full' (贪花不满), and 'Thirty — Bald-Clawed Dragon' (三十秃爪龙) — those, if one could set them to verse, would surely produce wonderful lines. As for restricting the source to the Western Chamber, that is also a bit narrow; better to allow any line from a dramatic libretto (qǔ wén) — then the scope is considerably wider. Only 'Knocking Over the Oil-Pot Lid' (推倒油瓶盖) would be somewhat harder.\" Ziyun said, \"From the Book of Songs there is 'the jar is emptied' — that could work; and for the tune-pattern name we could use 'Oil Gourd' (油葫芦).\" Cixian said, \"And for the Western Chamber, which line would you use?\" Ziyun thought for a moment and laughed: \"The lines available from the Western Chamber happen not to fit this rhyme.\" The four of them sat under the flowers; Ziyun asked why Qinyan had not come today. Baozhu said, \"Today he went again to a private banquet in my place. He has one particular virtue: when he performs, he does not pay close attention to the prescribed stage business; but his natural elegance and charm are such that his own expression and bearing, flowing freely as it ought to, often surpasses the conventional stage business of the script. That is why some say he is untutored while others say he is divine.\" Ziyun laughed: \"From now on, Mei Gengxiang will probably watch no theater but Yunong's and drink at no feast where Yunong is not present.\" Shufang laughed: \"Yunong's conduct is not yet as remarkable as Meixiang's. I hear that lately Meixiang goes to Hongji Temple once a day. There is a certain Tian Xiangfan there — also a renowned man of romantic temperament — who has created quite a stir. He once saw Meixiang perform and thereafter followed his carriage every single day: wherever Meixiang went east, he went east; wherever Meixiang went west, he went west — for a full month. Meixiang took pity on him and agreed to a conversation, and from a conversation they became bosom friends; now they are the closest of intimates, inseparable for a single day.\" Cixian laughed: \"Can this be true! I always thought Meixiang a quick-witted, worldly-wise old hand beyond the ordinary — surely no one could keep him captivated? This man must be no common person.\" While this conversation was at its most animated, a servant of Ziyun's came forward to announce: \"A visitor has come to call!\" Ziyun put on his cap and outer garments and went out.",
    "As for what happened next — let the following chapter tell the tale."
  ],
  16: [
    "After Academician Mei Shi Ze left for his post, all household matters proceeded without a hitch: Lady Yan managed affairs within, while Xu Shun handled things without. Ziyu continued his studies, going beyond the classics to explore the various philosophical schools. On fine mornings and moonlit evenings he would have two or three intimate friends over — bright windows and clean desks, sharing the work of brush and inkstone.",
    "Sometimes they drank wine and engaged in free conversation; sometimes they composed poetry and divided rhymes. Of those who came and went, Liu Wenze and Yan Zhongqing were the most frequent visitors.",
    "Xu Duxiang from Yiyuan also paid several calls during the month — sometimes he was received, sometimes not.",
    "For Duxiang moved in a grand circle of affairs and presently occupied a position of ease and fortune, living the life of a wealthy immortal; petitions and social calls came flooding in, and his social obligations were extremely numerous.",
    "Even on the rare days when he was free and at leisure, he still had to search out beauties for various patrons — fragrant flowers and stone-leaf petals, the splendor of doe-brocade and phoenix-silk. Though these brought a certain dazzle for a moment, they were in fact inferior to the tranquility and freedom enjoyed by Cixian, Zhujun, and the others, who had their secluded tower with its grove of slender bamboo and their paper-screened chambers opening to a few blossoming plum branches.",
    "Now let us speak of Wei Pengcai — a man neither coarse nor refined, drifting between circles of the fashionable and the literary, not truly a kindred spirit in any of them, yet perfectly capable of acting as a hanger-on in wealthy households. At present he was living in the Mei residence together with Li Yuanmao, with nothing to do but ramble about outside. Yuanmao, moreover, had a particularly dull-witted disposition; prolonged company with him was genuinely tiresome. Pengcai reflected: \"I came to the capital to pursue some name and advantage, but after several months in the city I have accomplished nothing. Master Mei has moreover gone to Jiangxi and will not return for two or three years; Master Wang is always grandly aloof, with not a trace of genuine concern. Though the capital is a fine place, it is not somewhere to linger indefinitely. Better to find myself a patron household — perhaps I can attach myself to a powerful branch and make something of it; it is not entirely unlikely. I think the Third Master Fu has the widest connections of anyone — asking him to find me an opportunity would not be too difficult.\" His mind made up, he took a carriage into the city, to the Fu household at Jinpai Tower. He sent his page boy ahead to inquire at the gate.",
    "When Pengcai was told that the Third Master Fu was not at home — he was playing cards at the great Lord Gui's residence across the lane — the page boy came back out, and Pengcai said, \"I called on Lord Gui last year but never met him; today is a good opportunity to pay my respects.\" He went across the lane at once, sent in his visiting card, and heard from inside: \"Please come in!\" The double central doors were opened, and Pengcai entered. It was a small and modest courtyard; he saw Lord Gui come out from the main hall and stride forward to shake Pengcai's hand, ushering him inside and onto the heated kang. Pengcai said, \"I have called several times, but my lord was always out — we simply kept missing each other.\" Lord Gui said, \"My duties keep me busy; I rarely leave the city. I have often thought of going outside the city with Third Brother Fu to call on you for a day of leisure — either he has no free time, or I have some matter to attend to. In just two more days it should work out.\" They chatted some more; Pengcai took note of the room, which was neatly arranged — three bays in total, with the eastern one partitioned off as a study. In the courtyard, the eastern side was a whitewashed wall; the western side had a moon-gate with a decorative screen behind it — presumably the inner chamber. On the kang hung a blue-ground white-character palindrome poem and a pair of gilded-paper scrolls written by the Supervisor-General of the Board of Revenue. On either side were eight square chairs; on the eastern side stood a writing desk, a small potted landscape, and on one side several square stools. Pengcai was just about to speak when Lord Gui said, \"Third Brother Fu is here playing cards — just in that room over there. Shall we join him?\" He led Pengcai inside. At the entrance to the study, a small boy lifted a fragrant-colored inner curtain; Pengcai stepped in and saw Third Master Fu push his cards face-down on the table, give a great yawn, and stretch his back. Seeing Pengcai, he stood up, grinning, and said: \"Haven't seen you in a long while — how are you?\" Pengcai shook his hand. In the room there were two other men — one facing south and one facing north. The one facing south rose at once to acknowledge them; the one facing north barely stirred — he just relaxed his posture slightly and remained seated, still looking at the cards in his hand. Pengcai observed: at the upper seat, a man with a face all wine and meat, a two-pronged yellow beard, and a pair of serpentine eyes; his clothing and cap were new but not quite of official cut, about forty-four or forty-five years of age. At the lower seat, a man past fifty, myopic, wearing eyeglasses, also in new clothing. Pengcai asked, \"May I know the honored surnames of these two gentlemen?\" The man in the upper seat answered at once: \"My name is Yang — I live in this neighborhood.\" He then asked the elderly man's name, and the old man answered slowly: \"My name is Yan.\" Lord Gui said, \"This is Master Yan Jian'an, a private secretary in the Hua household. That gentleman is a specialist in geomancy, and also Third Brother Fu's sworn brother; he lives in that large residence in Donghu Lane — his literary name is Meichuang, and he is the eighth in his family.\" With that, a servant moved over a stool and placed it at the upper seat beside Fu the Third; all sat down. The Third Master said: \"How are you! Every day you're out of the city having a fine time, but you won't come and see your older brother. You know I think of you — yet you don't think of me. I've come to look for you two or three times and you were hiding away, not showing your face. Every day watching theater — what a fine time you're having!\" Pengcai laughed: \"What are you talking about! There isn't a day I don't think of the Third Master. It's just that since my patron has gone to Jiangxi, all household matters have been entrusted to me to look after — so things have been a bit busier.\" The man named Yang then asked Pengcai: \"You are at Lord Mei's residence?\" Pengcai said, \"Yes.\" He then asked: \"Are you acquainted with the Mei family?\"  The man said:",
    "\"How could I not be? I myself planted the trees on their ancestral burial ground.\" Lord Gui said, \"Old Yang the Eighth's feng shui is outstanding — most families in the inner city ask him to assess their properties.\" Pengcai drew him further into conversation. Only Yan Jian'an sat coldly to one side, speaking only with Fu and Gui. The Third Master Fu said, \"Let's stop here — this card game is insufferably dull; and I've been losing. Let's settle accounts.\" Yan Jian'an said, \"Why stop so soon? We've only played two rounds.\" Meichuang said, \"Call it done — no need to continue.\" So everyone rose, shifted their seats, and counted the chips: Yan and Fu had both lost. Pengcai said, \"I seem to have broken up the game.\" Fu the Third beat his lower back with his fist and said, \"I never liked this game anyway — losing money and getting bored on top of it.\" Yan Jian'an said, \"Indeed.\" Yang Meichuang laughed: \"Who told you to play so recklessly? You kept issuing random wild cards — if you don't lose, who does?\" Yan Jian'an laughed: \"You may talk — but when have I ever seen you actually win money? All you're good at is bullying people; you can throw your weight around with me and Third Brother Fu, but not with Lord Gui.\" Everyone laughed and joked for a while. Lord Gui then ordered a servant to bring out food and wine — four or five meat and vegetable dishes and a pot of yellow wine — and the five of them enjoyed a modest midday drink together.",
    "During the meal, Pengcai asked Yan Jian'an about the situation in the Hua household. Old Yan perked up at this and said, \"My employer's young master is a rare person in this world. The grandeur of the mansion is beyond description.\" Pengcai asked how many colleagues were on staff there. Jian'an said, \"Those residing in the mansion number over ten; those serving at the old master's post number another ten or more; as for those who come and go intermittently, they are too many to count. I have been on terms of thirty years' friendship with the old master, and once served on campaign with him — my standing is quite different from those other friends; the young master treats me with the courtesy due a senior. The rest are another matter.\" In fact, this Yan Jian'an was a half-seasoned, half-green old sycophant; he had old ties with Lord Hua, who kept him in the household despite finding his narrow-mindedness, foul-smelling talk, and peculiar temper irritating. The young master Hua was even more difficult. Yang Meichuang was a thoroughly unrefined social parasite who knew only power and profit and had not a single genuine ability; he was moreover a man from the inner provinces, timid and apprehensive. By virtue of being Fu the Third's sworn brother, he had cultivated relations with a number of half-acquainted wealthy men, trading on the reputation of geomancy while making wild boasts, intent only on making money: sometimes colluding with landowners, sometimes going shares with landscape gardeners and their foremen to cheat people's money. He had even donated his way to a candidate status of the ninth supplementary rank; as for actual knowledge of geomancy, he had none whatsoever. On this occasion, he and Pengcai happened to get along well, and proposed to exchange visiting cards on a sworn-brotherhood basis; Pengcai was happy enough to cultivate the connection and showed him every attention. Only Old Yan was thoroughly mercenary at heart and could not bring himself to think well of Pengcai; Pengcai in turn found him deeply disagreeable. The five men spent a convivial while together, then prepared to part; Yang Meichuang also arranged with Pengcai to meet again another day.",
    "Pengcai then accompanied Fu the Third back to his residence for another brief visit, during which he brought up what was on his mind. The Third Master Fu said, \"In that case, why not simply move in here and stay for a while?\" He then added: \"In our uncle-by-marriage's household, friends are the most numerous. Today I heard Old Yan say that someone has recently left — there's actually a vacancy right now.\" Pengcai said, \"Who is the uncle-by-marriage?\" Fu the Third said, \"Don't you remember last year outside the city, when you saw that procession of a dozen or more carriages, with that man in a sable coat and embroidered python robe? That's the one they call Young Master Hua.\" Pengcai was inwardly delighted and thought: this Young Master Hua has influence that reaches to the sky — if I can ingratiate myself with him and secure even a minor official position, it should not be too difficult.",
    "He then asked: \"What sort of duties does one perform as a private secretary there?\" Fu the Third said, \"What duties? Accompany him drinking, accompany him to the theater, draft a few unimportant letters in leisure hours. And since you can also play and sing — that will suit his tastes even better. He is fundamentally a very good sort of person; you just have to keep presenting him with the hat of flattery, and he'll be pleased; contradict him and he turns cold. I can see that your social manner is excellent, your person is well-rounded, and your inner resources are naturally quite sharp. Our uncle-by-marriage also has some literary attainment — last year the Old Buddha (the Empress) asked him to compose poetry and responded favorably, even presenting him with a yellow-braided pouch and a four-happiness ring.\" If you want to go, I'll recommend you tomorrow — I can guarantee it will work out.\" Pengcai's face lit up with pleasure and he bowed in thanks. He then thought of Old Yan being in the way — but then reflected: \"Each person minds their own affairs; if I simply avoid dealings with him, that's that.\" He sat a while longer, then took leave of Fu the Third and returned to his lodgings.",
    "The next day, Fu the Third came to the Hua family mansion, met Young Master Hua, and recommended Pengcai to serve as a secretary handling miscellaneous affairs. Young Master Hua agreed and said: \"My establishment has no fixed limit on staff — as long as the person is good and is your close friend, there's naturally nothing to discuss. Say I have invited him; just tell him to come.\" He at once instructed Lin Shanzhi to inform the chief steward that the terms of Master Wei's stipend and board were settled. Fu the Third replied \"Yes\" repeatedly. He then went in to pay his respects to Madam Hua before taking his leave, heading straight out of the city to inform Wei Pengcai and ask him to come the very next day.",
    "That same day, Pengcai explained matters to Ziyu and thanked him for several months of hospitality. Ziyu was startled: \"Elder Brother, why leave? Surely it is not that I have done something to offend you?\" Pengcai laughed repeatedly and said:",
    "\"Since I came to this honored household, I have received such generous treatment from your father and mother and from you yourself — how could there be any lack? But I came to the capital this time with my father's earnest instruction that I must find some career before leaving the city.",
    "\"This situation offers a modest foothold, and Third Brother Fu has put himself out to make the arrangement. I'll go and see what it's like. It's only the distance of one city — I can naturally come by frequently. If you don't forget me, the Hua mansion's gardens and pavilions are said to be magnificent for outings. Before your mother, please first explain for me; when I set off tomorrow, I'll go in to pay my respects and take my leave.\" Li Yuanmao was nearby and, hearing that Pengcai was going to the Hua household, felt a pang of sadness. \"You leave and I'll be here alone — and you too will be losing a companion. I've heard Young Master Hua has a difficult temper; you had better not go and get yourself into trouble. Stay here instead, and we can talk things over after the New Year.\" Pengcai said, \"Each person has their own plans; things are no longer the same as they were for me. You are the son of a county magistrate, enjoying a comfortable livelihood handed to you — but I not only cannot enjoy ease myself, I also have to provide for my family!\" Hearing this, Ziyu understood that he could not insist on keeping him, and had no choice but to go to Lady Yan and explain. Lady Yan said: \"If that is the case, we have no choice but to let him go. Still, when your father left, he charged me to treat him well, and said he was a capable and efficient person. At the moment there is not much to be done, but if affairs arise in the future, we can always ask him back.\"",
    "That evening she had Ziyu host a farewell dinner for Pengcai and sent him off with forty taels of silver; Pengcai was profoundly grateful. Through the night he and Yuanmao chatted on and on, each reluctant to part.",
    "Early the next morning, Fu the Third sent two carriages to fetch Pengcai. Pengcai paid his respects and farewells to Lady Yan, said goodbye to Ziyu, and took his leave of Yuanmao. With everything packed and in order, he brought along Si'er and mounted the carriage. They went first to the Fu residence for a brief call; Fu the Third then personally escorted him to the Hua mansion. At the gate, Fu the Third sent someone in ahead to announce that Master Wei had arrived. Pengcai looked out from the carriage: the imposing façade was breathtaking — even the Viceroy's yamen in Nanjing was not this towering. In front of the gate stood a great spirit screen, built of finely ground brick, with carved floral patterns above and below, flower-corniced drip tiles, a roof of glazed tiles, and standing some thirty-odd chi high and seventy-odd chi wide. On either side stood a pair of great stone lions over eight chi tall. Looking in through the outer gate — at a distance of about one arrow-shot — one could see, within the enclosure walls, tall trees towering on both sides, flanking a central avenue that stretched straight to the inner gate, growing indistinct in the distance. There appeared to be dozens of people sitting at that inner gate. The messenger had gone inside for about half an hour before he returned and said: \"Please come in.\" Fu the Third and Wei Pengcai alighted from the carriage, straightened their clothing, and walked in. Approaching the inner gate, they saw the assembled men slowly rising — some twenty or thirty of them, all in matching attire. Several of them recognized Fu the Third and came forward to greet him, asking: \"Is this the master secretary who has been engaged?\" Wei Pengcai also acknowledged each of them. They passed through the inner gate and traversed another avenue of over a hundred paces before reaching the great reception hall. Guided by an attendant, they passed around the great hall, through covered corridors with winding balustrades on all four sides, and came to an inner courtyard with flowers, bamboo, and ornamental stones arranged in layer upon layer. They entered through a flowered gate and into a connecting hall (穿堂). Passing through the connecting hall, Pengcai felt he had stepped into a painted scroll: long galleries and tiered pavilions, painted beams and carved rafters, green tiles and glazed roofing gleaming against the sky and dazzling in the sun. In all his life, Pengcai had never seen anything so vast, magnificent, resplendent, and solemn; his heart was somewhat overwhelmed. Fu the Third, being a familiar visitor, led the way; a guide said: \"Please let me take the Third Master to the Western Flower Hall to be seated.\" The man led them along a long, winding path until they arrived at a polished-brick moon-gate with a flower design and stopped — he would go no further. He gave a slight cough; from inside four young and handsome household pages came out. The man told them: \"Please escort the guests to the Western Flower Hall.\" Pengcai followed Fu the Third through the gate into a garden; the ground was paved with Taihu Lake stones, intricately pierced, below which was a pool — looking down, one could see two golden carp swimming out through a gap in the stones. Slender bamboo obstructed the path; profuse flowers confronted the face. They walked several dozen paces, ascended several tiers of uneven stone steps, then crossed a flat stone bridge. Beyond the bridge was a pavilion; below the pavilion, a rockery blocked the way — exactly like the Lion Grove garden — requiring passage through a cave in the artificial mountain before one arrived at a garden reception hall.",
    "Beyond that were several more garden pavilions, with dense green tree-shade and the clamorous singing of birds. In front of the courtyard bloomed opium poppies, corn poppies, and similar flowers, setting off the hanging wisteria draping from old cypress trees along the poolside, and also some crabapple, redbud, and the like.",
    "Coming to the reception hall, the front was fronted by a carved railing, with five-colored glass windows on either side and a crimson double-gauze curtain with silver thread patterns in the center. A page boy hoisted the curtain up and fastened it to a silver butterfly-antennae hook decorated with kingfisher feathers. Entering the hall, the floor was laid with duck-green velvet carpet; above it was a paneled ceiling fashioned of fragrant nanmu wood, carved all over with delicate floral patterns. A plaque hung above, bearing the brushwork of Wang Duo: \"A Hall of Joined Emotions in Moss-flower Misty Rain,\" surrounded by pearl-tassel spirit canopies and countless lampshade ornaments. The central panel doors were engraved with the cursive calligraphy of Wen Zhengming; a large kang was spread with ancient brocades in brilliant patterns. On the kang table was placed a precious ritual vessel, from which dense, rich fragrance wafted. The walls on both sides were papered with white-floral damask; on one side hung eight landscape paintings in blue-and-green by Wang Youcheng (Wang Wei); on the other were two antique display cabinets topped with nanmu lacquered boxes — presumably containing rare books. Every table, stool, and chair was carved purple sandalwood with brocade cushions in five colors.",
    "It was a place of embroidered earth and brocaded heaven, dazzling the eye and bewildering the spirit. Fu the Third and Pengcai sat down in chairs, and after about the time of two cups of tea, a page boy came out and announced: \"The young master is indisposed today; he invites the Third Master and the new secretary to the Eastern Garden to meet with the other gentlemen, and asks Master Wei to take up quarters at the Eastern Garden, together with Masters Zhang and Gu.\" Fu the Third said, \"Please convey my respects.\" Pengcai also rose and said, \"Please convey mine as well.\" The page boy replied \"Yes,\" and the page outside the window invited the two gentlemen to the Eastern Garden, retracing the old route back through the moon-gate.",
    "The Eastern Garden lay to the front and east. Pengcai followed Fu the Third — winding their way outward again, walking entirely through covered corridors, with attendants stationed at every point. The Hua household maintained this rule: every gate had its own chief steward, and all comings and goings had to be entered in a register. After walking for quite a long while, Pengcai could no longer keep track of how many courtyards and halls he had passed through. When they emerged behind the connecting hall, on the eastern side was a narrow alley that seemed to run nearly half a li in length. Passing through one more gate, they arrived at a garden. This garden too was not small — with pavilions, terraces, artificial hills, and ponds, trees and flowers grown into thickets, an altogether different kind of scenery. The page boy who had led them handed them over to the garden's own staff and withdrew; other attendants came to receive them. They entered through a gate of speckled bamboo and a flower hedge, and arrived at a hall — two rows of rooms totaling ten bays, with some side-chambers as well. This was the place where Zhang Xiaomei and Gu Yueqing did their painting. Masters Gu and Zhang came out to meet them; learning that Pengcai was newly recommended by the Third Master Fu, they joined the company for conversation. Pengcai observed that Zhang Xiaomei was quite an attractive-looking man — a native of Hangzhou, around twenty years of age, who painted detailed-style figure compositions and also played and sang creditably. Gu Yueqing was from Suzhou, two years older than Xiaomei, also rather handsome, and painted landscapes and flowers. On the other side was a correspondence secretary named Wang Qingyun, an old friend of the previous duke (the senior Lord Hua), now over fifty years of age. Yan Jian'an handled brush, ink, and miscellaneous tasks; the two of them occupied a separate inner court. Everyone was now called to come and be introduced. Yan Jian'an said, \"Who would have thought that so soon after our first meeting the other day, you should be entering our household! What a remarkable turn of events.\" Pengcai said, \"This little student has been undeservedly favored by the young master's regard and invited to serve in the establishment. Having nothing but a blunt blade and a worn cotton sock — not a single real accomplishment — I rely entirely upon the guidance of these senior gentlemen.\"",
    "The two elder men, Yan and Wang, said: \"Not at all, not at all — the master sought you by name and reputation; naturally no reputation is without foundation. We are the ones who will be seeking instruction from you.\" Pengcai replied repeatedly: \"I would not presume.\" The Third Master Fu said: \"This Master Wei is my sworn brother and is the Academician Mei's junior generation relative from the south side of the city — a man of real ability and the most loyal friend. Having just arrived in the household, he is naturally not yet familiar with everything; the learned gentlemen must certainly take him under their wing. We are all family here — please do not be formal or standoffish. Tomorrow when I see our uncle-by-marriage, I shall mention him in person as well.\" He then said to Pengcai: \"Let's go look at the inner rooms and see which one to take?\" He also took Pengcai to the inner row of the building — also five bays; the two eastern bays were Zhang Xiaomei's room, and Pengcai settled into the two western bays, with the central bay left as a reception space. Fu the Third at once ordered the luggage moved in and had the pages put everything in order.",
    "Just as they were about to leave, a man came in and announced: \"The young master has sent a table of wine and dishes; he asks the Third Master and the various secretaries to accompany Master Wei in a drink. The young master says please excuse him — he genuinely cannot sit up today and cannot come to keep company, and also extends his regards to the Third Master for making the journey.\" Fu the Third rose and expressed his thanks. He then said: \"The hour is not early — it happens to be just time for a meal.\" Everyone sat at a round table in the central room and ate without ceremony, in most cheerful and unrestrained spirits. Pengcai saw that the dishes of this banquet simply kept coming — large bowls, medium bowls, large plates, small plates — over forty items in all. The company drank on until the second watch of the night before Fu the Third finally took his leave of everyone. His own attendants waited with lanterns; Pengcai saw him as far as the garden gate. Fu the Third still had a good deal more to say by way of parting instructions. Pengcai was about to see him further out, but Fu the Third said:",
    "\"No need to see me further — if you come further you won't be able to find your way back into the garden, which will only add to your trouble. We'll meet again another day.\" With that he went off without looking back. Pengcai went inside and chatted with Masters Zhang and Gu for a good long while, making further enquiries about the ways of the household, before finally retiring.",
    "The next day, Zhang and Gu took Pengcai to meet the various staff in the household — every type of associate, along with the chief stewards, account keepers, gatekeepers, head chef, stable master, warehouse master, and the register-keepers at each gate; everyone of any importance was met one by one. The marquis's gate was indeed as deep as an ocean; Pengcai, newly arrived, was thoroughly at a loss — he actually felt quite constrained and dared not say a single word more than necessary, maintaining only careful vigilance and expressing respect to one and all. Take note, reader: from this point on, Wei Pengcai entered the Hua household, and from this would gradually grow many an affair. But that is a story for later; let it rest for now.",
    "Now, Ziyu found himself genuinely missing Pengcai for several days after his departure. It was now mid-fourth month; owing to an intercalary fifth month, the seasonal nodes came later than usual, and peonies could still be seen blooming in full splendor. In the courtyard outside were also lilacs, crabapples, and the like — scarlet fragrance and powdery richness, pale faces and hearts of ice. He wandered among them alone for a while.",
    "The cacophony of birdsong, the spread of flower shadows — he began to feel somewhat tired, and found himself recalling the ancients' couplet: \"The breeze is warm and birdsong scattered; the sun is high and flower shadows deep\" — how perfectly it captured the scene. He then thought of how Sulan had treated him so graciously that day, and took out the fan that Sulan had written for him and studied it carefully for a while. Then he thought: \"I really ought to send him something in return.\" So he selected a fine antique inkstone, two boxes of quality ink sticks, twelve album leaves of ink-orchid paintings by Xu Songling, and a round fan; he also carefully wrote out in small regular script two recent regulated verses he had composed on \"Seeing Off Spring,\" intending at first to send them by a servant. But then, finding the long daytime hours oppressive, he was seized with the desire to visit friends and seek out beauty. He went to the inner quarters to report to his mother that he was calling on Liu, Yan, and the others; then, accompanied by a page boy, he took a sedan chair and made a circuit of visits — finding no one at home at any of them, which was greatly disappointing. He had no choice but to go alone to Sulan's quarters, arriving just as Sulan was returning from the theater; Sulan came out to greet him and they exchanged warm courtesies. Ziyu then presented the gifts he had brought; Sulan thanked him and examined them carefully. Seeing the elegant, regular calligraphy, he thanked him again and again. He then led Ziyu into a small study off the bedroom — Sulan's space for writing and painting, quite refined and tranquil. He asked Ziyu: \"Why are you out alone today? Have you been across the lane yet? Have you seen your beloved?\" Ziyu laughed: \"I've gone to several places today without seeing a single soul. I came specifically for you; I haven't gone across the lane — I don't even know whether Yunong is at home.\" Sulan let out a sigh and said nothing. Ziyu grew suspicious and asked: \"Xiangwan, why are you unhappy?\" Sulan said: \"I myself am not unhappy — it is your beloved I'm thinking of. The confused account between you two in private — how will it ever be settled? It has caused unrelated teardrops to fall in great numbers, and yet no one knows why they fall. If you ask him, he won't say; if you try to guess, there's no working it out. And yet it's not as if you see each other every day — so how has he been brought to such a state? Even his teacher doesn't understand it: he says that lately Yunong has developed some sort of phlegm-disorder — he gets downcast for no reason at all, and becomes even more indifferent to people around him. Before this he was merely cool toward people, but he had no inner preoccupation. Since the shared table at Yiyuan that time, he has stopped paying attention to people; whenever he talks with us, he always wants to steer the conversation toward plum blossoms (méi huā), and if it can't be connected to that topic, he forces a connection. He says how fortunate he is that there is a Plum Vale (Méi Yǎn) at Yiyuan — and he has even asked Xiao Jingyi to paint him four hanging scrolls of plum blossoms in various colors. That might still pass, but —",
    "\"— then he suddenly asked whether the bolts of silk being ordered for Duxiang from the south included any with sprays of plum blossoms, and whether there were any with mixed flowers. Remarkably, Duxiang actually managed to find several bolts; he has now had robes and padded jackets made up and is wearing them. Now you tell me: is this mindset not extraordinary? If it is not for you, who else could it be for?\" Ziyu heard all this and felt a surge of aching sadness; try as he might, the tears began to fall. He wanted to speak, but something seemed lodged in his throat and he could not get the words out; he could only gaze blankly at Sulan. Sulan continued: \"What kind of attachment is this between you two? I am your meritorious benefactor — I have spent some effort on your behalf. Because I bear a slight resemblance to you, he often comes to pour out his vague, half-formed words to me. I wonder: do you think he even knows what is in your heart?",
    "\"And I wonder whether he feels toward you the same kind of feeling? He actually put it well himself: 'This is my own heart's affair — what does it matter whether anyone else knows? What does it matter how anyone else treats me? In the end I myself understand clearly — that is enough.' Master Gengxiang — what is really in your heart? You need not feel shy about telling me. You find it difficult to tell him directly to his face — I can speak on your behalf. Naturally you have feelings of longing for him; why not tell me about them?\" Ziyu remained silent. Sulan surmised he was not going to speak, then said: \"Shall we both go over to his place for a visit?\" Ziyu hesitated a moment, then said: \"We may as well go.\" So Sulan led Ziyu out the door; just a few steps away they arrived at the gate of Qiushui Studio, where five or six carriages were parked outside. Sulan said:",
    "\"By the look of it there are guests inside — it may not be convenient to go in. Better to return and first send someone in to see how things stand.\" Ziyu felt slightly ill at ease, not knowing who was inside, or whether Yunong was there to keep the company. He also thought: of course one must entertain one's guests — naturally there was no such thing as refusing. He had no idea what to do and simply followed Sulan's lead.",
    "Sulan returned to his own gate, sent someone to Qinyan's place to find out, and in a short while the person returned to report that Qinyan was ill and confined to bed; the guests had been invited by his teacher Changqing and were several clerks from the Board — they had come for an early meal and would be breaking up soon. Sulan said: \"Please, come inside and sit while we wait.\" Ziyu's heart settled somewhat on hearing this, and he went back inside. He sat down, dispirited. Sulan kept up a cheerful stream of questions — asking about this and that, and asking again about what Ziyu really felt toward Yunong. When Ziyu could no longer put Sulan off, he said: \"The matter of Yunong is a long story.\" He then recounted the scene Wei Pengcai had witnessed during the journey; then his seeing Yunong perform the incomparable, incomparably moving \"The Startled Dream\" at the guild hall this year; his not yet knowing Yunong's character and inner life. Then the episode at Yiyuan when the false Qinyan tricked him and he confessed his admiration for Qinyan — which he had based on Qinyan's perfect self-possession and aloofness, so that the news of his self-abandonment came as a shock. And at that moment Yunong, listening from behind the screen, had been so moved he nearly sobbed aloud; and then when they sat at the same table they could not say anything to each other — as if they were old souls from a previous life meeting again in this life, each heart's secret known and seen by the other, needing no words to convey it. \"He acted so — involuntarily and naturally. I too acted so — without any deliberate intent.",
    "\"I find I cannot put him out of my heart or my eyes for even a moment. You had not told me, and I had no idea that behind my back he was so preoccupied with me. I understand what lies in his heart for me — but he — does he really know what lies in mine? And what is there about me that could have moved him so deeply? I wonder if we should simply not see each other anymore — it might spare us additional heartache at every meeting.\" As Ziyu said this, his expression grew more and more sorrowful, as if he were on the verge of tears.",
    "Sulan too was touched and let fall a few tears; after a long while he consoled him: \"You two must have had some bond in a previous life — otherwise how could things have come to this? By your talents and bearing alone, you are someone all would cherish and love. But it is singular that Yunong — with a heart of ice and snow — should be so tenderly entwined solely for your sake.",
    "\"Duxiang, for all his hundred attentions and gentle warmth — he is also a kindred spirit in the tender-feeling quarter. Yet I see that Yunong treats him as not even two parts of ten compared to the way he feels toward you; and yet Duxiang holds him all the more dear, saying: 'Each has his own predestined affinity — this is determined by heaven, and cannot be forced by human feeling.' Moreover Gengxiang's heart is set on Yunong alone, without the slightest wavering — this is truly the nature of a deeply passionate soul. None but Yunong could be worthy of Gengxiang's admiration; none but Gengxiang could be worthy of Yunong's devotion. The 'Airs of the States' (Guofeng) — expressing love without licentiousness — does this not refer to Gengxiang and Yunong?\" Ziyu, hearing all this, felt boundless gratitude toward Duxiang, and also admired Sulan's perceptiveness — no wonder the 'Qutai Flower Register' (曲台花谱) had awarded him the title of Tanhua (third-place laureate).",
    "They had been in conversation for quite some time when Sulan again offered Ziyu some refreshments, and sent someone back to Qinyan's place to look in. The messenger returned to report: \"The first batch of guests has dispersed. But then, as luck would have it, another group came, saying they wanted to engage Qinyan; Changqing told them he was not at home, but those people refused to leave and sat waiting. Since Changqing did not know who they were and would not receive them, he went to his own room to smoke his pipe. They then forced their way in and snatched Changqing's opium pipe, threatening to report him to the Bingma Siyuan (the Office of Metropolitan Police). Having no recourse, Changqing had to beg their pardon and also called in Li Si from the distillery next door and Duan Zi Wang San from across the way to mediate; by now the room is packed with bystanders and the whole business is still unresolved.\" Ziyu heard this, let out a long sigh, and said: \"Even a single meeting with Yunong is this difficult. The hour is already late — I must head home as well. When you see him tomorrow, please convey my regards on my behalf and say he must not go on like this. He must absolutely take care of his health; he should go to Duxiang's place more often and not let people start to talk. I cannot go out frequently — in a few days we'll meet. If you see Duxiang, please convey my deepest thanks as well. One of these days we should all go for an outing in his garden.\" Sulan said, \"Whenever you plan to come out, set a day and come here first — I'll arrange for Yunong to come over, and we can meet here; it is quieter here. His teacher has a difficult temperament, and it is most unfortunate that Yunong has landed with such a person — Yunong's luck is not good.\" Ziyu said, \"What sort of temperament does his teacher have?\" Sulan said, \"Loves money, fears the powerful, disdains the poor. Because Yunong is Duxiang's favorite, he has been treated relatively well; the way he treated others before was not like this.\" Ziyu heard this and added yet another source of worry to his heart; he could not set his mind at rest, yet there was nothing he could do — he hesitated and lingered. Seeing the day was already late, he hardened his heart, came out, mounted the carriage, and looked back several times before finally settling into his seat properly after emerging from the lane. The page boy stepped up onto the carriage's footboard, and there, coming straight toward them at a furious gallop, was another carriage with two horses — it happened to be Wang the Intendant-General, charging headlong in their direction. Ziyu had no time to get out of the way and prepared to step down; but Wang Wenhui quickly waved his hand to stop him, asked a few words, nodded, and drove off.",
    "Today Ziyu had gone out and only managed to chat with Sulan for half the day; all the friends he had tried to visit were absent. Instead he ran into his father-in-law — how vexing. He thought of calling on Gao Pin, but the road was long; and having been out so long, he feared a scolding from home. He had no choice but to go back in low spirits.",
    "It is true that nine things in ten seldom go according to plan. But let the following chapter tell the tale."
  ],
  17: [
    "When Ziyu returned from Sulan's and paid his respects to Lady Yan, he went to his study. After the evening meal, a round moon rose and cast its brilliance among the flowers; a mild breeze drifted in, and the sky and clouds shone bright all around. He rolled up the bamboo curtain and leaned against the railing to gaze out. Suddenly a page boy came in to report: \"Masters Gao, Shi, Yan, and Wang have all come together.\" Ziyu had been brooding in his reverie; seeing them all arrive together, his delight was unbounded, and he invited them in to sit.",
    "Ziyu recounted how he had called on each of them during the day without finding anyone at home. Wang Xun then spoke first: \"Today we were all at Zhuoran's study together, where we met Tian Xiangfan and Meixiang, and then encountered Zhujun who came along as well. This Xiangfan is truly one of us — the way he and Meixiang conduct themselves together is truly enviable.\" Gao Pin said: \"At this point Xiangfan has all six roots purified and all five skandhas emptied; he adheres strictly to the three-article covenant and is not allowed to wander and stray about freely. Now one truly believes that there are indeed many hen-pecked men in this world — no wonder Yongan and Zhujun guard their inner chambers so steadfastly, not daring to leave so much as a step without orders. Violations bring severe night-time consequences.",
    "\"And Xiangfan's is only a half-feminine, half-masculine partner — already he is brought to such a state. Is it any wonder about the rules in the Hall of the Four Fears?\" The others were about to laugh, when Zhongqing said: \"You too are from that household, and now that you've moved away, you boast.\" Nanxiang said: \"I saw Zhuoran write to his wife — just like a subordinate submitting a report to a superior, with phrases such as 'deeply indebted to your grace, permeating to marrow and saturating every sinew.'\" Everyone burst out laughing. Gao Pin said: \"Preposterous! That lie of yours doesn't even ring true.\" Everyone laughed and joked for a while more. Then Gao Pin said: \"Gengxiang, I have an excellent matter the day after tomorrow to discuss with you.\" Ziyu asked: \"What matter?\" Gao Pin said: \"The fifteenth is Meixiang's birthday. Today we all discussed it and decided: Qianzhou and you will join forces as the two hosts, pooling a shared contribution, finding a spacious venue, inviting all those famous treasures to gather for a day of festivity, and hosting Xiangfan and Meixiang for a birthday celebration — how does that sound?\" Ziyu said: \"Wonderful, wonderful! But where should we gather?\" Wang Xun said: \"My home would work, but I have no garden; Qianzhou's garden would be better. We six as hosts, plus Xiangfan makes seven; Meixiang, Yaoqing, Xiangwan, Peijian, Jingfang, Ruixiang, Shouxiang, and Xiaomei together make eight — that would require three tables to seat everyone; the shared contribution cannot be fixed in advance, we'll reckon it up after.\" Everyone agreed. Ziyu sat blankly. Zhongqing laughed: \"Yongan, you haven't done your duty in organizing this — you'll earn people's complaints.\" Wang Xun had not yet replied when Nanxiang said: \"What makes you say so?\" Zhongqing said: \"Don't you see that Yongan, in his mustering of guests, has left out one most important person? Will that not invite reproach?\" Nanxiang counted on his fingers and laughed: \"Indeed, indeed.\"",
    "Wang Xun said: \"Are you not speaking of Xu Duxiang? I have not forgotten him — I only feared his affairs were too numerous and he might not be able to come.\" Ziyu said: \"Duxiang has many social obligations, but given his character and manner, if we invite him, he will certainly come even if he has other things on. As for Xiao Jingyi, too — he absolutely cannot be left out.\" Everyone agreed: \"Very well — add those two. That makes nine, together with the eight others, seventeen altogether — quite lively indeed.\" Nanxiang said: \"No one else?\" Wang Xun said: \"Who else is there?\" Nanxiang said: \"What a memory you have — while convening this great gathering of flowers, you've forgotten the king of flowers. You have Gengxiang, but you have no Yunong — to leave him alone and excluded, what logic is there in that?\"",
    "Wang Xun said: \"Quite right — I deserve a reprimand. I entirely forgot Qinyan for a moment; he must certainly come. And that Qin Qiguan, whose stage name is Yuyan — let's invite him too, to make it a round ten.\" Everyone agreed: \"Even better.\" Ziyu said: \"Now then, let us discuss how to invite the guests.\" Wang Xun said: \"You write a short letter to Masters Xu and Xiao at Yiyuan, and to Qianzhou — the rest of us will go and inform the others ourselves tomorrow.\" So they chatted on until past the second watch before parting. After seeing the guests off, Ziyu sat alone in his own reflections for a while and thought: \"The gathering the day after tomorrow will be a moment for the ages — I only wonder whether Qinyan's illness will have recovered in time. When that jade-forest gathering of ten takes place, naturally Du Ruopu (Qinyan) should be ranked foremost. I wonder how Master Hua's Huifang compares to my Yunong? Thinking of the manner in which Tian the gentleman was received — he is clearly a man of real talent and wisdom; there must be a deep feeling of another kind in him. Each person has their own strengths; there is no need to make comparisons between them.",
    "So he gently ground the ink, slowly took up his brush, and wrote:",
    "\"The ninety days of spring are gone and past recall; two or three kindred spirits come unbidden to gather. Let us make a connoisseur's assembly of qin and cup, and try our mood amid birds and flowers. Though the site may lack the splendor of famous mountains, we rejoice that the courtyard is free of common weeds. We pity them — those of orchid essence — that they have fallen into the pear-garden world; we convene our bamboo-grove assembly, and count out the flower-tidings. The many work at refining the score; by chance they are alike to those who weave brocade. Their wisdom accumulated into heartfelt understanding — they would blush to be counted mere players of the money-counting trick. They have transported tender warmth into a cool temple; they have discovered elegance amid the dusty track. We celebrate the day when the pearl formed in its azure sea, and congratulate the moment when the jade issued from its Lantian hills. Famous gentlemen who have set the city aflame — how should they not cherish one another? The powder-red and the blue gown — they may well be placed on the same scale. Set out the thirty-six tiles of the mandarin-duck game, let the red beans be thrown together; prepare a thousand pairs of kingfisher-wing ornaments, let the purple clouds come and be welcomed freely. Respectfully, I address this note in advance of meeting. Set off your fine carriage early; together grace this humble lane. Mei Ziyu bows in respect. To the honored desks of Master Duxiang and the recluse Jingyi.\" When Ziyu had finished writing, he sealed the letter, applied his seal, handed it to a page boy to deliver to the gatehouse, instructing that it be sent first thing the next morning to Yiyuan, to invite Masters Xu and Xiao to come on the day after tomorrow to drink at Young Master Liu's residence — making the instructions clear and unmistakable. The page boy agreed, and Ziyu retired for the night. No more of that.",
    "The next day, Wang Xun, Shi Nanxiang, and the others came to Liu Wenze's house and told him; Wenze was very pleased and said the arrangements would be made in the \"Sword Reclining, Qin Sleeping\" study (倚剑眠琴之室) tomorrow. As it happened, orchids and thoroughworts were fragrant, and peonies, crabapples, and the like were in full bloom. They then went off to inform the assembled beauties to arrive at the chen hour (7-9 a.m.) on the morrow. Wenze said: \"Tomorrow among the flower retinue, I fear several may not be able to come. I know Qin Qiguan has an eye ailment; Du Qinyan is also ill and not yet recovered. He declined early this morning. Even if those two do not come, there will be eight — quite festive enough. Gengxiang and Jingyi will certainly be there.\" Nanxiang said: \"For the drinking-game rounds at table, fresh ideas are few; overly difficult ones may put our guests at a loss in the moment. We need something that suits both the refined and the common taste — easy to understand and easy to execute — and yet avoids what is overly familiar. Guessing-the-object forfeits (shè fù) are also rather dull.\" Wang Xun said: \"The linked-couplet game we did here before would work.\" Wenze said: \"Doing that game again would feel stale as well. Let us wait until tomorrow and improvise as the mood takes us.\" Wang Xun and the others stayed for dinner at Wenze's that day, chatted for a while more, and then dispersed. Wenze also sent around word to each place asking everyone to come early tomorrow, to enjoy a full day's pleasure; all to come in informal dress, no formal caps or sashes required. The messengers returned with everyone's agreement.",
    "Now let us speak of Tian Chunhang: since forming his bond with Huifang, he had not left the temple. Huifang came without fail once a day regardless of the hour — sometimes for leisurely conversation, sometimes for a small drink — and would often offer gentle words of counsel and encouragement. So Chunhang was already fully contented, concentrating only on his studies of the classics and on writing poetry and prose. By nature he was richly learned from long years of reading, able to produce ten thousand words as easily as a horse can cover ten thousand paces; his name had for a time made a stir throughout the capital, and those in power all wished to bring him under their patronage. But Chunhang, magnanimous and self-reliant, considered seeking powerful connections beneath his dignity; never once did he present a calling card to petition an important official. He preferred to dwell in the cool temple, with a beautiful person as companion and celebrated men as fellows. Through Huifang, he had also made the acquaintance of many fine friends — Xu Duxiang, Xiao Jingyi, Liu Wenze, Shi Nanxiang, Yan Zhongqing, Wang Xun, and others. Zhongqing had formerly been at odds with Chunhang — this had in fact been his way of spurring Chunhang on; after Gao Pin had explained the full circumstances, and mentioned too that Zhongqing had still sent the fifty taels for travel expenses, Chunhang naturally felt immense gratitude and respect. Zhongqing asked Huifang to serve as mediator; relations between them became even warmer than before. Only Ziyu he had not yet met in person. Knowing today that Wenze and the others were celebrating Huifang's birthday, his heart was immensely pleased; but then, their friendship having become common knowledge, he felt somewhat abashed about it, and was tempted not to attend. Yet he could not in good conscience disappoint the group, and had no choice but to keep his word.",
    "Wenze had the \"Sword Reclining, Qin Sleeping\" study arranged from very early in the morning. Since the occasion was a birthday celebration, it required a degree of decoration: in the center hung a large painting of \"The Immortals Gathered in Solemn Assembly.\" All the antique ornaments placed about were of the finest quality. Along the long gallery outside the blinds were ranged over ten pots of Cymbidium orchids; swaying gently in the mild breeze, their fragrance came in waves. Wenze was standing alone at the gallery's edge when he saw someone approaching from the front at a distance — he recognized it as Huifang, magnificently dressed, coming toward him. Huifang mounted the step-stone and at once began performing a full formal bow. Wenze hurried to raise him up and said: \"Meixiang, why do you do this? It should be me who first offers birthday congratulations to you.\" Huifang said: \"That the lowly anniversary of my birth should receive the attendance of all you honored persons is more than Huifang can possibly deserve. Yesterday I wanted to go around to everyone and decline with thanks, yet feared that would give offense — as if I were refusing to accept the kindness. And today is a great celestial assembly with all the immortals gathered: to allow those of our humble station to ascend with the chickens and dogs — though we cannot become immortals ourselves, at least we may escape the commonplace. That is why I have respectfully obeyed your summons and come with all humility.\" Wenze said: \"This is also a grand undertaking of like-minded friends — gazing in admiration at the beauty that enthralls a city, we are merely offering flowers as tribute to the Buddha.\" While they were speaking, Lu Sulan, Li Yulin, and Jin Shufang arrived together; shortly afterward, Gao, Shi, Yan, and Wang came in a group. Huifang thanked each of them in turn.",
    "While everyone was exchanging courtesies, they saw the servant who had received the letter lead Ziyu in. Though Huifang did not know him, his heart had already guessed who it was, and he stepped forward to bow in thanks. Ziyu held him back and said: \"Is this Meixiang? I, Gengxiang, have long admired your name and yearned for a meeting; never having had the chance to see you in person, today being fortunate enough to stand downwind of your refined presence, I already feel fragrant beauty permeating my whole body.\" Huifang responded repeatedly with polite demurrals; looking at Ziyu's bearing, he privately thought with admiration: \"Truly a sun and stars among men, a phoenix among mortals — there is an air of genuine, harmonious purity about him, bright and brilliant with a quality that stands above the crowd. No wonder Du Yunong is so deeply enchanted by him. Alongside my Tian — they might be called twin paragons, a Chu and a Liang born together!\" Ziyu then greeted Lu Sulan and the others; suddenly they heard from outside: \"Master Xu and Master Xiao have arrived!\" Everyone went out from the hall together to welcome them; there came Ziyun and Cixian, gracefully as sons of great families draped in their furs, with Yuan Baozhu and Wang Lanbao following behind. Further behind were eight bright-faced and handsome young attendants carrying clothing bundles, bronze basins, and rinsing vessels.",
    "Huifang stepped forward several paces to bow; Ziyun and Cixian each helped him up from one side and said: \"Meixiang has always been easy and unconstrained — why so formal today? Surely you're putting us to too much trouble.\" They then entered the room and exchanged greetings with all present; all the young dan actors also completed their introductions, seated themselves by seniority, and settled down. Ziyun said: \"Thanks to the kind invitation by letter from Gengxiang, Qianzhou, and all the gentlemen, today's occasion is truly a grand gathering. Yesterday I had my fill of reading Gengxiang's pearls and jade; even today my teeth still carry a lingering fragrance. And now we find ourselves in this great assembly of flowers, allowing your humble guests to follow in the rear and bask in the fragrance — truly a fine matter.\" Cixian said: \"Colored phoenixes of the scarlet mountains, black-robed families of the deep lanes — no elegance of sash and sandal could surpass this. And yet may the cold-hilltop wild cranes also soar freely among them?\" Wenze, Wang Xun, and the others all said together: \"Duxiang and Jingyi — foremost among celebrated men, leaders of the literary and poetic assembly — there is no moment we do not long for your refined example. That you do not disdain our humble abode and have come so graciously today is all we could wish for in this life!\" Nanxiang said: \"Between friends, what matters is congenial rapport; in my humble view, there is no need to maintain the formalities of mere social calls.\"",
    "Zhongqing said: \"Zhujun is a candid and open-hearted person — his opening words show it immediately. Today's gathering is all the closest friends; it would be best to speak freely of what lies in the heart, without standing on ceremony.\" Then Gao Pin laughed and said: \"Today the Queen Mother of the West has arrived early — it is only the Old Immortal of the South Pole who is coming late and late. Could it be that halfway here he ran into the somersault cloud of the Little Pilgrim (Sun Wukong) and was struck and injured the little longevity-star, making it inconvenient to walk? Or perhaps he slipped and fell again in a carriage rut.\" Everyone burst out laughing: \"Zhuoran's wit is priceless — when the birthday-star arrives, let him be fined three great cups.\" Huifang seemed to blush slightly. Baozhu said: \"How many guests are still to arrive today?\" Wenze said: \"Just the birthday-star, one person. Among the flower contingent, four are absent: Qinyan and Qiguan are both ill and sent their regrets early this morning; Guibao and Chunxi will certainly be here. Once Xiangfan arrives, we can be seated.\"",
    "Before Wenze had finished speaking, Chunhang had already arrived. Everyone exchanged greetings afresh; all the beauties were also introduced. The banter and teasing naturally followed. Baozhu and Sulan drew out a red felt mat and placed it on the floor, setting up two folding chairs, intending to ask Chunhang and Huifang to sit together and receive obeisance. The two of them absolutely refused to sit; the mat was quickly put away. By now Chunhang and Huifang felt they were outnumbered and simply submitted to the general raillery; to answer back only invited more. Ziyu felt a deep admiration for Chunhang's free and easy bearing — and, paired with Huifang, the two were truly ice-jar and autumn moon, each enhancing the other's radiance. He also observed all the beauties in turn, each with their own loveliness — the only thing that diminished his pleasure was the absence of Qinyan, which left him with an unsettled flutter in his chest.",
    "Wenze then gave the order for the servants to lay out three tables. He asked: \"Today's seating — shall we go by seniority, or shall we put the birthday honorees at the head?\" Chunhang and Huifang said together: \"We absolutely cannot accept that — seniority is the natural arrangement.\" Everyone agreed to go by seniority. Wenze arranged the wines; the center table was first set in order. By age, Cixian was eldest; knowing he could not refuse, he took the seat of honor, with Gao Pin beside him, then Zhongqing. The left-hand table: Ziyun at the head, then Nanxiang, then Ziyu. The right-hand table: Tian Chunhang at the head, then Wang Xun, with Wenze as host. Three guests at each table.",
    "Once the seating was settled, Wang Guibao and Lin Chunxi arrived and were introduced all around. At the center table, Shufang, Yulin, and Chunxi attended; at the left table, Baozhu, Lanbao, and Sulan; at the right table, Huifang and Guibao. The assignments made, everyone took their seats and began to pour slowly and drink at a leisurely pace. It was truly:",
    "Scholars of the Jade Continent gather first before the Dragon Gate; the assembled immortals of the Jasper Isle pay court together at the Golden Palace. Embroidered hearts and brocaded mouths — pearls from the ninth heaven falling profusely; moon-shaped countenance and flower-petal skin — at every table the court robes are immaculate. No less fine than wind-soup and unicorn-dried-meat — drinking the wine that grants long life, wisdom certified through three lifetimes; no need for jade chimes and cloud music-frames — singing the song that transcends old age, each hoping to grow old together. The Jade-Capital Gentleman, the Cloud-Feasting Gentleman, the Wind-Riding Gentleman, the Phoenix-Driving Gentleman — in the crimson dust and the azure beyond, spanning the present life and past lives; the Eyebrow-Painter, the Gauze-Washer, the Song-Treader, the Lotus-Picker — iridescent phoenix and brocaded phoenix, manifesting in different forms. Surpassing the forest-and-mountain hermit who, taking the plum tree as wife and the crane as child, merely counts as romantic; sufficient to melt the heart of iron and stone — encountering just the flicker of an eye's corner or the curve of a brow, the ice breaks at once. Guessing games and drinking forfeits — printing your heart against mine. Golden waves and jade-clear liquor — try the lord's lips again against the lady's. Humor and play at will, turning everything upside down; brief arias and long songs at the table, exhausting all artistry and making white even of brown. Most are here to borrow the famous flower to express their pride — with no concern at all for the common people's welfare. With this they enjoy themselves without limit; youth has its own time of waiting. Rightly one feels the Western Garden's elegant gathering had only household entertainers; even the Winding-Stream Cup-Floating had no such intimate companions.\n\nAs cups and chopsticks flew and sandals and shoes lay scattered, every pleasure of a youthful and refined assembly was had to the full. Several were already in a state of half-collapsed jade mountains, like crabapple blossoms about to doze. At the tables, everyone's heart was at ease, every face glowing with joy. Only Ziyu kept thinking of Qinyan lying ill in bed — he knew he would be listless and depressed, his medicine-stove half-burned, his green window shut tight; he could not imagine the degree of his tedium. And he knew that Qinyan, aware of today's festive scene, would certainly be yearning for quiet and solitude. How he wished he could slip over there at this moment and offer a few words of comfort, brew tea and add incense, and help restore his spirits. And yet Qinyan might suspect that Ziyu, in the midst of pleasure, had simply forgotten his sorrows — and, thinking so in this grand flower gathering, would feel all the more wretched. To make matters worse, Sulan was right here too; otherwise, he might at least have gone to him for comfort. He sighed: though the scene before the eyes was full of people like clouds, yet he whom his heart sought was not here. At this moment Ziyu's expression grew somber; he merely pleaded drunkenness and withdrew from his seat to lie down by the heated kang, and no one paid him much attention. Besides, the food and wine had been plentiful and most had drunk beyond their capacity, so each left their seat and scattered to sit where they liked.",
    "The servants cleared away the remaining dishes and set out fragrant tea and fresh fruit. Chunxi and Guibao went to the Taihu stone rockery and sat chatting by the peony hedge. Yulin and Shufang had drunk themselves into a stupor and lay asleep beneath the crabapple blossoms. Lanbao was fishing by the pond. Baozhu and Huifang were playing chess, with Sulan watching the game, while Nanxiang and Gao Pin stood by giving Baozhu advice. Huifang said: \"Three of you against my one — even if you win it's hardly a surprise.\" Baozhu said: \"I can win you without any coaching at all.\" Wenze said: \"Today we have had real pleasure — it is a pity that two are absent from the flower contingent. The other is no great matter, but first and foremost Qinyan's absence has prevented Gengxiang from being fully at ease.\" Ziyun said: \"Indeed! Qinyan's illness is rather mysterious — listless in spirit, no desire to eat or drink; it has been over ten days with no improvement.\" Cixian said: \"Yesterday I took his pulse — it appeared to be accumulated fatigue compounded by pent-up emotion and melancholy. And yesterday there were specks of blood in his phlegm; without several months of complete rest he cannot recover.\"",
    "Ziyu, lying on the kang, heard all this clearly and could not help feeling more agitated. Zhongqing said: \"Today's occasion cannot be without some literary record. If Jingyi would paint a picture and write a preface to commemorate this fine gathering, we could all bask in reflected glory.\" Cixian said: \"As for the painting — your humble servant will do his best. As for a high and classical composition, there are naturally the weighty brushes of all you honored gentlemen. The poor hermit's sparse and lean style is not suited to the luxuriance of the Golden Valley feast — it would only make the famous flowers lose some of their luster.\" Everyone said: \"Too modest.\" Ziyun said: \"Today's gathering arose from Meixiang as its inspiration, causing all the flowers to bloom in unison — surpassing the paper flowers of the Tang palace. My humble idea is that we first seek to admire all your honored ones' pearls and jade by composing a chain poem (liánjù) — what say you?\" Everyone agreed: \"Excellent.\" Chunhang said: \"Classical (gǔtǐ) or regulated form (jìntǐ)?\" Cixian said: \"The regulated form is harder to develop fully; with so many people, it tends toward flatness and directness. Better to use the classical form.\"",
    "So they went in order of age, with Cixian again taking the lead, followed by Ziyun, then Gao Pin, Nanxiang, Wenze, Zhongqing, Chunhang, Wang Xun, and Ziyu — nine people in all. Wang Xun had already roused Ziyu; Sulan produced a hangover-dispelling pill and gave it to Ziyu to take. Ziyu was embarrassed and had no choice but to make an effort to rouse himself. Sulan, seeing that Ziyu sat silent without speaking, in that not-quite-drunk state, guessed in his heart that it was because of Qinyan's absence. On the one hand, with so many people present it was not convenient to offer consolation; on the other, if she brought up Qinyan it might only stir Ziyu's inner preoccupations more, and rather than bringing relief would only deepen the gloom. So she moved away and went to talk to others. Wenze ordered the pages to place a small side-table before each person's seat, with a brush-and-inkstone set and several sheets of flower-patterned writing paper, the ink already ground. Everyone then asked Cixian to compose the opening line. Cixian said: \"Let's set aside the theme of longevity (shòu).\" He then said, \"Forgive the presumption!\" — raised his brush and wrote a line, then read it aloud: \"The jade-tree sings in the clear dawn — orioles call in confusion.\"",
    "Everyone listened, wrote their lines, and noted the character \"jìng\" (静, Cixian's courtesy name). It was now Ziyun's turn; Ziyun said: \"Should each person not write two lines?\" He hesitated briefly, then wrote: \"Day by day the spring wind blows yet does not scatter. / Flower-scattering celestial maidens, fresh and wondrous.\" Everyone wrote them down, marked the character \"yún\" (云, Ziyun's name), and all said: \"Beautifully connected — the third line opens it up, giving the imagination room to flourish.\" It came to Gao Pin's turn; without pausing to think, he wrote: \"Cut silk as flowers, scattered to the heavens' halfway point. / Flower-heart and flower-face — the more spirited they seem.\" Everyone said: \"Wonderful!\" — and each wrote it down.",
    "Nanxiang said: \"This line needs to shift the rhyme. These flowers are after all different from true flowers; if one simply treats them as flowers, then what sort of flowers would Xi Shi and Lady Yang Guifei be?\" He then wrote: \"Yet one feels the flower-heart is somehow still short of the real. / Butterflies have males — who will discern them carefully?\" Everyone clapped their hands: \"Magnificent! This line establishes the boundary precisely, preventing vagueness and confusion. Zhujun is always the inspired one.\" Nanxiang said: \"I dare not claim so — I merely read the topic clearly enough.\" It was now Wenze's turn; Wenze said: \"This line needs to match well to provide a pivot, or else the energy will dissipate. That 'male butterfly' is rather difficult to match.\" He concentrated in careful thought. Zhongqing said: \"Hurry up and hand in your paper — outside the music is about to begin with the door about to open.\" Wenze said: \"I have it. 'Mandarin ducks, though small, always cleave to each other.'\" Cixian and Ziyun said: \"That matches excellently — both skilled and apt.\" Nanxiang said: \"You did well enough with it.\" Wenze put down his brush; Zhongqing said: \"How can you stop at one line?\" Reminded, Wenze laughed: \"You urged me on so quickly, I forgot.\" He thought again and wrote: \"Creation's craft — selecting the flawless and polishing fine.\" Everyone said: \"This line too is well produced — and the rhyme shifts again.\" Zhongqing continued and wrote: \"Each one carved and engraved, setting eyebrows and eyes. / Spent ten measures of pearl from the dragon-palace storeroom.\" Chunhang's turn came; he continued: \"Cleaved from the azure sea a pair of jade branches. / Little Jade vexed, Jade-Green grieving.\" Everyone praised again: \"Fine! The distinction is kept clearly.\" Next was Wang Xun, who thought for a while and wrote: \"The jade person fears too that eternity will take her. / Cicada-slender, suspected of stealing Chang'e's elixir.\" Everyone was about to praise this when Gao Pin said: \"That's too vicious an insult — does this mean every one of them is like the rabbit in the moon-palace?\" Everyone burst out laughing. Wang Xun felt embarrassed. The young beauties all scolded Gao Pin, saying: \"Of all people, it is always him — never a good word his whole life. In the future let him be punished by becoming mute.\"",
    "Gao Pin said: \"How strange — other people scold you all, and I defend your honor, yet you scold me in return. Truly no good deed goes unpunished.\" It was now Ziyu's turn; Ziyu's mind was on Qinyan, feeling hollow and listless — as everyone well understood. Though Ziyu tried his utmost to conceal it, his inspiration was at a low ebb; he had no choice but to strain and write: \"A glance in passing — that jade-girl's eyes turned back once. / Luan-comb sweeping gently across cloudy-green tresses.\" Chunhang said: \"This takes us to the dressing scene — the continuation will need to describe things finely.\" Ziyu at this moment was thinking of the expression Qinyan had worn while performing \"The Startled Dream,\" which accounted for the line \"that jade-girl's eyes turned back once.\" The others did not understand why; they only saw that his spirits were poor and his mind not really on the poetry, so the lines came out somewhat flat and diffuse. It was again Cixian's turn; he wrote: \"In the mirror, the lotus face — fresh from sleep. / The charming voice forms the white-ramie song.\" Next came Ziyun: \"Lithe and pliant, knowing how to sing the red-gauze melody. / A clear and nimble beauty — touched by chance, the soul is lost.\" Gao Pin said: \"'The soul is lost — alas, what can be done?' \" And wrote: \"In the Bronze Sparrow's deep spring — the greater and lesser Qiao. / Where flowers are joined on a single branch — the sisters.\" Nanxiang said: \"Fine as it is, that Bronze Sparrow line is a little muddled.\" He matched it immediately: \"Jade-like, a pair of discs — surely Qiongyao and jasper. / Slender waist swaying into the Magic Harmony willow.\" Everyone praised: \"This 'sister flowers,' 'Qiongyao and jade' — the match is excellent. The poem's energy has been pulled back into shape.\" Wenze then continued: \"A city-toppling beauty without equal in the world. / Melts even this world's heart of iron and stone.\" Everyone said: \"Wonderful! This line needs a match of equal force.\" Zhongqing thought a moment, then laughed slightly and wrote: \"Spring returns on earth, to the tottering old man.\" Chunhang said: \"That is truly a marvelous match.\" Then he saw the next line: \"How a single smile gives birth to a hundred charms.\" He continued: \"At the banquet, silks compete — gold lightly tossed. / Zheng Yingtao — truly so remarkable.\"",
    "Wang Xun matched: \"Feng Zidu — his fame no empty claim. / Slowly the long days pass in the early summer.\" Wenze said: \"Feng Zidu — nowadays there is a Feng Zipei; they seem like brothers.\" Ziyun said: \"Feng Zipei is actually not bad; he has one particular trait — he simply refuses to take pleasure among the flower company.\" Wang Lanbao said with a cold laugh: \"Of course he won't join our crowd — he actually gets annoyed when he sees us.\" Ziyu said: \"Why so?\" Guibao cut in: \"He has his own feelings about it.\" Ziyu continued: \"Brocade seat and flower banquet — day turns easily to night. / In splendor and beauty, worthy of the 'Same Carriage' ode.\" The second round came to Cixian, who wrote: \"Yuan and Bai's poems — originally formed amid lotus gatherings. / On the red felt stage-carpet — passion and sentiment in abundance.\" Ziyun continued: \"Practiced in singing 'Ding Niang's Ten Requests.' / The plain and beautiful — no humble part left unremarked.\" Gao Pin said: \"Wonderful! For this line let me produce a good match.\" The young beauties, hearing this, suspected another jest at their expense and all crowded around to watch what Gao Pin was writing.",
    "Gao Pin, smiling, wrote out slowly: \"Rain and clouds — one travels all the way to Zhong'a.\" Everyone burst out laughing; the beauties all spat at him and pummeled him in a flurry. Ziyun laughed: \"It is my fault — I provoked that line from him.\" Nanxiang said: \"Even as playful writing, it should not be so cutting. Change one character and it can be saved — change 'traveled' (得) to 'how could' (岂).\" The beauties finally agreed to this. Gao Pin said: \"Very well — the wrath of the multitude must not be incurred.\" He then wrote: \"Heaven-born loveliness — to be cherished and preserved.\" Nanxiang said: \"A brigand reciting scripture, a butcher becoming Buddha — Zhuoran has actually developed a kind heart and knows how to cherish! That too is remarkable.\" He continued: \"Let not the flower branch be lightly cast aside. / Would that we could, like Wang Xian, buy a Taogen.\" Wenze linked: \"How laughable that Wang Rong bored through the plum pits.\" Zhongqing laughed: \"Here we go again, straying into impurity — your hearts still have something unclean in them.\" Then he saw what Wenze had written next: \"Once heaven gives birth to a fine jade youth.\" Zhongqing linked: \"Must heaven and earth make the yin and yang wrong? / Only heard of the female rainbow becoming a divine maiden.\" Everyone said: \"This is cautionary and admonishing verse — not vicious mockery. Such things do indeed exist in this world, though not among us.\" Chunhang linked: \"Let not the male wind turn into a great king. / In the painted hall, the fine banquet is held day by day.\" Everyone laughed again. Gao Pin said: \"Poetry expresses the will — the one who ties the bell must untie it. If I were to write this one, it would be wrong again.\" Wang Xun's turn came; he said: \"We can close now — let it fall to Gengxiang to write the conclusion.\" He wrote: \"Through the fan-base, peering at my lord — half a face glimpsed. / Picking up the piece of moonlight — a single bright sliver.\" Everyone exclaimed in praise: \"Fine! It is time to conclude — this conclusion is no small achievement. The closing lines must be able to hold together the whole poem.\" Ziyu thought for a moment and wrote: \"Snowflakes fly up on the jade branches bright.\" Everyone praised it unanimously as a powerful close, able to carry the whole poem in a single breath.",
    "Cixian made a fair copy and read through it several times aloud: \"It truly flows in one unbroken breath, with no sign of stitching or joint.\" He said: \"Tomorrow I will paint a 'Picture of the Hundred Flowers Competing in Beauty' (群花斗艳图) — how would that be?\" Everyone responded enthusiastically: \"Wonderful! Why don't we now make a comparison between the people and the flowers — fairly assessed, without personal bias.\" So they deliberated together and decided: Baozhu as the peony; Huifang as the herbaceous peony; Sulan as the lotus; Yulin as the green peach blossom; Shufang as the crabapple; Lanbao as the rose; Guibao as the cotton rose. Chunxi, small in stature yet richly talented and beloved by all, was assigned the orchid. The eight assignments all felt fitting. They then wondered what flowers Qinyan and Qiguan should be. Ziyun said: \"Qinyan's art and beauty are exceptional, yet his temperament is exceedingly cool — likening him to the plum blossom is most apt; and since his passionate love of the plum is not for Gengxiang's sake, then whose?\" Everyone agreed: \"Quite right.\" Gao Pin said: \"Only I fear that Lin Hejing (the hermit who called the plum his wife) would not consent — Gengxiang would have taken away his leather-shod little son.\"",
    "Ziyu could not help blushing. Zhongqing said: \"And Qiguan?\" Ziyun said: \"Qiguan's temperament is fierce and upright, his appearance extremely fine — he somewhat lacks a gentle, flowing charm. Let him be likened to the chrysanthemum.\" Gao Pin said: \"Chrysanthemums vary in variety — some white, some yellow, some red, some purple; the white ones are fine, but the rest tend to give a feeling of austere autumnal severity. Qiguan, though his temperament is fierce, has a tenderness in him that is quite winning. Better to liken him to the apricot blossom.\" Everyone agreed: \"A fine apricot blossom — perfectly fitting.\" Wenze said: \"Speaking of chrysanthemums, yellow or white — do you all know that in the eastern garden a new courtesan has recently arrived, called White Chrysanthemum (Bái Júhuā)? Have you heard anything about her?\" Everyone said they had not.",
    "Gao Pin said: \"There is nothing in the world that I cannot find out. I know that she came from Guangxi with a company commander who brought her to the capital; the commander has now abandoned her and left the city, so she ended up in the pleasure quarter. She is actually rather fine-looking in a pure, unadorned way — hence the refined nickname. But people from the two Guangs seldom bind their feet; they all have natural six-inch feet, smooth and round, with a double-footed gait, walking like the wind. As a person, she is exceedingly vivacious and charming.\" Zhongqing said: \"That explains your official title of Inspector-General of Intelligence from All Quarters.\" Everyone laughed again. Ziyun said: \"After today's gathering, such a magnificent feast will be hard to convene again. On the eighteenth, Yaoqing is moving to new lodgings — would all the gentlemen be willing to move the wine-jars there for another gathering?\" Everyone agreed: \"There is absolutely no reason not to come — anyone who fails to attend will be fined to host a day's feast, and we'll have another gathering.\" Baozhu said: \"I fear I don't have that standing; surely not everyone will come on my account.\" Chunhang said: \"Why would they not? And besides, you are the king of flowers — these assembled blossoms will naturally come to pay homage. As for us flower-admirers, when we encounter beauty as striking as national-fragrance and heavenly-perfume, how could we not be eager and enthusiastic?\" Nanxiang said: \"Leave it to me — if one person fails to come, I'll be fined to host a day; two people, two days' hosting.\" Baozhu said: \"Truly? After tomorrow's wine wears off, don't tell me you'll have forgotten.\" Only Ziyu sat in silence. The others went on talking and laughing; the bright moon was now directly overhead, the red lanterns about to burn out, and it was past the third watch.",
    "Cixian said: \"The night is already deep — we can disperse.\" So everyone rose; Baozhu confirmed the date of the eighteenth, everyone agreed, come rain or shine; then they each mounted their carriages and scattered in all directions. The next day, Huifang went around to call and express thanks; only Ziyu was ill and did not receive him.",
    "On the eighteenth, all the celebrated gentlemen and the celebrated young dan actors did indeed come to Baozhu's new lodgings, from the wu hour (11 a.m.) until the zi hour (midnight). That day the entertainment was confined to drinking games and guessing forfeits, clear singing and clapper-beat — and they dispersed having fully enjoyed themselves. Among them Ziyu did not come owing to illness. Zhang Zhongyu was added to the company — always the most eager to please in a festive scene.",
    "Qiguan was added to the flower register; only Qinyan had still not recovered. Gao Pin and Wenze held Nanxiang to what he had said — \"If one guest is absent, I'll be fined to host a day.\" Since Ziyu did not come that day, Nanxiang was fined a day of hosting; Nanxiang was thoroughly happy to oblige. Another day's gathering was held at his residence. Only Ziyu and Qinyan had both not yet recovered. Truly: a few plum blossoms, tender and about to fall; the moon has dipped once more below the bamboo bridge in the west. As for what happened next — let the following chapter tell the tale."
  ],
  18: [
    "Qinyan's illness lingered and he remained listless, keeping his door closed to visitors; only a few close friends from the same troupe came by from time to time to offer comfort. Baozhu and Sulan would also pass on word from Ziyu, saying how he had been the other day and how he could not come to see him often, but asked him to take good care of himself — and at this Qinyan grew all the more heavy-hearted. Since falling ill, he had gone nowhere at all; even Yiyuan he had long since ceased to visit. But his teacher Changqing depended on him as a money tree, and with Qinyan ill for so long and unable to receive clients, Changqing had lost a good deal of his enthusiasm.",
    "Now, those who made their career as teachers of theatrical troupes were originally dan role performers themselves; over thirty years their lives went through four transformations.",
    "What were the four transformations? In youth, their bearing was lovely and they were cherished by all; the undifferentiated was breached, the two positives met — people called them \"rabbits.\" After the age of twenty, the body would grow larger, the looks would coarsen, yet they still flirted and primped, wearing splendid headgear and fine clothes. When performing on stage, casting aside all shame, they would put out their utmost seductive wantonness — twisting and mincing, still trying to captivate souls and draw men's essence — at that stage they were called \"foxes.\" After thirty, the voice had gone hoarse, the beard had appeared, and acting was no longer possible; with no other recourse, they would put on the look of a market-town roughneck, buy some boys, train them for a year or so, and then send them out to earn money. Those who were well-favored earned more money and were treated almost like a father. Those of ordinary looks who could not charm people and could not earn were nagged morning and evening, scolded for a day's absence from entertaining clients and beaten for two days' absence. When the boy's apprenticeship was up, the teacher would open his mouth and demand three or five thousand cash; once the money was in hand, he'd send the boy out the door as bare and empty as he'd come in, without even an old garment to his name. If the teacher had no wife, he would require the disciple to share his bed at night. Such ferocious ruffians — more dreadful than a wild tiger by several degrees — were at this stage compared to \"tigers.\"",
    "Then when luck ran out, they could only stay in the troupe doing flag-bearing and bit-parts; at that stage they could only be compared to \"dogs.\" Such was the standard life-portrait of a troupe teacher. Since Qinyan had come to the capital last twelfth month, it had now been four months; Xu Ziyun had already spent several thousand taels of silver — not a small sum — which is why Changqing treated Qinyan exceptionally well.",
    "Were Qinyan to remain ill for a year and a half, one feared Changqing's heart might change — but this was others' speculation; let it rest for now.",
    "Now let us speak of Wei Pengcai, who had entered the Hua mansion full of expectation, imagining he would immediately make his mark. Who could have known that after a month inside, the host and guest had still not come face to face? The several times he had asked for an audience, he was put off with the excuse that the young master was busy. Those he did meet and mingle with were all dubious characters. There was also that class of arrogant household servants who put on great airs: they would meet him with merely a perfunctory bow, openly take the superior seat, and speak in nothing but muddled nonsense. The young ones were full of bluster and pretense of understanding; the old ones traded on their seniority and were thoroughly devious. Pengcai tried his utmost to get along with everyone and attended to all social obligations; he would not dare offend even a dog in the Hua household — all in hope of winning some favorable outcome. But unknown to him, the losses were mounting steadily. The household had several hundred friends, private secretaries, and servants; hardly a day passed without some occasion arising. Once accustomed to this social round, one could not be selective about whom to flatter — whenever there was a celebration of any kind, one had to contribute a share. Occasionally three or four friends would gather together and generate some matter — either splitting the meal bill or gambling away a stake. Then there were the young lads, the coachmen, the grooms, the cooks, and the like, who came regularly to extract small gratuities; fail to comply and gossip would spread at once. Though only one month had passed, he had by now gotten mixed up with all the idle hangers-on of the household — some congenial, some not. The congenial ones were Gu Yueqing, Zhang Xiaomei, and the like; the uncongenial ones were Yan Jian'an, Wang Qingyun, and the like. Pengcai could only attend to his own station — keeping close to the congenial and keeping his distance from the uncongenial. But what truly vexed him was that he had still not had a proper meeting with the young master, despite having been there a month. Meanwhile there was nothing useful for him to do — just mixing with the crowd every day. Truly: two meals of old rice, one pillow of dark and sweet sleep.",
    "On this particular day, he went out for a stroll, came out of the city gate, and found the scene much livelier than inside the city — carriages flowing like water, horses like dragons. Following the road, he came to Mei's residence on Mingke Alley, went in and found Ziyu still ill in bed, listless and low-spirited. Ziyu asked how Pengcai was doing; Pengcai could only speak positively, rattling off a few easy lies. He then went to pay his respects to Lady Yan and express his thanks, then came out to find Li Yuanmao — but found his door locked. So he took his leave of Ziyu again and went out — lonely and desolate, with nowhere to go.",
    "Wandering aimlessly to the edge of the Tiger-Subduing Bridge (Fuhu Qiao), he recalled that Zhang Zhongyu lived at the Wu residence nearby. He inquired at the gatehouse and, as luck would have it, Zhongyu was at home; he was invited in to sit. Zhongyu asked a few pleasantries, tea was served, and after a short while Zhongyu said: \"Now that my little brother is in the city, it must be hard to get out often — why not find a place to sit and watch some opera to dispel the tedium?\" Pengcai said: \"Very well — I've actually been quite worn out these past two days. If we're going, let's go.\" So the two of them went together to the theater, found seats, and watched two or three plays. Some young protégés came by to chat with them. Across the way, on the lower level of the opposite gallery, Pengcai spotted Li Yuanmao together with Sun Sihui. Pengcai went over, exchanged a few words, and came back.",
    "Zhongyu said: \"Those two brothers-in-law — a pair of born good-for-nothings if ever there was one. What's the point of looking after them?\" The plays that day felt stale and old-fashioned; Zhongyu grew restless and said: \"Let's go.\" He paid for the seats, and together with Pengcai went up to a wine-house for a small drink and a talk. Zhongyu, seeing that Pengcai seemed to be in poor spirits — not his usual self — asked: \"I heard you've entered the Hua family mansion. Given the grandeur of that establishment, and that the young master Hua loves social connections, things must naturally have taken a great turn for the better lately.\" Pengcai said: \"If elder brother hadn't asked, I would not have brought it up myself. At first Third Master Fu told me that the young master Hua had the reputation of Lord Mengchang — hundreds of retainers at his table. I went in, and there are indeed plenty of retainers — but all thoroughly mercenary people, either squeezing this one out or cutting that one down. I have been inside for over a month, and the young master continues to be cool and distant. If this goes on much longer, I fear I have misread the situation entirely.\" Zhongyu said: \"How many times have you met the young master?\" Pengcai said: \"I've met him a few times, but only for a few casual words before he moves away. He has many old familiars; a newcomer naturally cannot push through. \" Zhongyu was silent for a good while, then sighed: \"In the world today, if you want to maintain your self-respect and dignity, you can only stay home behind closed doors. To move in the circles of wealth and influence requires freshly drilling your speech and comportment — that too is no easy matter. At the highest level there were two men whom we could never emulate: the former worthy Chen Meigong (Chen Jiru), and the one who wrote the 'Ten Plays' — Li Liweng (Li Yu). Both had learning second to none; their fate was unfavorable and they could not obtain official position to render great service to the state, so they played the role of lofty recluses — and in so doing, they deployed all their lifetime's learning in running about at the gates of the powerful. They relied on a few brushstrokes of painting and calligraphy, a few poems and essays, to make princes and lords change their expression and the courtly world run toward them; even those great officials had to flatter them in return. If they offended someone, they could be cut down anywhere — so naturally they had to have unshakeable skill. Isn't that formidable? Those at the highest level, nowadays, are gone. Now, as for the second tier — even selecting from a wide pool, it would be hard to find one — their ten essential qualities are:",
    "Pengcai said: \"What are the ten qualities?\" Zhongyu said: \"A full measure of amiability; a second-tier degree of talent; three jin's capacity for wine; four-seasons appropriate dress; mastery of the five musical scales; an official rank of the sixth grade; skill at the seven-syllable verse; ability to cast the net eight ways; comprehension of the nine streams of learning; and perfect ease in all social occasions.\" Pengcai shook his head: \"So many requirements?\" Zhongyu said: \"After each, there is an additional word to be added — the word 'not'! Amiability — but never changing; talent — but never showing it off; wine capacity — but never getting drunk; seasonal dress — but never pawning it; mastery of scales — but never making an error; the sixth-grade rank — but never actually serving; seven-syllable verse — but never going rusty; casting the net eight ways — but never letting a thread drop; comprehension of all nine streams — but never running short; perfect social ease — but never being common.\" Pengcai said: \"On that account, being a person becomes very difficult indeed. I don't have a single one of these — how could I learn all of them?\" Zhongyu said: \"Actually, one needn't have all of them; a few will do for social management. Moreover, each person has their own timing and fortune — but one does need to have some genuine skill of one's own, so that people look up to you.\" Pengcai said: \"And the third tier?\" Zhongyu said: \"The third tier also has its seven-character formula. The first is 'tong' (童, a basic student).\" Pengcai said: \"What does that mean?\" Zhongyu laughed: \"If you've passed the first examination level, you've naturally read some books — you know a little about the refinements, which already puts you ahead of market-town roughnecks. The second is 'half-passable': knowing how to be obsequious, buttering up those inside and below, with the servility of a slave but calling them brother, pulling on the family façade and leaning on the ancestors, boring through cracks and filling holes, drumming up the draughty take. That is the third tier.\" Pengcai said: \"Don't look down on the third tier — I suspect nowadays everyone is of the third tier.\" Zhongyu said: \"Isn't that so! In my view, it's not a fixed pattern — even someone with all ten qualities may fail to get anywhere; even someone without a single one of the seven characters may stumble onto an opportunity. In the end it's all each person's own fate. As the saying goes: 'When luck arrives, the wind carries you to the Prince of Teng's Pavilion; when luck retreats, thunder smashes the Jianfu stele.' I know that this young master Hua is an easy person to deal with — look at how many people pass through his household and manage to extract all sorts of benefits. Let me give you a method: to get on his good side is not so difficult. I also know this person — he once entrusted me with some matters.",
    "\"I know there is someone in his household called Lin Shanzhi, who is his personal attendant.\" He put up a thumb as he spoke: \"He is a person of this caliber — his word is followed, his plan is adopted, he never leaves the young master's side. You must first work through this connection; once that gate is opened, everything else becomes easy. There is also that group of eight young pages, who are always at the young master's elbow — children have no great discernment; give them a small advantage and it's done. Slowly, word by word, blow it into his ears: today he hears that Master Wei is fine; tomorrow he hears again that Master Wei is fine — and it will work its way into the young master's heart. This is what's called 'releasing the leashed sparrow': let it out on fifty or sixty feet of string, and in the end it will always be reeled back in. Just don't begrudge the small initial outlay.\" Pengcai nodded and said: \"I am much obliged — truly grateful!\" Zhongyu continued: \"For instance, once you've established a connection with the young master, observe what his temperament is — what pleases him and what he dislikes — and naturally follow his preferences.",
    "\"Follow them to nine parts in ten, but always hold back one part for later — don't be too quick to spend it all. Take the handling of a wayward horse: if you want to manage it, going against its nature head-on is absolutely impossible; let it run, and let it run until it's exhausted — then one pull of the reins turns it around. Or take this case: if someone can think through a matter to nine parts, you must think it through to ten. That one extra part is the art of turning the wayward horse — that is what's called 'reining in the wayward horse.'",
    "\"Then there are those who have all sorts of faults and don't mix with people at all — they just stay in their rooms with their wives and concubines and enjoy themselves in isolation. With those, too, you must discover one or two things they enjoy; then meet those preferences, offer small tokens of loyalty and faithfulness, and never ask them for anything — and naturally they will set their minds at ease, saying: 'That man has a bit of genuine sincerity — he's not just trying to exploit me.' Once they've swallowed that bait, you can manage them however you like. This is what's called 'fishing for the golden cicada.' As for one's general manner — though one must be amiable, one also cannot be spineless through and through. Those who have no relevance and serve no purpose — the likes of Yan Jian'an and Wang Qingyun — don't bother with them; mingling indiscriminately with them serves no purpose at all. Among the household retinue, there are those who cannot say a single useful word inside, yet are masters at bamboozling outsiders. You must see clearly for yourself: those worth attending to, attend to; those not worth attending to, don't attend to. If you attend to those who are useless, the ones who matter will look down on you.\" Pengcai burst out laughing when he heard all this: \"Elder brother is truly the foremost great talent of our time — Chen Ping's stratagems and Zhuge Liang's plans are no more than this. You can describe the temperament and character of every sort of person in the world as if you had written them on the palm of your hand. Your little brother ought to come to you with a student's card and pay formal respects as a disciple, so that the method of the heart may be properly transmitted.\" Zhongyu laughed: \"I've already told you everything — what is there left to bow to a teacher for? Follow what I've said and it's guaranteed not to go wrong. In the future, if good things come to you, don't forget your teacher — that is all the good conscience a student needs.\" With that, both laughed; before they knew it, half the day had passed. Zhongyu settled the bill and they came out together. Zhongyu said: \"Little brother, go back into the city now. I have some business to attend to and cannot keep you company.\" With that, he bowed and departed. It was still early; as Pengcai walked along the way, he spotted Sihui and Yuanmao in the distance, just rounding a corner ahead. Pengcai thought: \"Where are they going?\" and quietly followed. Into a small alleyway — it was packed with idle onlookers, all crowded at someone's doorway peering in. Pengcai had heard people say that the East Garden was where prostitutes gathered; he joined the crowd and stood watching. In one household — a thatched-wall mud enclosure with two thatched rooms inside — he saw Sihui and Yuanmao standing just ahead of him. They were looking at two women seated on a long bench, both around twenty years old, both fat-faced and full-bellied, their hair greased and their faces powdered, their clothing rather showy. He saw one woman say to Sihui: \"Come in and sit.\" She laughed and simpered, making Sihui and Yuanmao itch with desire — hovering on the edge of entering but not quite entering, staring in a daze. He also saw an awkward-looking man of over forty squatting on the ground, wearing a short jacket belted at the waist with a large pouch hanging from it — big enough to hold two strings of cash. Then from behind the curtain walked out a woman of around twenty or so — rather good-looking: an oval face with a charming scattering of freckles, her hair done in a T-style knot, her temples soft and loose, a flower tucked in her hair. Her clothes were plainly dressed; on her feet she wore a pair of pointed-toe \"four-happiness bats\" high-soled shoes with pile ornaments. She also sat down on the bench and chatted with the other two. Her speech sounded different from northern speakers — more like a southerner. From head to toe she had an appealing prettiness, noticeably different from the others. He heard one of the plainer-looking ones begin to sing: \"Fine young lord, / Every day at the gate you stare and stare, / Your staring sets my heart astir, / Your longing has blurred your very eyes. / Wait a while — / Cloud and rain on Mount Wu, done in an instant, / All for a mere two hundred copper cash.\" Pengcai found this amusing, and then thought: though it is a crude and lewd ditty, the feeling expressed is truthful. He listened again: the homely one had turned and was singing directly at Sihui and Yuanmao:",
    "\"One of them has a pockmarked face, the other has bad eyes — / A blind-eyed hen paired with a mangy toad.",
    "\"You like me, I like him. Don't make such a fuss — in the tender quarter, you're clearly not an old hand.\"",
    "The bystanders could not make out the meaning; Pengcai understood perfectly that she was insulting those two, and nearly burst out laughing — he had to hold it in. He looked again at the good-looking one: she appeared to be a newcomer. In the capital, a prostitute who wanted to enter a proper establishment would first spend a few days in the East Garden or the West Depot to get a sense of the market, and naturally would soon enough lose all sense of shame and become practiced and worldly. Likewise, those who were no longer of use in the better houses were demoted to these two places. This was none other than the White Chrysanthemum (Bai Juhua) that Gao Pin had spoken of — newly arrived from Guangxi. Watching her behavior, Pengcai could see she still had a measure of bashfulness about her. A small boy came up beside her and offered a pipa lute; she took it and played a suite of \"Wang Zhaojun's Lament\" (昭君怨) — which caused the crowd at the doorway to grow even more numerous.",
    "Yuanmao, being shortsighted, pushed straight through into the doorway and stood there staring. Pengcai watched the woman play and sing: \"The willow branch, the willow branch — / In years past, within the palace, we vied in slender waists. / Now cast aside to grow at the roadside, / Kingfisher brows knotted, lamenting the crossroads. / Where is the painted boat moored? / The fine horse neighs into the wind. / I wait in vain for the harbinger of spring to come down the path in the second month, / And have become only the withered wood of autumn in the west wind. / Tightening the strings a notch, tuning again, one key higher, she sang on: / To think that once we were mandarin ducks and paired; / Today we are the stars Shen and Shang — never meeting. / And so it is that a dew-and-morning marriage does not last long. / Through ten thousand mountains and rivers I came to this place; / Two separated phoenixes gaze at each other in vain from afar. / I lament that for a beauty with ill-starred fate, there is seldom a good ending; / Even to hold the pipa again would weep the bowels dry. / I think of my love — / Seven feet tall, the bearing of a heavenly god. / A captain of a thousand, in command of a hundred — / From south to north of Dongting Lake, his fame was great. / A kindly father and loving mother, / One tender while on the Li River. / And now he has abandoned me — this slight, solitary, friendless girl — / Truly I have become a single spray of late chrysanthemum braving the autumn frost. / At Shi Gong Dam, the sorrow pierces the heart; / At Huamei Pond, the wasted body nearly perished. / Through all of Xiang and Yuan, the three rivers and nine rivers, / I only hoped to catch up — to welcome the twin oars on Tao-gen and Tao-ye. / Who knew that from Chu's end to Wu's beginning the sky stretched endlessly long? / Then passing Jinling where the royal air had not fully yielded, / Looking toward Yangzhou from the lamplight at Guazhou, / Crossing the Yellow River, / Dreading to see the three-dam current raging day and night, / Through Huai, Xu, Ji, and Yan — no heart to admire the scenery. / Mercifully, all the way safe and sound I came to the imperial capital. / Only — I know not where that fickle young man has hidden. / I am Zhao Wuniang who cut her hair to search for her husband; / Do not mistake me for a common street-walker on the road to Handan.\" / As she played and sang, her voice was full of grief; it moved Pengcai to tears. He thought: \"This person truly is a woman of deep feeling, recounting her whole life's suffering — I wonder where that heartless man has gone.\" Then he heard Sun Sihui say: \"Alas, alas — the things on my body are now completely empty — how vexing! How vexing!\" He stamped his foot and sighed: \"Ha! A gentleman has no cause to remove his jade from his person; yet it has been rolled up and carried away in his bosom. From now on I shall be as in mourning without my belt-ornament and see what he can do about that!\" Yuanmao said: \"These pickpockets in the capital are truly hateful. Last year I took ten taels of silver from my father for Wei senior Pengcai to take me to the theater; at the theater gate I stumbled and someone helped me up and dusted me off. I still thought him a good man — but when I looked later, the silver was gone. When my father found out afterward, he scolded me roundly for a full day. Now you see what these dog-things do to people.\" The listeners could not help smirking inwardly. Sun Sihui said: \"'That lovely person — a true lord's desire to match.' Why do you not hasten your steps and enter?\" Yuanmao laughed: \"Not me — with ten pairs of eyes watching, how could I go in?\" Pengcai heard this and gave an involuntary laugh. Yuanmao recognized the voice as very familiar, and looked around in all directions; spotting Pengcai, he flushed crimson and pushed his way out with Sihui to greet him. Sihui said: \"Elder Brother Wei, I know that you are now a crafty three-burrow rabbit — fully installed in the public gate with a bow and formal step. You don't even bother to look in on old friends any more. Today, having unexpectedly encountered you, my heart is glad.\" Pengcai said: \"Occupied with all manner of affairs, I had been meaning to come and pay my respects. The day has gotten late and I must return to the city.\" Yuanmao said: \"How are you getting on these days in the Hua household? Are you going back into the city now?\" Pengcai said: \"I'm heading back now.\" Yuanmao said: \"We are also heading back — let's walk together.\" So they chatted along the way. Pengcai said: \"Just now, when you heard them singing, did you understand what they were singing?\" Yuanmao said: \"Not a word — I was rather taken by that plump woman; she kept smiling and beckoning at me, and I didn't dare go in and sit down.\"",
    "Sihui said: \"Splendid, splendid! Cheap in price and little work required. Tomorrow I shall take you along and give it a try, cousin. If we delay our journey, the nimble-footed may get there first, and though we repent it will be too late. As long as one finds true pleasure, why mind ten pairs of watching eyes?\" Pengcai, hearing him still mouthing his pedantic bookish phrases and talking absolute nonsense, suppressed his laughter and let it pass. At the crossroads they went their separate ways. Behind Pengcai came the rumbling of a carriage passing at speed; Pengcai quickly stepped aside, and saw that seated in the carriage was the woman who had just been playing and singing, with an old woman sitting on the carriage's running board. It went rushing past like the wind.",
    "But let us set aside Pengcai's side of the story.",
    "As for this White Chrysanthemum: she was from Wuzhou Prefecture in Guangxi, extraordinarily good-looking. She had been married to a man named Song — a shiftless fellow. Chrysanthemum was by nature good at making connections; she had come to know a military officer surnamed Zhang, a native of Huguang. The two became very intimate in Guangxi, vowing to grow old together — this had gone on for several years. Last year this Officer Zhang was sent on a duty assignment to the capital; White Chrysanthemum, being a person of feeling and loyalty, set off after him as soon as he left, taking some travel funds and a small maidservant.",
    "Somehow she took the wrong road and ended up going all the way out of Guangxi Province and into Hunan, and still had not caught up with him; she did not know how far he had gone ahead; moreover her travel money was exhausted, she knew no one in this strange place, and she was trapped with no way forward or back, so she settled in Hunan. Then she received false information that this Officer Zhang had been stationed in the capital as a company commander and could not leave the capital.",
    "So she sold some of her clothing for travel funds, boarded a convenient boat, and headed for the capital. When she arrived, Officer Zhang had long since completed his assignment and returned; as a result, Chrysanthemum found herself stranded in the capital, and had no choice but to lean on her doorway and smile for a living.",
    "The woman who had come to fetch her today was from the Tao household, an establishment keeper. This Madam Tao had three girls in her house; the best of them, known as Jade Celestial Fairy (Yu Tianxian), was a native of Yangzhou, born vivacious and coquettishly attractive. These past two days she had received a big-spending patron — none other than Xi Eleven from Guangdong. Madam Tao had investigated his background and learned that he was from a wealthy family of Hainan, with assets in the millions; his ten brothers all held posts as circuit intendants and prefects; their father was a currently serving brigade commander and the family ran a foreign trading firm. She had also learned that he was a thoroughly naive big spender, and plotted to make a large profit from him. Unfortunately, none of her girls could understand much of his speech, and Xi Eleven was moreover addicted to opium — he smoked one or two liang a day; the three girls, though they could take a few puffs of white-earth tobacco, were laid low by a few fractions of the black-earth variety, and moreover neither side's speech was very intelligible to the other.",
    "As a result, Xi Eleven was not greatly pleased. Madam Tao knew that Chrysanthemum was from Guangxi and was also very good-looking — she was sure to be able to hold his interest — so she brought her over and formally adopted her as a foster daughter. At once new clothing was found for her; she was introduced to all her foster sisters, and she and Jade Celestial Fairy became especially fond of each other. After suffering such terrible hardships, Chrysanthemum felt as if she had escaped hell — what could there be to complain about? With one heart she awaited the coming of Xi Eleven.",
    "Now, this Xi Eleven had been in the capital for less than half a year, having already spent tens of thousands of taels of silver — all dumped into a cesspool. Someone advised him to take a concubine. Being a habitual wanderer, he found respectable women of good families most disagreeable; he hunted for someone among the prostitutes, but found no one to his taste. One day Madam Tao came to invite him, saying she had a new arrival from Guangxi at her establishment. Xi Eleven, hearing she was from Guangxi, was filled with joy; he called a small page boy and had him bring the opium equipment, then, making no use of a carriage, strode off on foot in a grand manner. When he arrived at the Tao household, Madam Tao came out first to greet him and spent some time fawning and flattering with the most eager of shoulder-hunched smiles, then said: \"Come quickly and bring out Fourth Miss.\" Not long afterward, White Chrysanthemum came out, graceful and swaying, fragrant in her attire, a spring-blossom expression on her face. She came forward to meet him, and they exchanged a few words — their speech perfectly matched to each other's. Xi Eleven looked at her appearance: she was beautiful as a flower, pliant as water, sweet as honey, sticky as candy. He was enormously pleased; after a few brief questions they went into the room together. He had his page arrange the opium equipment properly, lit the lamp, and smoked and chatted. Xi Eleven was a man who took big pulls of opium; Chrysanthemum prepared his pipe, beginning from half a fen per pull and gradually building up to three fen per pull before he was satisfied. Chrysanthemum's skill in preparing opium was excellent — she could produce it neither too raw nor too well-cooked. Xi Eleven also liked to smoke the \"noodle-style\" opium: she would take the opium and twist it into a narrow rod on the needle, hold it over the flame and turn it on all four sides until it hung in a string about five inches long, place it at the pipe-bowl opening, and Xi Eleven would take a great shuā-shuā-shuā pull and draw it all in at once, then hold his mouth closed so that not a single wisp of smoke escaped — this was Xi Eleven's lifelong supreme technique. Chrysanthemum also took a few puffs, then nestled into Xi Eleven's arms and continued preparing the pipe for him. Xi Eleven smoked seven or eight qian in all — enough; his ardor surged up, and the two of them put away the lamp, closed the door, and enacted a secret drama: the butterfly's love of the flower, the mandarin ducks turned upside down, with all its manifold subtleties — beyond description. One was as fierce as a tiger bounding down from the mountain; the other was as ripe as a melon dropping from the vine. They carried on for two full hours before each was fully satisfied and content; then tidied themselves up, relit the lamp and smoked more opium, followed by drinking wine and eating food.",
    "Xi Eleven stayed there seven or eight days running; each day he spent several dozen strings of cash, and the madam was already sharpening her ax: clothing on the person, jewelry to make, furnishing the room — needless to say; and then all the girls wanting this and wanting that; even the madam herself, the hangers-on, and the general crowd — every single one was putting on their act. But Xi Eleven was by nature free and generous, never stingy.",
    "Chrysanthemum saw that Xi Eleven's powerful and vigorous manner surpassed her previous love by twice over; and knowing he was a great gentleman waiting in the capital for an official appointment, she conceived the desire to become a proper wife. Xi Eleven had originally come searching for a concubine; seeing Chrysanthemum's great beauty and her expert skills, he too wanted to buy her as a concubine. But the madam was not entirely willing: Chrysanthemum had only been there a few days, was not actually her person, and there was no purchase price to extract; she wanted to keep her in the house to earn more money — if the girl went off to make a proper marriage, would all that effort not be wasted? So she worked to stir up trouble between them: to Chrysanthemum she said Xi Eleven was a heartless man who had dozens of concubines at home; she had heard from his second brother that once a woman was brought home, she was immediately forgotten as he went off chasing new ones — a man of the new-is-exciting, old-is-discarded type. A woman absolutely must not marry such a man; don't make the wrong decision. To Xi Eleven she said that Chrysanthemum still had a husband living and was unwilling to be sold. She also said that Chrysanthemum's nature was difficult, and having grown accustomed to this way of life could not settle to propriety; if the lord wanted to take a concubine, she could guarantee to find him a perfect one — he need not take this one. But the two of them had already formed so warm a bond that despite the madam's interference, neither believed a word. Chrysanthemum told Xi Eleven her whole history in full detail, explaining that the madam had brought her over expressly to serve him; that her desire to make a proper marriage had nothing whatsoever to do with these people, and only required gifting them a few taels of silver. Xi Eleven made up his mind at once, summoned an official matchmaker, bestowed fifty taels of gold on Old Madam Tao, took Chrysanthemum away, bought a maidservant and hired an elderly female attendant. And so Chrysanthemum married Xi Eleven as a concubine, and from that point entered the proper path of life. As for what happened next — let the following chapter tell the tale."
  ],
  19: [
    "Following Zhongyu's instructions, Pengcai put them into practice: he first lavished every effort on winning Lin Shanzhi's favor, and then painstakingly cultivated the good will of the eight young pages. Shanzhi had originally been a celebrated young dan actor in the Lianjin troupe; he later joined the Dengchun troupe, and Young Master Hua, having taken a liking to him, purchased him at a high price. The eight pages who came afterward had all been trained by Shanzhi. Needless to say, this Lin Shanzhi was thoroughly schooled in music and song. Wei Pengcai was by nature a quick-witted person, and his kun-opera singing was superb; even playing and strumming, he could hold his own. Moreover, on the journey up the previous year he had traveled along with a troupe, and on the boat had managed to pick up a great many operatic texts; after arriving in the capital, with theater-going every two or three days, he had naturally added a good deal more to his repertoire.",
    "One day, Lin Shanzhi was teaching Yuling to sing an aria when Pengcai happened to wander in. Shanzhi invited him to sit while continuing the lesson. The aria in question happened to be one of Pengcai's greatest accomplishments; he began to join in from the sidelines, his five tones pure and his lips and teeth articulate, singing with such inspired mastery that Lin Shanzhi was quite astonished. From that point they became close; Shanzhi thereupon praised Pengcai to Young Master Hua morning and evening, without stint.",
    "Young Master Hua placed the most trust in Shanzhi; since Shanzhi did not praise people lightly, if he was willing to praise someone, that person must truly be fine — and the young master formed a favorable impression. The eight young pages were all natives of Suzhou and Yangzhou, so their dispositions were naturally congenial with Pengcai's. Pengcai knew how to please them: today he gave one a fan, tomorrow he gave another a fragrant sachet — always just the kind of things that delighted small children, so that they all felt this master secretary truly knew what people liked. As for the senior stewards and the office staff — he cultivated those even more thoroughly. Within a month, everyone was speaking well of him. As for Yan and Wang — needless to say. Even Zhang and Gu, though also sociable, could not match Pengcai in warm-hearted thoroughness and devoted attentiveness.",
    "One day, having learned that the young master had gone out, Pengcai invited Zhang Xiaomei to come out of the city with him. Xiaomei wanted to find Feng Zipei; the two rode together in a carriage directly to Feng Zipei's residence. This Zipei was on the closest terms with Young Master Hua, had already met Pengcai, and the two got along naturally. Feng Zipei too was the son of an official family, who had lost his father early and had accumulated some official savings; his mother doted on him and let him drift freely among performance halls and theaters, mingling with the powerful and wealthy. In time, the family's affairs gradually declined; but some good friends helped prop things up, so that he always seemed to have money at hand, his clothing was fine and fresh, and the way he combined naive charm with gentle appeal inspired a certain fondness and sympathy.",
    "That day, Zhang and Wei came out, brought a small page boy, and arrived at Zipei's gate; they had the page boy go in to enquire. He happened to be at home; they were invited inside and sat down in the study. Pengcai was calling for the first time; he observed the room — two bays facing north, the furnishings rather splendid, but the entire tabletop covered with half-read books, brushes, inkstones, curios, and all manner of things piled in helter-skelter disarray. On the walls hung xiao flutes, pipa lutes, and bows and arrows and the like. Pengcai said to Xiaomei: \"Little Feng lives like this, so why doesn't he at least tidy things up a bit?\" Xiaomei laughed: \"He probably doesn't have time to tidy things — there's no one in the world busier than he is.\" As they spoke, Zipei came out; it being the end of the fourth month, he was all in silk and gauze, looking all the more graceful and charming. Before he had cleared the entrance screen he was already preceded by laughter, calling out: \"What are you two coming for? Have you come to pay your respects to Lord Number Two?\" Pengcai laughed and was about to reply when Zhang Xiaomei stepped forward and wrapped him in a tight embrace; Zipei also embraced Xiaomei back, and they gave each other a good hug around the waist. Xiaomei said with a grin:",
    "\"Indeed, we have come to pay our respects to Lord Number Two.\" He then pressed his face close to smell Zipei's cheek, and added: \"How fragrant! Not a Lord Number Two at all — positively a little darling.\" Zipei said: \"There you go being wanton again — stirring up Lord Number Two so his heart can't bear it.\" Pengcai laughed loudly from the sidelines; the three of them romped together for a while, then sat down — and found they had nothing particular to say to each other.",
    "From outside came the sound of someone shouting: \"Is Feng Number Two at home?\" Zipei answered back: \"He's not at home.\" Pengcai recognized the voice as very familiar; then a man barged straight in, saying: \"Look at this! You're right here in your burrow and you still answer 'not at home.'\" Everyone looked up — it was Yang Meichuang, whom all knew; the group grew livelier still, and the talk ran entirely to amusements and merriment. The four deliberated: \"Are we just going to sit around chatting and call it a day? Would that not be a waste of this fine time?\" Xiaomei said: \"I was planning to watch some opera.\" Feng Zipei said: \"Pah! You're like a country bumpkin coming to the city who mistakes a bright lantern for a pig's bladder. Today is a memorial day — and you're still thinking of watching opera?\" Yang Meichuang said: \"It really is a memorial day today — let's go to a restaurant.\" The other three were all happy with that. Zipei went back inside to change his clothes, then they all walked out together and went to a wine-house.",
    "The waiters, seeing four young men and recognizing Yang and Feng, perked up immediately and knew today would be a lively table. Old Yang the Eighth said: \"What shall we eat?\" Feng Zipei said to the waiter: \"Recite the menu.\" The waiter ran through dozens of items; the four ordered five or six dishes and settled in to eat while they talked. The waiter first brought four pots of yellow wine and a table of fruit and snacks, then gradually brought out the dishes one by one. The four drank for a while, told some jokes, and then Meichuang said: \"Are we just going to do this and call it done? The waiter would look down on us — let's summon someone.\" Pengcai was most enthusiastic and said: \"Certainly — but who?\" Meichuang laughed: \"I have a lot of people in mind, and I have a taste for novelty — unlike some people who always call the same person every time. The other day I saw someone in the Lianzhu troupe called Yulin who was very good-looking; as soon as he came offstage someone was already taking him out — I imagine he's quite popular.\" Pengcai said: \"He can't be as good as Qinguan.\" Meichuang said: \"Which Qinguan?\" Pengcai recounted what he had seen of the theater visit at New Year, then added: \"This Qinguan, other than with Mei Gengxiang, gives everyone else the cold shoulder; I fear he may not come if summoned.\" Meichuang said: \"What young protégé cannot be summoned? You go and summon him today.\" Pengcai thought inwardly: \"Now that I'm at the Hua household, they must know about it — naturally they'll regard me differently from before. I'll go and summon him; if he doesn't come, I'll summon someone else.\" Meichuang then asked Xiaomei: \"And you — who will you call?\" Xiaomei said:",
    "\"I'll call Rong-guan.\" He then asked Zipei; Zipei said: \"With three already summoned, that's quite festive enough. I won't summon anyone — I'll just be a guest who drinks the sideshow wine.\" Meichuang laughed: \"You might as well count yourself as the young protégé.\" Zipei, hearing this, took a mouthful of wine and spat it straight at Meichuang's face; Meichuang dodged, but quite a bit still landed on his robe. Meichuang said: \"What need to be so agitated at a single remark — it must have hit your real sore spot.\" Everyone laughed. He took off the robe, asked for some spirits to spray it with, spread it on the railing in the eaves to dry, then laughed again: \"What a waste of that mouthful of wine — why didn't you spit it into my mouth?\" Zipei threw a handful of melon-seed shells at him; Meichuang received them without retaliating.",
    "Then the waiter came in and said: \"Qinguan and Yulin both say they're ill and can't come; Rong-guan will be here shortly.\" Pengcai had expected Qinguan not to come and took it philosophically. But Yang Meichuang was irritated: \"Odd — how can two out of three summoned fail to come? I wonder if they're really ill or just making excuses?\" Xiaomei said: \"Of course they're really ill — what excuses would they make?\" Pengcai said: \"There's also that Qiguan — also very fine; I called him several times in the first month and he always came without fail.\" Pengcai wrote a note to summon Qiguan, and Meichuang summoned Er Xi (Second Happiness). The waiter reported: \"Someone has been sent to summon Qiguan. Er Xi is over there at another table keeping a guest company; they've already eaten and are about to break up.\"",
    "The waiter informed Er Xi; before long, Er Xi came over, greeted everyone in turn, and sat down beside Meichuang. He poured a round of drinks and sent around some dishes, then asked: \"Who else is summoned for today's table?\" Meichuang said: \"Those we summoned are all sick — they couldn't come.\" Pengcai, upon seeing Er Xi, was not greatly pleased, since at the New Year banquet Er Xi had said quite a few cutting things to him. Er Xi, however, bore no grudge; and since the payment from that day had been sent over by Pengcai the very next morning without any trouble, Er Xi still thought well of him. So Er Xi asked Pengcai: \"Where is that one from before — whose surname I can't remember — the one who was looking at me sidelong? The one who had the silver stolen by Xiao Li? I don't see him around anymore.\" Pengcai said: \"I'm now living in the city; I don't have much contact with those friends anymore.\" Er Xi said: \"Where in the city?\" Pengcai said: \"The Hua household.\" Er Xi exclaimed: \"Oh! The Hua household!\" He then asked where Zhang Xiaomei lived; Xiaomei said: \"I'm in the same residence as he is.\" Er Xi said: \"I hear that at the Hua household they have opera every single day — do they have their own troupe?\" Pengcai said: \"Several troupes, in fact.\" Er Xi then went around to each person urging wine, with finger-guessing games and drinking forfeits — no end of amusements.",
    "They had been making merry for a while when still neither Rong-guan nor Qiguan had arrived. Xiaomei said: \"Strange — today being a memorial day, we can't even summon a young protégé.\" Er Xi said: \"Who else?\" Xiaomei said: \"Your troupe's Qiguan, and Rong-guan from the Lianzhu troupe.\" Er Xi said: \"Rong-guan — when I was going out I saw him heading to Sanhe Tower; he's probably not done yet.\" Meichuang said: \"That Yulin in your troupe — is he really sick?\" Er Xi said: \"Yulin! Don't even bring it up — he and Qiguan both had a terrible incident the day before yesterday; it nearly cost someone their life. Their teacher is still insisting on pressing charges. Qiguan can't come today either.\" Everyone asked what had happened. Er Xi said: \"It's quite a story — let me have a couple more cups first.\" Everyone drained a few more cups. Pengcai, hearing that Qiguan had been involved in an incident, asked Er Xi again: \"Just tell us — let everyone hear.\" Er Xi said: \"Are you acquainted with a certain Cantonese gentleman called Xi Eleven?\" The three said they were not; Feng Zipei said: \"I have met this man, but we are not on familiar terms — just say what you have to say.\" Er Xi said: \"This Lord Xi is in the capital as a candidate for office; I heard he brought several tens of thousands of taels of silver with him and wanted to purchase a large post. Somehow it all got used up without reaching the right amount, so he only managed to purchase a district magistracy. This man is truly a lavish spender: when he first came to the capital he got to know Chunlan of the Dengchun troupe, and immediately installed Chunlan in his rooms every day — clothing, gold bracelets, fine carriages, and so on goes without saying. Chunlan has the most stage roles of anyone; for each of Chunlan's performances Xi Eleven had a dozen or so sets of stage costumes made, with gold hairpieces — the total value must be around ten thousand taels. Chunlan's teacher would deliberately call Chunlan back to vex and squeeze Xi Eleven; in drips and drabs, still more was spent. Later, to buy out Chunlan's apprenticeship contract, another five thousand strings of cash were spent; and then Chunlan went to live with him — smoking opium together on the same kang, eating at the same table. For instance, if a dish tasted too salty or too bland to Chunlan, he would smash the whole bowl. A lined fur coat costing several hundred strings of cash — if Chunlan said 'the fur trim is poorly done, I don't want it,' Xi Eleven would look and agree it was not good, and with one hand tear it to shreds and order a new one made. This kind of eccentric spite might be excusable as a personal flaw, but having been so intimate with Chunlan, he should not have gone after others. Yet he paid no heed — anyone he fancied, regardless of whether the other person was willing, he simply forced the issue.\" Everyone was listening in perfect silence. Pengcai said: \"I asked you about Yulin and Qiguan's business, and you just keep going on about this naive spendthrift.\" Er Xi laughed: \"Let me tell it in order — in any case it's better than an opera. Now, this man had many ways of luring people. He is from Jiayingzhou, so he had those Western-style methods. His way of enticing people was first to move their hearts with money — though there are also those who are not attracted by money but by personal quality. This Lord Xi's appearance was rough and coarse — very tall and broad, like a military officer — and his speech was also dull. He also smoked opium — an ounce a day — and his face was a greenish-black.\" Meichuang said: \"Get to it — what Western-style methods?\" Er Xi said: \"He had a wooden barrel, with a narrow mouth and a wide bottom, lacquered in Western style with gilt designs. Inside it went ding-ding-dang-dang, rather like the sound of a clock.",
    "\"On top was a lid; inside was a layer of board, and under the board a crossbar; on the outside there was a brass-lock door — you couldn't see anything from outside. Whenever he had his eye on someone and they were being uncooperative, he would lure them into his inner room to look at the barrel. The person, hearing the sound inside, would naturally lean over the barrel to peer in; then Xi Eleven would take some objects — perhaps gold or silver ingots, or jade and kingfisher-feather trinkets, all valuable things — and throw them into the barrel, saying, 'If you can fish them out, they're yours.' The person, of course, not knowing the trick, would reach a hand down. Now, the board in the middle had two holes — a hole just large enough for one hand, no more; so not finding anything, one would reach the other hand in too. Then he would take the key and turn it in the lock door, and both hands could no longer be withdrawn. The barrel was also too heavy to lift; there you were, bent double over it. He would then do as he pleased whether you were willing or not — only when his satisfaction was complete would he release you. Calling out was useless — it had already happened. Once released, there was nothing to be done about it. The savvy ones knew to demand more things from him; there were also those who didn't know better and made a scene — he would turn on them and accuse them of extortion, beat and scold them, and even have them sent to the ward office for processing. Most of the ward officials were in league with him; once delivered, the person was locked up and subjected to all manner of humiliation, and the teacher would have to pay cash to get them out — at minimum a hundred or so strings. Such was Xi Eleven's manner of operating. Now, you ask about Yulin and Qiguan — this was the same Xi Eleven. The first time was at Yulin's place for a meal and drinks. Yulin is an honest, gentle sort — not skilled at flattery. But Xi Eleven took a fancy to him and gave him a set of clothing, a pair of bracelets, and forty strings of cash for his teacher — which worked him into a fever. The second time he invited Yulin alone, without many other guests, and gave Yulin another hundred strings of cash. Yulin couldn't stand the way Xi Eleven looked and always acted cool toward him, which made Xi Eleven annoyed. For the third occasion, his teacher organized many young protégés and invited Yulin again — but this time Yulin simply didn't come. His teacher, still seeing Xi Eleven as a big catch, forced Yulin to go and pay his respects. Xi Eleven then went even further: he apparently had it all planned — he kept Yulin for dinner, poured several cups of wine into him, and then tried to trick him into looking at the barrel. But somehow Yulin had heard about the barrel trick beforehand and refused to look. Having no recourse, Xi Eleven tried to assault him by brute force. Having the advantage of strength, he pinned Yulin down; Yulin refused and wept and screamed. His attendant heard it, and tried to come in to look; but Xi Eleven's people wouldn't let him in. He forced his way in regardless and saw Yulin pinned down with his trousers already pulled off; only the sight of someone entering made Xi Eleven release him, and he had to claim it was only playful teasing — the boy didn't know how to take a joke. Yulin rushed out, straightening his clothes as he went, weeping and cursing; the attendant also made a scene in the gatehouse. Xi Eleven wanted to beat Yulin but couldn't catch up, so in a fury he sent him to the ward office — and that might have been the end of it. But as true ill-luck would have it, more trouble was yet to come. That evening he also summoned Qiguan. You all know Qiguan's temperament — how could he possibly comply? Xi Eleven tried to lure him into looking at the barrel; Qiguan, not knowing about it, fell for the trick and put both hands in — he could not withdraw them; and Xi Eleven tried to use the same method again and started pulling at Qiguan's undergarments. Qiguan understood what was happening and let fly with his leg, landing squarely on that particular organ — Xi Eleven nearly died of pain and sank down in a crouch.\" At this, Zhang and Wei burst into laughter and said: \"Served him right! Served him right! Such a thing must have its heaven-sent retribution. More wine — let's all raise a cup to celebrate.\" Feng Zipei said nothing; Yang Meichuang said:",
    "\"Get on with it.\" Er Xi drank some wine and continued: \"Qiguan was also in a terrible state — his hands couldn't be withdrawn, and he became furious; ignoring the pain, he wrenched and twisted with all his strength until the mechanism was broken. Qiguan's two hands were scraped raw, dripping blood; he too came out weeping and cursing. Xi Eleven, his own vital part in agony, retreated to hide. Qiguan went back and told his teacher; and since he is close to Yuan Baozhu, he also told Baozhu. Baozhu was furious and went into Yiyuan to tell Lord Xu. Lord Xu was outraged and said: 'How can the world contain such a creature — that anyone would tolerate him behaving like this? This is beyond endurance!' He then learned of Yulin's situation as well, and immediately sent someone to the ward office to have Yulin released overnight. At the same time he considered reporting the matter to the Metropolitan Circuit Censor, intending to have Xi Eleven's barrel confiscated and Xi Eleven prosecuted. Lord Xu is a straightforward and upright person; his words were spoken without any attempt at concealment, and somehow word leaked out. Xi Eleven, afraid of a public scandal, and moreover having run out of money, gave up his debts on the western account, rushed to the Board of Personnel and paid to have himself listed as unable to continue due to insufficient travel funds — and left the city. I hear he went to Tianjin; he'll probably hide there for a while and then come back. So Yulin is furious and unwell, and Qiguan's hands are not yet healed — how could he possibly come out? That's the whole story — now you all drink a big cup. My tongue is quite dry.\"",
    "This tale set everyone laughing and marveling at the strangeness of it. Feng Zipei said: \"What a vile, despicable creature — he doesn't care who anyone is; if he sees a young good-looking person he thinks they're fair game. And he doesn't even look at himself.\" Meichuang laughed: \"You're so indignant — can it be that you've already had a look at his precious barrel?\" Zipei spat at Meichuang twice. Meichuang said: \"Can they make that kind of barrel here in the capital, or not?\" Xiaomei laughed: \"Are you thinking of copying the design?\" Meichuang gave a little laugh. Pengcai laughed and said to Er Xi: \"You've described it so clearly — you must have had a look at the barrel yourself.\" Er Xi's face reddened, and with a sideways glance he reached over to pinch Pengcai's mouth. Meichuang said: \"He probably doesn't need to use the barrel.\" Er Xi then gave Meichuang two pinches and said: \"Those of us who work in this trade — if you have money, everything is fine; why go to all that bother with such theatrics? It's a pity they can't read feng shui the way you can — that's why they had to suffer like that.\"",
    "Having said this, Er Xi laughed himself. Pengcai thought privately: \"Who would have expected that Qinguan and Qiguan, even as performers, should be so proud and dignified — so steadfast in their principles. That is something to marvel at.\" He then asked Er Xi who exactly this Xi Eleven was — how he could behave so lawlessly and still have so much money. Er Xi said: \"I heard from Chunlan that he too is the son of a well-born family — his grandfather served as a Provincial Administration Commissioner, and his father is currently serving as a Brigade Commander; his family runs a foreign trading firm.\" Pengcai said: \"What about Chunlan now?\" Er Xi said: \"Went out with him.\" The group then talked and joked some more, drank another round. Seeing that the day was growing late, Xiaomei and Pengcai both needed to return to the city and settled the bill. Meichuang arranged with Er Xi to settle the payment the next day. Meichuang declined to accompany Pengcai and the others into the city — since he lived outside the city, he went back to Zipei's place, and the two of them had a smoke of opium together; then Meichuang dragged Zipei off to Jade Celestial Fairy's establishment in Vermilion Cosmetics Lane.",
    "Now let us speak of Pan Qiguan: since being tricked and humiliated by Huifang, he had been genuinely vexed, wishing to settle scores with Huifang but fearing his wide connections and numerous supporters. At the same time his lascivious urge had not been extinguished and he still hoped to actually get what he wanted. He was also smarting over the two hundred strings of cash, and had begun to suspect that Zhang Zhongyu had colluded with Huifang to make a fool of him, so he made veiled, insinuating remarks to Zhongyu. Zhongyu, having been unjustly blamed, truly had nowhere to air his grievance, and came to resent Pan Qiguan. \"Since he suspects me anyway, I might as well dig a proper pit for him — I'll scheme with Huifang to deal with him.\" Pan Qiguan then had to go to Baoding to inspect some fabric shops he owned there and was away for two months before returning. Idle with nothing to do, he had a series of quarrels with his wife and was suffering from pent-up frustration with no way to relieve it. He thought again of going to Huifang's place for amusement, but this time without Zhang Zhongyu — he came alone.",
    "It was already evening that day; as chance would have it, he arrived at Huifang's gate at the very moment Huifang was returning from Chunhang's place. Huifang, seeing it was Pan Qiguan, was inwardly startled but had no choice — he jumped down from his carriage and invited the Third Master Pan inside. Pan Qiguan seized Huifang's hand and puffed along into the inner room, where they sat down in the reception room. Huifang said: \"Third Master Pan — I haven't seen you for days. Where have you been making your fortune? You rarely honor us with a visit. I recall that the other day, because the young master Hua was staying outside the city, I was summoned there and was truly remiss in attending to you — please don't hold it against me. We have plenty of time ahead of us to be friends.\" Pan Qiguan, seeing Huifang so warm and gracious, felt half his former indignation dissolve, and said slowly: \"What have I come here for — I know perfectly well you look down on me. Two hundred strings of cash, and all I got was old Zhang Number Two spitting a mouthful of wine in my face. The rabbit hides in its burrow while the wildcat can only drool and dream.\" Huifang heard these words and was quite annoyed, but had to put on a smile and say: \"What interesting things you say. So what are we going to do tonight? Let us find somewhere to sit together.\" Pan Qiguan said: \"What other place is there to look for? Right here is very comfortable. But I have sworn an oath and given up drinking — today I won't have a single drop.\" Huifang heard this and grew more anxious still, thinking: today is truly bad — here he is alone, not even willing to drink, and he certainly won't be willing to leave. If I make some excuse to go, he probably won't let me. She turned it over and over in her mind, and a flush gradually spread across her face. After a long silent pause she made up her mind defiantly: \"I might as well let him stay — if I were afraid of him, I wouldn't be called Su Huifang.\" She said: \"Third Master, if you won't drink wine, at least you'll eat dinner.\" Pan Qiguan nodded; Huifang personally went to the kitchen for a while, then brought out the meal: three meat dishes, three vegetable dishes, a bowl of Shaoxing soup, and a pot of yellow wine.",
    "Huifang said: \"Even if you've given up wine, since you've come to my place you must keep up appearances.\" With a smiling face, she took up a large jade cup, filled it to the brim, and presented it with both hands. Pan Qiguan had not actually given up drinking — he simply feared wine would impair his plans. Seeing Huifang's manner now, he could not help grinning and saying: \"All right — finish this whole pot, no refills.\" Huifang paid no attention to his conditions; the two drank together, also eating some boiled dumplings and similar fare. Pan Qiguan was becoming tipsy; as the cups went back and forth and another pot was added, he gazed at Huifang's peach-blossom cheeks and autumn-water eyes — glances full of allure, a hundred seductive expressions — which revived all Pan Qiguan's old nature. He sighed: \"You little creature, you'll truly be the death of me — what are two hundred strings of cash? You have no need to do me such harm! Son — as long as you show me just a little heart, there's nothing I won't agree to.\" Huifang forced a smile and said: \"Third Master — I don't understand. What do you mean, agree or not agree?\" Pan Qiguan said: \"As long as you have heart for me, whatever you want I'll agree to.\" Huifang said with a laugh: \"You may not really be willing — what I want, what I want is a silver exchange house (yin hao). You yourself said so before.\" Pan Qiguan said: \"I have three silver houses; and I'm already forty-eight years old, still with no sons — to give you one is no great matter. And what will you give me?\" Huifang said nothing. Pan Qiguan said: \"Why have you gone quiet again? It's just the two of us — no outsiders here. Is there anything that can't be said?\" Huifang continued to give that not-quite-smiling, not-quite-unsmiling expression and said nothing. Pan Qiguan moved closer and pulled Huifang into his embrace; with his sticky, syrup-soaked face, he tried to press it against those fragrant, powder-warm cheeks. Huifang interposed a hand lightly and softly said: \"You're being too impossible — let go, and then I'll talk.\" Pan Qiguan rubbed his face back and forth on the back of Huifang's hand, panting: \"Good boy, good darling — just say it.\" Huifang put on an expression of feigned annoyance: \"Third Master, with you being so impatient, I simply won't say it now.\" Pan Qiguan had no choice but to release his hold. Huifang's hand was wet with saliva; she wiped it with a handkerchief and stood up, saying with composure: \"Third Master Pan, I am no fool — do you think I can't see through what's on your mind? But since I am a performer, I cannot pretend to speak of purity and cleanliness. Still, I am only eighteen years old this year and I have just completed my apprenticeship; out there in the world, I ask you to leave me some dignity and let people regard me as a person — please don't harass me this way. If I have heart for you, that should be enough — don't let people see through it. Don't treat me like the disciples of a barber's shed. Third Master, you think I spent two hundred strings of your cash and you begrudge it — well, if you want it back, I can repay it.\" Pan Qiguan said: \"Good boy — who wants you to repay money? Don't blame me: I've been thinking about this for a full six months, and you won't let me feel just a little ease. If you truly have heart for me, that's fine — but I still fear you're just taking me for a fool again. If you try to trick me again, I won't stand for it. But whatever you say, I'll go along with it.\"",
    "Huifang laughed again: \"I just said, Third Master is used to frequenting the barber's sheds — you're treating my place as just the same kind of thing. I heard from Zhang Zhongyu that Third Master Pan is most generous: if he sets his heart on someone, not only three or five hundred, even one or two thousand strings he'll spend freely. How is it that Third Master also takes a liking to me, yet after spending a mere two hundred strings here you're already trying to recoup your investment? As for two hundred strings, not only would Third Master not look twice at it, even I, surnamed Su, don't consider it anything at all. Could it be that Third Master, for a cup of wine and a song, wouldn't even tip a hundred or so strings? Like those small-time operators who call a young protégé for a whole day and give four or five strings of Beijing cash? Let me tell you this: as long as you can truly show heart, I guarantee I won't let you down. But don't forget me — don't treat me as a lowly person, so that once you've had your way you drop me and go chasing someone else. Then don't blame me.\" Pan Qiguan, having been worked over by Huifang's speech, was left with nothing to say. Hearing line after line of apparent agreement, yet with the implied sense of wanting more money and that two hundred strings was too little. And then he thought again: \"Such a celebrated young protégé — naturally doesn't come easily to hand.\" He said to Huifang: \"If you truly won't let me down, I can put my mind at ease. But words are no guarantee — later I fear you'll change your tune again.\" Huifang laughed coldly: \"You mistrust me a thousand times and ten thousand times — what, do you want me to write you a contract?\"",
    "At this moment Pan Qiguan's lascivious heart was blazing; and yet he also wanted to appear generous, so he couldn't resort to brute force. Thinking it over, the only recourse was to win Huifang over with more money. He said: \"I know you're a free-spending young protégé with a big style, always needing cash. Starting today, whenever you're short of money, just come to my shop and take what you need.\" Huifang said: \"How could I go there? We can't let Third Mistress find out — she'd give you such a scolding that you'd suffer all over again.\" Pan Qiguan laughed: \"Nonsense — tell me honestly: are you actually short of money or not?\" Huifang thought: \"This creature has been cut short by me and still doesn't understand — he still imagines he can buy me with money. I might as well milk this muddled fool for some — it can serve as lamp-oil money for Tian darling.\" With a smile she said: \"Money? Of course I want money — it's just awkward to say so. I fear Third Master would suspect that I'm always taking money and giving nothing in return — spending a great deal and getting nothing.\" As she spoke, she looked down at the kingfisher-jade bracelet on her own wrist, then took it off and showed it to Pan Qiguan: \"Tell me — is this jade any good?\" Pan Qiguan looked: it was clear as water and entirely green in color. He praised it: \"Fine kingfisher-jade — rarely seen in the city. It must be Yunnan-origin jade.\" Huifang said: \"It was a gift from Lord Xu at Yiyuan — one of four identical pieces he gave to four people; I received one. I heard it was bought in Guangdong; one piece was priced at one foreign silver dollar.\" Pan Qiguan clicked his tongue: \"More expensive than gold — ten liang of gold weighs as much but is worth only two hundred silver.\" Huifang said: \"Fine as it is, it's a pity there's no gold piece to match it.\" As she spoke, her eyes kept glancing at a heavy gold bangle on Pan Qiguan's wrist. Pan Qiguan understood; he wanted to give it to her, but it weighed ten liang and was worth two hundred silver, and his heart ached to part with it; yet if he didn't give it, he feared she would look down on him — so he said nothing.",
    "He raised his arm and studied the bracelet for a while, then said to Huifang: \"Pair it with this one and it would look perfect — if you want it, take it.\" He kept raising his arm but made no move to remove it. Huifang moved close beside him, thanked him, and began to take the bracelet off his wrist; the moment it was slipped onto Huifang's own hand, Pan Qiguan grabbed her around the waist, murmuring endless endearments — \"my heart, my darling\" — nuzzling and sniffing at her face incessantly, and then began groping and pawing. This time Huifang was truly in a difficult position; saying anything more would be useless, as Pan Qiguan was past listening. He had clearly resolved not to leave empty-handed today; and having parted with the gold bracelet, he felt his face was quite bright and shining with it. Huifang could only put on a smiling expression; noticing a small ivory comb hanging from his lapel, she took it and began combing his beard. At this critical moment, they suddenly heard from outside someone calling out: \"Is Huifang at home?\" Then another voice: \"The old father has come!\" There seemed to be the sound of many footsteps. Huifang hurriedly broke free and said: \"Something's wrong — the ward official is here to do his nightly inspection!\" Pan Qiguan was a wealthy merchant; at the words \"ward official's nightly inspection\" he was instantly agitated and looked for somewhere to hide. Huifang said: \"There's nowhere to hide — you'd better just go now, rather than running into them and being questioned up and down, which would look quite bad.\" Pan Qiguan had no choice; just at the moment when he had gotten his hands on something, he was scattered away again. He could only slink out through the dark and make a dash for the main gate. As for who the actual caller was — let the following chapter tell the tale."
  ],
  20: [
    "The previous chapter told how Pan Qiguan had Huifang cornered at the crucial moment when someone suddenly came shouting, and Huifang feigned alarm and cried: \"Dreadful — it's the ward officials come to do their inspection!\" Pan Qiguan was a wealthy man of timid nature, naturally afraid of causing trouble, and had no choice but to slink away.",
    "In fact, when Huifang had gone to the kitchen earlier, he had calculated that Pan Qiguan would certainly not let him off tonight, and so had instructed the household servants to pretend to be ward officials conducting the nightly inspection, and had also brought in two actual ward constables; at the moment when Pan Qiguan's harassment became intolerable, they were to come in shouting. Knowing that Pan Qiguan's lust was great but his nerve small, the scheme worked perfectly and he left tricked once more. Though she had obtained his gold bracelet, Huifang was still genuinely troubled in her heart, fearing he would come back the next day. The only recourse was to move to Chunhang's lodgings and hide for a few days, then see. Pan Qiguan went home in low spirits; fortunately he was afraid of his wife and dared not cause scenes openly outside the home — otherwise, even clever as Huifang was, it might have been hard to hold him off. Today had once more come to nothing; the only plan was to gradually win her over with more money and buy her heart around.",
    "This chapter now turns to speak of several men of elegant tastes engaged in an affair of elegant taste. The company of celebrated men had by now gradually thinned. Since Ziyu's one meeting with Qinyan at Yiyuan, they had never managed to see each other again.",
    "Qinyan's illness came and went; he was not appearing in the troupe's productions, and only occasionally, forcing himself despite illness, would he go to Yiyuan for a visit.",
    "Meanwhile Ziyu's own illness had also arisen from melancholy and worry; sometimes when he went to Yiyuan, Qinyan happened not to have come; sometimes when he went to Qinyan's lodgings, there was always some inconvenience — either his teacher Changqing was entertaining guests, or someone was sitting there. He also could not easily go to Sulan's again; Ziyu felt utterly helpless and could only mourn the grudging lot of fate. Qinyan, at home, did not know how many times Ziyu had come by; and hearing that Ziyu was ill, he felt all the more heartsick — yet since he had never once called at the Mei residence, it was awkward for him to go on his own initiative. Thus a deep and tender feeling of admiration and longing had nowhere to be eased; all he could do was sigh short sighs and long sighs, and let it haunt his dreams. You may wonder, reader, why when Ziyu went to find Qinyan, his teacher never tried to bring them together. First, Ziyu was only an occasional visitor — not one of those who regularly kept company outside — and so Changqing did not know him well, and not knowing what position Ziyu held, took him for no more than a young student with no great usefulness. Second, Ziyu had not spent a single cash on Qinyan. The spiritual sympathy between Ziyu and Qinyan being of a purely ideal and heartfelt kind, neither of them had thought about this dimension. Changqing, on the other hand, thought only about money and not at all about quality of person. That is simply how those of the inferior dan-actor class are — such was Changqing's nature, unchanging from beginning to end.",
    "Let us speak of Ziyu: he was at home recuperating from his illness and not going out at all. Gao Pin had been invited by the prefect of Hejian, Lord Hu, to assist in compiling a local gazetteer. Liu Wenze's mother-in-law had been missing him and had come to fetch him along with his wife née Wu to the office of the Viceroy of Zhili. So three of the group were gone; only Ziyun, Cixian, Nanxiang, Zhongqing, Chunhang, and Wang Xun — six people — continued to meet from time to time.",
    "One day, Ziyun and Cixian invited the celebrated gentlemen to the garden to view the dragon boat and enjoy the pomegranate blossoms. This day was the first of the fifth month, which happened also to be the Intendant-General Wang's birthday; though no formal celebration was held, a number of close friends, relatives, and colleagues came to offer their congratulations, and indoors there were also ladies — such as Lady Yan from the Mei household and Madam Lu from the Sun household — so it was quite festive. Wang Xun and Zhongqing were thus unable to attend the Yiyuan appointment. On learning of this, Ziyun and Cixian also went to offer birthday congratulations; there they happened to find Nanxiang and Chunhang both present, so they invited them to come back with them. Zhongqing and Wang Xun said that if the guests dispersed early, they would also come to keep the appointment.",
    "\"But don't wait for us — we may be early or late.\" Cixian and the others agreed and returned to Yiyuan. Coming together to the foot of the steep rock face at the garden's entrance, Ziyun invited everyone to change out of their formal attire. He also said: \"The day is very hot and the red sun beats down on people; moreover the dragon boat is at the Chanting-Autumn Water Pavilion, and the pomegranate blossoms are at Little Red Citadel — both are quite far from here. Better to ride over.\" The servants had already prepared horses in advance and brought them forward; the four mounted. From below the steep rock face they turned left, going up and down over a winding and twisting path along a small sheep-track of blue stone, with old vines brushing their heads and fragrant grasses catching their clothing. When the mountain path was done, they followed the enclosure wall; on the other side was the rippling surface of the pond, red and green reflected in the water, with a short red railing running along the embankment, slender bamboo and drooping willows, and assorted flowers covering the trees in abundance, orioles flying and calling here and there — enough to wash away all worldly care. Less than half a li further, another mass of towering stones had been piled into a high hill over ten zhang in height — like a single peak of Luofu overlooking the curve of the sea — blocking the way ahead.",
    "Ziyun invited the guests to dismount; they walked up stone steps from the foot of the hill, over thirty tiers, to a small pavilion with a stone table and stone benches inside, called the \"Misty Void Pavilion\" (缥缈亭). Looking across, several dozen old pines, their dark color rising to the sky, cut off the view; at their tips one could just make out a glimmer of green tiles and a corner of a vermilion tower. Here one felt a fine breeze drifting and the water and stones cool and clean — a floating sensation as of rising above the void. Chunhang said: \"How wondrous and profound! Even if a literary imagination were to come here, even the Incense Burner Peak of Mount Lu would offer nothing superior.\" Nanxiang said: \"The earlier view resembled Wang Lutai's style; this reminds one of Xiao Chizhu — secluded and deep without being narrow or precipitous.\" Ziyun said: \"Both were designed by Jingyi's hand; when laying out the arrangements, the plan went through several revisions.\" Cixian said: \"Those several old pines are really what makes it — without them, one glance would exhaust the entire view.\" Chunhang said: \"One can only wonder how much landscape lies in Master Jingyi's imagination — truly a divine hand that commands mountains and rivers. Ni Yunlin and Xu Qingteng would certainly want to take him by the arm into the woods.\" Cixian could only respond with a few modest disclaimers. The four rested briefly, then descended the stone steps. On the side was a two-story loft of five bays, arranged at varying heights — neither quite a tower nor quite a pavilion — with painted beams soaring in the clouds and pearl curtains rolled up against the rain; a different kind of spectacle altogether. Beyond the railing outside the windows lay a square pond of about ten mu, its surface covered in overlapping lotus leaves, half of them already grown into canopies. In the center was a six-curve red bridge, angled and slanted, connecting a row of a dozen or so rooms and pavilions on the opposite side. To the right were moored several small painted boats, all with brocade cables, ivory-white sides, and orchid oars of cassia-wood. Cixian said: \"That over there is the Chanting-Autumn Water Pavilion (吟秋水榭).\" Looking again at the water pavilion, it was three stories high; on the left ran an unbroken line of willows drooping to the water's surface, connecting to the bamboo groves and long woods of the opposite bank, the two shores seeming to want to meet.",
    "Ziyun asked the guests to hold back and not cross the bridge yet, but first to enter this loft. It was a neat set of three central bays, with curtains strung from fine copper wire, water-polished nanmu carved railings, and the furnishings inside of uncommon refinement — precious tripods and jade-stone zithers, jeweled tables and marble desks beyond enumeration. By the railing was placed an antique bronze water-clock, with several bamboo arrows inserted in it; suspended from the center was a plaque reading: \"A Studio of Gathering Clouds and Exchanging Rain\" (停云叙雨之斋). Beside it was a couplet reading: \"Prostrating before the rock, there are times one dons formal robes and hat; / Looking at the clouds, everywhere one becomes a celestial immortal.\" The signature read: Huaguang Suxiu. Nanxiang exclaimed in surprise: \"This is Young Master Hua's calligraphy — I had no idea his literary arts were like this.\" Ziyun said: \"Young Master Hua has exceptionally high natural ability — his effort has only been somewhat shallow, which is also due to being misled by his position and circumstances. In terms of calligraphy, painting, poetry, and lyrics — he runs rather counter to what one might expect from his station.\" Chunhang said: \"If one judged only by what circulates in common gossip, one would nearly miss this person entirely. From this couplet alone one sees the refinement of his mind; from this calligraphy alone one sees the gallantry of his spirit.\" As they were speaking, two flower-decked boats appeared in the distance, gliding out from the water pavilion — white hulls and green curtains still separated by the red bridge and green willows, the lazy creak of soft oars, and the graceful tune of a lotus-picking song. The water bright as a mirror, pavilions reflected in the water, swallows skimming low, fish blowing at the surface — and in an instant the boats had passed the red bridge and drawn slowly, slowly in to moor. One could now see Wang Lanbao with his silk robe hem lifted, his pigtail wound up, a pomegranate blossom tucked sideways at his temple, holding a small purple-bamboo pole, punting and at the same time driving away the domesticated ducks and wild ducks, which startled the mandarin ducks and water birds into a scatter of flight. Then a white egret came swooping straight at the railing, and reaching the eaves with one tilt of its wings, had already flown up to the rocky ridge.",
    "Cixian laughed: \"The proverb about 'catching the duck and startling the mandarin ducks' — today one sees it in action.\" While everyone was watching with interest, they saw figures stepping out of the boats like blossoming flowers: one boat held Baozhu and Shufang, the other Huifang and Sulan — five people in all. The boatmen moored the craft against the railing; Nanxiang said: \"The hibiscus has not yet opened, and the water pavilion lacks a certain brilliance. With all this company of flowers making the crossing, it will no longer be desolate. Xiang Consorts and Luo Goddesses sporting on the river's edge — I imagine Duxiang-xiong would receive them with his jade pendant offering.\" Everyone laughed. All the young dan actors came up and made their greetings all around. Cixian said: \"Look at the way Jingfang's narrow-sleeve movement stops and starts with an ease and flow — it really brings out an air of free and graceful charm. Zhujun's praising words — 'Gliding like a startled wild goose, swaying like a wandering dragon' — one feels truly captures the essence.\" Nanxiang said: \"Jingfang's free-spirited ease, Meixiang's lively wit, Yaoqing's soft grace, Shouxiang's prettily quiet refinement, Xiangwan's rich elegance — all are celestial immortals become human. As for their artistry — Zhao Feiyan dancing on the palm, Zhang Jingwan singing within the curtains — these could perhaps give some idea of it.\" Ziyun invited the guests onto the boats; Nanxiang and the others stepped aboard. The prow was carved with a pair of mandarin ducks neck to neck; the boat's body was of crabapple-pear wood, with short red railings on both sides, glass windows running the length of the interior, and on the canopy a great rolled pavilion of green clay-dyed cloth with scattered flowers, with painted-flower silk in white hanging down from both sides. Inside were two cabins; the floor was laid with fine white velvet carpet; the aft section also had long windows; in the center was a bed-platform with Hu-style rattan chairs on each side interspersed with tea tables; a round table in the center could seat five or six people. The second, slightly smaller boat was for the attendants. By now Wang Lanbao had already changed his clothes and was sitting there quietly and decorously. Baozhu said to Nanxiang: \"Did you call at Lord Wang's this morning?\" Before Nanxiang could answer, Ziyun said: \"I invited them from Wang's residence directly.\"",
    "So everyone chatted and talked, looking at the garden scenery along the way. In several places soaring lofts rose to the clouds, carved ridgepoles overlooking the ground below; in several places towering crags jutted out starkly, with ancient trees and gnarled branches. They could also see, to the northwest, a long gallery that was the Peach Grove (Taohu); next to it was the Apricot Village (Xinglun); to the due north, looking through the bamboo grove, was the Pear Courtyard (Liyuan), behind which was the Peony Fragrant Kingdom (Mudan Xiangguo); to the northeast was a stretch of delicate and ingenious rock-work, below which were thousands of trees in green shade, with golden globes — the plum fruits hanging thick, half green and half yellow — covering the Plum Vale (Mei Yan) so it could not be clearly seen. The opposite shore was thickly overgrown with trees and rocks; how many more pavilions and courts it concealed one could not know. Chunhang asked Nanxiang: \"How many parts of this garden have you toured so far?\" Nanxiang said: \"I've been here many times, but I've never actually toured it properly. A drinking session takes the whole day — when would one find time to stroll about? I've been to perhaps seven or eight places.\" Baozhu said: \"I have toured it completely with Shouxiang.\" Huifang said: \"I haven't been to Osmanthus Ridge, Chrysanthemum Patch, or Orchid Path; all the rest I've seen.\"",
    "Sulan said: \"Osmanthus Ridge is in front of the front hill; Orchid Path and Chrysanthemum Patch are behind the back hill. You cross the ravine into a large open space where there is a village-style compound — that's the Chrysanthemum Patch. Orchid Path is on the hillside, going from the foot of the hill up to the halfway point, with high and low galleries and winding paths — a most delightful place to explore. Beyond Chrysanthemum Patch there is also a Rice Farm, with shadoofs drawing water, looking like a genuine village — fishing nets, crab weirs, everything. There are also two craneenclosures and a deer pen nearby.\"",
    "As they finished speaking, the boat had traveled over half a li to a bend, and the pond opened out into a spacious expanse. The Chanting-Autumn Water Pavilion was built out in the water, surrounded on all four sides by the pond, standing three stories tall. The first story had twelve bays arranged in a hexagonal pattern, with windows open on every face — purely glass-inlaid carved windows — partitioned into six sections. Each section was further divided into yin-yang, bright-and-dim arrangements, making twelve subdivisions in all, each varying in shape — square, round, flat, and angled — each with its own setting. The furnishings inside were beyond description. Looking from one room through to the next, only a pane of glass separated them, yet to actually get from one to the other required winding through several turns. The company roamed about this first story for quite a long while. Ziyun said: \"The guests must be hungry by now; it is nearly noon — shall we be seated?\" Four small pages were seen carrying in four gold-lacquered trays with several bowls of apricot-kernel porridge, which were distributed to each person. Chunhang said: \"Why not go up to the upper two stories and then come back to sit?\" So they turned up the stairway to the second story, which was somewhat smaller — four-sided in design, with an open corridor running around it with railings on all sides, and carved windows partitioning it into eight sections, with antique vessels and utensils of equal refinement. Looking northeast at the willow shade, one could see the dragon boat moored there — over three zhang in height; the hull was carved and painted in the form of a green dragon, with five or six tiers of framework built in the center, made entirely of five-colored silk, brocade, velvet, and clay, fashioned into parasols, canopies, and pennants — embroidered with scattered-thread, flat-gold, and knotted-stitch flowers of every variety, set off with peacock-gilded parasols, pearl parasols, and parasols threaded from silver needles. In the center were constructed paper-cut towers and pavilions, royal palaces and Buddhist temples, adorned with scenes from famous historical sites. Every figure inside moved by pulleys — the mechanical ingenuity was extraordinary. Layer upon layer of construction, a blaze of brocade and cloud, glorious as bright flowers and blazing flames. Atop it all stood a constructed golden peacock; the boat's bottom was weighted with stones; twenty-four rowers on both sides propelled it, with a band of eight musical tones inside — drums, gongs, strings, and winds, both the coarse ten-beat and the refined varieties. This design had been seen by Cixian in Jiangsu and drawn in a sketch from which artisans had been engaged to build it. Chunhang had come from the south and had also seen something like it before; he said: \"Truly magnificently made — even the dragon boats of Changzhou Prefecture, the finest in the entire province, are no better than this.\"",
    "They then all went up to the third story, which was three-sided in plan, with an outer corridor on three sides as well, the interior partitioned into six sections. Here all the windows, storage units, and doors were a uniform fragrant nanmu wood, exceedingly old and simple in style — even more refined and tranquil than below. The elevation being higher, the atmosphere was cooler and more refreshing; leaning on the railing and looking out, eight or nine tenths of the entire garden of Yiyuan could be taken in at a glance, only the shaded side of the hills remaining out of view. One felt only layer upon layer of pavilions and towers, trees and flowers spread in gentle profusion, fragrant grass like a green carpet laid flat, clear springs flowing like quicksilver, water winding like ribbons, hills arranged in the relations of host and guest — where much, not overcrowded; where little, not sparse. A natural painting — the Wangchuan scroll was no finer than this. The product of human ingenuity — the Pingquan Villa need not even be mentioned. The company each leaned at the railing to gaze in all directions; only the sound of xiao flutes and drums from the dragon boat came drifting, as its green-wave rowers rowed it out in stately procession.",
    "At the stern of the dragon boat hung a swing frame, with two children swinging up and down. Cixian said: \"Please, let's go back down to look — looking from above down is not as fine as looking from below up.\" Everyone descended the goose-step stairway back to the first story, where they found a round table already set out in the front corridor of the central bays. This gathering was four host-and-guest gentlemen and five beauties. Ziyun was about to change into formal dress, but Cixian, Tian, and the three others stopped him; so they sent round the wine in informal attire, seating by seniority. To the east sat Nanxiang; Ziyun asked Lanbao to sit at his shoulder. To the west sat Chunhang, with Huifang at his shoulder. At the head sat Cixian, with Shufang at his shoulder.",
    "Ziyun took the host's seat, with Sulan and Baozhu on either side. The table talk was the usual sort; let us not linger over it.",
    "The dragon boat had now drawn up before the pavilion and was circling round and round, coming and going without end.",
    "Servants at a distance set off a string of five-thousand-cracker \"all-red hundred-seeds\" — the sound unceasing. Everyone was watching and cheering when suddenly four men appeared at the railing outside, wearing short green-lacquered silk jackets and red-lacquered silk trousers, bare-chested with sashes at the waist, red scarves bound at their foreheads, barefoot in straw sandals, their legs wrapped tightly in blue cloth. They lined up at the railing and performed a full bow toward those above. Nanxiang did not understand the meaning; he was about to ask when a drumbeat sounded from the dragon boat, and all four men simultaneously turned somersaults and plunged into the water. Ziyun said: \"These foolish fellows — they want to show off some skill too.\" He ordered servants to catch several pairs of ducks, and also told them to bring several red-lacquered gourds to throw into the water; then everyone understood it was a competition to seize the prize. The servants obeyed, first throwing a white duck into the water; the duck, hitting the water, gave a flip of its head, turned a somersault itself, then stretched its neck, flapped its wings, and quacked qua-qua-qua several times.",
    "One of the men pressed himself flat on the water's surface, kicked both legs, and shot across like a shuttle. The duck, seeing someone coming to catch it, fanned its wings and, half-submerged and half-floating, sped away. Just as it was going, a head suddenly emerged from the water, and one hand seized the duck. Ziyun said: \"Well done! Make a note to reward him.\" Three more ducks and two gourds were thrown in together. The four men competed with each other to excel, displaying every skill: now face-down, now face-up, now sinking, now surfacing, now turning sideways, now lifting a leg — swimming and playing without end. Some caught their prizes, some could not; some caught and then lost hold; some caught halfway and had their prize seized by another — drawing laughter and delighted shouts from everyone at the table, and each person drank several cups. The young dan actors were even more excited and all came out from the table to lean at the railing and watch the performance.",
    "Ziyun called them back inside and poured fresh cups. Cixian said: \"Shall we use this as the basis of a drinking game today?\" Everyone asked: \"How would the game work?\" Cixian asked the servants: \"Those large gourds that were cultivated in the garden last year — I imagine you still have some.\" The servants replied: \"There are a dozen or so lacquered ones; the rest are unlacquered.\" Cixian told them to bring the lacquered ones. Before long, the servants brought a large string of them; the ropes were undone and they were placed on an empty side table. Cixian then asked for the set of wine-forfeit tallies; the servants brought up a set of ivory tallies. Cixian drew out several at random, placed them face-down on the table with the blank side up, and said to everyone: \"Each person take one tally at random — don't look at the written side — and inscribe your own name on it.\" Everyone did as he said.",
    "Cixian then lifted the lid of a gourd, placed one tally inside each, screwed the lid back on tight, and instructed the pages to throw them into the water. \"Whoever's gourd is retrieved — that is the person who must drink. This is a perfectly fair amusement.\" Everyone agreed: \"Excellent — but what does it say on the tallies?\" Cixian said: \"This set of tallies takes its figures from the Water Margin — each character has a drinking episode associated with them. I drew them at random; I don't know exactly which names have come out.\" Ziyun laughed: \"These tallies would also be good fun — the drinking would be hearty. Only, among them there are a few characters with large capacity; drawing one of those would really put one to the test.\" Everyone said: \"There is nothing to do but submit to fate.\" One gourd was seen retrieved from the water; a page brought it to the table, dried it with a towel, opened the lid, and poured out the tally — it was Xiao Cixian's. Everyone looked at the other side, which had seven large characters and two lines of small text as annotation. The large characters read: \"Li Kui Creates a Great Disturbance at Xunyang River.\" The annotation read: \"The first two seats are Song Jiang and Dai Zong; the last seat is Zhang Shun. Li Kui drinks one large cup by himself; Song and Dai accompany with one small cup; then Li Kui finger-guesses ten rounds with Zhang Shun. If Li Kui wins, Zhang Shun drinks; if Zhang Shun wins, Li Kui drinks plain water.\" Everyone laughed. Cixian first drained the opening cup; Nanxiang and Chunhang accompanied with one cup each. Then he finger-guessed with Ziyun; Ziyun drank six cups of wine, Cixian drank four cups of plain water. Everyone said: \"Quite entertaining.\" Then another was retrieved; the tally was Nanxiang's. The inscription read: \"Wu Song Drunkenly Seizes the Happy Forest.\" The annotation read: \"Without three cups you cannot cross the ridge — first drain three full cups. The person opposite is Jiang Menshen; win three rounds in a row to pass, then play a general round.\" Nanxiang said: \"This one is too much — I'll drink the three cups, but let the general round be waived.\" Ziyun said: \"Waiving is not allowed; and moreover you have a great capacity.\" Lanbao said: \"For the general round, perhaps use half a cup, or split one cup into three portions.\" Everyone agreed. Nanxiang drank three cups, then began finger-guessing with Chunhang, and actually won three rounds in a row; then played out the general round; twelve cups of wine in all.",
    "Then two more were retrieved from the water. Opening the first: it was the character for Xu Ziyun. The inscription read: \"Song Jiang Kills Yan Poxixi in a Rage.\" The annotation: \"Drink two cups; the person seated beside is Yan Poxixi. Song Jiang first drinks one cup himself, then urges one cup on Yan Poxixi; if Yan Poxixi refuses, Song Jiang drinks it himself.",
    "\"\" Ziyun laughed: \"Who is Yan Poxixi among us?\" Everyone laughed. Cixian said: \"No need to guess — it's the two sitting right beside you; and moreover, you still drink it yourself. There's no need for them, but you still have to invite them.\" Ziyun laughed and drank one cup, then offered a cup to Sulan: \"Xiangwan — you are a good person; you mustn't imitate that Yan Poxixi, who only had Zhang Sanlang in his heart and paid attention to nothing else. Just drink this cup.\" This set everyone laughing. Sulan was originally going to drink, but the laughter made a flush rise on his face, and he pursed his lips toward Baozhu and said: \"Yan Poxixi is over there — ask him to drink.\" Baozhu also gave a titter. Ziyun then took a cup and said to Baozhu: \"What do you say — will you drink?\" Baozhu took the cup, turned to Sulan, and said: \"You fell into the trap — look at the tally: Yan Poxixi is the one who doesn't drink; if you drank, you wouldn't be Yan Poxixi.\" And he drained the cup. Sulan thought about it and realized that Baozhu had outwitted him. Now the second tally was looked at — it was Huifang's. When everyone saw it they burst out laughing; only Tian Chunhang managed to suppress his laughter, though his face showed some color. As it happened, this tally fell to Huifang — which was rather a case of karmic retribution for the Pan Qiguan business. The inscription read: \"Pan Jinlian Flirts with Her Brother-in-Law on a Snowy Day.\" The annotation: \"Three cups; the person seated to the left is Wu Song. For the first cup, one must reveal the chest, place one hand on Wu Song's shoulder, and say: 'Brother-in-law, drink this cup.' For the second cup, one must first drink half oneself, then say: 'Brother-in-law, if you have feeling for me, drink the other half.' For the third cup, one must stand up, feign an expression of anger, and drink it oneself; the whole table accompanies with three cups.\" At this Huifang flatly refused, saying: \"Let's finger-guess away these three cups.\" Ziyun said: \"The tally makes it perfectly clear — it was retrieved from the water; how can it be changed?\" Cixian said: \"And moreover you yourself wrote it on the tally — how can you go back on it now?\" Nanxiang said: \"If you're going to change the game, why did we follow ours as prescribed?\" Huifang had no choice and hesitated for a long time. Lanbao laughed: \"Retribution comes swiftly — now you're truly going to play Pan Jinlian's role for real.\" The company did not entirely understand, assuming Lanbao meant only the Pan Jinlian on the tally — not knowing that Lanbao had heard about the Pan Qiguan business. Chunhang understood perfectly and only lowered his head without speaking. Huifang, hearing this, blushed all the more and paid no attention; he had no choice but to take a cup of wine, stand up, lean toward Baozhu, and say: \"Brother-in-law, do drink this cup.\" Baozhu was in the middle of eating some vegetable when Huifang's unexpected address caught him off guard, and he spat his mouthful all over the table with laughter, leaned against Ziyun, wiped his mouth with a handkerchief, and still could not stop laughing. Everyone broke into uproarious laughter. Huifang was at a complete loss; he put down the cup and started laughing himself. Cixian said: \"Meixiang — another mistake. The annotation says the person seated to the left is Wu Song — not the person on the right. How is it you've offered this cup to Yaoqing?\" Huifang said: \"After all, who do you want me to offer it to? Isn't he seated beside me?\" Baozhu said: \"I don't quite count as beside you. Though it's a round table, I'm facing north and you're facing east — I certainly didn't expect you to address me as 'brother-in-law.'\" And he laughed again. Huifang still refused to comply. Ziyun laughed: \"Meixiang — can it be that you've never offered Xiangfan a cup of wine? Quickly, quickly! Look — two more have been retrieved. If you break the game rules, what will happen after this? In any case it's a one-time thing — it won't be your turn two or three times in a row.\" Cixian said: \"Be quick and offer the wine!\" Nanxiang said: \"When Pan Jinlian was flirting with her brother-in-law in the old story, she had to show some seductive manner to make it convincing — none of this stiff, by-the-book stuff.\" Each one saying a word, everyone pressing together — Huifang truly had no recourse. The sharp-tongued too can sometimes come to grief. Huifang had no choice but to lean slightly toward Chunhang, raise the cup, and say: \"Brother-in-law — drink this cup.\" Chunhang also had no recourse; he could only brazen it out and drink. For the second cup, Huifang also had to first take a sip, then bring it to Chunhang's lips; Chunhang, without waiting to be asked, drank it. Everyone said: \"That cup doesn't count — start over. The tally says the correct words must be spoken for it to count.\" Chunhang pleaded again and again; finally it was let go. For the third cup, things were much easier. Huifang poured a cup for himself, stood up, and Cixian said: \"This cup must be done with an expression of anger.\" Sulan said: \"He has genuine grievance in his heart.\" Huifang gave a laugh, then quickly composed the beautiful face into an expression of anger and drained the cup in one go. Ziyun, seeing all this, felt great admiration in his heart; he drank three cups himself and urged everyone else to drink three cups as well.",
    "They then looked at the next tally — it was Lanbao's. The inscription read: \"Lu Zhishen Drunken at the Mountain Gate.\" The annotation: \"First drain one large cup; the first two seats are the Guardian Kings; finger-guess three rounds with each.\" Huifang said: \"He gets off so easily, while I had to go through all that trouble.\" Lanbao followed the game rules and finger-guessed three rounds each with Nanxiang and Chunhang.",
    "The next tally was Shufang's; the inscription read: \"Jin Cuilian Selling Her Singing in the Wine-House. She must play the pipa and offer a respectful cup to Lu Da, Li Zhong, and Shi Jin each.\" Everyone said: \"This one is still manageable — on the edge between closeness and distance. And since she really does have the surname Jin — what an extraordinary coincidence!\" Shufang had no choice but to take up the pipa, and offered cups to Nanxiang, Chunhang, and Cixian.",
    "The next gourd retrieved contained Tian Chunhang's tally. Chunhang quickly looked at the inscription, thought for a moment, and said: \"Terrible!\" Everyone burst out clapping and laughing again: \"Today Meixiang and Xiangfan are clearly bound together by fate.\" Huifang's face reddened and she said: \"You've arranged this on purpose — otherwise why would only these two tallies come out like this?\" Cixian said: \"An absolutely unjust accusation! Say I purposely chose them — did you then purposely choose to draw them?\" The inscription read: \"Yi Zhangqing Captures Wang Duanhu.\" The annotation: \"After, they became husband and wife; hold a red handkerchief between yourself and the person beside you, exchange three cups in bridal-goblet fashion; the whole table raises a congratulatory cup.\" Chunhang wanted to change the game rule, but everyone refused to allow it. He could only hold a handkerchief between himself and Huifang, and they each drank half a cup; the third cup set the whole table talking and laughing together — talking and laughing, laughing and talking — saying: \"To witness this bridal goblet is rare indeed — let us each raise a great cup.\" So the whole table drank a congratulatory cup, which so embarrassed Huifang that she said: \"From now on my unlucky stars have all passed. Now it will be my turn to laugh at people.\" The next tally was Baozhu's; the inscription read: \"Wang Po Discusses Romantic Intrigue Upstairs.\" Seeing the annotation, Huifang laughed: \"Now this is karmic retribution — who expected that someone else would also put on a fine show for people to watch.\" Baozhu's face had already flushed bright red. The game required three cups: for the first, the person to the right is Ximen Qing; adopt the manner of lifting the window curtain with a bamboo pole, strike Ximen Qing once with a fan, and offer the first cup. For the second, Ximen Qing must kneel, one hand clasping the tip of Pan Jinlian's tiny foot, and offer this cup to Pan Jinlian. For the third, the person to the left is Wang Po; Pan Jinlian curtsies and says: \"Godmother, please drink this cup.\" Ziyun laughed: \"As luck would have it, it has now come around to me.\" Chunhang said: \"Having fragrant dust cling to one's stockings is the finest of affairs — and moreover with a lotus hook in the hand; why not drink ten cups?\" Nanxiang laughed loudly: \"'Fragrant dust cling to the knee' is still manageable — only don't kneel in the mud; then the lotus hook would be out of reach, and what you'd grasp would be a donkey's leg.\" This set everyone into wild uncontrollable laughter; Jin Shufang laughed so hard she twisted at the waist and tumbled straight into Cixian's lap. Wang Lanbao and Lu Sulan laughed and moved away. Baozhu said: \"Another case of heavenly retribution — perfectly clear and precise.\" Everyone kept laughing, which made Chunhang quite uncomfortable; yet unable to take it seriously, he had to hold it in and say: \"Zhujun's mockery deserves to be punished — he should draw an unpleasant tally.\" Nanxiang laughed: \"I was speaking from the facts — what mockery is there?\" Huifang said: \"That is enough — don't be so boastful. You too will have your moment of losing the wind someday.\" Cixian laughed: \"Yaoqing — what to do about this tally? It seems it cannot be changed — one can only accept some discomfort. And it is asking a lot of Duxiang's golden dignity on his knees.\" Everyone burst into laughter again. Huifang urged Baozhu to offer the wine quickly. Baozhu, being of a gentle and compliant nature, and unable to withstand the general pressure, had no choice but to brazen it out, and with the handle of the fan gave Ziyun a light tap, offering the first cup. Ziyun received it with a smile; everyone said: \"Splendid! Let us each drink a cup.\" Ziyun said: \"The drinking-game law is stricter than military law — no choice in the matter; honored guests, please don't laugh at the short man trying to see the show.\" He poured a cup, bent one knee, and offered it to Baozhu; Baozhu promptly took it and drank. Everyone said: \"Splendid!\" and each drank another cup. Baozhu then offered the third cup to Huifang, curtsied, and said: \"Godmother, please drink this cup.\" Huifang accepted it and drank, laughing: \"Good daughter — you've gone to such trouble.\" Everyone praised: \"What a fine godmother and god-daughter! Let us drink another congratulatory cup.\" And each drank again. The last remaining tally turned out to be Sulan's; it read: \"The Heroes of Liangshan Marsh Assemble in Righteous Unity.\" The whole table each drinks three cups. Everyone said: \"That closes things out most entertainingly — this drinking game today really seemed as if it had been arranged on purpose.\" Baozhu said: \"Only, it's too easy on him, and too easy on Jingfang — and Shouxiang only had to play the pipa. First of all, it's Yaoqing and I who had the worst of it.\"",
    "Huifang said: \"Someone knelt to offer you wine — and you're still not satisfied? What more do you want?\" Baozhu said: \"If you wanted someone to kneel to you, why didn't you take my tally and perform it for me?\" This round of drinking lasted until the red sun was setting in the west, and then they had their meal.",
    "After rinsing their mouths and washing their hands, they drank another round of fragrant tea. Nanxiang said: \"We still haven't appreciated the pomegranate blossoms at Little Red Citadel — shall we take advantage of the evening glow to go look at those blazing pomegranate fires?\" Ziyun then led everyone back to the boats, which crossed the red bridge back to the west side, where they disembarked at the foot of the artificial hill, passed through the Immortal's Cave, wended through the Apricot Tower (Xinglou) and Peach Grove, and arrived at Little Red Citadel. They saw pomegranate blossoms ringing in all directions like a rampart — some hundred or two hundred trees — crimson gleams flickering, a flowing fire about to blaze; interspersed were several varieties in yellow, white, and variegated agate colors, all blooming in succession. Truly as the \"Rhapsody on the Tiantai Mountains\" says: \"The red citadel glows and rises to mark the summit\" — which is why the place was called Little Red Citadel.",
    "The day was now late. Nanxiang and Chunhang wished to leave; small attendants brought their outer garments and hats, they dressed and put them on, thanked the host and Cixian, and took the roundabout path out of the garden. Ziyun said: \"Today there was actually one matter I had meant to trouble you two gentlemen with. The paired inscriptions for various spots throughout the garden still need several more sets added; today we were sidetracked by the dragon boat. Perhaps another day I can invite another outing and also include Gengxiang, Jiantan, and the other gentlemen — what do you say?\" Shi and Tian both agreed, then mounted their carriages and departed. The five young dan actors also gradually dispersed. This second grand entertainment at Yiyuan — it was a pity it was not fully attended. As for what the second volume will relate — one must await a careful reading."
  ],
  21: [
    "This installment turns again to Wei Pincai. After dwelling in the Hua mansion for more than a month he had cultivated everyone above and below with such thorough success that Young Master Hua granted him some dignity and his purse grew easier; thereupon he began to show the petty man's triumph and would no longer keep his place. Within were Gu Yueqing and Zhang Xiaomei; outside Yang Meichuang, Feng Zipai, and such company — nightly revelry — and whatever he saw and heard ran to schemes of influence and trimming to power; his heart grew fat and his daring swelled. Formerly at the Mei residence Academician Mei had been at home: though he did not lecture Pincai, fear naturally restrained him. Moreover Ziyu kept company only with gentlemen of name — none of those idle roamers. Like a horse stalled in its manger, however much it wished to bolt the traces it could not. Now he might indulge every whim without scruple.",
    "One day Zhang and Gu both had business; Pincai therefore went out of the city alone, hired a fashionable thirteen-panel glass-windowed heated carriage, dressed up Fourth Boy as well, and with an air of triumph came expressly to inquire after Ziyu's illness.",
    "Arriving at the Mei house he paid his respects to Lady Yan and went straight to Ziyu's chamber. Ziyu had now been ill over a month; though not gravely sick, he felt leaden and weary, ate far less than before, and his spirits flagged utterly. Sometimes he diverted himself with books, but his vitality was too weak for any pursuit; he sat alone without speaking, wearing the vacant brooding air of one who reads into empty air. Even Lady Yan could not guess what ailed her son — she assumed only that study had worn his blood and prescribed ginseng and tuckahoe tonics; useless as medicine ill-matched to the ailment. As the proverb runs, the heart's sickness needs a heart's cure; passions stirred from the seven emotions cannot be soothed by roots and bark. Only Ziyu himself understood — unless Qinyan came in person and talked freely through a whole day and night he could not suddenly recover. Pincai guessed part of this; entering, he asked many questions. With no visitors these few days Ziyu felt stifled — Pincai's presence eased him somewhat. Asked how things stood at the Hua mansion, Pincai praised Young Master Hua as unequalled under heaven, boasted how fine were his attendant Lin Shanzhi and the Eight Ling troupe — and declared even Qinyan could not match them.",
    "At mention of Qinyan Ziyu's old sorrow stirred; he said to Pincai: \"You were the first to speak of Qinyan — when I met him he seemed peerless in the world; how can there now be so many said to surpass him?\" Pincai replied: \"Qinyan's looks are indeed fine, but his temper is cold — like a blossom whose color is superb yet hangs on the highest branch where you cannot climb to reach it; whoever loves flowers naturally loves what lies near the hand. Or like winter's moon: brilliantly clear, yet when you lift your eyes that cold radiance pierces flesh and bone — beside the moons of spring's third month or autumn's eighth it seems less kindly though brighter.\" Ziyu said: \"Those are coarse analogies. A blossom no hand plucks keeps its fragrance for itself; a moon no eye admires yet shines alone in its purity. Hard-to-reach blooms only gain by rare birds and dew and fairy wind — their worth lies in being hard to climb. Cold-season moonlight seems ill-suited to idle viewing — yet paired with winter plum and white snow and bright waves and tinted clouds its clarity only deepens — how can mere cold constrain it? Roughly speaking, Qinyan's living fragrance and vivid color anyone may note; Qinyan's deep earnest feeling few can grasp. Taking him only by ordinary likeness misses him — hence vulgar and refined part ways. That Qinyan should meet fortune such as this is Heaven shaping the man — not turning him into roadside peach and plum.\" In these words Ziyu spoke from true insight into Qinyan; without noticing he treated Pincai as a vulgar sort of different taste. Pincai inwardly smarted but answered dryly: \"Quite so, quite so — Qinyan's merits I said long ago — few in this world beside Your Excellency and myself appreciate him so far. I mean to visit him — what truly is his illness?\" Ziyu said: \"Will you go today?\" Pincai said: \"If errands permit — I'll pass by.\" Ziyu said: \"If you see him, do not say I am ill. If he asks, say you do not know.\" Pincai said: \"I understand — what message shall I carry?\" Ziyu said: \"Nothing much.\" After a pause: \"Only tell him not to be ill.\" Pincai laughed: \"If you can bid him not to be ill, he can bid you the same.\" Ziyu knew he had slipped and smiled, then amended: \"Since he is already ill, nothing can be done — only urge him not to heap illness on illness. If he hears I am ill, do not hide it — say mine is slight and will clear in days. Say Xiangwan is the kindest soul — he may often seek him out and talk away gloom — then recovery comes faster.\" Pincai did not fully grasp this but agreed. Ziyu added: \"I cannot visit him myself — seeing Xiangwan will do.\" As he spoke his look grew bleak. Pincai saw clearly this sickness rose from Qinyan and thought: \"Yuxiang is useless — if he loves Qinyan why not summon him often and pour out both hearts — then neither would ail — why bottle it — he is no boudoir maiden barred from sight.\" Taking leave he did not seek Yuanmao but exchanged brief civilities at accounts and gate offices, then went straight to Cherry Lane and Qinyan's lodging.",
    "As it happened Changqing had gone out; Pincai walked straight into Qinyan's bedchamber. Green windows were tightly shut; the small yard stood empty; a plum tree bore clusters of yellow fruit, half flushed red on one side, several fallen on the ground. Suddenly a voice cried: \"A guest — do not enter!\" Looking up he saw a white parrot hung under the eaves — at sight of Pincai it began to speak. Someone stepped from the opposite wing and barred the way: \"The young gentleman is ill and cannot receive visitors — sir, please sit in the outer guest room.\" Pincai said: \"I am no stranger — we are closest of friends. Go in and say my surname is Wei; I come from Academician Mei's house to see him about his illness — I have something to say.\" The man relayed this; Qinyan's cough sounded twice within; then he heard: \"If he is from Academician Mei's house, show him in.\" The fellow came out smiling: \"Sir, if you please.\" The suite ran to three bays — outer room held a table and stools. A page lifted the curtain; crossing the threshold Pincai caught a mingled fragrance of incense and medicine, sharp and clearing. This was still the antechamber; he sat and studied the green glass windows reflected on the white wool carpet — green-shadowed tints. Beyond stood the kang; between hung a painting \"Shouyang Dots Her Forehead\"; flanking couplets read: \"Heart embraces the ice-jade autumn moon; man leans on paper curtains and plum.\" On the kang table a vase held a spray of plum; to one side four panels of red plum by Xiao Cixian; to the other four seal-script scrolls by Xu Ziyun. Before the window stood an antique brick-and-pearwood qin stand bearing a plum-patterned duan qin. The inner chamber hung a moonlight autumn-gauze embroidered curtain patterned with every variety of plum — this was the sleeping room.",
    "Pincai was about to step further when Qinyan lifted the curtain and came out. At first sight he wore a pale lake-green lined silk jacket and blue gauze short-sleeved surcoat — somewhat thinner than before, like plum in snow that prefers cold — only the more pitiable and lovely. He seated Pincai in the place of honor but himself sat far off on a plum-blossom stool by the qin table; they brought tea and a lad offered a white brass water-pipe and filled several bowls for Pincai. Pincai said: \"I heard you were unwell — I came out of the city especially to see you — are you better lately?\" At the words \"out of the city\" Qinyan pondered — so Yuxiang had not visited because he had moved inside the walls — and asked: \"When did Yuxiang move into the city? Which ward? How far from here?\"",
    "Pincai realized Qinyan had misunderstood: \"Yuxiang has not moved — I now lodge in the city; I no longer stay at his house.\" Hearing this Qinyan fell silent; his spirit seemed to slacken and vexation crossed his face. Pincai thought: \"Ask after Yuxiang and he brightens — speak straight to me and he turns ice.\" To probe he asked: \"Have you seen Yuxiang this month?\" Qinyan said: \"Since New Year's meeting at Yiyuan we have not met.\" Pincai smiled faintly: \"I gather Yuxiang no longer remembers you.\" Qinyan started: \"What do you mean — remembers?\" Pincai feigned hesitation: \"Nothing — only Yuxiang has been busy lately — naturally he forgets.\" Qinyan pressed: \"Busy how?\" Pincai said: \"Nothing special — friends, opera, wine.\" Qinyan reflected — something felt wrong — \"I heard Yuxiang was ill — that he went to Yiyuan several times — I never crossed him.\" Pincai gave a cold laugh and said nothing. Qinyan's doubts sharpened: \"Could Yuxiang truly have forgotten me — taken up with someone else?\" Yet he recalled how Yuling had flirted that day and Yuxiang flared — hardly likely. Pincai's manner was evasive — half swallowed — as if hiding something. \"He said he lives in the city — not at Yuxiang's — yet how does he know Yuxiang's affairs? If Yuxiang had nothing against me why would he lie? Still Pincai has never been trustworthy.\" Resolving that Yuxiang could not mean ill, he asked aloud: \"Yuxiang is an upright man — not one for idle romps.\" Pincai calculated: \"If I name someone he knows he will verify — I'll name someone distant.\" Slowly he said: \"Desire is never fixed — without companions to lure one, one never thinks it; without tasting sweetness one never seeks it. They say 'near vermilion you turn red — near ink you turn black.' Bad company hooks you onto that road; a taste of honey draws you in.\" He sighed: \"Pity Yuxiang — he began so principled and tasteful — would not run wild. At first when people gossiped I doubted — today I visited him — I enter without announcement as always — reached his study outer room — heard laughter inside. Yun'er cried loudly: 'Guest!' When I stepped in Yuxiang lay on the couch face flushed — flustered — I saw no one — the laughter was not his — I thought nothing of it.\"",
    "\"When we talked he fenced with me — answers missed questions. Behind the bed-curtain came rustling — someone hiding — I could not ask openly — anyone who might meet me would not hide. I sat on his bed awhile; the curtain stirred again — my fan dropped; I stooped as if to retrieve it and lifted the hem — beneath I glimpsed boots and the hem of white patterned crepe — I guessed an actor — thought perhaps you — yet you were sick — unlikely out — nor would you hide from me — Yuxiang's face burned; he feigned sleep — spare him embarrassment — I withdrew. At the gatehouse pages gossiped with Lianzhu troupe Rongguan's boy Dezhi — then I knew it was Rongguan. Yuyong — why keep company with such — even an actor need not be hidden — I cannot fathom our brother's temper. I know you bore deep feeling for him — at first he missed you too — they say he sought you several times — you refused — his heart cooled. You did not ask — I kept silent — now that you ask I cannot hide — frolicking with actors is common — I hate only that he cast you aside for Rongguan — wasting true feeling and staining his own clean name.\" Qinyan listened blankly, half believing; hearing this his heart twisted — tears slipped — he forced them back — finger slowly traced the gold studs on the qin — \"When you saw Yuxiang — nothing else was said?\" Pincai said: \"Leaving he only asked what troupe I would hear.\" Qinyan said: \"All this is true?\" Pincai sneered: \"When do I lie — believe what you like.\" Qinyan said: \"You sat so long — only that?\" Pincai said: \"I did not stay long — seeing him troubled I did not press.\" Qinyan said: \"Truly only one sentence?\" Pincai said: \"Not two — else may I perish.\" Qinyan's chest tightened — he could ask no more. Pincai added: \"They say at Yiyuan you were close — you gave him a qin — why drift apart — I hear the qin passed to another.\" Qinyan bent his head — could not answer. Pincai added: \"Perhaps because you often visited Duxiang — he grew jealous — if you truly cared you should not always haunt Duxiang — some distinction of near and far is owed — no wonder he turned sour.\" Qinyan's bitterness welled — near tears — he burst out: \"What words are these — what 'close' — what 'jealous' — I understand none of it.\" With that he wept outright. Pincai secretly rejoiced and soothed: \"I misspoke — you cannot bear jest — forgive me.\" He stepped up to wipe the tears — Qinyan flushed with indignation, rose, and withdrew to the inner room — called the boy: \"See Master Wei out — I am exhausted and cannot keep company.\" With that he lay down on the bed.",
    "Pincai heard this and rage flared — almost to explode — then thought: \"He is Yuxiang's darling — ruin him and Yuxiang may blame me — endure for now — settle slowly — time and again his cold eyes treat me as worthless — hateful. If I cannot master him what am I as Young Master Hua's man?\" Swallowing fury he swept out, climbed his heated carriage, and flew off.",
    "Qinyan lay on the bed — wave on wave of acid grief — tears without end — could not puzzle it out. He recalled Sulan's words that day — he and Yuxiang had come but the master was feasting guests and could not enter — then someone cut the tale short; these days he could not find Sulan — sent for him; Sulan changed to plain dress and came; Qinyan received him and they sat in the room. Sulan opened: \"You wanted me — not again to play Yuxiang's stand-in?\" Qinyan forced a smile: \"A puzzle I cannot fathom.\" Sulan said: \"Speak.\" Qinyan asked: \"You mentioned Yuxiang — have you seen him lately?\" Sulan smiled: \"As expected — aside from Yuxiang you never send for me. The other day at Yiyuan watching dragon boats Duxiang invited him — illness kept him away. Duxiang spoke of his illness — more than a month — face grown thin — ten days ago he did visit Duxiang. There's a joke — hilarious — I'm afraid you'll weep — maybe I should not tell.\" Qinyan's heart already shifted — he pressed:",
    "\"What joke — say it now.\" Sulan said: \"On Meixiang's birthday Tian Xiangfan wrote a short preface — everyone praised it — Duxiang copied it. The day Yuxiang came Jingyi showed him the piece; Yuxiang admired it. Standing by, Duxiang said: 'Xiangfan's style — the thicker the richer — the richer the better.' Jingyi and Duxiang at first did not catch Yuxiang's drift — then realized: he misheard 'thick and rich' as asking which of you or Qiguan ranks higher — he answered: 'Yuyong naturally above Yuyan — Yuyan though fine still falls short of Yaoqing and Meixiang — while Yuyong stands like trees of jade and blossoms of pearl — no place on human flower-lists.' Jingyi and Duxiang laughed until they could not stand — Yuxiang saw his error — deeply embarrassed — covered with a few mumbled words — so one moment he has not forgotten you — this illness may be hard to cure — will you cry?\" At this Qinyan could not hold back — silent sobs — tears strung like thread — his blue gauze half-sleeve dark with a spreading wet patch across the chest.",
    "Sulan soothed: \"Why weep — you are barely mending — grief only heaps frost on snow — that is why I would not tell.\" Qinyan stamped: \"Wei Pincai is less than human — slandering and staining people for nothing.\" Sulan asked who Wei Pincai was; Qinyan hid his face in the sleeve and wept without stopping; Sulan coaxed until he ceased, then told the drinking game the other day with Baozhu and Huifang — Yaoqing was middling — Meixiang sharp and unwilling to lose yet had swallowed that dull loss; also how Pan San plagued him — Meixiang would not tell — gossip said Meixiang feared him and hid at Xiangfan's for days — now he instructed servants: if Pan San called, always answer not at home — rumor added he had opened a door behind his bed through to the kitchen to dodge Pan San.",
    "Hearing this Qinyan smiled slightly. Sulan asked who Wei Pincai was; Qinyan sketched last year's boat north and lodging at Mei's — then said: \"Listening close, that Wei is a petty man — why ask — better not speak of him.\" Sulan said: \"Nothing special — yesterday at Chunyang Tower I heard the boss tangled with a secretary of the Hua mansion — dragged to the constabulary — twenty blows — dozens of strings fine — two tables of wine besides.\"",
    "\"People said the man was also surnamed Wei — something Cai — from the Hua mansion.\" Qinyan said: \"I heard him say he lives in the city now — not at Yuxiang's — I did not ask where.\" Sulan said: \"The waiters told the tale end to end. New Year's week this Wei and others brought Baozhu and Er Xi — fifty-odd strings — the boss did not know him and must have spoken out of turn when tallying credit.\"",
    "\"Later the Wei man repaid in scraps — account still unsettled. Another day he brought five actors from si hour to shen — seventy-odd strings — the boss, not knowing he was from the Hua house, stalled on the chit and mentioned old debt — the Wei drunk smashed brush and shoved the inkstone off — shattered a table of crockery below — boss raised uproar — crowd parted them — ticket named Hua mansion secretary — next morning constables yoked the boss away — Zhang Zhongyu spent dozens of strings to settle — twenty blows only — two feasts for Master Zhang — they said the name was Wei something — hearing you curse him I guess it is Pincai.\" Qinyan said: \"Whether or no — anyone called Wei Pincai is no good.\" He asked again what Sulan and Yuxiang had begun to say the day the master feasted guests. Sulan recounted that day in detail — \"I've talked myself dry — you offered no tea.\" Qinyan laughed: \"Talk ran urgent — forgot — brew tea.\" Sulan drank and smiled: \"Yuxiang matches your heart — cast from one mold.\" Qinyan asked how. Sulan said: \"Your rooms and dress — everywhere plum blossoms — because his surname is Mei — you cherish the token. Yuxiang lately wears nothing but qin motifs — brocade pouches, fan tassels — fans painted front and back with two qins — isn't that the same bent?\" Qinyan laughed through tears: \"Don't tease — how carry heavy instruments on the body?\" Sulan laughed: \"Fool — did you plant plum blossoms on your skin?\" Qinyan smiled; Sulan added: \"Duxiang says Yuxiang's every trinket is qin-shaped — fans show two instruments, one face, one reverse.\" Qinyan wept again; Sulan said: \"You cry again and I'll hush.\" Qinyan swallowed: \"Go on — I won't cry.\" Sulan asked why Pincai earned his hate; Qinyan repeated Pincai's lies about Yuxiang. Sulan reflected: \"Yuxiang would never — you must not believe him.\" Qinyan said: \"At first his tale seemed true — hearing you I know it cannot be — why must that mongrel invent slander — is there no decency?\" Sulan said: \"Perhaps Yuxiang crossed him — perhaps he seeks to drive you apart for some scheme.\" Qinyan sneered: \"His schemes — do I flatter him because he entered the Hua mansion?\" Sulan warned: \"Now that knave rides Young Master's favor he may throw weight — wrong no petty villain — evil men make mischief — guard yourself as against thieves.\" Qinyan said: \"I ignore him — what can he do?\" They talked on until past second drum; Sulan rose — parting she said: \"In a few days I'll devise a way for Yuxiang to meet you.\" Whether Pincai could swallow such cold treatment without further plots — hear the next installment."
  ],
  22: [
    "In the previous chapter, Sulan promised to arrange a meeting between Ziyu and Qinyan, but Dragon Boat Festival duties and several days of performances delayed everything. Qinyan waited in torment, while Sulan finally decided to rent a quiet boat outside the East Gate, furnish it tastefully, and invite only Ziyu for a day on the canal under Duxiang's name.",
    "The letter reached Mei Ziyu while he sat in melancholy practicing easy qin passages. Seeing Sulan's message, he read it again and again with rising joy, then wrote an earnest reply promising to come at the appointed hour and sent it back immediately.",
    "When Sulan entered Qinyan's compound he heard shouting and, peering through a window crack, saw two rough men cursing and threatening the household, demanding Qinyan come out.",
    "Qinyan's attendants pleaded that he was truly ill and begged for a few days' grace, offering tea, tobacco, and apologies while trying to calm the men.",
    "The men began extorting money; two strings were refused as too little, so the household added more and finally got them to leave.",
    "As Sulan fled after being spotted, one thug chased and insulted him, then questioned the servants about who he was and where he lived.",
    "The servants lied that Sulan belonged to another troupe and lived far away; the two thugs staggered off while Qinyan inside burned with rage.",
    "They were later identified as hirelings connected to the Hua mansion, bought by Wei Pincai to create trouble.",
    "Sulan returned shaken and nearly in tears, then, unable to rest, went to Qinyan's room, where he found him sobbing behind a curtain and speaking despairingly of death and burial under Yiyuan's plum trees.",
    "Qinyan's grief drew Sulan into tears as well; both wept uncontrollably.",
    "They cried together for a long while, and Sulan reflected bitterly that heaven seemed jealous of beautiful and gifted people.",
    "Their crying alarmed the household. After attendants briefly soothed them, Sulan asked about the attackers, and the two concluded Wei Pincai was the likely instigator.",
    "Qinyan asked what grudge Wei could hold. Sulan warned him not to give up on life, then showed him Ziyu's reply. Qinyan first misunderstood the address, then read the contents, smiled through tears, and agreed to come next morning with warm clothes in case of canal wind.",
    "By overnight the illness had retreated by eight-tenths, but a new ailment appeared: the more he wanted to sleep, the less he could.",
    "At fourth watch a violent storm broke with thunder and lightning, and only at dawn did the rain finally stop.",
    "Exhausted, Qinyan slept and dreamed thugs seized him as he tried to board the boat; he woke in cold sweat to full daylight.",
    "A parrot's words frightened him again, but it was only Sulan's messenger coming to fetch him. He washed, took nourishment, packed clothes, and set out.",
    "At Sulan's, he asked about Ziyu; Sulan said Ziyu was already guided to the boat and preparations were being finished with his usual careful attention.",
    "On Ziyu's side, he too had endured a sleepless stormy night, then at dawn prepared gifts instead of money so as not to insult Sulan.",
    "He selected silk, small valuables, and silver, received his mother's permission to go out, and was warned to return early and avoid chill.",
    "Li Yuanmao delayed him at the door, first stalling and then asking to borrow money; Ziyu had the accounts room handle it before finally escaping.",
    "By the time Ziyu reached the East Gate area it was late morning. Sulan greeted him formally, brought him aboard, and both changed into lighter clothes.",
    "Sulan smiled: \"I have not served you well — Yunong is worse today and cannot come out. Moreover, yesterday two ruffians gave him a thorough verbal thrashing, which has left him quite ill from rage. Having invited you today and not wishing to send word to cancel, I thought we two could sit a while together and then I will find another time to bring you two together.\"",
    "With reddened eyes Ziyu declined going to visit Qinyan, saying fate would only frustrate them again. Sulan teased him about detachment and hinted at a \"substitute\" companion.",
    "Ziyu objected, but Sulan called someone from the rear cabin. It was truly Qinyan, thinner and weeping. They spoke in sorrow, each blaming himself, and soon both were crying again.",
    "Seeing each other cry made both men cry harder, and Sulan was moved to tears as well.",
    "Sulan finally urged them to stop weeping and use the remaining daylight. Qinyan lamented Wei Pincai's persecution; Sulan recounted Wei's slanders and yesterday's assault, leaving Ziyu shocked and furious.",
    "The boat moved on as wine and food were served, but Ziyu and Qinyan drank only under persuasion, each feeling this meeting resembled a painful farewell.",
    "After several li the mood softened; Ziyu admired Qinyan's delicate beauty and Sulan's grace, while Qinyan gazed at Ziyu's refined tenderness. Their glances slowly warmed their hearts.",
    "Sulan watched them and thought them a perfect pair envied by heaven itself, toasting them gently while all three wished time could stop.",
    "Just at the height of this fullness of happiness, a boat was seen approaching from ahead; at a distance came the sound of silk-string and wind instruments.",
    "As it passed, they saw obscene drunken revelry. Sulan identified one man as Pan Third and named the actors aboard; Ziyu found the spectacle coarse and joyless.",
    "Sulan laughed: \"Each person finds pleasure in their own way — if they did not behave like this, they would not consider it pleasure.\" Looking on, the red sun was nearing the western horizon. Ziyu's heart at this moment was full of joy — he almost felt the pleasure of having forgotten to return.",
    "Fearing gate closure, Sulan ordered faster rowing and packed up. Ziyu distributed gifts to Sulan and Qinyan and rewarded their attendants with silver.",
    "At the East Gate they parted by carriage. Ziyu held Qinyan's hand with tears, and Qinyan, choking with sobs, promised they would find another way to meet.",
    "Ziyu returned home; the lamps were already lit. Lady Yan asked where he had been; he could only give a vague answer to put her off. As for what happened next, listen to the following chapter to find out."
  ],
  23: [
    "On the day Ziyu toured the canal, Li Yuanmao borrowed money, converted part of it into notes for convenience, and went out roaming, still obsessed with a woman he had seen before in East Garden.",
    "At East Garden he ogled doorways and was drawn toward a flirtatious woman who invited him inside while bystanders teased him for inexperience.",
    "Encouraged and pushed in by two loafers, Yuanmao entered; an accomplice immediately demanded payment, and he handed over a one-string note.",
    "He said to the man: \"The note says one string of cash — you should give me change for the difference. Just bring me the change.\" The man smiled, looked at the note, stuffed it into a large leather satchel pocket, and went back into the interior.",
    "Li Yuanmao then summoned his courage, lifted the curtain, and went inside, feeling somewhat assaulted by odors.",
    "He saw the woman sitting on the kang, with a strip of matting, a red pillow, and a long bench beside it.",
    "She gave him tea, washed herself crudely, beckoned him close, and just as things began, a violent commotion erupted outside and she rushed out.",
    "Men burst in fighting; amid the chaos several pinned Yuanmao down, stripped him completely, and robbed him clean before scattering.",
    "The woman and collector vanished. Crowds mocked him while he hid with a straw curtain and shouted for his boy Wang Bao, who eventually fetched fresh clothes so he could leave in humiliation.",
    "The whole incident was a planned swindle by the woman and her associates targeting a naive outsider with money. The scandal spread widely, even reaching his future in-laws.",
    "The narrative then turns to Sun Sihui seeking out his relative Ji Liangxuan, a morally dubious legal secretary who came to Beijing to curry favor and secure employment.",
    "A long aside contrasts upright, principled secretaries with corrupt, factional profiteers who flatter patrons and sell recommendations.",
    "Once installed in a position, they simply hold up past cases as their guiding principles and treat the clerks as their models; they bring in a couple of idle, impoverished friends to do the copying and writing, while they themselves live in comfortable dignity without exerting their minds in the least. They put on a few new sets of clothes, ride in a grand sedan chair, and wear stiff-toed boots — and pass for perfectly respectable gentlemen.",
    "That day Sihui invited Ji to dine and hear opera, bringing actor Fenglin; Ji also brought a handsome young attendant he had bought and renamed Yingguan.",
    "Ji boasted of Beijing actors' polish and hinted at his own arrangement with the boy, while jealousy and flirtation simmered around the table.",
    "\"For example, right now in summer: just one robe, a summer hat, coming into the yamen in groups of three or four — they absolutely refuse to come singly. Payment is casually one tael or two taels, any amount will do.\" Sihui said: \"That cheap! If one comes in alone, could I then climb the host's wall and embrace him?\"",
    "Liangxuan laughed: \"Brother-in-law is joking — how could one scale the host's wall? Even if it's very late, the second or third watch, the mansion gates can still be called open.\" Sihui said: \"Calling at the gate at the third watch causes all sorts of fuss and commotion — there are still inconveniences. Why not open a back entrance? Then people could come and go without being seen.\"",
    "Feng Lin said: \"Hard to say precisely — adding it all up over a year, three or four thousand strings of cash is the usual amount.\" Liangxuan stuck out his tongue: \"That much? More than we legal secretaries earn in tuition fees! Now I feel some regret — I should have learned to perform at the theater; it would have been much more enjoyable than learning the secretarial trade.\"",
    "This remark struck home with Liangxuan, who laughed: \"This little page-boy has done double duty — both a donkey and a concubine, he has been both at once.\" Sihui said: \"How remarkable! What does 'donkey and concubine' mean? I wish to hear in detail.\" Liangxuan explained: \"I use him only as my attendant for now — the two roles complementary, neither wasted.\"",
    "Sihui answered in muddled classical quotations; Fenglin mocked his pockmarked red face and the men tumbled into coarse joking and teasing.",
    "Fenglin slapped and laughed, Sihui chased him, and Ji smoothed things over with more drink and food.",
    "Jealous Yingguan sulked while Ji launched into explicit, technical obscenities, comparing sexual methods to boats and carts.",
    "Fenglin cut him off with ridicule and drinking penalties. As night fell, they ate, settled tips and bills, and dispersed.",
    "The narrator then defends including such indecency: the world contains both refined passion and base lust, and a truthful book must depict both right and wrong."
  ],
  24: [
    "This chapter concerns Yan Zhongqing and Wang Xun. One day at home Zhongqing asked Wang Xun: \"Heard the news these past few days — any of it reach you?\" Wang Xun said: \"My sister-in-law was unwell — I waited on the doctor daily and did not go out.\" Zhongqing said: \"Yesterday Zhang Zhongyu told me: a silvershop man Pan the Third since the third month has been trying to take Su Huifang as a dry-son. The first time he dragged Zhang the Second along to pester Meixiang — no recourse — Meixiang feigned deep courtesy, lent Pan two hundred strings, and when he wanted a \"leather-cup\" toast feigned a fishbone in the throat. Then she got them dead drunk to insensibility and had them sleep together in the guest room — Pan rolled off, pissed in his own boot, woke confused; they said Young Master Hua had called them — Pan railed all night and had to slink home. In the fourth month he pestered again and ran into a fake night watch — Pan fled and lost a gold bangle.\" Wang Xun laughed: \"Meixiang is sharp as a needle — only Xiangfan tames her — a silversmith was bound to be cheated.\" Zhongqing said: \"I also heard Li Yuanmao made a great fool of himself in the East Garden.\" Wang Xun asked how. Zhongqing said: \"Someone saw him in a brothel — thugs burst in, stripped him; he wrapped in a straw mat and could not come out — the crowd toppled the whole hovel. How he got home — who knows.\" Wang Xun said: \"Can that be true — or slander?\" Zhongqing said: \"Cai Sheng saw it — Zhongyu said so.\" Wang Xun said: \"Yuanmao looks honest — how could he?\" Zhongqing laughed: \"Honest men do such things — the cunning won't. Lately your bookworm brother-in-law has led him astray.\" Wang Xun laughed: \"Your doing — handsome face and dull wit — my in-laws would burst.\" Zhongqing continued: \"Wei Pincai entered the Hua mansion and changed — unruly outside — stirred Chunyang Restaurant — the boss was whipped twenty — worse, Lu Sulan says Pincai hired a Hua groom and page to bully Qinyan — they reviled half a day till Qinyan's people kowtowed and paid strings to leave.\" Wang Xun said: \"Strange — so much in days — both seemed refined — faces deceive.\" Zhongqing said: \"Cheerier news: Yuxiang spent a day on the canal with Qinyan and Sulan — lately both mended.\" Wang Xun smiled: \"Yuxiang revels alone — never invites us.\" Zhongqing said: \"Sulan arranged their meeting — lovers' grievances — outsiders must not intrude.\" Wang Xun said: \"I cannot fathom Yuxiang and Qinyan's bond — where does passion sprout among us voluptuaries? Surely not one glance — on New Year's sixth Yuxiang saw Qinyan's \"Startled Dream\" — name unknown — at Yiyuan lantern-night the qin riddle fell to Yuxiang so Duxiang paired them; Baozhu says a false Qinyan teased first — Yuxiang nearly left — true Qinyan appeared weeping — hearts pledged — since then scarce meetings bred illness — all guessed longing — on Meixiang's birthday Qinyan stayed away sick and Yuxiang grew restless and fell ill. Yuxiang is smitten — yet whence the root? Qinyan is stranger still — one glance in a sea of faces — how cling so fast? Had they daily converse one might understand — they met by dew-chance yet cling like shadow to body — is this Buddhist karma?\"",
    "Zhongqing said: \"Their passion is among the most upright — there is a root — I shall tell you. The root came through an unworthy man. I asked Yuxiang: before Qinyan reached the capital Wei Pincai shared their boat and praised Qinyan morning and night — Yuxiang listened till longing planted itself — that is the root. Later he saw Qinyan's art — face and skill above the crowd — heard his proud cold temper — love bred respect and respect deepened love. Had they never met again it would have scattered like colored cloud. Heaven sent Duxiang as matchmaker — false tested true — light caught hidden corners — Yuxiang's whole heart was photographed into Qinyan's breast. Had that day the false Qinyan succeeded, Qinyan would have cooled. Consider: one meeting reading face and station — \"I love you for beauty and for rank; beauty without rank is ordinary.\" Others might barely feel it — Qinyan's proud soul fears any slip toward mockery — yet one glance at young Master Mei pierced him like lightning — saw straight through. People suppose love is only face — but what heart loves only face — though unspoken it may hide within — even if none — when one loves a person one never prefers refusal to flattery — so Yuxiang's anger deepened Qinyan's gratitude; Qinyan's tears deepened Yuxiang's love — one meeting yet hearts align like breath — root and branch spread everywhere — can you say none exists? Baozhu says Qinyan marked Yuxiang before Yiyuan — since New Year's sixth glimpse he wandered in dreams — that part puzzles — karma may hold.\" Wang Xun said: \"You preach like the Surangama — no veil — their love stands deepest and straightest above common folk. How compare Xiangfan and Meixiang?\"",
    "Zhongqing laughed: \"Another species. Xiangfan loved Meixiang first for beauty — wasted oceans of silver — seeing such loveliness he suffers insult without rage, mockery without shame — like a mortal glimpsing heaven — must gaze every hour. When Meixiang pitied his hidden pain and thanked his tireless patience — barely yielding color — Xiangfan saw his elegant speech and gentle face, humble without lewd purpose — pure sincerity — and she softened. Once moved they stuck like lacquer — day firmer than day. At first Xiangfan scarcely weighed Meixiang's station — only saw flower face and tender feeling — finding her stern and beyond reach yet aiding and advising him love turned to respect and respect to love — like a friend's warning or another mountain's stone — wrong righted itself without preaching. Compare to Yuxiang — Sima Xiangru and Yang Xiong — same craft different tune. Only those who love beauty without debauch hold true passion — lust-born feeling is not from nature. Take Pan Third — he covets Meixiang — is that 'passion'?\" Wang Xun said: \"Still a kind of feeling — if none he would not think of her.\" Zhongqing laughed: \"If Pan had true feeling he would never lust after Meixiang — his lust is his heartlessness.\" Wang Xun laughed: \"Forced logic — passion has upright and crooked — Pan's is crooked lust — not Xiangfan — yet say he felt nothing why pester five times?\" Zhongqing laughed: \"Easiest answer: if Pan truly loved Meixiang he need not make her dry-son — casual friend without lewd thought would do — had Meixiang taken silver without yielding joy I fear Pan would hate her to the marrow — who loads insult on the beloved? Slights when I offend him not he offend me — still forgivable — that is love. When feeling crawls into a miser's chest Heaven's gate of passion must be rebuilt by new immortals.\" Wang Xun clapped: \"You open veils — I see — you are passion's transcendent.\" Wang Xun asked: \"What of Duxiang's passion?\" Zhongqing said: \"Duxiang is a great spendthrift yet bears himself with ease and vast tolerance — love wide yet not promiscuous — spirit strong yet not proud — self and other dissolve — he is passion's host.\" He continued: \"Xiao Cixian is wild crane idle cloud — still a scholar's habit — but in stillness none match him — talk all day without weariness — passion shows there. Nanxiang proud of talent — fierce — yet where feeling runs earnest — though wild little cruelty — moves like cloud and water — no fixed intent — wit cuts yet toward those he favors never a cruel syllable — devoted passion. Qianzhou resembles you — mild thick kindness — rather others wrong him than he wrong others. As for me I forget no feeling yet spend it rarely — easy to begin and hard to end — if I threw it about without close I would drown — better lend my passion and watch others — where their feeling cracks or blocks I lend a little to complete theirs and thus complete mine — passion is the world's common treasure — need not be hoarded for oneself.\" Wang Xun said: \"That philosophy is vast — turning all under heaven into one feeling — assign each its place — even dying for duty springs from this. At rough glance Zhu Guojie loaned passion — you are passion's knight.\" Zhongqing said: \"Praise undeserved — natures differ. At Duxiang's I hear Young Master Hua though unmet — generous feeling matches Duxiang's source though not same stream — Duxiang honors him. Wei Pincai, Feng Zipai, Pan Third are worms in passion's grain — near them rots body — follow them rots heart — born to plague the decent. There is Xi Shiyi who ruins actors — tricks them with a wooden barrel — many poisoned — Qiguan was trapped — broke the barrel by strength — hands torn raw — still healing — passion's bandit. Your bookworm brother-in-law and that brother-in-law know not what feeling is — joy and grief unlike mankind.\" Wang Xun laughed: \"Those fools — every vulgar joke theirs — Sun Laoda gained another brother-in-law — like Pincai but duller — bound to make scenes.\"",
    "Zhongqing said: \"The worm-eaten Thousand-Character Classic needs a bowl of ink to stop loose talk.\" Wang Xun asked what Li Yuanmao should take. Zhongqing laughed: \"Yuanmao dull with all seven orifices stopped — rhubarb and mirabilite to purge the muck.\" Wang Xun asked about Zhongyu. Zhongqing said: \"Between good and ill — still knows decent folk — conscience not dead.\" As they bantered Li Yulin arrived with Guibao; greetings done they sat. Zhongqing asked: \"Two days unseen — busy at home?\" Wang Xun said: \"I go out often — never see you.\" Guibao said: \"We rehearse new plays at Yiyuan.\" Zhongqing asked which. Yulin said: \"Sixth of sixth lotus birthday — Young Master Hua tours the garden — Duxiang knows he loves opera — consulted Jingyi — Jingyi said ordinary plays he has heard — no troupe beats his Eight Ling — better pick stars from many companies into one grand cast and compose fresh pieces — unlike outside ears — altogether new.\" Zhongqing said: \"Good — what plays?\" Yulin said: \"Once Mao Shengshan listed titles in notes on The Lute Song — set called Mending Heaven Stone — never set to music.\"",
    "Zhongqing laughed: \"Vile mouth — Mao teased readers — only listed from his Lute commentary titles like 'Li Ling Returns to Han,' 'Prince Dan Extinguishes Qin,' 'Zhuge Extends Life,' 'Bright Consort Returns to Han' — eight or nine.\" Yulin said: \"Jingyi added four: 'Green Pearl Leaps at Golden Valley,' 'Consort Yang Escorts at Mawei Post,' 'Li Bai Receives Edict at Night Lang,' 'Du Fu Honored at Golden Hall' — huge casts — nearly everyone on stage.\" Zhongqing said: \"Those four vent for lovers and scholars worldwide — Mawei noose breaks every heart — An Lushan's revolt — fault was Guozhong — what crime the Lady? Popular tales slander the harem — the bath scandal appears in neither Old nor New Tang — only Yuan Zhen's cheap line about golden-rooster tent washing — posterity mistook it for proof — hateful — minister executed — army pacified — reasonable — Chen Yuanli lacked loyal heart and troop discipline — should be cast off — reverse these wrongs and more remain.\" Wang Xun asked how many rehearse. Guibao said: \"Ten female roles — twenty-some sheng jing lao chou from five or six companies.\" Zhongqing listed the ten female names. Wang Xun said: \"That is the Ten-Beauties company.\" Guibao said: \"Guests unsettled — you two are certain — Duxiang wrote Baoding inviting Qianzhou — likely for this.\" Wang Xun said: \"Close — today twenty-sixth — ten days enough for new plays?\" Yulin laughed: \"You forgot intercalary fifth — over a month remains.\" Wang Xun laughed: \"Secluded — lost track of days.\" Zhongqing asked if Qinyan still ill. Yulin said: \"After his canal day with Yuxiang he mended at once.\" Wang Xun said: \"Joy lifts the spirit.\" Zhongqing asked if Qiguan's hands healed. Yulin lowered eyes — brows knit — anger shadowed. They asked why; Guibao said Zhongqing's mention of Qiguan touched sore nerve — told Xi Shiyi's workshop trick — Zhongqing and Wang Xun swore — \"Such people exist — how do victims live?\" Guibao said: \"He hides in Tianjin — may return.\" Zhongqing asked Xi's background; Guibao traced merchant grandfather, father now river intendant, brothers twelve in trade or office — Xi nearly bought a circuit seat — funds fell short — bought sub-prefect instead — Wang Xun recalled old men calling him Xi Old Earth for peddling opium profit — Yulin and Guibao rose to leave — Wang Xun pressed supper — sent kitchen word.",
    "Presently sun slanted west; Zhongqing ordered curtains rolled and table moved to gallery — four seats. Wang Xun said: \"Plain meal — no extra dishes — cannot match Duxiang.\" Guibao said: \"Your plain feasts I've lost count of — Dongcheng Kitchen cannot equal — Duxiang spends too much — who can eat so much anyway.\" They sat; kitchen hearing actors added eight plates and four dishes — yellow wine and snacks came first — Yulin and Guibao toasted — talk flowed — Zhongqing and Wang Xun asked news — seeing Yulin abstain they asked why — he said hoarse throat — heat — dared not drink. Zhongqing ordered fruit — said drinking without games cannot delight — few people limit games — Guibao proposed \"Paste-Emerald Forfeit\" — Wang Xun agreed — dice appeared — rounds passed — many cups down.",
    "Earlier Wang Xun had heard Zhongqing judge each man's passions and thought of Flower Register actors and their feelings — he asked Yulin and Guibao: \"Rehearsing at Yiyuan — among the ten do you know temperaments — whose easiest company?\" Guibao said: \"Ten sorts — Yuyong coldest — rest mild enough.\" Yulin said: \"For refined taste and keen mind — not chasing power — proud spirit — that is Yaoqing. Spotless and bright — rivalrous talent — Meixiang. Gentle grace — measured speech — harmonious yet firm — sweetly poised — Xiangwan. Frank talk — lofty manner — high and low welcome — free — Jingfang. Quiet ease — apt words — Shouxiang.",
    "Quick mind nimble speech — elegant bearing — Xiao Mei. Versatile — romantic self-regard —\" nodding at Guibao — \"him. Secret heart few grasp — steadfast till seas dry — Yuyong. Pure fidelity heedless of gain — Yuyan. I have no merit — dull — people despise — that is me.\" Guibao said: \"You sell yourself short — my verdict: Fragrant restraint — pleasant grace — neither proud nor base — neither loving nor hating — that is Peixian.\" Zhongqing and Wang Xun said: \"Sharp — Ruixiang's insight grows.\" Yulin demurred. Wang Xun asked judges on Rongguan, Er Xi, Yumei, Chunlin, Fenglin — outsiders. Guibao laughed: \"Different sect — we are Yuqing gate disciples crusading Zhou — they are Tongtian sect aiding tyrants — tortoise-spirit and Shen Gongbao sorts — uncanny tricks — dangerous — when fate seats us together we tread soft — dare not jest — Peixian's scandal — did not Rongguan expose it? Qiguan's pain — did not Er Xi engineer it? I fear Du Yuyong — he offends everyone — foes multiply — memory weak — after days he forgets faces — all hate his cold pride — even toward Duxiang cool — only young Master Mei he calls life's soulmate — sick with longing — who is Master Mei?\" Zhongqing said: \"You met him — Mei's son — style Yuxiang.\" Guibao remembered: \"Yes — beauty pairs Yuyong — but does Yuyong's temper suit?\" Yulin said: \"That day Yuyong absent — no wonder Yuxiang drooped — silent — sipped little — lay down — promised Yaoqing's house yet never came.\" Wang Xun said: \"Other day he boated canal with Sulan and Qinyan.\" Guibao clicked tongue: \"No wonder Yuyong returned healed.\" They laughed past second watch — actors took leave — carriages home — Zhongqing and Wang Xun talked then retired. Next installment: Yiyuan feast and new plays — how Young Master Hua responds — hear then."
  ],
  25: [
    "In the previous chapter, Yulin and Guibao at Wang Xun's place were speaking of the new plays being rehearsed at Yiyuan in preparation for Young Master Hua's garden visit. Time flew swiftly; in the blink of an eye a month passed, and Liu Wenze had returned. Of this circle of distinguished scholars, the one Young Master Hua had long been acquainted with was Liu Wenze alone; the rest he had mostly not yet met.",
    "On the sixth day, taking advantage of the early morning cool, he came to Yiyuan at the chen hour. He arrived in a carriage with two horses, his attire fresh and splendid; as he entered the garden gate, a servant went ahead to announce him. Wenze meanwhile admired the garden's scenery as he walked slowly. Though many people had visited Yiyuan, those who could remember their way around were surprisingly few.",
    "The garden ran some three or four li around its circuit. The small hills within were piled from Lake Tai rock; the long ridge of great hills sat on packed-earth footings crowned with towering peaks, dressed in flowers and trees and framed by pavilions — indistinguishable from living mountains. Inside the grottoes water was secretly pumped with chain-pumps and sprayed upward to form cascading waterfalls.",
    "The pool belt linked to an outer river, winding and circling, broad or narrow as terrain allowed. Within the grounds stood also archery ranges, ball courts, fishing lodges, rice paddies, wineshops, tea arbors — all run by gardeners, uniformly neat and clean — to occupy those with duties in the garden and keep them from slipping outside to neglect work: such was Duxiang's arrangement. Formal courtyards and halls numbered twenty-four in all — linked yet broken apart, never repetitive — if one toured conscientiously, a whole day might cover only three or four spots; eight or nine days were needed to finish the whole.",
    "Even the garden's lord might not recall every turn at once. At the center rose a great hall named Han Wan Lou — \"embracing the myriad things and resolving them into light\" — the garden's chief building, windows on every face, spirit vast and open. Outside stretched a stone terrace with rails on three sides and seven tiers of steps at center. Before it ran a belt of parasol trees screening like a folding screen; beyond rose tier on tier of towers and galleries. Along the eastern willows lay the sheet of water connecting to the Chanting-Autumn Waterside Pavilion — lotus now in countless bloom, white and red, emerald canopies and feathered parasols — a slight breeze and fragrance filled every courtyard.",
    "At that moment Ziyun welcomed Wenze; they seated themselves below Han Wan Lou. Ziyun asked after Baoding; Wenze told his news, then asked: \"Besides Young Master Hua, what notable guests come today?\" Ziyun said: \"Several elderly gentlemen in gauze caps would have nothing to say to Young Master Hua — they care only rank and stipend — better not invite — only Zhang the Second might join — he sits outside refined circles yet pours wine well — otherwise we five alone.\"",
    "Wenze asked where Cixian was. Ziyun said: \"Jingyi rehearses today's new plays — staging and modes still grate — he corrects each passage himself — he comes soon.\" While they spoke Zhang Zhongyu arrived; Ziyun rose to greet him; Wenze welcomed him.",
    "Wenze said to Ziyun: \"Zhang the Second is thoroughly capable — sharp in every line — abroad he will shine as an official — fame and fortune await.\" Ziyun laughed: \"Fame and fortune yes — superiors delighted — ordinary folk may fare worse.\" Wenze guffawed — Zhongyu overheard and fired back pleasantries — all three laughed.",
    "After a pause footsteps rustled everywhere — one figure in sixth-rank robes rounded the artificial hill; next four retainers in caps and feathers bore a sedan-chair — Young Master Hua inside in lustrous silk and stitched gold — some twenty followers trailing — Ziyun led the party forward to greet him.",
    "It emerged that Lord Hua and Duke Xu had been deepest friends twenty years and served two campaigns together — friendship moss-thick as hill herbs, oath-bound as metal and stone. Xu Ziyun and Young Master Hua had sworn brotherhood and revived the tie between houses. Ziyun was five years elder; Young Master honored him as elder brother — courteous and yielding. At once Ziyun yielded Young Master Hua the seat of honor while servants poured tea. Young Master Hua said: \"Days ago I meant to pay respects — imperial escort duties stacked up and heat warned against disturbing you. Today cooler — we may talk half the day happily — pity one city wall divides us — we cannot carry lamps all night — hard to satisfy the heart.\" Ziyun said: \"Repeatedly you honor us — glory reaches grove and spring. I idle alone, lazy as habit — long wished to invite you yet feared official duty left no leisure — and the wall between blunts cheer. Tonight I hoped to detain you till dawn — will you lodge one night in the humble hall?\" Young Master Hua smiled: \"Your famous garden fills my dreams — I long for a full roam. Later I shall trouble your studio — not one night — I want ten days like Lord Pingyuan before this petty temper clears — today I must return — tomorrow perhaps an imperial commission waits — vulgar dust blocks refined pleasure — summer swells and the bright moon is not yet round — wait till mid-autumn for our all-night revel?\" Ziyun laughed: \"Sound — moonless nights dull drinking — no need for mid-autumn — seventh month will do — shall we fix late seventh month?\" Young Master Hua agreed: \"Cooler autumn lifts the heart — pity my grounds are cramped — less than half yours — built by no master hand — little hill-and-stream surprise — summer stays sultry — only autumn and winter suit short rests.\"",
    "\"If elder brother does not disdain plain fare, I shall send a carriage of welcome.\" Ziyun said: \"Excellent — whenever I cannot leave the city I shall trouble you. Your Western Garden is superbly laid — could it join the Eastern Garden it would be finer.\" Young Master Hua said: \"So many main halls stand between — cannot link — and the east quarter lodges many guests — mixed folk — nowhere to ornament.\" While they spoke drums and pipes sounded behind; Ziyun urged Young Master Hua inward; past the vestibule they reached Chengyin Hall steps — three men inside advanced to the gallery to greet him — all old friends — Young Master Hua exchanged bows with each.",
    "He bowed to Cixian: \"Master Jingyi took trouble to arrange these plays — how shall we watchers repay? Today we offer a few extra cups.\" Cixian laughed loudly: \"Rustic tunes may wound refined ears — if you nod once I shall gladly drain a full cup for everyone.\" All agreed it was good — wine was ready — servants bore jars forward — Ziyun poured and set seats — Young Master Hua held chief east seat with Zhongyu attending; Wenze chief west with Cixian attending; Ziyun played host beside Young Master Hua's table.",
    "Young Master Hua said: \"No further guests — only our five. Why not one table? Distance muffles talk — once opera rises speech stops.\" Wenze said: \"Then combine.\" Ziyun said: \"Good — crowded — swap to a round table — seat by seniority — avoid pushing rank.\" They agreed; servants fitted a round top and merged the banquet.",
    "The opening plays were \"Li Ling Returns to Han\" and \"The Bright Consort Enters the Pass.\" Next came \"The Talented Scholar Receives the Edict\" — principal male role — imperial wine and golden flowers bestowed, farewell money along the route — bearing proud and free, tones bold and grave — conjuring Li Bai's wandering soul entire. When singing ceased a figure emerged — guests fancied Li Bai himself had stepped down.",
    "The second bill was \"The Yang Consort Enters Shu.\" Yang Guozhong died first; Chen Yuanli instructed emperor and minister on mutual duty; the six armies thundered approval. The Bright Emperor halted at Omei inn with the consort on the tower; he blew the jade flute while she sang \"Qingping\"; peach-sleeved ladies danced \"Returning Wind\"; Li Guinian backed on eight-tone instruments — grandeur beyond telling.",
    "Those two performances ran long. Ziyun, seeing Young Master Hua's spirits soar, halted the show and summoned the ten performers still in full face-paint — each stepping forward with a huge cup. Young Master Hua refused nothing — smiled and drank — demanded others match — their capacities failed — they shrank to smaller cups — laughter rolled round after round.",
    "Everyone stared — a tray blazing with gold ingots — lucky shapes, ruyi shapes, plum shapes, water-chestnut tips — each above one tael, perhaps a hundred pieces — portioned among the ten performers. After Shanzhi handed them out the ten kowtowed thanks; Ziyun hastened thanks as well.",
    "By now the clock showed nearly the end of the wei hour; the banquet was cleared. Young Master Hua rose and said: \"I came to stroll the garden — today again there was no time — yet the lotus must be seen.\" Ziyun had the feast carried to the Chanting-Autumn Waterside Pavilion, ordered lotus-gathering boats prepared, and told the ten performers to dress as maidens gathering lotus and paddle into the pool; guests were shown to the pavilion. Young Master Hua and company stepped inside — lotus stretched on every side, red perfume thick, emerald leaves layered — a world of color and scent. They sat again to wine. Four or five little boats slipped to the pool's heart; aboard sat the celebrated dans, costumed in long skirts and short sleeves, lotus faces above peach cheeks, threading through the blossoms — each lovely profile half-lost among the flowers. Along the shore lay a craft with brocade sail and silk hawser; within, an ensemble struck up the full wind-and-percussion \"ten-fold.\" The gatherers sang the \"Lotus-Gathering\" song — voices tender and winding — heard like midnight song, seen like river goddesses at play — as if Zhang Lihua had dressed as an immortal and Zhu Gui'er played Chang'e — all grew dizzily happy, nearly rolling from their seats. Only Young Master Hua's high spirits mounted: he said to Ziyun: \"Earlier plays never finished — that one alone took half the day. Why not sing 'Golden Strand' again and dance 'Rainbow Skirts' — let each show a glimpse of his art — worthy of elder brother's choosing colors and tones — let the troupe give their utmost and not waste the stage — what say you?\"",
    "Ziyun laughed: \"Exactly my wish.\" He had the whole troupe summoned up. Hearing the order, they plied orchid oars toward the pavilion, landed, and drew up in goose formation beyond the railing. Young Master Hua called four men in by name: Huifang, Qinyan, Baozhu, Sulan. To them he said: \"In 'Immortals on Mount Emei' just now the whole cast stood forth but not every gesture appeared. Each of you name a piece you do best.\" The four thought and each named one. Ziyun said: \"Those are not yet your acme — only Meixiang and Xiangwan's 'Exclusive Claim' and Yaoqing and Yuyi's 'Startled Dream' and 'Seeking the Dream' are peerless — no one else performs them — pity they overlap.\" Wenze said: \"Why not pair the two sides and sing together — each perfecting his part — pearls strung on one string?\" Cixian and Zhongyu both said: \"Excellent — though evenly matched there will still be shades to savor.\" Young Master Hua laughed: \"Fresh — I have never seen two sing the same piece together — even 'Seeking the Dream' may be doubled.\" Ziyun relayed orders to the troupe to wait in the wings and had tables shifted forward. Baozhu and Qinyan withdrew to dress. Soon rose grieving bamboo and piercing strings — bright as bells. Young Master Hua watched Qinyan emerge from the east — like bright moon first rising on a breeze — those steps like spring clouds drifting toward heaven's edge of longing. Baozhu came from the west — like a shy bloom about to open, dawn dew still clinging — steps like willow strands trailing into crimson dust. When they sang, both voices turned and flowed, clear and round; amid green trees and kingfisher bamboo fledgling phoenix answered fledgling — each word honey-warm as jade, each tone shaking soul and bowels. One cast idle autumn glances, neck bent low; the other drew brows faintly knit, spring stars briefly meeting. The whole company sat entranced — hearts adrift, eyes drunk.",
    "Ziyun only nodded and smiled. Young Master Hua smacked the table and cried: \"Splendid! Splendid! Today I first believe peerless beauty exists under heaven — I deeply regret filling embroidered curtains with Momu and Wuyan look-alikes.\" He added loudly: \"I blame Elder Brother Duxiang for hoarding goddesses — selfishly feasting his eyes — only after your fill do you invite guests to pick up what fragrance remains — today you drink ten huge cups before anything else.\"",
    "He ordered Lin Shanzhi to bring his own great jade wine-cup. Shanzhi saw the hour late and knew his master's temper — once roused he would go day or night — though he answered aloud he stood frozen, eyes on Ziyun. Ziyun took the hint; knowing his drinking could not match, he said: \"My shallow capacity truly cannot stomach more — let my door cup stand for your great dipper.\" Young Master Hua still refused until Cixian, Wenze, and Zhongyu mediated: \"Not only Duxiang — none of us could match those cups — fine him three small cups instead.\" Knowing Ziyun drank little, Young Master Hua yielded. They made Ziyun drain three cups in succession while he himself, needing no urging, emptied a dozen large cups and still shouted praise — forced Wenze through three more and Cixian and Zhongyu five or six. Suddenly he turned to Baozhu and Qinyan: \"Sing on — when done, sing again.\" He studied them again minutely and told the company: \"These two each have marvels — like five sparrows and six swallows, weight in balance — Lady Zhao and Consort Yang, lean and plump each right. Baozhu's tenderness stirs pity at sight; Qinyan's bones shine like jade — who could bear to send him away? Apart each is supreme — together both shine. Elder Brother Duxiang — today you have truly gladdened me.\" Ziyun saw Young Master Hua somewhat drunk and knew his habit — at height of mood nothing could stop him — yet could hardly check him — resigned himself to drinking till dawn.",
    "Meanwhile on stage the two finished singers were not permitted to descend — they must sing again. Baozhu, seeing Young Master Hua's fervor, rejoiced inwardly; seeing him watch once and demand again, he poured still more grace into gesture — both to bind the master's eye and give Duxiang face. Qinyan inwardly resisted — Young Master Hua could not be offended — he swallowed shame — and resented sharing the stage only with Yuan Baozhu as rival, striving to outdo him in skill and feeling. He recalled Young Master's face bore something of Yuxiang — remembered that day performing \"Startled Dream\" when Yuxiang appeared — hearts had recognized each other across the hall — pity Yuxiang was not here today — else these two songs would not be wasted. \"Let me treat Young Master Hua as Yuxiang on that balcony — replay that scene — perhaps spirit moves spirit and Yuxiang dreams me — even if he does not see me, it is as if I saw him.\" With that he poured himself into every glance — sang again with utter abandon.",
    "All sat transported — only Lin Shanzhi, watching his master's infatuation, seethed inwardly yet dared not show it. The hour pressed toward you — linger longer and the city gates would shut — yet he could not urge aloud — slipped out and told retainers to hold the gate open, then returned and stood behind Young Master Hua, eyes pleading at Ziyun; everyone understood but none wished to prompt. When Young Master Hua stepped out briefly to relieve himself, Shanzhi bowed low to Ziyun and whispered: \"Beg Second Master persuade our lord to drink less and return soon — the gates will close — palace duty waits — delay is no joke.\" Ziyun nodded: \"Quite right — and it is time.\" Young Master Hua returned and saw Shanzhi whispering: \"Still early?\" Shanzhi said: \"The watch reads you hour proper.\" Young Master Hua said: \"This watch runs fast.\" Ziyun said: \"Since brother is so merry — as I said this morning we should revel to third or fourth watch — stay tonight — do not re-enter the city — Qianzhou and Zhongyu live outside the walls — they fear no gate.\" Hearing both an invitation to lodge and the remark about outsiders needing no gate, Young Master Hua wavered — charmed by the pavilion yet uneasy about staying.",
    "Twilight neared lamp-lighting — stay or go tore at him; his train stood in neat ranks below the steps — he half wished to leave; Baozhu and Qinyan were finishing their song — he said to Ziyun: \"I had better return to the city.\" Shanzhi cut in: \"Gates will shut — if you go, hurry.\" Young Master Hua had no choice — rose, dressed formal wear, thanked Ziyun and took leave of the company.",
    "By now Baozhu and Qinyan had washed off greasepaint and came to see guests off. Young Master Hua clasped Qinyan's hand: \"Your singing tops the capital — rest a day then visit my mansion — I have much to ask in detail.\" From his waist he unclasped a Han jade paired-dragon pendant with purse and gave it to Qinyan — Qinyan bowed thanks. Young Master Hua took two steps, turned back to Baozhu: \"You two are matched opponents — hard to declare a winner. You are Duxiang's darling — that is why you seldom come to my house.\" He asked Ziyun: \"Second Brother — may I give him a gift?\" Ziyun smiled: \"As you will — why ask me?\" Young Master Hua undid another jade plaque for Baozhu — Baozhu thanked him. All ten performers escorted them out; Young Master Hua reeled yet turned again and again toward Qinyan, Baozhu, Huifang, Sulan and the rest: \"When idle, visit often.\" At Han Wan Lou he bowed once more to Ziyun and guests, boarded his sedan chair — Shanzhi and Eight Ling aside, sixteen personal attendants and five titled servants shouldered the poles and flew over hill and grove. The ten performers saw them to the garden gate and bowed farewell. Young Master Hua shifted to his green-canopied carriage and nodded repeated injunctions to the actors; followers mounted — the driver feared the gate and lashed once — the carriage flew; luckily Shanzhi had held the gate or they would have missed entry.",
    "Young Master Hua's ride back to the city needs no further tale.",
    "Here the ten performers entered; Ziyun had them change into plain clothes, swapped for a larger round table, cleared scraps and ordered fresh dishes. Wenze said: \"Today Xinbei had his soul stolen away — I never saw him cling so.\" Ziyun answered: \"In his heart it still was not enough — I feared only he might fall ill from excess — luckily his nature is vigorous — drunk one night — sober next — no harm.\"",
    "Of today's ten acts the clearest triumph was Qinyan's — next Baozhu. Baozhu glowed inwardly; only Qinyan stayed cool as frost. Ziyun asked Qinyan: \"Today you gained another true connoisseur — Young Master Hua seldom praises — sing for him again at his mansion and your name will ride highest.\"",
    "Cixian said: \"Young Master Hua truly cherishes beauty — outside gossip lies — today he was warm throughout — no spoiled-young-master air. Yunong — do not stay too cold with people.\" As all spoke Qinyan seemed about to answer —",
    "Ziyun knew Qinyan's blunt tongue had nettled Zhongyu and explained: \"Yuyong drank too much today — Yaoqing, take him aside to play until the wine sleeps off then return.\" Baozhu drew Qinyan inward and urged: \"You spoke too straight — that Zhang the Second holds grudges — mind yourself.\""
  ],
  26: [
    "Word has it that when Young Master Hua reached his mansion upon returning to the city, lamps had already been lit for quite some time. He stopped briefly in his wife's quarters; Lady Hua asked after the pleasures of the Garden of Contentment, and Young Master Hua spoke of them in outline. Then he summoned two young maids with lanterns and proceeded to his bedchamber in Star Canopy Arbor. Beneath the lamplight appeared the Ten Pearls—all dressed alike in loosely cut white satin jackets, hair done up in Hemp Maid buns with long braids trailing behind, each with a pomander of jasmine pinned at the crown, emerald-trimmed gauze leggings below, faintly revealing three-inch crimson slippers. Seeing the master enter, they lined both sides with smiling faces. Young Master Hua surveyed them once and asked: \"Why have you all changed costume today?\" One of them reported: \"Today Madame went to the ancestral temple's Guanyin pavilion to burn incense—she ordered us servants to dress like this and follow her out.\" The master seated himself. The Pearls were all fifteen or sixteen, broadly matching in appearance, neither above nor below the others. Mingzhu first brought chilled plum soup; Zhangzhu fanned lightly with a goose-feather fan. Zhenzhu stepped forward and removed his boots, swapping them for beaded cloud-step slippers. Hezhu helped him change into a sheer gauze jacket; they all stood by in pairs. Baozhu said: \"Has Master eaten? Shall I bid the inner kitchen prepare something?\" Young Master Hua replied: \"I drank too much today—I feel thirsty. After the evening drum, prepare that ledebouriella porridge recipe I gave you the other day—pair it with those flower distillates and fruit powders; boil with alternating strong and mild heat; do not expose it to copper utensils for even a minute or two; brew it yourself—do not let those old fussy hands touch it—they're filthy. Hot as it is now, we're in the season of dispersion—use sparingly ledebouriella distillate and mint distillate; add generously rose, scented-rice, lotus, and osmanthus distillates—powder of poria, lotus seed, rare maize mush, cubilose—all in the proportions on the list.\" Baozhu agreed, drew Huazhu along, blended the ingredients, fetched a bowl of scented rice and a jug of melted snow-water, skipped the main kitchen altogether, and under the gallery of the octagonal glazed pavilion outside their master's chamber lit a charcoal brazier and brewed slowly in a silver kettle. Huazhu crouched nearby, trailing a scarlet sash half along the floor, saying: \"Master looked drunk tonight—always staring at us—and then laughing for no reason by himself.\" Baozhu said: \"Yesterday I heard Madame say that come autumn she's taking you in as concubine.\" Huazhu spat and retorted: \"If anyone's taken in first it'll be you—you're clever as a squirrel and suck up every errand—you may not last till autumn at all.\" Baozhu gave Huazhu a push; Huazhu tumbled over, legs splayed—her foot clipped the kettle and nearly overturned it—she scrambled up and pinned Baozhu's shoulders trying to wrestle him down; the pair dissolved in laughter.",
    "Meanwhile Aizhu emerged carrying an amber gauze lantern: \"Nearly time for the evening drum—we still must send for Lin Shanzhi.\" Baozhu asked: \"What's Lin Shanzhi wanted for?\" Aizhu answered: \"How should I know? Surely something important.\" Her wooden-soled slippers clicked as she hurried to the corner gate and found the stewardess; that woman found the inner gatekeeper, then the outer attendant's quarters, tracked down Lin Shanzhi, and said: \"Master wants you.\" Lin Shanzhi had been cooling off in the courtyard—two lackeys beside him airing tobacco and fanning. Shanzhi donned his long robe, belted it, lit a small horn lantern, followed the gatekeeper inward, halted by the glazed pavilion, greeted Aizhu and company, and asked: \"What's Master summoning me for?\"",
    "Aizhu lifted the lantern toward Shanzhi's face and chuckled: \"You've drunk yourself pink—you'll earn a tongue-lashing upstairs.\" Shanzhi smiled: \"When did I drink? It's your red lantern tinting people's faces—you accuse me of drunkenness.\" Aizhu smiled too and led Shanzhi inward at an easy pace. Inside they heard Young Master jesting with the maids. Aizhu went first: \"Shanzhi's here.\" Young Master summoned him upward. Shanzhi stood outside the window; Young Master sat cross-legged on the drunkard's couch—four Pearls beside him. At sight of Shanzhi Young Master said: \"Go invite Secretary Wei to Quiet-Green Retreat—I'll cross over from here and speak with him.\" Shanzhi replied: \"The drum has sounded—the east garden gate is locked—that is, the superintendent's triple gate is bolted—unless it's urgent, wait till morning—calling him through two or three more gates would take till nearly second watch—the secretaries must be retiring too.\" Lin Shanzhi guessed summoning Wei Pincai was inconsequential—probably chatter about today's opera—and blocked the errand on purpose. Young Master considered and saw no pressing matter; he conceded: \"If the gates are locked, tomorrow won't be late either.\" After a pause he added: \"Baozhu's opera—first time I'd seen him—and so unexpectedly superb. Why don't they ever come to the mansion?\"",
    "Shanzhi said: \"On new and full moons they arrive early—only the gate assumes Master hasn't risen and turns them away. Troupe folk calling to pay respects don't sign the gate register. As for Qinyan—his teacher once brought him too—but they never came inside.\" Young Master asked: \"Whose disciple is Qinyan?\" Shanzhi: \"Changqing's.\" Young Master: \"Changqing—wasn't your own teacher also named Changqing?\" Shanzhi assented: \"Yes—this servant began in the Lianjin troupe, then transferred to Dengchun.\" Young Master: \"Why switch to Dengchun?\" Shanzhi: \"That Changqing's temper was harsh—this servant offended him—he traded me to Dengchun's Xiufang. After Xiufang graduated he bought Qinyan—barely half a year ago.\"",
    "Young Master asked: \"What do you make of Qinyan?\" Shanzhi said nothing. Young Master repeated the question; Shanzhi answered: \"Fine enough—but Second Master Xu favors him—and word is he won't oblige callers outside.\" Young Master: \"Second Master Xu savors Yuan Baozhu—not him.\" Shanzhi: \"They say Second Master likes him nearly as much as Baozhu—and that he's laid out several thousand taels on him already.\" Young Master fell silent. Presently he said: \"The other day Secretary Wei praised Qinyan highly—I only saw him today. Some Young Master Mei is closest to him—Second Master Xu is the pretense.\" Shanzhi: \"The inner truth escapes this servant—today was my first glimpse of Qinyan too.\" Young Master continued: \"You too came up inside this gate—of today's joint piece Searching the Dream—which was better?\" Shanzhi considered and replied: \"Judging opera one weighs bearing and gesture—those two resemble each other—but for singing Baozhu's is practiced—Qinyan's first round was stiff; second improved somewhat.\" Young Master nodded: \"He's new—Baozhu's sung two or three years—naturally smoother. By looks I'd say Qinyan—something immortal in his bones—different from ordinary men.\" Shanzhi lowered his head without reply.",
    "Zhangzhu fanned while watching master and Shanzhi—her mind wandered from the fan—it slipped from her hand; Mingzhu tittered; Zhangzhu flushed, snatched it up. Young Master laughed: \"Have you never heard opera—such talk that your hearts fly away with the show? Another day I'll have that whole troupe in for a full-day performance for Madame—you'll all owe them thanks.\" Aizhu piped up: \"What troupe beats ours at home?\" Young Master smiled: \"You're ten too—have you play sheng roles while they play dan—join one scene—and you'll grasp how others excel.\" The Pearls reddened and murmured: \"We can't perform—there's the Eight Ling troupe for that.\" Young Master laughed: \"Learn and you will—women players aren't rare.\" Shanzhi smiled faintly. After standing while longer without further orders he withdrew—three or four Pearls still clustered by the kettle. Shanzhi exchanged a few words and left. Fragrant porridge finished, homemade refreshments followed; Young Master cooled awhile and retired—the Pearls each to their rooms.",
    "Next morning Young Master still groggy from wine—physically slack—rose late—not until si hour proper did he wash—maids dressed his hair and garments. Lady Hua feared wine had harmed him—sent medicinal ginseng soup by a maid—he drank it. Baozhu entered to report: \"Shanzhi waits outside—whether to summon Secretary Wei as ordered last night for breakfast at Quiet-Green Retreat?\" Young Master hesitated briefly: \"Tell him invite Secretary Wei—breakfast at Quiet-Green Retreat.\" Baozhu left. Young Master visited Lady Hua—her morning toilette complete—maids flanking her. Light brows, modest rouge—double coils glossy green—high chignon piled like clouds—she faintly resembled Su Huifang—he sat, exchanged pleasantries, declared he'd dine in her quarters, recounted yesterday's opera—the Eight Ling troupe not one tenth their match—and remarked her likeness to Huifang. Lady Hua inwardly bristled but held her tongue. Ordinarily they harmonized like qin and se—deeply devoted—Young Master loved luxury yet wasn't debauched.",
    "Lady Hua several times proposed taking Huazhu and Baozhu as concubines—Young Master always refused: \"Once they're concubines the charm fades—better serve a few years then marry them off handsome youths—a meritorious deed. Moreover—were Madame plain I'd seek comfort among maids—but Madame being what she is—even lovely maids can't compare—like miscellaneous blooms—pretty on their own—yet beside peonies on the terrace they're mere awkward mimicry—maids playing mistress—only growing more embarrassed.\" Lady Hua delighted in this—never suspected infidelity however lavish Young Master grew—the Ten Pearls tumbling daily together aroused no jealousy—Lin Shanzhi, Feng Zipei suspicion's shadow only—nothing proved—temperaments differ—not like Xi Eleven obsessed with carnal grading.",
    "Young Master breakfasted with Lady Hua—talk and laughter carried them past noon—forgetting Wei Pincai waited at Quiet-Green Retreat. Lin Shanzhi went to summon Pincai—Pincai risen long since—about to dine—when word came Young Master invited breakfast at Quiet-Green Retreat—elation like palace roll-call—boots hurriedly donned—fresh gown—round fan—swaggering—without briefing Zhang or Gu—followed Shanzhi from the garden—flattering along the way—\"Old Shan,\" \"young brother,\" shoulder to shoulder—until Quiet-Green Retreat—mind on duty—father summons without excuse—eyes never strayed to scenery—straight inside. Four lackeys sat beneath the gallery—rose at sight of Pincai—Shanzhi asked: \"Any word Master emerges soon?\" They answered: \"Silence—we don't know if he'll come out.\" Shanzhi: \"Secretary Wei wait—I'll inquire.\" Gone. Pincai studied the appointments—unspeakably sumptuous—finer than the west salon—windows, rails, screens carved hollow with miniature landscapes—figures inlaid gem by gem—almost jade pillars jade beams—first glimpse to widen his eyes. A full hour passed—no Young Master—lackeys refreshed tea repeatedly—Pincai's intestines rinsed hollow—belly rumbling like hungry kite—could only sit and endure.",
    "Lin Shanzhi meanwhile waited outside Crimson Wash Pavilion—chatting with the Pearls—unable to ascend and disturb. Zengzhu said: \"Upstairs earlier I heard Master dining with Madame—talk running hot—likely not emerging.\" Shanzhi: \"What's to be done—Wei summoned since dawn—over an hour—I'm famished too—have you eaten?\" Mingzhu: \"We're done—leftovers remain—unless you mind eating—hard to guess his timing.\" Shanzhi: \"Dear sister—your scraps exceed my fortune—I'd be honored—how dare I disdain?\" Aizhu: \"Silver tongue—I wager your eyes hunger too.\" She led Shanzhi to a side room—summer fare needed no heating—meat and veg laid out—Shanzhi ate, wiped hands, resumed joking with maids—still no Young Master. Past wei hour proper Shanzhi fretted: \"Will he or won't he—keeping someone waiting—Dear Aizhu run word—Wei still waits at Quiet Retreat.\" Aizhu: \"I won't carry word—you go yourself.\" Shanzhi: \"Dear sister—could I reach inside I'd not beg you.\" Delay dragged—Aizhu teased—Hezhu relented and entered—half an hour later footsteps—Young Master emerged—he and Madame had chatted till exhaustion—he'd lain on her bed—who'd dare wake him—until near wei hour's end he woke.",
    "Seeing Hezhu inquire Young Master recalled morning's appointment—already late—supper only—slipped through a side gate opening onto Quiet Retreat's courtyard—only one courtyard apart—Shanzhi hurried ahead to receive him—Pincai stepped forth to the window—Young Master arrived—Pincai bowed—Young Master seized his hand: \"Meant you this morning—yesterday's wine overslept me—kept you waiting—have you eaten breakfast?\" Pincai lied he'd eaten—Shanzhi pitied half-day fast and said: \"Sir arrived si hour dawn—likely no breakfast yet.\" Young Master scolded Shanzhi: \"What's your office—can't feed a guest?\" Shanzhi: \"This servant too entered si dawn—waiting within.\" Young Master ordered pastries fetched—Shanzhi sprinted—soon eight refined dishes filled a kang table—Young Master urged Pincai eat—then recounted yesterday's eight dan entrance—Qin and Bao duetting Searching the Dream—and continued:",
    "\"I lavished effort buying eight—forming a troupe intended to eclipse outsiders—who'd guess outsiders eclipse us instead—have you seen their acting?\" Pincai caught the drift—flattered upward: \"Seen them—overshadowing outsiders isn't hard—fine flowers needn't crowd—buy the choicest few—that suffices.\" Inwardly: \"He fancies Qinyan—little knows Qinyan's heart hangs on Mei Gengxiang—unlikely to favor you—or Qinyan's snobbery scorns me—inside this mansion he'd change—or not—once admitted he'd never glimpse Gengxiang again—or Qinyan's eccentric temper unknown to Young Master—in time disgust follows—better drag him inside—two years suffering—then my spite vents.\" Aloud: \"Why not purchase Baozhu and Qinyan—join your eight—make ten—won't that beat outside troupes?\"",
    "Young Master said: \"I hear both are Duxiang's favorites—hard to wrest them.\" Pincai: \"Duxiang cherishes Baozhu—not truly Qinyan—if Master likes him—I know him—often patronize—teacher Changqing loves silver—learning Master wants—he'll crawl to oblige—deliver him gift-wrapped.\" Young Master hesitated—Xu Ziyun weighed on him—nine only if Qinyan joined—Baozhu impossible—thus wavering—Pincai argued and cajoled till Young Master stirred: \"Go tomorrow—probe—if unwilling drop it—even buying later—you trail Duxiang—already second best.\" Pride—loathe seeming to copy Duxiang—supped with Pincai—table talk piled praise on Qinyan's gifts—commended Qiguan—until drum hour they parted.",
    "Next morning after breakfast Pincai took Four and a large saddle-cart—out the city found Ye Maolin—Maolin rode with him to Changqing's—ran into Zhang Zhongyu—both halted carts—Maolin yielded—Pincai stepped out to speak—Zhongyu asked—Pincai explained Young Master's commission—Zhongyu said: \"No wonder other day so generous—over hundred gold—gave his own jade pendant to Qinyan and Baozhu.\"",
    "He whispered in Pincai's ear at length—Ye Maolin couldn't hear—only saw Pincai nod: \"I know my mind—once inside—won't he bend?\" Further words—then each went his way.",
    "At Qinyan's door Maolin alighted—entered with Pincai—Changqing home—seated them—sized Pincai up—Maolin's escort marked him minor—cool greeting—Maolin said: \"Secretary Wei—Young Master Hua's secretary—closest to Young Master—heard your fame—comes especially—business to discuss.\" Changqing bloomed obsequious—Secretary this Secretary that—seeing Pincai clever—courted eagerly: \"Young Master Hua favors me beyond measure—two disciples inside—grace heaven-high earth-deep—inexpressible.\" Tea served—more talk—Changqing opened the opium lamp—invited lie-down—Maolin: \"I don't partake—you host Secretary Wei—easier talking.\" Pincai: \"Beginner—can't prepare pipe.\" Changqing roasted a prime bowl—passed to Pincai—Pincai returned pipe: \"Outsider—no courtesy smoke back.\" Pincai asked Qinyan's situation lately—Changqing: \"Fine lad—clever—other day sang at Second Master Xu's garden—your patron Young Master—rewarded ten gold ingots—over fourteen liang—seven hundred strings worth—Second Master Xu piled gifts himself—Young Master gave his purse ornament too—yellow-red jade—I asked Degu Zhai's Sha Huizi—two hundred strings—without boy's flattery—who'd pamper him so?\"",
    "Another puff offered—Pincai took—continued: \"Today's business—I consult you—yesterday our patron saw his Searching the Dream—besotted—praised all day—wants him in the mansion—could you bear parting?\"",
    "Changqing listened and pondered a moment: \"Secretary—not that I refuse the honor—the lad's pitiful—only arrived tenth month last—I bought him—quick study—handsome—Huifang Baozhu at their fame barely rival him—you may judge:\"",
    "Since twelfth month's first stage debut—seven months elapsed—Second Master Xu alone poured oceans—\"This much—\" Changqing stretched his palm—\"my purse gapes—spent as fast as earned—you see twenty mouths—we live on him—send him mansion—he thrives—I founder—fifteen years—five till graduation—won't he earn tens of thousands—how relinquish—unlike Lin Shanzhi—surly temper—spoilt—vexed me—I swapped Dengchun's Xiufang—Xiufang graduated eight thousand strings—all know—Qinyan tops Xiufang manifold—Secretary plead—Changqing's lone fine disciple—lifetime reliance—other boys worthless—costume losses—few wine nights monthly—scrapes erupt—\" Pincai began replying—Ye Maolin smiled stroking beard: \"Old Qing—things negotiate—Young Master Hua's ways—you know—others crawl to enter—he seeks you—your fortune—hit his fancy—not one lifetime—two—later you enter mansion—minor post—minor rank—face—beats opera rice—\" Pincai: \"Maestro Ye speaks plain—glance rewards gold—serious hire—would he stint—lifetime secured—early graduation pays more—late pays less—fourteen fifteen—body uncertain—bad turn in year or two—then what—thousands wasted—I urge reflection—anything negotiable—no injustice—\" Changqing listened smoking dozen bowls—sat up: \"Sounds fair—discuss—I must ask his will—\" Pincai laughed: \"Old Qing—bright folk hide nothing—you know Qinyan's temper—besides Second Master Xu who favors him—who obliges whom—offend Second Master—\" cold laugh—\"then lifelong reliance reverses—home—you miss why he fell ill—Mei Young Master—everyone clicks—wine with Mei pleases—without Mei tears—everyone tires—you blind—protect disciple face—truth ugly—bank on Mei Young Master's lift—cock laying eggs—think—is my counsel kind or cruel?\" Changqing resented Qinyan's temper—price inflation—truth struck—couldn't argue: \"Boy's stubborn—you're glass lantern seeing through—whatever—I'll lean on him—numbers don't work—no deal—\" Maolin pulled Changqing window-side whispered: \"Name your price—for Wei to report—\" Changqing thinking Young Master legendary sucker—wanted ten thousand—could ask five six thousand—whispered Maolin—Maolin told Pincai—Pincai shook head: \"Hard—a boy ten thousand—not miracle goods—four five thousand suits—\" Maolin: \"Ballpark—best actors graduate three four thousand strings—twice plus—\" Changqing shook head—finally: \"At that—impossible—and half year only—money aside—heart won't release—I never wished him gone—\" wiped eyes sham tears—Pincai thought: \"Crafty devil—sky price—how tell Young Master—no suspicion myself—others suspect graft—must crush with bluster—\" feigned rage standing: \"Splendid—grow rich yourself—I meant kindness—you bite hand—few days you crawl begging—worthless—\" stormed out.",
    "Ye Maolin eyed Changqing—seeing rage Changqing smiled: \"Secretary calm—sit—discuss—\" Pincai: \"Discuss what—no patience hollow talk—Maolin sit—I'm gone—\" marched out—Maolin chased—clutched Pincai—Pincai whispered: \"Six Harmonies Inn wait—\" shook free—vanished cart—Changqing couldn't escort—dragged Maolin inside—Maolin: \"His wrath—speak plain—Young Master offends ill—Wei returns gossip—storm brews—how then—\" Changqing: \"Not dull—my cash-tree—can't bear—must ask his will—two days word—beg curry favor—reply him—maybe maybe not—\" Maolin heard little flex—carted away—found Pincai—repeated Changqing verbatim—Pincai helpless—returned had Shanzhi report couldn't find Changqing—try later—whether Qinyan's fate—next installment."
  ],
  27: [
    "As for Wei Pincai returning from Changqing's—he'd caught the slippery tone—a ransom like ten thousand taels of silver.",
    "He meant to think of a way to harry him—leave him no peace—until he submitted to entering the mansion. Pincai had no other schemes—once he looked for Zhang Zhongyu but missed him. He planned again to send the carter Ji San and the boys to kick up trouble—but wanted to delay a few days—or they'd smell the plot. Young Master Hua had been enthusiastic on a whim—besides his pleasures were inexhaustible—he would hardly fix on one person alone.",
    "This installment turns to another man. Earlier you heard of him—now you must meet him in person. Who? Xi Eleven. He'd hidden a month with the Changlu salt administration—just then a fleet of foreign ships arrived—his family being foreign-trade merchants—with old ties—he wired twenty thousand taels—and threw in five thousand taels' worth of foreign goods—then was flush again. The wooden barrel affair had broken—the scandal had cooled—so he returned to the capital—and raised hell as before.",
    "Xi Eleven came from a great clan—had he no proper name? His formal name was Xi Zhengshen—but folk had called him Eleven so long it stuck. In Lingnan slang \"eleven\" sounds like \"earth\"—so they dubbed him Xi the Rustic. First entering the capital he'd spoken thick Cantonese—barely intelligible—now he was sliding into mandarin speech. He kept company with two others on good terms—Zhang Zhongyu and Pan Qiguan. Zhongyu haunted the bustling haunts—flattered the account shops—seeing Xi Eleven's wave-rider spending—had ferreted out his family's bottom line—and befriended him thoroughly. When Xi's silver ran dry and loans were due—Zhongyu went to Pan San's silver shop for him—a ten-thousand-tael note—nine-tenths actually paid out—Zhongyu skimmed one thousand—Xi received only eight thousand—but when silver was wanted—he had to swallow it. Now that money returned—he paid that loan first—back in the capital with nothing to do—only eating wine and watching opera daily with Zhongyu and Pan. The three were cut from one cloth—their intimacy deepened daily. Pan too loved \"carriage\" gossip—when dry-road pleasures were discussed—Xi counted him a soul mate. Compare Xi with Pan—Pan was somewhat better—repulsive though he looked—his nature was soft—first timid—second his wife fierce—third he was rich—feared being shaken down—lust in heart yet tiny courage—never dared indulge—that nearly counted as virtue. Xi Eleven—riding wealth and influence—was utterly lawless—people nicknamed him the Smoke-Scorched Grand Divinity—with hangers-on egging him—nothing sacred. His fixed notion: linger in the capital barely a year—once selected—leave the capital—unless he debauched to the limit—folk would sneer—unworthy of a gentleman-official's son. Lately awaiting selection—he'd hired a clerk for lawsuits and accounts—recommended by Director Wang—twelve hundred taels a year salary—already lodged together—and began playing sycophant in advance. Guess who—that same Mr. Ji from the dung-cart—seeing Xi due for posting—a Zhili department magistrate—a fat stint—one or two years could yield a fortune—and knowing Xi a lavish muddle-headed son—the yamen work would surely fall to him—he'd begged Sun Liangong to speak to Wang Wenhui—and settled at once. Birds of a feather—another sewer-raker—matching stench—within days he'd read his patron's temper—set out to curry favor—and had already lent Ba Yingguan several times—Xi was delighted—Ba Yingguan having served grandees—before the clerk grew arrogant—got new robes pressed—felt splendid—Ji Liangxuan begging him urgent favors now got grudging half-service—not the old obedient ease.",
    "Enough digression. One day Zhang Zhongyu breakfasted at Xi Eleven's lodgings—host and two guests summoned two young actors. Zhongyu chased coin not flesh—in those circles he feigned manners—never indulged truly—while Xi and Ji—without this—had no hobby—Xi Eleven especially low—even during one meal had to slip inside twice—once only one boy—now Ba Yingguan added—even more devoted than Chunlan. Ba Yingguan's skin though dark—sleek and glossy—the oil trick—so lovers swarmed—Ji Liangxuan drunk had told people so.",
    "That day over wine Xi Eleven called Chunlan inside once—emerged sat a while—then called Ba Yingguan in. Zhongyu guessed errands—chatted with Liangxuan. The two actors—Rongguan and Chunlin—were Xi's usual calls. Rongguan signaled Chunlin—Chunlin smiled—Liangxuan too rolled his eyes—Zhongyu glimpsed it—didn't grasp—didn't ask. Rongguan suddenly asked Zhongyu: \"You know a patron surnamed Wei—I met him first coming to the capital—nothing special then—other day at Master Fu San's—grand saddle hot carriage—lackeys mounted—what office does he hold now?\" Zhongyu: \"No office yet—secretary at Young Master Hua's—struck silver—naturally plush.\" Liangxuan: \"I hear Young Master Hua's house tops wealth short of the throne—true?\"",
    "Zhongyu laughed: \"Outside gossip. Still—Hua lands span forty-odd estates—annual rent rivals a prefecture's grain taxes—wealth indeed.\" Liangxuan nodded: \"Our patron mentions often—Young Master Hua is his father's generation uncle—Lord Hua was my old patron governor's teacher—such connection—yet our patron won't cultivate—I've urged visits—patron says that was army promotion ties—Young Master Hua was a child—wouldn't recognize—won't go—same with Xu Zhongtang now governor-general at Guangdong—same army bond—only Second Young Master remains in capital—other day I saw him—seven-eight horses trailing a flying-eave carriage—looks destined for governor rank—our patron still won't visit—who knows his temper.\" Zhongyu laughed: \"Second Master Xu is lavish indeed—pairs with Young Master Hua—for your patron I begged and strained—he doesn't even know—I didn't tell—by rights your patron owes me heavy thanks.\" Liangxuan pressed what matter—Zhongyu smiled: \"You'll learn—no need now.\" Xi Eleven emerged—sliding in grass sandals—triple-dyed fragrant-cloud trousers—pheasant-pattern ramie jacket—Ba Yingguan behind with black lacquer foreign fan—pattering heavy-light laughter—Liangxuan rose—Zhongyu nodded—Xi seated—Zhongyu asked: \"Busy today?\"",
    "Xi smiled then said: \"Small errands—cleared.\" Added: \"Sorry to leave you—few more cups?\" Zhongyu: \"Enough wine.\" Xi: \"Good words—two more rounds—we'll finger-guess.\" Zhongyu: \"Fine.\" Xi guessed ten rounds with Zhongyu Liangxuan Rongguan Chunlin—early calls clear—later bizarre yowls—Cantonese guessing sounds worst—like slaughtering dogs and ducks.",
    "Guessing done—idle talk—Zhongyu suddenly asked Xi: \"There's a prime actor called Qinyan lodging at Autumn-Water Hall—teacher Changqing—have you met him?\" Xi: \"Not seen—heard he's good.\" Zhongyu began—Rongguan cut in: \"Good how—only two-three plays—summon him to pour wine—won't speak whole feast—pour for him—never happens.\" Chunlin: \"Such airs—visit his house—never receives—even Wang Jiqing Li Chunfang of old—today's stars Yuan Baozhu Su Huifang—never such pretense—only seats those he favors—those he dislikes—ignored outright—gifts—no thanks—never bows.\" Xi: \"Such an actor hasn't met me—met me—I'd curse whore-born—could he bite off my balls?\" Zhongyu sneered: \"Forget you Xi the Rustic—your two elder patron friends—famous young lords—couldn't bend him—often ate his temper—you'd never cross his threshold—dream of seeing him.\" Liangxuan: \"How so—I don't believe—won't a grandee's silver tempt him?\" Zhongyu: \"Others—silver smokes him—this cub—silver won't move.\" Xi: \"Preposterous—don't spin tall tales—watch me go—he'll come out—treat me fine.\"",
    "Rongguan: \"Unlikely—maybe a glimpse counts as favor—treat you well—never—I've never seen him warm—even to great officials—cold. His junior disciples Tianfu Tianshou butter up—ugly faces—folk dislike them—teacher Cao Changqing—odd temper—loves only silver—silver in hand—ignores people.\" Xi refused belief—said to Zhongyu: \"Wait—come with me—see how it is?\" Zhongyu: \"I'll go anywhere but there—and other day I cursed him.\" They ate—sat—Zhongyu left—the two actors carried on awhile—then departed.",
    "Xi Eleven overnight—next morning after breakfast—remembering Zhongyu's boasts about Qinyan's fierceness—had to test—after opium—with Ji Liangxuan—Chunlan Ba Yingguan—fresh gauze jacket—carriage—Chunlan and Ba Yingguan on the footboards—Liangxuan hired another cart—to Autumn-Water Hall.",
    "Meanwhile Qinyan was miserable—Changqing seeing Pincai storm off—though he'd begged Ye Maolin to mediate—no word returned—uneasy—remembering May two men raising row—four strings payoff and apologies—rumored Hua mansion carters—yesterday Pincai's threatening tone—seemed inevitable—Changqing worried—entered to consult Qinyan. Since returning from the Garden of Contentment till now Qinyan had wept daily—himself unsure why—only grief—as if calamity loomed—his mind roiling—first Young Master Hua favored him—soon summoning him to mansion—how navigate that crowd—second at every lively scene Gengxiang absent—so sorrow deepened—never expecting Pincai would come wanting to buy him.",
    "Changqing entered—found Qinyan weeping—didn't know why—comforted briefly—raised Pincai's words—his angry exit—intent to make trouble—block your singing—asked Qinyan's heart—entering meant pleasure—but lifelong bondservant—forever Hua household menial. Qinyan heard—burst wailing—Changqing panicked—comforted—Qinyan sobbed: \"Teacher—you took me disciple—trained half a year—I owe gratitude—so I endured—lived two months more—now teacher discards me—I won't flee elsewhere—spare teacher trouble—simply I'm gone—teacher rests easy.\" More tears—Changqing sighed: \"Not so—I can't bear lose you—only consulting—fear crossing them—sparks trouble—everyone suffers—they're not taking you free—they promise thousands—my sums don't work—lose on the deal—so undecided—entering—splendid days for you—only pain for me.\" Qinyan: \"Teacher needs silver—easy—I earned here a year—paid plenty—if I enter—that stops—can I earn more—teacher short—needn't sell me—I'll feed teacher years yet.\" Changqing: \"My mind matches yours—many snags—don't mind me—decide yourself—don't cry—I must go out—Tianfu Tianshou at theater—if bored summon Sulan—he's off stage today—you two talk.\" Speaking—he left—sent for Sulan at once.",
    "Just inside—Xi Eleven reached the gate—Chunlan Ba Yingguan descended—asked within—answered not home—Xi felt anger rising—entered himself—Liangxuan still outside—a man stepped grinning: \"Sir seeking whom—if actors—none inside.\"—blocked the way—no \"please.\" Xi three parts furious—about to bark—Chunlan first: \"Ah—this is Great Master Xi—whether actors home or not—you always invite Master inside—how block at door?\"",
    "The man stepped back: \"Please Master—tea inside—\" opened inner gate—Xi and Liangxuan crossed courtyard—entered salon—three bays—",
    "east partitioned—guest room—opposite two bays—one gate room—one empty—",
    "Both entered inner seating—Yingguan Chunlan outer room—the man served two cups tea—recognized Chunlan—asked provenance—informed Changqing. Changqing said: \"Already said not home—needn't entertain—\" thought: \"This Xi—heard he's a sucker—tasteless—many actors ruined—no redress—Qinyan hopeless—or summon Tianfu Tianshou—maybe sweets—\" sent for them from theater—donned coat boots—went out to receive Xi Eleven.",
    "Meanwhile Lu Sulan arrived—asked Qinyan: \"What's wrong?\" Found him tear-stained—collapsed on kang—Sulan comforted: \"Again—why fetch me?\" Qinyan: \"This time I truly die—not like before enduring—\" Sulan pressed—Qinyan relayed Changqing—Sulan shocked—silent—then: \"Teacher's intent?\" Qinyan: \"Teacher undecided—both ways hard—only my death closes it—\" Sulan: \"Death first word—think slowly—no riot yet—no forcing—easy path—\" Qinyan: \"What path—forget Wei Pincai—would he spare my life—only line—Yaoqing ruined me—\" Sulan: \"How Yaoqing?\" Qinyan wept mute—Sulan pressed—Qinyan sighed: \"Had sixth day New Year Yaoqing sung Startled from Dream—I wouldn't mount stage—clean till now—no attachment—forced me understudy—half year no joy—other day disaster—that Searching the Dream ended me—duet with Yaoqing—had he eased—I wouldn't mind—had he crushed me on stage—shame—so I strove—sparked this—always Yaoqing's fault—\" Sulan: \"Young Master Hua I've seen—no cruelty—I never saw him ruin actors—if no worries in heart—few years there might profit—only missing Gengxiang hurts—\" Qinyan: \"Even if Hua good—won't Wei Pincai corrupt him?\"",
    "Sulan: \"If you suit—Wei Pincai can't harm—must flatter you—But one word—don't resent—our sort befriending hearts—yet don't excess—Duxiang Gengxiang favor you equal—Gengxiang fixes on you—won't shift—so you fix on him—won't budge—that's devotion—yet Gengxiang unlike others—young—rarely out—all inconvenient—if parents learn—they'll lecture—block outings—if they trace your bond—they blame you—that's one—heart may hold Gengxiang—face don't show—or folk say equal treatment yet double standard—what bond with Gengxiang—that's two—for now Duxiang bears your slights—long cold—lose Duxiang—you suffer little—teacher suffers—now Duxiang feeds him—won't make you seek others—if Duxiang cools—teacher squeezes silver from you—who treats like Duxiang—then bitterness exceeds Hua mansion—that's three—then Gengxiang rescue—if still helpless—only tears—only illness news—you pair apart—dreaming—body outside millstone turning—mind inside alchemy—bear that—true death—that's four—enter mansion—maybe exit—I've heard Young Master loves pairing lovers—if he learns your deathless bond—might unite you—or rest days—leave—visit me—call Gengxiang—free—if you rank Xi Pan among them—I vouch—never so—enter—better—\"",
    "That speech limpid—no veil—even a fool grasped—let alone quick Qinyan—nodded: \"I foresee—heart now—events later—so heart weighs heavy—ease conscience—await joy or pain—at worst—give life—repay feeling—no regret—\"",
    "Sulan: \"Die for love—we can—but weigh cause—die for Gengxiang—why—yourself can't say—dead—not martyr chaste widow—wise pity lovesick fool—fools call idiot—guess darker tales—Gengxiang after your death sees through—parents to honor—career to strive—no wife heir—why die for you—then laughs—mirror flowers water moon—empty—only you—underworld lonely—wait him—no voice—sing Yang Gao again—die twice—hard—\"",
    "Speaking thus he laughed; Qinyan laughed too and cried: \"Brother Lan—Brother Lan—I utterly admire you—whence such insight?\" Sulan needed the privy—asked whether the small courtyard behind had one—Qinyan said: \"There's a latrine—quite clean.\" Sulan opened the small rear door and went. Knocking sounded—the east-corner postern gate rattled—\"Who's there?\" Outside: \"Across the way Wang Lanbao—sent melons for Qinyan—\" Qinyan had it opened—a porter carried four watermelons in—said Lanbao praised the fruit—had used the rear gate—saved half a li—Qinyan tipped two hundred cash—sent thanks—asked if Lanbao were home—porter said yes—and left by the rear. When Sulan returned Qinyan split a melon—they ate deliciously—then uproar outside—the runner went and came back frantic: \"Disaster—that Xi is raising heaven-high havoc—your teacher's been knocked flat—\"—before he finished Qinyan's and Sulan's souls nearly fled—Sulan: \"Bar the doors—have them padlocked outside—\"—they slipped through the rear gate to Wang Lanbao's house.",
    "Meanwhile Changqing came out to Xi Eleven—bowed—studied him—Xi burly tall—smoky face dark with anger—the companion weasel-snouted mouse-eyed—short—two handsome tail boys—recognized Chunlan—ushered them to the guest room—Xi said: \"I'm surnamed Xi—you must have heard—no need of speech—I hear you keep a Qinyan here—I've come especially to meet him—bring him out at once—\" Changqing smiled apologetically: \"Qinyan happens to be out—gone into the city—\"",
    "Xi frowned: \"Not in the city every day—today of all days in the city—nonsense—bring him out quick—why hide—others one might hide—but didn't you ask who I am—think you can hide from me—don't play stupid—\" Changqing saw ill intent—smiled and stalled—planned delay—must deploy big hat first—heaped smiles: \"Truth—our troupe lately staged new plays—a month at the Garden—just opened—other day Young Master Hua saw them at Lord Xu's—summoned to mansion—two days sung—three days remain—Qinyan's roles are many—Young Master favors him—anywhere else we'd recall him—only that mansion—we small folk dare not approach—if Lord shares ties—send a steward with a card—demand him out—if he suits—keep him—long heard Great Master's fame—often wished invite—feared noble feet won't tread low ground—never served—didn't presume—don't suspect us hiding—why hide—even middling callers—we produce—\"",
    "Saying this he stepped near Xi—fanned him—grinned: \"Loosen your jacket—lie on the kang if you like—I have aged mud opium—\" Xi seeing such deference—anger faded—couldn't explode—and hearing opium offered—exactly his vice—said: \"If he's truly away—let it be—I don't boast lightly—every actor in the capital knows me—if you read cues—days from now bring him to call—even Young Master Hua—we're family friends—you tell him I summoned—he can't refuse face—\"—undid two buttons—Changqing peeled his jacket—folded—handed Chunlan—ushered him to the smoking room—Liangxuan followed.",
    "Xi's apparatus traveled with him—Chunlan unpacked from a pocket piece by piece on the kang—Changqing attended—burned several bowls—a wicked idea struck—smiled: \"This small one has two more disciples—one Tianfu one Tianshou—today let them serve—another day bring Qinyan to your mansion—would Great Master honor us—\" Xi smoke-lulled—lazy to rise—seeing such zeal—nodded: \"Call them look—\" Changqing sent for Tianfu Tianshou—they reached the kang—Xi raised his eyes—one round face—one sharp—features clear and fair—matching lake-blue gauze robes—powder-soled boots.",
    "After bows—they greeted Liangxuan—Changqing had them attend the pipe—and slipped away.",
    "Tianfu lay opposite Xi—Tianshou on the kang edge—Liangxuan dragged a stool beside the kang—watching them smoke—Chunlan and Ba Yingguan peered from the doorway curtain—Tianshou climbed Xi studying his jade bracelet—Tianfu leaned across the lamp tray holding Xi's hand—both admiring—Liangxuan climbed the kang—two actors rotated burning—Tianfu pressed Xi—Tianshou leaned Liangxuan—whispering both sides—Liangxuan ignored heat—hugged Tianshou—Ba Yingguan coughed—hawked—spat inside—Liangxuan fanned: \"Sweltering—\" Xi pinned a leg on Tianfu—passed one mouthful smoke split two ways.",
    "Chunlan and Ba Yingguan couldn't stomach it—wandered inward—saw women—Changqing's kin—east small door ajar—they pushed through—quiet—a big plum tree—three rooms—east windows green gauze—blinds drawn—they crept to the window—through the crack—two peerless actors on the kang—one silent—one whispering—Chunlan knew both.",
    "Sulan suddenly turned—saw a shadow in the window crack—asked: \"Who's there?\" The two tittered and bolted—Sulan rose to look—Qinyan said: \"Why look—naturally Tianfu Tianshou mischief—\" Sulan still uneasy—still frightened from before—ordered the door barred—no visitors—Chunlan told Ba Yingguan: \"They told Master Qinyan wasn't home—aren't they sitting on the bed—\" Ba: \"Who's the other—\" Chunlan: \"Sulan—wait till we tell Master—won't spare them—\" They returned to the door—still heard Xi: \"When does Qinyan return—\" Tianfu about to answer—Chunlan cut in: \"They lied—Master—Qinyan's inside talking with Sulan on the bed—they said he was singing in the city—\" Xi heard—heart caught fire—leapt up—Tianfu Tianshou grabbed—Xi flung—both fell—Xi: \"Where's Qinyan—\" Chunlan: \"Behind—small gate in—\" Xi beyond furious—stormed inward—Changqing heard—rushed to intercept—smiling: \"Great Master—where bound—inside are women's quarters—\" Xi roared: \"I'm not here for your women—\"—tried again—Changqing knew wind leaked—gatekeeper had seen—sent word within—how could Changqing block—Xi shoved—Changqing stumbled flat.",
    "Xi entered the yard—windows lowered—he poked the gauze—empty—turned center—door locked—demanded keys—Changqing ran up: \"That's my kinsman Wu's room—keys carried off—nothing worth seeing inside—\" Xi hesitated—Chunlan: \"This small one saw—and Ba Yingguan—must be under the bed—\" Changqing: \"Broad daylight—you seeing ghosts—\" Chunlan: \"I saw no ghosts—you're ghost-talking—\" Xi couldn't endure—two-three kicks shattered the door—searched round—Chunlan lifted bed curtains—under bed too—empty.",
    "Xi saw a small rear door open—looked—yard—back gate ajar—knew they'd fled—beside himself—first ripped Qinyan's bed hangings—flipped the table—smashed odds to the floor—Changqing inwardly furious—dared not vent—wanted argue—Xi seized him—five slaps round-robin—Changqing wanted strike—overmatched—half face red—shouted: \"My ancestor—release—speak outside—who paid you—raid without cause—I eat opera rice—never seen unprovoked beatings—street justice—\" Xi silent—dragged Changqing out—threw him again—Liangxuan intervened—pacified—family pulled them apart—Xi sat—Changqing rose—eyes wide—only gasping—Liangxuan dressed Xi—dragged him out—Xi walking cursed: \"Today you slipped—tomorrow I search this turtle nest—find you—smash this whore-womb den—hide him in your women's sea—I still dredge him—\" Liangxuan pulled—into cart—still cursing—Liangxuan boarded—Tianfu Tianshou had vanished—",
    "Changqing took that beating mute—shut the gate—sent to Lanbao's for Qinyan—Sulan sent Lanbao too—all said Xi Eleven's brute savagery—terrifying—maybe someone stirred him—wouldn't rest—Wei Pincai feud unsettled—now Xi—what then—Changqing more helpless—more frightened—Qinyan only wept—Lanbao said: \"I have a sound plan—if Yuyi agrees—tomorrow deliver him to Young Master Hua's—if they offer ransom—refuse—say the boy might breach etiquette—trial service two months—then judge—if trouble—request leave—bring him out days—Young Master seeing no stage—must reward—then wealth and power—idle folk won't knock—inside—if unsuitable—still dismiss—same end—if you demand ransom first—haggle—anger—bad—once inside—life and death are theirs—\" Before done Sulan clapped—\"Sound—Boss Cao—will you hear—\" That speech cleared every face—even Qinyan seeing today's havoc—yielded—Changqing convinced—that night moved to Sulan's—next day Xi came searching—gone—left cursing—",
    "As to what followed—listen to the following chapter for the explanation."
  ],
  28: [
    "Word came that after his beating Changqing was beside himself—again beseeched Ye Maolin to go with him to Secretary Wei's study in the Young Master Hua mansion—thorns on their backs to beg pardon—willing to hand the boy over first and not take a single string of cash. Seeing him so meek and—moreover—refusing all purchase money, Pincai swelled; he thought his fit of anger had shamed them into delivering the goods to his door, as he had said, and he found Lin Shanzhi, had the Young Master called, and made his report. Young Master Hua asked: \"Why ask no price?\" Pincai said: \"He is afraid the child may not know the rules, and second, if there is fault and your lordship wearies of him, he can still take him back—hence he dares not take the money.\" The Young Master nodded: \"That will do—he may enter tomorrow—but once he is in my household, whether there is a price or not, he will not be allowed to take wine and sing in the outside world.\" Pincai said: \"Of course—how many heads has Changqing, to dare that sort of thing?\" Young Master Hua also instructed Shanzhi: \"Tell the accounts office: two hundred taels of silver a month to Changqing; have him draw it at the mansion by the month.\" Shanzhi assented, left with Pincai, met Changqing, and explained everything. Pincai heaped on more favor; Changqing was overjoyed, kowtowed his thanks to Pincai, and left. He went back and told Qinyan. At this point Qinyan knew he could not avoid it; but this disaster had risen within his own walls, and Ziyu had no inkling. The next day he would enter the Hua mansion—who could say when they would see each other again? He wanted to take his leave of Ziyu, yet feared a meeting would shatter them both, and there were too many eyes, too many obstacles. He wanted to write, but his mind was a tangle; ten thousand words would not go to the brush, and he could only entreat Sulan to pass on his meaning. He thought a long time, then took the silk handkerchief with which he was always drying his tears, chose four ingredients of medicine and wrapped them separately, wrapped the handkerchief about them, sealed the whole in an outer paper, and gave the packet to Sulan, to place in Ziyu's own hands when she saw him.",
    "The next morning Changqing sent Qinyan to the Hua mansion. The Young Master looked him over again in fine detail, was very pleased, and assigned him to wait on them at Quiet-Green Retreat. He was also led to kowtow to Lady Hua. She saw his frail, graceful form and not a trace of the mean actor's air, and said a single \"good\"—the Young Master need not be mentioned. Qinyan's heart was always on Ziyu, and he could only weep in secret and sigh with his back turned. After a few days he found the Young Master's temper quite proper, with no indecent pestering, and his mind eased a little. Only toward Wei Pincai he kept the silence of Lady Xi of old; Pincai was powerless, and any design to \"settle\" him was for the moment out of the question.",
    "As for the things Qinyan had left at parting, to be handed to Ziyu by Sulan, Sulan planned in a few days to ask Ziyu over and speak with him heart to heart.",
    "As for Ziyu, from that one talk with Qinyan in the fifth month until this day, it was not that he had never tried to find Qinyan, but a tangle of mistakes had come between. This day the air was cool; after breakfast he went to Sulan's, first had Yun'er find out if he was at home, and Sulan, on learning the news, was glad and hurried out to welcome him. Two people came from the inner room. Ziyu knew one as Wang Lanbao, the other as Qiguan; it had been a long time since he had seen the latter, so he gave him a good look. Apricot cheeks like cream, willow brows in kingfisher green, bright and shining, slim and graceful, of an age with Sulan, a little shorter; they came forward and paid their respects.",
    "Ziyu said: \"I truly did not expect you still had fine company at Xiangwan's today.\" Lanbao said: \"This is your little sister-in-law—have you met the in-laws yet?\" Ziyu said: \"What kind of talk is that? How can there be such a name?\" Sulan said: \"The name is not so far off.\" Qiguan, abashed, said: \"Jingfang, don't tease.\" Lanbao said: \"It is hardly teasing—if you are Yuyi's junior, are you not his little sister-in-law?\" Ziyu laughed: \"This is absurd.\" So saying, they all sat. The table was a mess of dishes, as if a meal had just finished. Sulan had it cleared, then brought tea herself and asked: \"Your visit today is odd; you must already know.\" Ziyu, again at a loss, said: \"What is it I am supposed to know? I really do not.\" Lanbao looked at Ziyu: \"You still do not? It has been five or six days; even if you never went out, surely someone told you?\"",
    "Ziyu grew more baffled—the thought never touched Qinyan—and said: \"I honestly do not understand what you mean; I do not cross my gate, and no one has called these two days—how should I know affairs outside?\" Qiguan smiled faintly. Sulan said: \"You really do not know—I must tell you—and sit steady. Jingfang, Yuyan, brace him—I will speak.\" Ziyu said: \"Xiangwan has always been blunt; why these airs today? Surely nothing so strange—it is only meant to frighten.\" Sulan stared at Ziyu again till Lanbao and Qiguan laughed; seeing their mood Ziyu grew truly uneasy and said: \"Xiangwan—out with it.\" Sulan hesitated again: \"It is hard to tell—something to show—and you will know.\" Ziyu still knew nothing when Sulan drew from a small stationery case a paper packet—like a letter—no inscription on the label—square—in his hands weightless yet, when pressed, softly rustling. He tore the seal: white gauze—a handkerchief—and his suspicion deepened; he shook it—four tiny paper parcels fell out. Lanbao and the others crowded over. Ziyu opened them and laid them on the table: four drugs—none he recognized. Sulan asked: \"What medicines are these?\" Ziyu said: \"I do not know—I ask you: why show them to me—and how do you not know?\" The three fell mute and only stared at the parcels. Ziyu saw they looked as lost as he; his suspicion deepened and he asked Sulan: \"Whose bundle is this—why so mysterious?\" Sulan said: \"Not I demanding it—it is from the one you dream of asleep and waking; he left it at parting and charged me to send it to you. I thought something vital—in fact he simply wrapped several of the doses he takes every day. That handkerchief—he believed you would know—meaning look on the thing and recall the person.\" At the words Ziyu's heart gave a violent leap; he looked at the gauze and thought: going by her words—could something ill have befallen Yuyi—as if ill omen? One thread of grief climbed from his breast to his crown and poured down again—it broke from eyes and nose—he could not hold back—and wept softly. The three sighed together. Seeing this Ziyu dared not press further—as if he already understood—he wiped his face with the kerchief and thought: these medicines must be what was taken at the final hour—thus sent—and felt ten thousand arrows pierce him, hands and feet at a loss; he rose and sat in the outer room—he wished to burst into loud grief, but at Sulan's it was awkward, and he only muffled his weeping and stared blankly. Seeing this Sulan regretted being rash—the way she had spoken sounded as if Yuyi were dead—thus touching his sorrow—and she hurried out and said to Ziyu: \"Do not panic yet—let me finish—Yuyi is not gone bad—come inside and sit—I will tell you properly.\" Ziyu said urgently: \"Xiangwan—speak plain—do not scare me in half sentences—what of Yuyi?\" He went back into the inner room; Lanbao and Qiguan watched him, bleak too. Sulan said: \"Listen carefully to what happened in these months of the fifth month,\" and from first to last told how Wei Pincai had come, how Xi Eleven had raised a riot, how she and Lanbao had counseled and schemed, how they had hidden from Xi Eleven, how they had sent him into the Hua mansion, how at parting he had wept and charged her, and the lies about refusing the price and safe passage—and comforted him with a few words.",
    "Hearing that Qinyan still lived in this world, Ziyu's heart eased a fraction; he paused and said: \"Yuyi's going—it is like leaving the dust of this life behind.\" Tears rolled again; he fell into a trance; he looked again and again at those drugs—only recognized one as peony root—the rest were strange—and said to Sulan: \"Yuyi's sending these must hide a meaning—but what drugs are they? Send someone to the pharmacy and have them named on the wraps.\" Sulan said: \"Quite right,\" and was about to call someone when Qiguan said: \"No need—my man knows—he clerked at a pharmacy.\" He called him in and showed him the four—the man looked and said: \"This is morning-glory seed—this thoroughwort root—this peony—this stephania root.\" Qiguan wrote them down but could not puzzle the sense. Sulan said: \"Apart from you he is 'thoroughwort alone'—I grasp that line.\" Lanbao said: \"Stephania guards himself—puts your mind at ease—the other pair I cannot crack.\" Ziyu said through tears: \"Yuyi's whole heart is here—the peony's other name is 'about to part'—meaning once inside the Hua mansion they are already parted; having parted, naturally he is 'alone alive'; alive inside that hall—how bob and bow with the crowd—he must guard himself with care every moment—keep his body like jade. As for morning-glory—I read no other sense—it must be the Seventh Eve—the appointment to meet—the night of Cowherd and Weaver.\" Sulan said: \"Exactly—clever—you read him true—Yuyi's mind is unlike others; a letter risks other eyes—and grief too deep for the brush—this riddle is better. On the Seventh Eve you must lodge here a day—we will tell him today's scene—it will not waste your devotion.\" They talked on; the three comforted him earnestly, and Ziyu could only endure. It was Qiguan's first long sitting with Ziyu—seeing his bearing he admired him beyond measure—no wonder Yuyi's heart held only him—and seeing such depth of feeling—like a bride worthy of her general—only fate was thin—few meetings, many partings—and he believed heaven grinds mortals still.",
    "To Ziyu they also told at length the vulgar manners Wei Pincai had shown on the boat when they shared passage. Remembering Xi Eleven, they cursed him again between their teeth. Sulan pressed Ziyu to eat; his spirits were low and he wished to leave early—took his leave and went straight home—and in the carriage his limbs began to feel unwell.",
    "At home he greeted Lady Yan and lay down in the study, talking to himself, now sighing, now weeping, as if drunk. The next day he fell seriously ill—mind overturned—speech disorder—and within a day wept many times. At first when others were present he could hold back; gradually he could not. Even before his mother he wept both eyes streaming—dazed of hue. Lady Yan thought him possessed—called physicians, divined, vowed, prayed gods—for ten-odd days not a trace of better. Within a day he was sometimes stuporous, sometimes clear; in stupor he was blank and heard nothing; when clear he was like a well man. In sleep he muttered—sometimes \"Yuyi,\" sometimes \"Xiangwan,\" sometimes cursing Xi Eleven and Wei Pincai by name. Lady Yan was frantic; Yan Zhongqing and Wang Xun came every few days—they understood—could not cure—and only spoke gently round it. Lady Yan heard Ziyu's dreams cry \"Yuyi\" again and again—she suspected some entanglement outside—and imagined Yuyi a woman—with shame she could not voice—and thought Ziyu rarely went out—with Yun—one day she called Yun and pressed him: \"Where did you follow the young master—who is Yuyi—a courtesan—or what?\" Yun at first denied—said the master only went to the Garden, Wang young master's, Shi young master's—never saw a woman—swore he would not live if lying. Lady Yan thought soft questions useless—ordered rods—\"beat the truth out of him.\" Yun saw the rods and knelt and kowtowed: \"There truly is a young dan called Qinyan—the master often sought him—they met mostly weeping, seldom laughing. In the fifth month one day they said Yiyuan Lord Xu—it was a lie—they went with that young dan and another young dan on the canal east of the gate half a day—cried half a day—this small one on the bow heard no other words. The other day the master went to that young dan's house—that young dan said Qinyan had entered Young Master Hua's mansion—and gave the master a paper bundle—this small one did not know what—the master wept there—they soothed him—since returning he has been like this—not one word false—nothing else happened.\" Lady Yan heard—burning anger—and scolded Yun: \"You deserved a thrashing—why not tell me sooner until the rods drew it—if not for your truth today I would have beaten you dead.\" She dismissed Yun—and hated her son—young and reckless—for a mere young dan to waste this ill—she wanted to lecture—yet saw him this sick—and she herself past forty—with only this son—ill as he was—what good would lecture do—if lecture worsened the sickness—better wait till he mended. She thought left and right—and summoned Li Yuanmao to learn the truth.",
    "Yuanmao said: \"This student never went abroad with him—whether Qinyan or not—I do not know. Last year I heard Old Wei Pincai often praise Qinyan—my uncle took notice. On New Year's sixth, at the guild gathering, uncle saw his opera—heard praise—after that this student witnessed nothing—you must ask Wei Pincai for detail.\" Lady Yan ordered the gatekeeper Xu Shun to the Hua mansion to invite Secretary Wei—there was business to discuss. Pincai did not guess it was this matter—he had grown distant from Ziyu—over a month absent—heard Lady summon—thought some favor awaited—next day dressed splendid—rode out—arrived at the Mei house—met Lady Yan—saw care on her face—first asked news from Jiangxi—whether letters came—then Ziyu—and exam season—and sure top rank—all pleasantries.",
    "After a turn Lady Yan said: \"Ziyu has taken a strange illness,\" described its signs, repeated Yun's and Yuanmao's words, and asked: \"What bond is there between my son and this Qinyan?\" Pincai felt uneasy—conscience stirred—his face showed guilt—paused—and said: \"Last year nephew entered the capital—shared an actors' boat—among them a young dan Qinyan. On guild day this year I happened to see his opera. Later how elder brother knew him—I heard they met at the Garden lantern riddles—and brother gave a qin. Nephew is coarse—I cannot join such literati—how close—what bond—nephew does not know. Elder brother's usual young lords—madame knows them—the depth of feeling—they must know—why not ask them?\" Lady Yan said: \"Where is Qinyan now?\" Pincai said: \"Qinyan studied new plays at the Garden—Young Master Hua favored him—\"—half rose—\"nephew owes lord and lady deep kindness—knowing elder brother's illness came from that actor—wasted his books—ruined his health—therefore urged Young Master Hua to buy him—a Mr. Xi made trouble there wanting to ruin them—Qinyan's teacher was frightened—had no plan—nephew urged—days ago sent Qinyan into the Hua mansion—once inside—not soon out—nephew inwardly rejoiced—elder brother might shut that heart—turn to proper things—or that actor would drag him down forever.\" Lady Yan heard—anger rose—hated her son's failure—and thanked Pincai: \"Your brother this ill—in dreams he raves—cries and laughs—mouth only says Yuyi—surely because that actor entered the Hua mansion—your brother is worthless—but my only son—if harm comes—when his father returns—what face have I—you are capable—think how to cure him.\" Pincai shook his head: \"Hard—the proverb says heart's disease wants heart's medicine—nephew knows your house rules—would lord father allow him to roam outside?\" Lady Yan said: \"I do not mean indulging him to chase young dan—even if I doted—I would not go so far. I hear Yun say when he met the young dan they only wept—children's whim—maybe fate—now he dreams only that actor—you dwell in the Hua mansion—think of a way—bring that actor out—comfort him—perhaps he heals faster.\" Saying so she wept. Pincai knitted his brow and sighed: \"But this man obeys no human feeling—and two hundred taels a month wage—how summon him out?\"",
    "Lady Yan asked: \"Why two hundred taels a month—some living treasure—your brother has no money—how did he know him?\"",
    "Pincai said: \"Qinyan never wanted money—the teacher will not budge without silver—nephew thought hard—no path—must negotiate the teacher—the teacher will not plain-talk.\" Lady Yan said: \"What is the teacher like?\" Pincai said: \"Hard mouth—lives inside the coin's eye—to negotiate unless you promise plenty—you still may not—he fears offending that side—loses twenty-four hundred taels a year—plain talk—hopeless.\"",
    "Lady Yan heard money must be spent and said: \"Only bring him—give money—I do not mind—but how much?\" Pincai said: \"Nephew will go negotiate—will spare no effort—ease madame—\"",
    "—saying so he rose to take leave. Lady Yan said through tears: \"Much trouble, nephew—I say little now—since so—go today—if you can—word today is best.\" Pincai agreed—looked in on Ziyu—Ziyu saw Pincai—even ill—remembered old wrongs—shut his eyes feigning sleep—and ignored him.",
    "Pincai exchanged a few words with Yuanmao—left—straight to the Hua mansion—sat in his own room—thought—no plan—and found Shanzhi—repeated Lady Yan's plea—added color—and said—this brother and I three generations bound—Madame Mei only this son—clever—handsome—do this good turn—cure him—I owe you endlessly. Shanzhi said: \"What can I—only report Young Master—say you told—have him visit—\" Pincai waved—\"cannot—Young Master's temper—we know—so saying—refuses—ugly—need another plot.\" Shanzhi said: \"You plot—I do not meddle.\" Pincai bowed deep—\"good third—good brother—secure this—my brother sends two bolts fine patterned treasury gauze.\" Shanzhi pressed until he yielded—remembered his own jealousy—and said: \"Tomorrow let him go—if asked—I answer—won't name you.\" Pincai beamed—bowed thanks—early—carriage—saw Lady Yan—acted hardship—teacher demands two hundred to call him out—fears if cannot re-enter mansion—then wants twenty-four hundred—nephew scolded him slippery—feared—later inside unknown—now two hundred firm—else won't risk—Lady Yan—pained—\"tomorrow—two hundred—later see—\"—hooked—silk shop—two bolts—next day Shanzhi.",
    "Why did Shanzhi dare arrange it? Qinyan had only been half a month inside—even Lady Hua doted—often gifted—and said: \"This child is honest—not like an actor.\" Shanzhi turned jealous—thought: \"I three years—first rank—he days—clever head—won't he crush me?\"—meant to squeeze—heard Pincai—chance—and went to Quiet-Green to tell Qinyan. Qinyan heard—tearful—said: \"How can Gengxiang be this ill—Brother Lin—you truly can send me—they want me to visit?\"",
    "Shanzhi said: \"Why lie—rest easy—half the day Young Master won't descend—even if summoned—I say leave—visit teacher's illness—return—if trouble—I answer—you go early return—and—heal him this once—second visit—hard.\" Qinyan flushed—silent—grateful—inside he relied on Shanzhi—and could visit Gengxiang—must not forget—after—even hate for Pincai faded—this owed him.",
    "That day quiet—at last dawn—and Heaven favored—Young Master unwell—in Lady's quarters—did not emerge—Qinyan relieved—ate—found Shanzhi—\"how exit—I don't know the way.\" Shanzhi said: \"Go with Secretary Wei—the gates won't ask—rumor won't pierce inner.\" Qinyan swallowed pride—found Pincai—Pincai glad—face cold—\"go—careful—if exposed—don't say I went.\" Qinyan agreed—passed gates layer on layer—keepers knew Wei—dared not question.",
    "Outside the gate—Qinyan in the carriage—curtains drawn—Pincai on the footboard—Four on the tail—soon Mei house—Pincai did not wait for announcement—with Qinyan straight to the study—Xu Shun startled—could not block—followed—Lady Yan hoping—Xu entered as if to report—Lady asked—\"Wei master brought someone—like an actor—must report—\" Lady said: \"I know—bring them—\"—Pincai and a youth fifteen-six—at a glance—Lady Yan startled—seen before—like betrothed daughter Qionggu—marveled—\"I have watched opera—actors painted like women—offstage never studied—this Qinyan—jade bones ice flesh—noble air—hair dressed—great lady—bare face—still gentry scholar—like my son—had anger—words ready—seeing—smiled instead.\"",
    "When Qinyan stepped in—Ziyu gravely ill—love unbearable—he ignored fortune—braved Lady's scolding—and Pincai in the carriage had threatened—timid—trembling—he kowtowed—stood head low—Lady called him near—studied—bid Pincai sit—\"where from—when to capital—how know my son—how close—truth—I won't harm.\" Qinyan gentle face—tearful—mumbled—Lady soothed—\"don't fear—my son sought you—not you him—truth—I won't hurt.\" Qinyan paused—\"humble Suzhou—last winter capital—Lianjin troupe—parents gone—uncle's wife sold—sixth New Year Suzhou guild—first saw young master—like known before—Lantern Festival Yiyuan Lord Xu—riddles—loved 'fallen flowers man alone—fine rain swallows pair'—Second Master Xu set a jade qin as prize—said guesser would be introduced—that day young master guessed—two days feast—first true meeting—second Sulan canal outing—half day—only twice—truth—ask Wei—madame knows son outings.\"—tears—Pincai: \"truth—never three faces.\" Lady puzzled—pity—\"half year—two meetings.\"—\"son dreams you—you know.\" Qinyan: \"madame grace—humble dare lie—strange—not only I felt I knew him—he said knew me—family at once—no cause.\" Lady smiled: \"odd—I cannot fathom—but son because you entered Hua—this ill—I called—comfort—heal—I blame not—I reward.\" Qinyan grief—stifled sob—murmur—Lady pitied—bid Pincai Qinyan Ziyu's room—she and Pincai outer—listen—Xu Shun stood till now—understood illness—followed bedroom—as to whether Qinyan cured Ziyu's sickness—listen to the following installment."
  ],
  29: [
    "As for Qinyan's coming to the Mei house—his heart had been terrified; he fully expected abuse this time. Yet after meeting Lady Yan—not only was there no scolding—there was pity—and she ordered him go comfort Ziyu—which he had not foreseen. Joy and grief surged; he did not know Ziyu's state—how he could comfort—only obeyed Lady Yan, braced his face, and walked to Ziyu's bedchamber. The curtains hung unrolled, the desk dusted thick, the medicine tripod smoking, the incense ash cold—a small nanmu bed with a sheer white gauze curtain. Yun'er first lifted the bed-curtain and called: \"Young Master! Qinyan has come to see you.\" Ziyu was half asleep; he made two sounds—like answer, like not. Qinyan came to the bedside, sat on the edge, raised his eyes and looked carefully—Ziyu's face was sallow and thin—wasted. Qinyan leaned to the pillow and called low—tears burst like a spring—drenching Ziyu's face. Suddenly Ziyu gave a soft laugh and said: \"'On the seventh day of the seventh month, in the Palace of Long Life—at midnight when no one hears whispering'—this is the very hour.\" He laughed twice more. Qinyan knew delirium—his heart ached—patted him twice—Lady was outside—couldn't say Gengxiang—changed to \"Young Master!\" Ziyu still in dream—thought it Seventh Eve—already met Qinyan at Sulan's—the three in the courtyard—fruit, tea, talk—so he recited those two lines from Song of Everlasting Regret—the dream soul so deep hard to wake. Qinyan saw him laugh again—heard him say: \"I thought 'Yellow Springs and azure heaven—both hard to seek.'\" At that he slapped with his hand—turned inward sleeping again. Qinyan's tears flowed harder—could only stare—dared not call again—saw Ziyu shake his head—\"Such heavy rain—if tomorrow morning too—what then—the boat so far.\"",
    "After a pause he said: \"Below thoroughwort and stephania—I ought add one more dose of angelica root.\" Outside Lady Yan heard—knew delirium—couldn't parse all—still grief—two streams of tears—only stared blank at Pincai—Pincai too felt bleak—and said: \"Yuyi—wake him.\" Qinyan called twice \"Young Master!\" Ziyu tittered: \"How foolish you are!\"—and said: \"Yun'er—why keep calling—such a short road—what fear—you still think Great East Gate?\" Qinyan wanted to shout—throat strangled—only patted him. Suddenly Ziyu opened his eyes toward Qinyan: \"Xiangwan—once again you saved me—such heart—I can rest easy after.\" Qinyan leaned closer—hand on shoulder—\"Young Master—Qinyan is here—are you better?\" Ziyu's mind blurred—eyes colorful—couldn't see—sneered coldly. Qinyan repeated—Ziyu burst laughing: \"You've tested me once—think I don't know you?\" Lady Yan in the next room—heard—heart breaking—couldn't bear—came to door—saw Qinyan on bed holding Ziyu's hand weeping—Ziyu only laughing.",
    "Lady Yan said: \"He doesn't know people—what can we do?\" Pincai had to come bedside—called several times: \"Dear brother—the Qinyan you long for has come especially—I'll raise you to sit—you'll talk—be well.\" He told Yun'er wring a hot towel—wash his face—wipe eyes—raised him sitting—folded brocade quilt—propped behind.",
    "Lady Yan would not enter—lest her son feel shame—and Wei Pincai kept his distance.",
    "After sitting Ziyu felt somewhat clear—eyes suddenly sharp—saw Qinyan beside—and asked: \"Who are you—sitting here?\" Qinyan wept: \"How can you not know me?\" Seeing windows closed—and sitting back to light—naturally unclear—he shifted outward—half profile to Ziyu—\"I am Yuyi—Madame sent me—I never thought ten-odd days—you'd waste so.\" Speaking—whimpered again—Ziyu heard clearly—heart jumped—straightened—looked—\"You're Yuyi—I don't believe—how can you come—must this be dream?\" Qinyan held tears: \"I am Qinyan—Madame sent—why ill like this?\" Ziyu sneered coldly: \"You do resemble Yuyi somewhat.\"",
    "Lady Yan hearing—said to Pincai: \"Those words sound strange.\" She heard Qinyan: \"I came for your sickness.\" Ziyu laughed: \"You truly Yuyi—how could you come—even if willing—would they release you?\" Qinyan: \"I truly am Yuyi—I've been here long—Madame's order—Wei secretary brought me—I urge you ease mind—don't brood—body matters—heal fast—I've moved once—I can often visit.\" More tears fell—Lady Yan seeing Ziyu clearer—felt glad—had a maid move a chair outside the curtain—Pincai stood behind Lady Yan—Ziyu clearer still—leaned to Qinyan—studied—laughed: \"Yuyi—you truly came—not false?\" Qinyan turned to answer—choked—only wept—Pincai outside whispered: \"Yuyi—steel yourself—don't draw more tears.\" Qinyan hid face with handkerchief—forced one sentence: \"It's true.\" Ziyu: \"Truly true?\" Qinyan: \"True—true—true.\" Ziyu wild laugh—lunged forward—fell on Qinyan's shoulder—still giggling without end.",
    "Pincai couldn't help laughing—the maids and matrons all laughed—Lady Yan nodded and sighed—saw Ziyu both hands on Qinyan's shoulders wanting rise—first laughed awhile.",
    "Qinyan said: \"What illness is this—I urge you—don't be ill—from today heal—spare so many suffering you—and Madame worry.\" More tears—Ziyu laughed: \"What illness—my illness—comes when it likes—goes when it likes—never mattered.\" Qinyan: \"Don't say never mattered—this isn't before—your face all sickness—ten thousand words one line—ease your heart—you used say you saw through—why today not?\" Ziyu laughed: \"When did I not see through—if I didn't—I'd be thoroughwort's opposite—lucky I see through—there's still today.\" Laughed again—Qinyan: \"I'm well at Hua house—Young Master Hua very proper—high and low treat me well—you needn't fret.\" Ziyu: \"You truly well?\" Qinyan: \"Truly—ask Wei.\" Ziyu: \"Good then good—why ask—\" laughed—Qinyan: \"Only your fast heal makes me better—slow heal—I worse—you perfect health—I'm immortal joy.\" End forced smile—Ziyu great joy—almost dancing—Qinyan: \"There they allow leave—not like teacher's bonds—never came—now came—I'll often visit—if you well I sit longer—if ill I fear tire you—and I grow drearier seeing.\" Ziyu: \"You truly can take leave?\" Qinyan: \"Today isn't leave?\" Ziyu: \"Wonderful—I thought once you entered—we'd never meet—never dreamed you could come—here—strange—wonderful—Heaven!\" Clapped laughing—Qinyan wondered if this laugh too was sickness—heart sad—held in.",
    "Now Lady Yan saw Ziyu only laughing—much of her gloom lifted.",
    "She thought—if he could laugh so—his mind must open—and the illness could mend—yet Qinyan always wretched—she could not fathom why—Ziyu laughed again: \"Inside—what did you do?\" Qinyan: \"Nothing—they keep me at Quiet-Green—the mansion's grounds—another world from Garden—rules may not be slipped.\"",
    "\"No singing needed—we do nothing—I only serve as a study page boy.\" Ziyu: \"Did they know you left?\" Qinyan: \"He's often in upper halls—several studies—rest days—then one place—sits briefly—gone—servants don't enter those rooms unbidden.\" Qinyan usually spoke truth—today to cure Ziyu—threaded lies—said Hua house joyful—could visit often—only to ease Ziyu's heart—Ziyu hearing—mind steadied—truly happy—laughed—Qinyan: \"Before—teacher—going out tired—never came—dared not—today I saw Madame—she favors me—orders frequent visits—under command—who blocks—free coming and going.\" Ziyu heard—brow knit—flustered—low: \"You've seen Madame—she didn't scold—who brought you—permits entry?\" Qinyan: \"Wei secretary brought—I told Madame I can cure your illness—she rejoiced—instructed—if you heal—not only allow entry—often come—when lord returns—discuss buying me to serve you—asked willing—I said willing—only beg grace.\" Ziyu: \"You never lied—today—lies to coax me?\" Qinyan: \"Don't believe—I'll fetch Madame—face to face.\" Stepped—Ziyu waved urgently—no—\"every sentence true?\" Qinyan: \"When have I lied?\" Ziyu nodded: \"Never false.\" Steadied—more joy—great laughter—joy reached outer room—Lady laughed—Pincai swollen proud—low: \"Nephew sees dear brother may heal today—credit Qinyan's teacher—though he vexed us—worth it.\" Ziyu didn't heed outer—attention thin—didn't hear—slowly stepped off bed—Qinyan helped—two steps—legs soft—laughed: \"I'm well—I had no illness—summer muddle—head fog—they took for grave illness—fed medicine—more stifling—stifled to death.\" Called Yun: \"I'm hungry—bring food.\"",
    "Lady Yan lightly slipped out—Pincai followed—Lady: \"Strange—strange—can't read those two little ones—today truly owed Qinyan—I'll reward heavy.\" Pincai grinned: \"Rare—madame see—they're open—nothing shameful—today owed him—or Ye Tianshi reborn couldn't cure so fast.\" Lady: \"Still nephew's power—called him out—credit nephew's—grateful.\" Pincai: \"Dare not—nephew owes house favor—should serve—not just this—even fire water—\" face beaming—Lady thanked—ordered Yun lotus porridge two bowls—Qinyan keep Ziyu company—Ziyu seeing Qinyan—joy—hearing words—all gloom gone—ate bowl—clear spirit—said to Qinyan: \"I'm healed—you rest—leave early today—don't give gossip—hard to take leave later—I heed every word—you too take care—yield upward—better than singing—I thought never meet—today so fast—all worry gone—only shame never met Young Master Hua—or I could visit—Wei went with you—\" asked where—Qinyan: \"He came—called—raised you—missed—now upper with Madame.\" Ziyu low: \"Past grudges—forget—friend him—today owed him.\" Qinyan nodded—hard parting—Ziyu finally few tears—Qinyan urged—Ziyu promised—saw to door—Qinyan: \"you just well—don't come—I'll see Madame.\" Ziyu anxious—\"speak carefully—not all truth.\"",
    "Qinyan agreed—came out—upper hall—Lady smiled: \"Today owed you—cured him—don't let him sick again.\" Qinyan flushed—paused—\"Young Master bright—sees through—after—no illness.\" Lady studied him: \"When return?\" Qinyan: \"Leave permits—come—ease madame.\" Sigh—\"two little ones—I can't guess—today one cry one laugh—little said—if not witnessed—anyone would gossip—say I spoil—indulge son—nephew—you saw—funny—how could I be harsh—let him waste?\" Pincai about speak—Lady turned Qinyan: \"Only you understand—must rely you serve him whole.\" Qinyan low assent—thought: never thought Madame so merciful—others wouldn't—even loving son—not extend to me—deep gratitude.",
    "Pincai saw time long—would return with Qinyan—Qinyan anxious—bid farewell—Lady: \"Wait—I have words—\" entered—called Xu Shun—weigh two hundred silver—\"give Wei young gentleman—\" Pincai had Four hold—servant brought bundle—Lady to Qinyan: \"Madame rewards—take—then thanks.\" Silver knife—large purses pair—small pair—handkerchief—foreign watch—ten plum ingots—fan—Qinyan took—with Pincai thanked—Pincai vague thanks—out—Lady escorted corridor—instructed—gate Xu Shun grinning: \"Today's affair—what cause—can't guess—\" asked Qinyan's troupe—Pincai: \"once Lianjin—now not acting—Hua mansion duty—cause later know—\" Xu sent out—carriage—Qinyan thanked endlessly—Pincai modest—very pleased.",
    "Entering city past shen hour—at gate—followed Pincai—superintendent struck register—Qinyan knew upper book—Pincai had Four carry silver to room—lock chest—found Lin Shanzhi—Shanzhi seeing Qinyan: \"So long—must have healed.\" Qinyan ashamed—\"Young Master summon me?\" Shanzhi: \"Summoned thrice—no return—great anger—sent for your teacher.\" Qinyan shock—face red—speechless—Pincai: \"He can't take scare—don't scare—\" Shanzhi grave: \"Why scare—at wei hour Young Master emerged—missing—asked—I said teacher's birthday—Qinyan home felicitation—waited your descent to ask leave—heard you not coming—couldn't wait—asked me report—Young Master angry—if truly birthday—fine—if lie for other outing—I won't spare—sent man your teacher—investigate—returns—I'll be scolded—you worse—gate book shows Wei escort—Wei won't escape fair.\" Qinyan's heart hammered—eyes red—truth found—scold mild—shame worse—Pincai half believed: \"Third—don't bluff—I'm clean—you sent—ask you first.\" Shanzhi sneered: \"Ask me—I tell straight—what you plotted?\" Qinyan tears—begged mercy—Pincai laughed—fanned—bowed—\"Good brother—cover—brother's face—owe you.\" Shanzhi seeing real panic—chuckled: \"Ease—true—not lie—arranged Zhu Gui—don't investigate—roam gate—return say truly teacher birthday—soon back—if you won prizes—split thanks—\" Qinyan: \"I'll give him silver.\" Shanzhi to Pincai: \"Erase gate book—or seen later.\" Pincai: \"beg Third Master magic—I can't ask.\" Shanzhi: \"Too cheap you—yesterday two bolts gauze—I disdain—colors bad—return.\" Pincai: \"gauze finest—change pattern can—\" Shanzhi: \"Enough clothes—undied dozen sets—I want give away—few taels favor—I lately saw two things—love—can't buy out—\"",
    "Before done Pincai pressed: \"What things—I'll fetch.\" Shanzhi: \"Sha Huizi's—gold wire flower basket—two liang—fine work—his Shi Dabin Yixing teapot—jade in lid—my thumb ring not match—basket offered forty—he agreed—teapot twenty-four—refused—tomorrow bring—Sha says teapot treasure—Shi Dabin century—spout drips not—brew with or without leaf—boiling water—fine tea—green—I dumped leaves—tested—true—odd?\"",
    "Pincai: \"Old pots ripen—I'll buy both—gauze keep—gift.\" Shanzhi laughed: \"Can't refuse empty—I'll accept grudging—\" returned room.",
    "At Quiet-Green Shanzhi asked—Qinyan outlined.",
    "Shanzhi doubted—\"Why ill for nothing—many saw your play—not all ill—your bond—or other?\" Qinyan ashamed—couldn't answer—bucket in his well—swallowed anger.",
    "As for Ziyu's grave illness—and Qinyan's excursion from the Hua mansion—Wei Pincai swelled with pride—thought it striking—and hawked it outside the walls until folk took it for fresh news. Actors who disliked Qinyan or lived to sow tales reshaped and embroidered until Ziyu and Qinyan sounded unspeakable. Wang Wenhui ran into Rongguan and Erxi at someone's feast and heard the yarn spun vivid as living dragons; he had seen Ziyu's sickness himself—thought it odd—but never guessed love-sickness—and listening now his heart sank—and he thought:",
    "\"Young men's affairs resist restraint—you only play along at the feast. Besides, Ziyu is only eighteen—the bud just forming—why sink into this? Last year we betrothed our beloved daughter to him—the first unhappy thing in marriage is wandering fancy—future peace between qin and se won't stay pure.\" Home he summoned his son Wang Xun—who answered vaguely—and argued Ziyu's side—said never so bad—Wenhui still doubted. Lady Lu overheard—though not yet wed—already vinegar for her daughter—and said to Wenhui: \"Brother Yu's looks are superb—last year I agreed to Sun's match—now you wash hands—how well? Betrothal not sealed—already jokes—if he keeps debauch—how will Qionggu live—his father home can leash—his mother spoils—follow whims—later good-for-nothing—so young—shameless love for young dan—those old roués carousing outside—no wonder young men.\"",
    "\"What good are these young dan—have they no shame?\" In her heat she lectured Wang Wenhui too—he only smiled—dared not speak—and said: \"The matter is strange—I looked into it—even Xun knows—they've only met two or three times.\"",
    "\"Only longing for each other—nothing else—and children so young—how grasp such things—ease yourself—I'll tell cousin Yan—stricter gate—no outings—fine—marry this winter—once Qionggu crosses—maybe he'll leash.\" Lady Lu sneered: \"Such habits come from the heart—I've seen—body leashed—not heart—thieves don't change nature.\" Wenhui heard himself targeted—laughed hollow—escaped to study—Lady Lu railed at daughter Qionggu—daughter silent—impatient—thought groom dissolute—\"talented men trip short\"—remembered brothers praising Ziyu's goodness—maybe only lust for beauty—blushed—pondered—Lady pitied—stopped—and left.",
    "Again—after Qinyan's visit Ziyu was eased—knew his mother did not blame—and that she had commissioned Pincai to bring Qinyan—his heart rejoiced—he mended in under ten days—only before his mother he still looked ashamed—Lady Yan loved him finely—knew no shameful deed—and never spoke Qinyan's name—Wang Wenhui came several times—Lady Lu came—and before Lady Yan could say outright—needled with barbs—as if telling kin to watch—don't indulge—yet seeing Ziyu healed—handsome—graceful—a worthy son-in-law—and seeming honest—half her doubt melted.",
    "Days later Ziyu still could not rest—begged his mother—on pretext of visiting Pincai—to see Qinyan—and met Pincai—begged Shanzhi—called Qinyan out—they talked more than an hour—then felt easy—but within the Hua mansion mouths were many—each heart its own—and after several days someone carried the tale to Young Master Hua—who grew furious—summoned Shanzhi—Shanzhi pled—got scolded—and afterward barred Qinyan from going out—assigned him to Crimson Wash Residence—given into the Ten Pearls maids' watching—cut off from outsiders—like a cage—the Pearls were kindly—yet Qinyan—young—and oddly pure—even guarded himself against them—so Young Master trusted his honesty among maids—treated him almost as another maid—forbade outside dealings—even Lin Shanzhi unless summoned might not reach him—to say nothing of others—Qinyan could only endure the long gate—by day chatting with the Pearls—few words—by night lone lamp—only resenting autumn wind and rain—as to what followed—listen to the following chapter for the explanation."
  ],
  30: [
    "Of Qinyan's return from Ziyu's—the Young Master Hua knew no particulars—yet blamed him for quitting the mansion on his own—a clear breach of rule; thinking it a first offense he waived punishment for the moment and reassigned him to the inner chambers—a place neither inner nor outer ever meets. One day Qinyan sat alone beside Crystal Hill, weeping toward clusters of balsam; he reflected that men live in this world—and if they cannot rise to name and deeds, mingling only with shallow sorts, years slip away and they rot like grass and wood. Plants flower—everyone finds them sweet—yet they snap the stems to stick in vases or pin in hair—within a day or half the bloom withers; calling it love of blooms in truth destroys them. This clump of balsams planted here lean into each other like limbs of one body—with natural charm—wind and rain may scour them awhile but hardly touch the root.",
    "Uproot them and rear them in golden basin and jade urn—they still lose their nature. Then there are the forced gardener's tricks—trimming sprays, plucking leaves, rope and thread binding, weeding moss—to please men's eyes while draining color—is it unlike binding a soul so he dare not laugh aloud or weep aloud?",
    "Thought deeper—men fall short even of flowers: blossoms return next spring; men year by year decline. Take me in this dusty world—trampled at whim—put through every affectation—tasted every bitterness and sweetness—when the hour comes men despise me, shall I not drift like blossoms to privy or carriage-mat—mud-spattered—nowhere to land—the thought aches and bites. Thought on one cheek, tears on the other. Then Yuxiang—though his illness mended—I once fed him lies; did he glimpse my plight now—he cannot come—I cannot reach him—the old ailment might flare anew; summon me then—I fear I could never go again. Turning it over morning to night brought only dreariness; each day dragged—the months fly—cassia perfumes the courtyard.",
    "That day was the twelfth of the eighth month; Young Master Hua recalled the twenty-first of the sixth at Yiyuan Opera—had said once autumn cooled he would bid Yuxiang visit. Fifteenth being a family banquet—unsuited for guests—he fixed the fourteenth—to entertain Ziyun, Cixian, Wenze and others—in the West Garden—several spreads—and lantern opera; they lived outside the walls—a daylight feast could not suffice—invitations named a night banquet. Same day fell the second session of autumn exams—why sat Liu Wenze them not? This round's chief examiner was Grand Secretary Liu Shouzheng—Wenze's father—the associate Wang Wenhui risen to Hanlin—with Lu Zongyuan, Yang Fangyou, Zhou Xijue, Sun Liangfang as symmetrical readers—half the famed candidates stayed screened away. Xu Ziyun and Shi Nanxiang—former juren—Xiao Cixian lofty recluse—all passed save Tian Chunhang and Gao Pin entering. Ziyu, Wang Xun, Wenze, Zhongqing kept rule and stood aside; Ziyu stayed home sunk in gloom—with never a word from Qinyan—inner and outer cut off—no ferry for messages—several times wished to call on Pincai—yet Hua mansion awe and arrogant lackeys barred him—so he stayed shut in study—silent gloom alone.",
    "Early on the fourteenth Ziyun consulted Cixian: \"Today Young Master Hua bids an all-night cup—and lantern-viewing—they say five great troupes in chorus.\" Servants dispatched attendants—inventoried robes and trifles—tips and gifts; the steward packed all—family checked—to spare last-minute lacks. Already past midday the two breakfasted—dressed—rode straight to Hua mansion.　　　Young Master Hua meanwhile trimmed each scenic spot himself. West Garden scenes—though beneath Yiyuan—were wrought so fine and splendid as to rival—only plot was tight—barely one-third Yiyuan's breadth. Twelve towers stood in the grounds; west flower hall where Pincai once arrived—still first gate into garden. Late Lord Hua's friend Xie Lishan—a skilled painter—spent twelve years laying it—light and dense in balance—until Young Master grew—loved sumptuous display—and reworked Lishan's brush again and again—so every corner blazed carving and color—not a patch of rustic plain left.",
    "That morning Zhang Zhongyu entered early—breakfasted at Pincai's—with Zhang, Gu and others laughed half the morning; past noon he pulled Pincai and Lin Shanzhi to roam West Garden.",
    "Zhongyu had toured only one or two corners; though Pincai wandered twice he'd never covered all.",
    "One marvel wound layered paths through the whole garden—twenty mu square—opened a pool named Jade Belt River—six bends—six bridges each bend. Long galleries and curved belvederes hugged the banks—front and rear views—grace from every angle—several skiffs moored along shore—shore band named Little Su Causeway—great trees—gnarled pines—trained bamboo. Two kinds of rockery—small Taihu heaps hollow and clever—tall yellow-stone stacks—ivy and moss—pavilions tucked—flowers framed; pick a theme—water meets hill—hill roots in water—hollows hold houses—trees stitch spaces—spots where raising eyes lost sky—where bowing head lost earth.",
    "Zhongyu and Pincai followed Shanzhi—paths rose and fell—into a fairy grotto—left ascent—cassia—within ten paces a curved gallery concave—sheer blinds—half-drawn lattice; seven bays—wings spread like wings—three central bays—rear glass windows pressed the pool—chamber decked rich—tablet \"Returning-Geese Shoal\"—small colophon in Young Master Hua's own brush; admired—right gallery west door—tiny yard—spirit rocks—plantain—nanmu moon gate ice-prunus octagonal—stairs within—upper floor carved windows—dozens of shelves—two buildings T-shaped—three tiers one side—two the other—bright windows—four great cabinets below—long table—tripod incense—vases smiling.",
    "Three men sat briefly—stairs behind screen—red railing—weeping willows row—wutong ahead—inner loft refined—qin on walls—broidered antique splendor—bronze vessels—no vulgar air—admired—descended—open on four sides—waterside—dustless chamber—furniture lacquered bamboo—paired bamboo aisles—autumn sounds stirring—chess table—two lacquer chess-boxes—Zhongyu said: \"Quiet enough—yet rinses away garish bustle.\" Shanzhi said: \"Young Master loves crowds—yet cherishes silence too.\" Zhongyu descended—followed pool—crossed red bridge—white marble terrace—carved rails like jade—three-bay pavilion—glass panels—entered—glitter pierced cold—summer retreat—tables and stools all glass—paired mica screens—great vat—clear water—goldfish within—four-foot crystal hill centerpiece—already autumn chill—sinister breath—stepped out—heard distant watch-clapper—Shanzhi said: \"Summoners stirring—Young Master emerges—guests nearing—I must go ahead.\" Left—Zhongyu with Pincai returned east garden—changed clothes—waited banquet.",
    "Meanwhile Young Master Hua feasted guests—three venues today—day banquet with opera at Enqing Hall.",
    "From you and xu hours acrobatics at West Garden Little Ping Hill—night lantern opera at Quiet-Green lodge. Young Master Hua caps and belts—waited before Enqing Hall—happily Xiao Xu Liu arrived together—entered main gate—left carriages—sedan chairs within—straight through pendant gate—to main hall—Young Master greeted—opened central doors—four guests walked slowly—two courts more—Enqing Hall. Cixian first ascent—studied hall—towering splendid—stage hung bright drapery—flanked dressing rooms—saluted anew—about to seat—Wei Pincai emerged with Zhang Zhongyu—all exchanged courtesy—sat by generation—tea thrice—six-rank stewards led four servants—spread two tables—music struck—silver dishes jade bowls poured—Young Master rose to settle seats—Ziyun Wenze yielded—wanted single round table—Young Master refused—yielded Cixian head seat Wenze next—other table Ziyun head Zhongyu next—Pincai paired himself last.",
    "Five troupes joint performance—tablet bearer knelt—each guest chose one play—performed in order—opening crowd-pleasers everyone knows—save ink. Host poured wine—four guests sampled—courses arrived—sea-rare hill-delicacy—fat crisp savour—witty talk spiced with jest—far table Pincai asked Cixian Yiyuan sights—Cixian sketched several—then Baozhu Huifang Sulan Shufang Yulin Lanbao Guibao Chunxi Qiguan nine—plus one—staged Qinhuai Flower-Viewing Assembly—demure—coquettish—still—bold—lush charm—applause—Ziyun Cixian tipped mid-act—Young Master laughed: \"That plagiarizes my brother's old draft—felt thrice familiar.\" Ziyun: \"Well sung—demure utterly demure—wild utterly wild—no two alike.\" Wenze: \"Never saw them attempt this.\" Cixian: \"Qinhuai runs cold nowadays—even Ma Xianglan's looks were middling—and golden-lotus jibes.\" Ziyun: \"I've seen Xianglan's portrait—grace in brush remains.\" Pincai Zhongyu chimed—Young Master warmed wine—pressed rounds—Ziyun remembered Qinyan absent—asked: \"I heard Qinyan lodges here—why missing?\" Young Master: \"Odd temper—still honest—assigned inner study—will appear presently.\" Ziyun scanned—no Shanzhi nor Eight-Age troupe—thought such feast—were they backstage in greasepaint? Piece ended—Young Master summoned ten dans to toast—all advanced—slender lush each charm—beyond nine one Quanfu troupe Quan Gui— fetching—raised golden cups wine round.",
    "Huifang poured before Ziyun—asked Chunhang exam essays—Huifang: \"Other day Shi Zhujun said his superb—sure pass.\" Wenze across table laughed: \"I heard you home burning incense daily—Xiangfan's prose poor—still he'd pass.\" Huifang: \"Who said that—if passes came by prayer I'd pray everyone through.\" Young Master: \"What's this?\" Ziyun began—Huifang poured blocking him—Young Master stared awaiting—Wenze: \"Let me finish.\" Huifang shot him glance—Zhongyu laughed: \"Meixiang—crowd tonight—you'd gag mouths—can't gag so many.\" Huifang: \"Why gag—nothing I fear—you may prattle.\" Crossed to Wenze—Baozhu Young Master tipped cup—Baozhu thanked—Young Master praised opera—pressed Huifang matter—Baozhu: \"I wouldn't know.\" Young Master: \"You shield each other—vexing—we'll ferret yet.\" Called Huifang—Young Master: \"I'm impatient—can't abide muddle—what truth hide from me?\" Huifang lowered head: \"Don't heed their taunts—they jest me.\" Ziyun smiled: \"Meixiang—your affair—outside walls all know—even inside someone may—why not tell Young Master?\"",
    "\"What have I to say?\" Zhongyu suddenly laughed: \"You borrowed shield in crisis—now forget kindness.\" All puzzled—Huifang started—cheeks reddened. Young Master remembered prior words—softened—guessed shameful tale—would ask Du Xiang in good time—and turned chat elsewhere—much wine—several plays—two dessert rounds—Young Master rose: \"Stroll garden awhile.\" Cixian Ziyun: \"Good—wine already plenty.\" Guests rose—four-five servants dashed gallery shortcut—warned garden gate.",
    "East and west gardens flank main hall—doors everywhere—Young Master led party—gallery wound courts—another cloister—wall inset Zhu Zhishan grass-script plaque—six feet tall—as guests paused—an attendant pushed—it was door disguised—beyond green shade—water murmur—all yielded into garden—red bridge—greenstone terrace—white marble short rails—small green silk awning—left hillside cassia clusters—right winding stream bamboo screens blocking view.",
    "Above stood three-bay pavilion—inscribed 「Tan Shui Fang Shan」—Deep Pool and Mountain Dwelling—most refined quiet.",
    "Ziyun wished sit—Young Master ushered within—past screen—a chamber wider outside narrow inside—three faces fan-shaped—carved lattice fret—ebony ivory zitan yellowwood delicate tracery—partitioned five-six bays—front without curtains—green gauze railing—before pavilion ran clear stream—two miniature painted boats moored—opposite water pavilion—heavy Xiang blinds—Young Master ordered long table before gauze—fine incense—fragrant tea—seated—autumn light painted—heart rinsed clean—Ziyun glanced back—Shanzhi led Qinyan up—bowed—Ziyun party hailed.",
    "Ziyun saw Qinyan—eyes down—no proud air as before—two months gone—once morning-and-night familiar—now like strangers meeting—speechless—poignant—called him near—asked—almost raised Ziyu—checked—Cixian Wenze few words.",
    "Guests conversed long—late afternoon—Young Master ordered fruit plates—snacks—light drinking—summoned cluster of dans to attend—opposite water pavilion a ten-trick variety troupe mounted—jokes—ventriloquism—Dragon Diagram casebook—Cixian tired of listening—played finger-guessing with dans—passed cups—Young Master added conjuring act—moon mounting—feast cleared—strolled garden—dozen pairs red lanterns led—guests changed dress—followed lanterns out—returned Enqing Hall route—lamps blazed like sunset clouds—east from screen—music everywhere—lights rainbow—through moon gate—ahead rainbow-silk arch—hundreds glass painted lanterns—central glass plaque—flanking couplets—under moon courtyard eight tin branch-lamps shaped blooms—lamps in flower-hearts shot flame—trees of silver flower—beyond another lantern shed—stage blazed—side galleries sweet song—opposite Quiet-Green lodge.",
    "Guests ushered within—seated—host set order—opera reopened—feasting and cheer beyond telling—past second watch—host and guests tipsy—dishes stopped—fruit served—loose seating awhile.",
    "Suddenly steward reported gate message—Young Master Feng arrived—begged enter.",
    "Young Master Hua paused—said: \"Good—show him in—no strangers present.\" Pincai: \"Why arrive third watch midnight?\" Young Master: \"Likely bolted inside city—with nowhere lodge.\" Waited long—footsteps—two small horn lanterns—Feng Zipai hurried forward—saluted Young Master—all recognized—Young Master seated him above Pincai—about speak—Zipai laughed: \"Fine merry host—never called me—I must crash.\" Wenze: \"Thought you busy—knew leisure—I'd fetch morning.\" Laughter—Zipai ignored—surveyed performers—pledged full table two cups—then ate several chopsticks dishes.",
    "Young Master saw him starved—asked: \"Where today—why so late?\" Zipai shook head: \"Better not tell.\" Ate apple slice—added: \"Splendid gathering—spoiled—broke unhappy.\" Lazy continue—Young Master pressed: \"Why unhappy—speak.\" Zipai: \"Today with wife's uncle Gui Zirong—to his wife-uncle Wu Dashan's—celebrating aunt's birthday.\" Zhongyu nearly laughed—Ziyun: \"With Wu Dashan—trouble certain.\" Wenze nodded: \"Worth hearing—finish.\" Zipai:",
    "\"Gui Zirong also invited his father-in-law—brought four musicians—Dashan hosted two tables—southern friends.\" Several loved amateur opera—joint pledge: \"Each ten strings cash—ninety total—hired Quanfu troupe—Gui Zirong delighted—performed Exclusive Possession with a Mr Lü.\" Wenze: \"Gui handsome enough—shouldn't lodge concubine outside walls—heard he's broke.\" Zipai winked—Wenze stopped—Cixian cold sniff—Pincai nearly spoke—held back.",
    "Zipai: \"They love opera—why drag me.\" Young Master: \"True—you sing best—I say stronger than them—what piece today?\" Zipai: \"With others fine—Dashan nagged—forced Caught Alive—ill-omen title—Dashan dull and clumsy—beyond telling—audience laughed nonstop—just entering—I kerchiefed his head—suddenly crowd burst in—no questions—Ministry warrant shown—iron chain—dragged Dashan off.\"",
    "Inner women wailed—crowd baffled—would intervene—they'd fled—aimless scatter—Zirong couldn't leave—Dashan's cronies stayed—I came straight here.\" All marvelled—Zhongyu: \"I guessed eight tenths—for Zirong—Dashan only chorus wine—bore Gui's disaster.\" Zipai: \"What cause?\" Zhongyu: \"Guess—heard Wu forged deed—loaned Zirong six hundred strings—lender learned—would sue—must be it.\" Zipai: \"Plausible—money split—now Wu alone pays.\" Wenze: \"Wu singular—dull yet mad for opera—ten suburban playhouses daily—each four-five rounds—sloping shoulders—worst those cracked black boots—shuffling—nod acquaintance—plants himself—none keep him—shuffles on—I skip opera—else meet him.\" Cixian: \"Our Zhejiang man—seems literate.\" Zhongyu: \"Not so—his characters misshapen.\" Young Master: \"Enough foolishness—Zipai you act—show skill—critics here—might win favor.\" Zipai spat: \"I'm no actor—to flatter whom?\" Xu Ziyun: \"Who calls you actor—step on stage—grace self—your looks—mute praise—waste.\" Banter moved Zipai: \"No troupe mates tonight—can't.\" Young Master: \"How not—won't you sing with company?\" Nod: \"Zhang Two Wei One excel.\" Zhongyu shook head: \"I only old-sheng arias—can't match—Wei can—xiaosheng erhua sanhua all.\" Pincai smiled—neither yes nor no—Ziyun: \"Then Wei and Zipai—matched skill.\" Pincai: \"Styles may clash—never coached Zipai?\" Young Master: \"Adjust beforehand—I have Suzhou musicians stage-side.\" Pincai: \"Need Zhou San's flute—Qin Jiu's clappers.\" Summoned—Pincai listed Fold Willow, Exclusive Possession, Lotus Viewing, Small Banquet, Lute Tease, Poem Theft—Zipai shook head—some unknown—some rusty—laughed: \"None—I can't sing.\"",
    "Pincai asked: \"What can you?\" Zipai: \"Front Lure, Back Lure, Reverse Deceit, Raise Curtain, Cut Robe pieces.\" Pincai laughed: \"Wrong set—can't pair.\" Behind Young Master several Eight-Age boys—one whispered Shanzhi: \"Why not Caught Alive—other day Wei sang it?\" Young Master overheard—said Pincai: \"Sing Caught Alive with him?\" Pincai demurred—crowd urged—consented—Zipai: \"Sing then—no Ministry warrant chaining Wei away.\" Laughter—Zipai pleased—delayed—then backstage with Pincai—Pincai expert—steady nerve—Zipai rehearsed scenes—matched—hand-gongs tapped—Zipai emerged—plaintive—voice smoke-thin—lamps dimmed—graceful as drifting woman.",
    "Guests astonished—as strangers—Young Master left seat—approached stage—all stood watching—Young Master: \"Strange—like a fine woman tonight—outshines the rest.\" Zipai heard praise—slight shame—saw beside Ziyun Huifang Baozhu—Huifang looked—whispered Ziyu—Baozhu smiled—Wenze Cixian heads together—judging—not Zipai—they discussed Gui Zirong.",
    "Gui Zirong native Jiangxi—registered Zhili—passed xiucai—young face handsome—now twenty-seven-eight—much shady living—family once rich—father great merchant—young Gui bought juren—purchased secretary—now rests home—Zirong eight years capital—squandered fortune—had wife—lied widowed—married Wu Dashan's sister—dissatisfied—took Ye Maolin's daughter concubine—south city separate—Ye girl restless—loved society—Zirong doted insanely—her dowry thick—he drained it—within two years nothing left.",
    "Couple couldn't bear poverty—quarrel scorn—Ye girl preened doorstep—old lovers renewed—Zirong first furious—later cash flowed—accepted—openly kept house—hired clerk—scholar circles despised—yet Zirong boasted patrons—shameless roués sought him—his house near Huifang—so Huifang knew fine detail—Wenze once drank there—hosts forced Zirong attend—many declined.",
    "Zhang Zhongyu closer still—Pincai hadn't heard.",
    "Young Master cared not for gossip—ignored—only watched Zipai entrance—suddenly called large cup—servant bore great jade goblet—Young Master sent before Ziyun—whether Ziyun drank—hear next chapter."
  ],
  31: [
    "Young Master Hua—watching his delight—raised wine to Ziyun and company—the whole table drained a cup together—praising Pincai and Zipai for acting beyond mortal players—beyond common troupers' reach.",
    "Soon both left the stage—Zipai pointed at Wenze and swore: \"You can't tell good from ill—I sweat on stage—you sit judging my every fault.\" Wenze protested: \"When did I judge you—picking blind faults? I chatted with Master Jingyi.\" Cixian said: \"True idle chat—besides you sang so superbly—we couldn't stop praising—what critique?\" Young Master Hua laughed: \"I heard them say—you truly resembled Yan Poxi—had you woman's form—you'd be restless too.\" Zipai: \"Fine—you drag me on stage—then mock.\" Xu Ziyun asked Pincai: \"Brother Wei—your music is exquisite—I must study later—when free visit my garden.\" Pincai bowed: \"I had no teacher—all learned by ear—first time on stage—don't laugh.\" They guessed fists and drinking games—made merry—clock struck midnight—Ziyun said: \"Only autumn equinox—nights shouldn't run short.\" Cixian: \"Feels long—try sitting alone till now—quite tedious.\" Ziyun: \"We've crossed midnight into fifteenth—dawn nears—clear the feast—stop opera—talk till light—we'll scatter.\" Zhang Zhongyu: \"City gates already open—could leave now.\" Young Master Hua: \"What's the rush—scatter at chen is fine.\" Ordered feast cleared—opera stopped—servants brought tea—Ziyun noticed Qinyan gone—only Shanzhi leaned on screen weary—Young Master Hua asked—Shanzhi said: \"Unwell—asleep.\" Truth—Qinyan in crowds recalled his cares—grew sore—seeing Feng Zipai act with Pincai—despised them—asked Shanzhi plead illness—and left.",
    "Young Master Hua summoned the dans again—no stage hats or robes—everyday dress—seated by age in a row—said: \"Beyond opera each of you excels—verse or painting or calligraphy or silk-and-bamboo. Today and last time wine and drama blocked your gifts—still early—who writes—compose lines—who paints—brush a few strokes—no modesty.\" Dans silent—Ziyun and Wenze rose: \"Splendid—we'll assign.\" To Huifang: \"Meixiang excels verse—Yaoqing painting—Jingfang sword-dance—Xiangwan calligraphy—Peixian lyrics—Ruixiang riddles and wit—Shouxiang vertical flute—Xiaomei mouth-organ. Pity Yuyi ails—yet he plays \"Wild Geese on the Sand\".\" Young Master ordered him roused—told Shanzhi fetch pipa—servants spread brushes instruments at stations. Cixian said: \"I'll marshal generals—first Yuyi and Shouxiang blend qin and xiao—Yaoqing paints—Meixiang, Xiangwan, Peixian improvise poems on the scene—inscribe—then Shanzhi and Xiaomei sheng and pipa in contest—Ruixiang riddles and jest—last Jingfang sword-dance—bright as Yuyang drum—how say you?\" All approved—dans performed in order.",
    "Qinyan—no choice—drew brows tight—matched strings—Shufang blew xiao by score beside him.",
    "Qinyan's mind was troubled—fingers rusty—he ground through one set \"Wild Geese on the Sand\"—halting and harsh.",
    "The xiao flowed mild. Young Master Hua shook his head: \"Qin poor—xiao fair.\" Ziyun: \"Qin is hardest—still credit him.\" Cixian: \"You seldom practice—rust showed.\" Qinyan: \"Half a year idle—fourth movement third phrase nearly forgot—Shouxiang's flute improved on before.\" Shufang: \"I study under master—Master Jingyi tutors my blowing every third day—so no rust.\" Qinyan silent—past and present ached—tears nearly fell—drew back standing—Cixian and Ziyun pitied deep.",
    "Meanwhile Yuan Baozhu spread silk on painting desk—pondered left and right—what to paint?",
    "Long thought—no theme. Huifang and Sulan whispered before him: \"What will you paint—we'll fix themes—draft in mind.\" Baozhu stalled—pulled them to railing—consulted—time pressed—couldn't use fine gongbi—few strokes orchid bamboo wouldn't suit scene. Huifang: \"I have a theme—unsure if it fits?—paint a small handscroll—ink a few towers—add thickets bamboo—near and far—moon above—wash indigo clouds and mist—tonight's air—title 'Fine-Night Wind and Moon'?\" Baozhu rejoiced—bowed behind others—seated—bold—three craft seven freehand—Wang Lutai manner—brushed freely.",
    "Cixian and guests dared not crowd—feared spoil his work—watched from distance—brush moved fast—unfettered—already brightening face.",
    "Huifang's party of three clustered—Li Yulin bowed in thought—Sulan told prayer-beads without end—Huifang watched Baozhu's brush—hinting still.",
    "Within half a shichen—done—two feet odd small horizontal scroll. Young Master Hua and Ziyun drew near—unceasing praise. Young Master delighted: \"What labor—how achieve this—no wonder lately all praise their talent and looks—puts the old money-grubbing xianggong to shame.\" Cixian touched up a few spots—fine painting. Young Master asked Huifang: \"Your verse ready?\" Huifang: \"We have—but poor.\" Stood by desk—found paper—wrote quatrain. Young Master read: Fine night lanterns and moon—autumn light—silk-bamboo clamor both wings. I said Consort Chang'e fears solitude—sent wind to waft her to splendid hall. Clapped marvel—Cixian Wenze Ziyun praised: \"You romped all day—he sums in twenty-eight words—more than enough—we could not.\" Read twice—admired.",
    "Wenze: \"Superb—third line wants a tweak.\" Huifang: \"Edit for us.\" Wenze: \"Try 'Perhaps Chang'e feared lonely still'—mood more remote.\" All cried fine. Zhongyu and Pincai secretly startled—never guessed such depth—suspected ghost writers—tonight's test proved real. Feng Zipai never looked—heaped osmanthus from plate—got red thread from page—held one end—page other—threaded blooms—till great ball formed—tossed light—hung on Young Master Hua's lapel—Young Master plucked—smelled—laughed: \"Your labor—you keep it.\" Zipai took—back to fiddling pipa. Sulan and Yulin also finished. First Sulan's: Gold cups brim jade nectar thick—autumn glow gentle as spring face. Chang'e's palace gates unlatch tier on tier—light pierces pearl blinds twelvefold.",
    "Young Master praised same: \"Matched craft—like Yuan Zhen and Bai Juyi in one age.\" Ziyun: \"Two characters shift—third line 'Chang'e' repeats first poem—better 'Cold Moon palace gates unlatch tier on tier'?\" Sulan: \"That improves.\" Ziyun had feared Sulan short of Huifang—now eased. Yulin's lyric—\"One-Trace Sand\"—tender dance deep courtyard—brocade curtains screens soft—pearled guests three thousand—gather worthies—if moon has heart—hold fast—if man has heart—do not depart—",
    "Hear not dawn cock—random cries. Readers beamed—praised—\"Such tender mouths—alive on paper—who could not adore.\" Young Master: \"Fine—yet I'd swap—'gather worthies' → 'meet immortals'—'random cries' → 'only third watch'—good?\" All: \"Good.\" Cixian told them ink quickly—Huifang Yulin asked Sulan copy—Young Master refused—they wrote themselves—admired again—sat listening—Shanzhi's pipa and Chunxi's sheng—Shanzhi leaned—struck sandalwood frets—fingers like rain on plantain—tone like shoal-water—spring chaos filled hall—sheng answered high low—every limb thrilled—they played \"Moon Ascending High\" suite—praised again.",
    "Wind instruments done—Guibao's riddles next. Guibao: \"Others guess me—or I guess others?\" Young Master: \"I'll guess yours.\" Recited offhand: \"Green ripples smile shallow—uneven—this spring later than last. I say Bashang poet's mood thin—better Red Cliff night boat time.\" Guibao pondered—laughed: \"Master names wind flower snow moon—masterfully wrought.\" Young Master: \"Sharp—first guess.\" Zipai: \"Mine—unused wrapped thousand layers—in use shattered bone—who knew black heart inside—still vaults sky.\" Guibao: \"Firecrackers.\" Young Master: \"Such broken riddle?\" Zipai: \"Why broken?\" Young Master: \"Crackers must bang—yours silent—use?\" Laughter. Pincai: \"My broken one—guess—thunder rage shakes earth—gone never returns—like battlefield sigh—ancient wars—when return?\" Guibao: \"Also crackers.\" Zhongyu: \"You mocked Zipai's mute—so your first line leads with noise.\" Dawn breeze—bells tolling—east whitening—Young Master urged Lanbao sword-dance—Lanbao rolled sleeves—drew bright blade—opened stance—rhythm rose—light blazed—lastly cold gleam—man invisible—cheered—done—crimson sky—sun rising—Mid-Autumn—each had business—rose to leave—Young Master saw them out—dressed to escort.",
    "Ziyun distributed trinkets among dans—guests scattered—Young Master Hua escorted to vestibule—only Feng Zipai exhausted—asleep on Quiet-Green couch—Pincai to his rooms—Young Master told pages tend Zipai—then inner chambers.",
    "The dans agreed to leave city together—pause that thread.",
    "Fifteenth passed—sixteenth morning Wang Xun and Yan Zhongqing brought Shi Nanxiang to visit Ziyu. Since mid-seventh moon recovery—twenty-eight days nursing—Ziyu was strong again.",
    "Knowing Qinyan trapped Hua mansion—could not emerge—he nursed world-weary mood—banquets and opera—never joined—sat alone with tea bowl and censer—spun round them. Called renunciation—heart still bound—thought of Qinyan—tears streaming—couldn't loose. Fifteenth visited Wang Wenhui—Xun Zhongqing set next noon for Tian Chunhang and Gao Pin. Ziyu breakfasted—waited study—soon Shi Yan arrived—Nanxiang sat—talked with Ziyu—Zhongqing Wang Xun inner first—Lady Yan—tea—then urged Ziyu go.",
    "Carriage waited—Ziyu changed no clothes—Yun'er feared cold—wrapped extra cotton—rode to Chunhang Gao Pin lodgings—both home—entered together—Gao Pin's laughter—birdsong within—Chunhang study—Su Huifang Li Yulin within—Gao Chunhang delighted—seated four—Su Li greeted.",
    "Brief talk—Zhongqing asked exams—Chunhang Gao Pin confident. Zhongqing: \"Xiangfan's essays I've seen—sure success—Zhuoran's—show—must tower above.\" Gao Pin: \"Poor—don't look.\" Wang Xun: \"Nonsense—show anyway.\" Nanxiang: \"Three topics—Zhuoran shines—even unseen fine.\" Ziyu: \"Still look—several approaches—some annotations fit—some not.\" Gao Pin: \"That day mind fog—no characters—night scribbled—submitted—done—first essay draft exists—somewhere—\" fetched—verses attached—Nanxiang half—stopped—Wang Xun: \"Superb—short—four hundred odd words.\" Ziyu: \"Brush mature—tone high—rare in hall.\" Gao Pin nodded Ziyu: \"Yuxiang has eye.\" Zhongqing: \"Zhuoran honest verdict—good or bad?\" Gao Pin: \"Good works—bad works—halls don't judge essays—pass no fluke—fail no injustice.\" Zhongqing asked Nanxiang Xiangfan—Nanxiang: \"Xiangfan tops list—Zhuoran might strike slack reader—or head case—who knows.\" Zhongqing shook head—Gao Pin tore manuscript: \"Fortune fixed—don't debate—I'll pass one to spite you—talk else.\" Silence—knowing Pin vexed—changed topics.",
    "Huifang told Hua mansion verse and painting night—detail—delighted all—had them recite—praised—especially Yulin's lyric finest. Gao Pin: \"Strong general—no weak troops—Peixian's opening lyric—could those scholar-cap hacks match?\" Ziyu: \"True—even Young Master Hua's edits fine.\" Asked Qinyan—Yulin Huifang told—Ziyu froze—Gao Pin's boy summoned him—guest—Pin left long—Nanxiang: \"Who talks so long?\" Chunhang: \"Lately Pin odd—seekers vulgar—lots of silver packets—don't know whose.\" Zhongqing: \"Pin broke—must sell essays—that toss-off piece—why else rush.\" Nanxiang: \"He said he'll pass—means it.\" Pin returned—all hushed.",
    "Huifang: \"Rare all gentlemen here—I'll host today—what say?\" Wang Xun: \"Good.\" Gao Pin: \"Xianggong—not hitting us for subscriptions?\" Huifang laughed: \"Caught—I want subscriptions.\" They thought jest—agreed—Huifang ordered feast from restaurant—servants spread—Huifang seated them solemn—all wondered: \"Meixiang stern—subscriptions real?\" Huifang: \"When drank xianggong wine free?\" Laughter—Pin: \"Missing Pan San.\" Huifang spat—poured rounds—Yulin helped—dishes.",
    "Huifang drew papers from boot—like essay—handed Nanxiang first: \"Master Zhujun—I beg subscriptions for this—read—I'll explain.\" Crowded—title \"Biography of Master Fragrant-Snow.\" Page-boy brought bundle—opened—\"Fragrant-Snow Posthumous Draft\"—two volumes verse and prose. Nanxiang read line by line—Huifang's teacher who taught letters and opera—once scholar—failed exams—burned brush—entered troupe—great writings—Huifang came capital—kin as bone—all arts from him—died date—coffin traveler—lodged south-city Shoufo Temple—widow and son arrived destitute—learned Fragrant-Snow dead years—Huifang emptied purse—two hundred taels—beyond travel enough for household—asked Xiao Cixian portrait and poems—son Yuanzuo thirteen—too poor for school—bright—overhears tutors—memorizes—Five Classics half learned—Huifang wished notables verse epitaph biography—honor hidden virtue—raise descendants—reading—Huifang wept—listeners stirred—stood: \"Such righteousness rare—we'll wash hands and write—praise him—such pupil and son—even poor death—no regret.\" Chunhang Ziyu doubly praised—Nanxiang: \"You wrote this biography?\" Huifang: \"Facts—needs polish.\" Zhongqing: \"Xiangfan could refine.\"—\"I'll elegy.\" Wang Xun: \"I'll elegiac poems.\" Nanxiang: \"I'll tomb inscription.\" Chunhang: \"expand his draft—I new biography?\" Huifang: \"Better—his draft mere outline.\" Ziyu: \"Big pieces yours—I write praise.\" Gao Pin: \"I'll funeral ode—heavy grief.\" Zhongqing: \"We disciples gather—twilight quiet—offer sacrifice—pool travel cash?\" Chunhang agreed—all treated Huifang serious friend—little jest—Nanxiang: \"When soul departs?\" Huifang: \"Midnight thirtieth—twenty-ninth deep night.\" Nanxiang: \"Essays soon—printed collection—dozens copies—homeward—subscriptions each means—or Du Xiang Jingyi Qianzhou contribute—",
    "We'll gather twenty-ninth second watch—one rite—done—other disciples I'll arrange.\" All: \"Good.\" Huifang: \"Sacrifice unnecessary—I dare not—temple cramped—your brush honor enough—outside gossip—would shame you.\" Nanxiang: \"No harm—scholar circles know—decide nearer—Xiangfan needs this—we follow tail.\" Huifang's plea stirred pity—little joy—first watch scattered.",
    "Next day Nanxiang Zhongqing wrote Ziyun Qianzhou etc.—days later subscriptions arrived—verses—counted—Ziyun twenty-four—Wenze sixteen—Cixian twelve—fifty-two taels total. Zhongqing: \"We six shares—eight taels each—hundred taels enough.\" Nanxiang: \"Plenty.\" Letters sent—all pooled in days—writings and anthology carved—hundred copies—sixty taels—Huifang paid alone.",
    "Flower-register pupils of Fragrant-Snow—four remain—Yuan Baozhu Wang Guibao Jin Shufang Lu Sulan—painting or verse—all advanced—these four pooled hundred taels—with Huifang four hundred total—mother son old servant three—boat canal home—ample.",
    "Twenty-eighth Zhongqing visited Nanxiang—planned morrow—\"some won't come—Yong'an timid—fears Father learn—Yuxiang needless—ruined temple midnight—can't ask him.\" Nanxiang: \"Idea—rite pretext—country stroll—daytime bring wine—after offering—Brook Autumn Mound Haoran Pavilion—meet xianggong—fine?\" Zhongqing: \"Excellent—I missed—if Yong'an Yuxiang absent—we four suffice.\" Went Chunhang—set noon feast waiting.",
    "Next morning Nanxiang Zhongqing rode out—Shoufo Temple gate—dismounted—grooms tied horses—five-six carriages parked—entered—ancient shrine desolate—grass knee-deep—mules grazing—broken walls wells—tilted Buddha images.",
    "Entered Amitabha hall—empty—great Buddha hall west corner collapsed—wind shook trees—leaf heaps—desolate—one man emerged rear—Zhongqing knew Huifang's servant—hands down—asked where—\"Behind—follow.\" Past hall—west door—ruined loft—no doors windows—beyond three huts—stacked coffins—twenty-thirty—one coffin—small table—incense candles—that must be it.",
    "East courtyard—another small door—three-four rooms—Chunhang Gao Pin Huifang party inside—old monk with them—Chunhang Huifang came out.",
    "Nanxiang: \"Grim place—no wonder some refused.\" Huifang dragged bench—sat—Zhongqing: \"All here—pour libation—then Brook Mound stroll.\" Huifang spread offering in room—Huifang incense—Sulan wine—Shufang pitcher—Baozhu dishes—Guibao paper—Chunhang Nanxiang Gao Pin bowed together—five dans kowtowed thanks.",
    "All restless—ordered pack—one string cash to monk—left temple—Nanxiang Zhongqing mounted—others carriages—porters poles—straight Brook Autumn Mound—sparse woods yellow leaves—bleak everywhere.",
    "About a li—reached mound—hill-like—temple above—summit great pavilion Haoran—gaze round—dozens li walls villages—interesting. Chunhang: \"Today's desolation pains—here mind clears.\" Gao Pin: \"Never visited Brook Mound—Zhujun you toured?\" Nanxiang: \"First time—read ancients' poem on mound—far—who comes?\" Zhongqing: \"Good change—always bustle—need cold spell.\" Nanxiang: \"Shoufo cold enough—Jiantan—you said only pure hearts pierce silence—only dull wills probe depths—dare lodge that temple nights?\" Zhongqing laughed: \"At that pass—must lodge—moonlit calm—maybe fox ghosts visit—not bad.\" Gao Pin: \"Jiantan loves contrary talk.\" Sulan: \"Alone—daytime I dare not.\" Guibao: \"Many broken coffins—nights must haunt.\" Shufang: \"Monk one novice one altar—unafraid—if ghosts—why monk fine?\" Huifang: \"When saw ghost eat man? Monk said—wind rain nights—deep hours—cries common.\" Baozhu: \"Yiyuan ghost story heard?\" Huifang: \"No.\" Sulan: \"What ghost?\" Baozhu: \"Osmanthus Hall page Chunxi loved fruit—saved banquet fruit in jar—night big monkey stole—Chunxi asleep—heard fruit scatter—called—no answer—lamp—nothing—again noise—again looked—monkey hid in warming brazier—",
    "Chunxi grabbed knife—neared brazier—monkey bolted—shouldered brazier fled—fire out—knife dropped—howled ghosts—neighbor Qing'er ran—smashed monkey—fluffy—tripped—all woke—only brazier floor—puzzled—Chunxi swore five-foot yellow-haired ghost—Qing'er green-fanged ghost—slapped him—two days gossip—third dusk saw monkey sneak for fruit—understood—else masters would hear.\" All laughed—Huifang prepared two vegetarian tables—four snacks—borrowed temple kitchen—nine sat mats on ground—Chunhang Huifang half-year friends—now saw his generosity—old loyalties—revered more—Chunhang recalled last spring poverty—near ditch—without Huifang—talent useless—west wind bleak—autumn drear—mist rising rain threatening—clouds dark—grief rose—tears—others puzzled—Huifang guessed—tearful—Baozhu asked—burst sobbing—remembered hardship—without Fragrant-Snow—nine deaths—wailed—all hearts sore.",
    "Nanxiang sick at heart—drank deep bowl wine—howled toward distant hills—wind rose—trees shook—Gao Pin said: \"You weep and laugh—every breast holds lumps—mine alone—Zhuoran—empty as a belly with no guts.\"",
    "Sun Deng's whistle—mere frenzy—Ruan Ji's grief—spirit drained—ancients climbed heights—composed—grief bound us—shall we improvise verse today?\" Nanxiang: \"Good—you open.\" Gao Pin: \"Stirring pours through He Xin Liang—I hold the tune—listen—does the age ask you?\" Ages turn mulberry seas—cannot bear glance back—Gao: Only poets keep bright whim—daily wild songs with wine—Shi: Autumn stands in shred cloud and ruined willows.",
    "Test horses on border moor—idle gaze—Yan—Ask Golden Terrace—want kirin's tread? Soul fled—who guards still?",
    "Chunhang—Long I've drifted world's edge—with dawn dusk—chess board tea bowls—two three friends. Gao—Dead thousand years—gone—what fame undying? Shi—Grief piles my chest like a peck—Sing by autumn graves as tears—Yan—Hear wailing smash Qin man's jar—drink our fill—heed no dawn's call— All chanted—laughed—rain threatened—packed—Nanxiang rode Huifang's carriage—Zhongqing Sulan's—home—fine drizzle falling—to be continued."
  ]
};
